INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(93, 'Install OED Version 4 upgrade on linux', 'install-oed-version-4-upgrade-on-linux', '', '<p>This weekend I was able to finally get my <a href="http://www.amazon.com/Oxford-English-Dictionary-ROM-Upgrade/dp/0199565945" target="_blank" title="Oxford English Dictionary upgrade to version 4.0">Oxford English Dictionary upgrade to version 4.0</a> to install under linux. First,  I installed it into a Windows 7 virtual machine running in virtual box. After this was successful, I decided to try and install it under wine. This, too, was successfull. Here is how I did it.</p>\n<p>1. Under <a href="http://www.playonlinux.com/en/" target="_blank" title="play on linux">play on linux</a>, go to the install button</p>\n<p>2. Choose "install an unlisted program"</p>\n<p><img src="images/0.png" border="0" width="802" height="579" /></p>\n<p>3. Click "next" on the manual installation page and then chose "Install a program in a new virtual drive"</p>\n<p>4. Name the install (e.g., OED4)</p>\n<p><img src="images/manual-installation.png" border="0" width="522" height="427" /></p>\n<p>5. Click "Configure wine"</p>\n<p><img src="images/configure-wine.png" border="0" width="522" height="427" /></p>\n<p>6. Choose "32 bit installation" and click "Next"</p>\n<p>7. Once the Wine Configuration screen launches, choose Windows 7</p>\n<p><img src="images/win-7.png" border="0" width="412" height="475" /></p>\n<p>8. Click on the "Drives" tab. At this point (assuming you have placed your OED 4.0 install disc in the CD-ROM drive, you will see a mapping to that drive:</p>\n<p><img src="images/install-only.png" border="0" width="412" height="475" /></p>\n<p>The install will not go forward properly when you are asked to insert you previous version''s data disk. At this point, do the following: eject the install disk, insert you previous version''s data disk, and add an additional drive for the data disk. Alternatively, you could just start the wine install process with the previous version''s data disk in the drive. The key element here is that there is a drive mapping explicitly for the previous version. As long as you have that mapping, the install will work. Here is an image of what my list of drives looks like at this point:</p>\n<p><img src="images/data-only.png" border="0" width="412" height="475" /></p>\n<p>click the "OK" button to continue</p>\n<p>9. On the next screen click the browse button</p>\n<p><img src="images/browse-2.png" border="0" width="522" height="427" /></p>\n<p>10. Eject your data disk and insert the Version 4 OED Install disk. Note--you may have to eject one more time and insert the install disk one more time. It appears that you have to do this because wine has a little trouble realizing that a new CD was mounted. If you have an external CD drive, the easiest thing to do is to just disconnect the USB cable and reconnect. Navigate to the install.exe program on the CD-ROM and click "OPEN".</p>\n<p><img src="images/install-exe.png" border="0" width="854" height="744" /></p>\n<p>11. Click "NEXT" when back at the Manual Installation wizard screen:</p>\n<p><img src="images/start-install.png" border="0" width="522" height="427" /></p>\n<p>12. At this point you will be asked to insert your previous data disk. Eject the install disk and insert the data disk from your previous version at this time. Once again, make sure that it mounts properly before proceeding. Execute the double insert-eject trick again if needed (or disconnect and reconnect the USB cable if the drive is external). At this point, click the "OK" button:</p>\n<p><img src="images/insert-old.png" border="0" width="370" height="217" /></p>\n<p>Note: on my system, I know the mounting of the next disc is successful once a windows opens to show it:</p>\n<p><img src="images/old-data.png" border="0" width="802" height="579" /></p>\n<p>13. If you see the screen below, you''re well on your way to a successful install:</p>\n<p><img src="images/success-data.png" border="0" width="370" height="217" /></p>\n<p>14. Once again, eject the data disk and insert the install disk, ensuring that it is fully mounted using the disc change procedures mentioned above. On my system, I see that the disc can be recognized when the window opens:</p>\n<p><img src="images/install-disc.png" border="0" width="802" height="579" /></p>\n<p>15. Next the windows install screen will appear:</p>\n<p></p>\n<p><img src="images/windows-install.png" border="0" width="1301" height="744" /></p>\n<p>16. Proceed with the install accepting the defaults. After a minute or so, you will be asked to insert the OED 4.0 data disc. Follow the aforementioned procedures to make sure it mounts properly and click "OK"</p>\n<p><img src="images/windows-data.png" border="0" width="1301" height="744" /></p>\n<p>Note, when my data disc is properly mounted, I see the following:</p>\n<p><img src="images/data-disc-4.png" border="0" width="802" height="579" /></p>\n<p>17. After the data disc has finished copying it''s files, you will see the following:</p>\n<p><img src="images/complete.png" border="0" width="433" height="376" /></p>\n<p>Click the "Exit" button.</p>\n<p>18. Note that the original "insert previous version''s data disc" dialog is still open:</p>\n<p><img src="images/success-data.png" border="0" width="370" height="217" /></p>\n<p>Click the "Cancel" button as directed.</p>\n<p>19. Next select an icon:</p>\n<p><img src="images/icon.png" border="0" width="522" height="427" /></p>\n<p>Click "Next" and then give your program a name:</p>\n<p><img src="images/OED4.png" border="0" width="522" height="427" /></p>\n<p>Click "Next". On the following screen, select "i don''t want to make another shortcut" and click "Next"</p>\n<p>20.<span style="line-height: 1.3em;">At this point, eject the data disc and re-insert the install disk following the aforementioned procedures. I believe that this is required for the first time you run the dictionary program. After the first time, the disc will not need to be mounted. Note, if you do not have the right disc installed, you will get the following message:</span></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;"><img src="images/wrong-disc.png" border="0" width="469" height="221" /></span></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">If you get the above screen, just get the right disc mounted and click "Retry".</span></p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">At this point, you can now launch the dictionary. You should see the following once it loads:</span></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;"><img src="images/yay.png" border="0" width="782" height="569" /><br /></span></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;"> Make sure it all works by looking up a word:</span></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;"><img src="images/success.png" border="0" width="782" height="569" /></span></p>\n<p>You have now installed OED correctly!</p>', '', 1, 1, 0, 37, '2014-02-15 17:27:23', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:41:22', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-02-15 16:23:08', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 6, 0, 2, '', '', 0, 9535, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(94, 'How To Mount A Western Digital TV Live Hub on Ubuntu (WD Live TV Hub)', 'how-to-mount-a-western-digital-tv-live-hub-on-ubuntu-wd-live-tv-hub', '', '<p>In order to sync files quickly between my server to my WD Live TV hub,   I wanted to mount the Hub in Ubuntu and then issue an rsync command to rsync the files. Here are the steps:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li>Make a location on the file system where you want to mount the WDTV Live Hub:\n<ul>\n<li>sudo md /media/wd</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Edit the /etc/fstab file to include the following line (note,   your IP address will vary:\n<ul>\n<li>\n<div>//192.168.1.3/WDTVLiveHub /media/wd cifs username=guest,password=,nounix,rw,iocharset=utf8,file_mode=0777,dir_mode=0777 0 0</div>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Next mount the device manually (it should mount automatically on the next reboot):</span>\n<ul>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">sudo mount //192.168.1.3/WDTVLiveHub</span></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Create a location (if you haven''t already) to move the files to on the hub:\n<ul>\n<li>mkdir /media/wd/network_sync/music</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Now, you will be able to use rsync normally to copy the files. In my case, I have a lot of video and archive files in my music collection that I did not want to push to the Hub, so I added a lot of ""--exclude=" parameters. Here is the command that I use (the text in bold is specific to my case):</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">rsync -av --progress --exclude=*.VOB --exclude=*.avi --exclude=*.mkv --exclude=*.ts --exclude=*.mpg --exclude=*.iso --exclude=*ar --exclude=*.vob --exclude=*.BUP --exclude=*.cdi --exclude=*.ISO --exclude=*.shn --exclude=*.MPG --exclude=*.AVI --exclude=*.DAT --exclude=*.img --exclude=*.nrg --exclude=*.cdr --exclude=*.bin --exclude=*.MOV --exclude=*.goutputs* --exclude=*.flv --exclude=*.mov --exclude=*.m2ts --exclude=*.cdg --exclude=*.IFO --exclude=*.asf --exclude=*.ite <strong>/media/2TB Data/data/music/*</strong> /media/wd/network_sync/music/</p>\n<p>I was able to achieve 4x the speed using rsync in linux compared to copying files under Windows.</p>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 1, 0, 37, '2014-04-30 16:21:18', 62, 'iisaphd', '2016-08-20 01:08:22', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-04-30 16:10:25', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 3, 0, 1, '', '', 0, 9615, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(95, 'On this day in jazz (July 12)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-july-12', '', '<p>On this day in 1968,   <a href="https://www.facebook.com/bobbyhutchersonmusic" style="color: #3b5998; cursor: pointer; font-family: Helvetica,   Arial,   ''lucida grande'', tahoma, verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;">Bobby H</a><a href="https://www.facebook.com/bobbyhutchersonmusic" style="color: #3b5998; cursor: pointer; font-family: Helvetica, Arial, ''lucida grande'', tahoma, verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;">utcherson</a><span style="color: #37404e; font-family: Helvetica, Arial, ''lucida grande'', tahoma, verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;"> recorded Total Eclipse (with </span><a id="js_23" href="https://www.facebook.com/chickcorea" style="color: #3b5998; cursor: pointer; font-family: Helvetica, Arial, ''lucida grande'', tahoma, verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;">Chick Corea</a><span style="color: #37404e; font-family: Helvetica, Arial, ''lucida grande'', tahoma, verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;"> on piano and </span><a href="https://www.facebook.com/pages/Joe-Chambers/112378672106565" style="color: #3b5998; cursor: pointer; font-family: Helvetica, Arial, ''lucida grande'', tahoma, verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;">Joe Chambers</a><span style="color: #37404e; font-family: Helvetica, Arial, ''lucida grande'', tahoma, verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;"> on drums). Bobby is one of my favorite vibraphonists (along with </span><a href="https://www.facebook.com/pages/Milt-Jackson/109494069070209" style="color: #3b5998; cursor: pointer; font-family: Helvetica, Arial, ''lucida grande'', tahoma, verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;">Milt Jackson</a><span style="color: #37404e; font-family: Helvetica, Arial, ''lucida grande'', tahoma, verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;">) and is a recipient of the lifetime Jazz Msaster Fellowship Award from the National Endowment for the Arts. Bobby also just released "Enjoy The View" on Blue Note last month. Here''s "Matrix" from Total Eclipse:</span></p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SyQxoGDwaVQ" target="_blank" title="Matrix">Matrix</a></p>\n<p><img src="images/tdij/Bobby-Hutcherson.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 53, '2014-07-13 03:53:03', 62, '', '2016-08-16 21:29:28', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-07-13 03:49:48', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 7, 0, 28, '', '', 0, 5074, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(96, 'On this day in jazz (July 11)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-july-11', '', '<p><span style="color: #37404e; font-family: Helvetica,   <a href="href">On this day in 1958,   </span><a href="https://www.facebook.com/JohnColtraneMusic" style="color: #3b5998; cursor: pointer; font-family: Helvetica, Arial, ''lucida grande'', tahoma, verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;">John Coltrane</a><span style="color: #37404e; font-family: Helvetica, Arial, ''lucida grande'', tahoma, verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;"> recorded The Stardust Session. I like this album because it is similar in tone and accessibility to the work he did with Miles Davis a year later. In fact 2 other members of that </span><a href="https://www.facebook.com/MilesDavis" style="color: #3b5998; cursor: pointer; font-family: Helvetica, Arial, ''lucida grande'', tahoma, verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;">Miles Davis</a><span style="color: #37404e; font-family: Helvetica, Arial, ''lucida grande'', tahoma, verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;"> sextet are on this album (bassist Paul Chambers and drummer Jimmy Cobb). Red Garland rounded out the rhythm section on the piano and flgelhornist Wilbur Harden had some great solos on this album.</span></p>\n<p><span style="color: #37404e; font-family: Helvetica, Arial, ''lucida grande'', tahoma, verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;"><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7xY6Ce0bF5I" title="Stardust Session">Stardust Session</a></span></p>\n<p><img src="http://cps-static.rovicorp.com/3/JPG_400/MI0000/516/MI0000516637.jpg?partner=allrovi.com" border="0" height="250" /></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 53, '2014-07-13 03:58:27', 62, '', '2016-08-16 21:30:13', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-07-13 03:57:13', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 6, 0, 29, '', '', 0, 4589, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(97, 'On this day in jazz (July 10)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-july-10', '', '<p><span style="color: #37404e; font-family: Helvetica,   <a href="href">On this day in jazz history, </span><a href="https://www.facebook.com/pages/Jelly-Roll-Morton/109638035721164" style="color: #3b5998; cursor: pointer; font-family: Helvetica, Arial, ''lucida grande'', tahoma, verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;">Jelly Roll Morton</a><span style="color: #37404e; font-family: Helvetica, Arial, ''lucida grande'', tahoma, verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;"> passed away at the young age of 56 in Los Angeles (1941).</span><br style="color: #37404e; font-family: Helvetica, Arial, ''lucida grande'', tahoma, verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;" /><br style="color: #37404e; font-family: Helvetica, Arial, ''lucida grande'', tahoma, verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;" /><span style="color: #37404e; font-family: Helvetica, Arial, ''lucida grande'', tahoma, verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;">Here''s JRM playing Wolverine Blues in Chicago in 1927: </span></p>\n<p><span style="color: #37404e; font-family: Helvetica, Arial, ''lucida grande'', tahoma, verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;"><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=s5XOjIhTMK4" target="_blank" title="Wolverine Blues">Wolverine Blues</a></span></p>\n<p><span style="color: #37404e; font-family: Helvetica, Arial, ''lucida grande'', tahoma, verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;"><img src="images/tdij/MortonBricktopRowCropMortonFace.jpg" border="0" height="250" /><br /></span></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 53, '2014-07-13 04:09:07', 62, '', '2016-08-16 21:30:37', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-07-13 04:07:18', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 6, 0, 30, '', '', 0, 4760, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(98, 'On this day in jazz (July 09)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-july-09', '', '<p><span style="color: #37404e; font-family: Helvetica,   <a href="href">On this day in jazz history,   </span><a href="https://www.facebook.com/MilesDavis" style="color: #3b5998; cursor: pointer; font-family: Helvetica,   Arial, ''lucida grande'', tahoma, verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;">Miles Davis</a><span style="color: #37404e; font-family: Helvetica, Arial, ''lucida grande'', tahoma, verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;"> and </span><a href="https://www.facebook.com/charlesmingus" style="color: #3b5998; cursor: pointer; font-family: Helvetica, Arial, ''lucida grande'', tahoma, verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;">Charles Mingus</a><span style="color: #37404e; font-family: Helvetica, Arial, ''lucida grande'', tahoma, verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;"> recorded Blue Moods. While it''s not one of my favorite albums, I do find it technically interesting that they cut the record at 160 lines/inch instead of the 210-260 lines/inch normally used on LPs. The length of the album because of this was less than 27 minutes long. The reason they did it was to enhance the bass frequencies of Charles'' double bass.</span></p>\n<p><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blue_Moods" target="_blank" title="Blue Moods">Blue Moods</a></p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tp-k4WQPp2Y" title="Blue Moods">Full Album on youtube</a></p>\n<p><img src="images/tdij/front.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 53, '2014-07-13 04:13:01', 62, '', '2016-08-16 21:31:00', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-07-13 04:11:44', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 6, 0, 31, 'Jazz history', 'On this day in jazz history', 0, 4727, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(99, 'On this day in jazz (July 07)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-july-08', '', '<p>On this day in 1956, <a href="https://www.facebook.com/dukeellingtonmusic" style="color: #3b5998; cursor: pointer; font-family: Helvetica, Arial, ''lucida grande'', tahoma, verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;">Duke Ellington</a><span style="color: #37404e; font-family: Helvetica, Arial, ''lucida grande'', tahoma, verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;"> played at the Newport Jazz Festival in Newport, Rhode Island. The performance can be found on the album <em>Ellington at Newport</em>. The concert was very important as it is credited as revitalizing the big band leaders'' diminishing career. George Wein described the concert as "the greatest performance of [Ellington''s] career... It stood for everything that jazz had been and could be." </span><span style="color: #37404e; font-family: Helvetica, Arial, ''lucida grande'', tahoma, verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;">The concert is also featured in the Ken Burns'' Jazz documentary (</span><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XNBpMRPfw0A" target="_blank" style="font-family: Helvetica, Arial, ''lucida grande'', tahoma, verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;">link</a><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">). </span></p>\r\n<p><span style="color: #37404e; font-family: Helvetica, Arial, ''lucida grande'', tahoma, verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;">Specifically, the song featured in Burn''s documentary was "</span><span style="font-family: Helvetica, Arial, ''lucida grande'', tahoma, verdana, arial, sans-serif; color: #37404e;"><span style="font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;">Diminuendo In Blue and Crescendo In Blue". The reason is because this is probably the song that saved Duke''s career. The song</span></span><span style="color: #37404e; font-family: Helvetica, Arial, ''lucida grande'', tahoma, verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;"> features a very long solo by Gonsalves  with Ellington yelling "Come on, Paul  dig in! Dig in!". The crowd, which had been filing out of the festival, quickly turned around and came back in. Some ended up dancing in the aisles--possibly due to the platinum blonde woman in a black evening dress (Elaine Anderson) getting up and dancing enthusiastically. When the solo ended, Gonsalves collapsed in exhaustion, but Ellington took over for two choruses before the full band returned for the "Crescendo in Blue" portion of the song.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style="color: #37404e; font-family: Helvetica, Arial, ''lucida grande'', tahoma, verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;">Here''s Duke with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5vnrNWyvI-U" target="_blank">Diminuendo In Blue and Crescendo In Blue</a>":</span></p>\r\n<p><span style="color: #37404e; font-family: Helvetica, Arial, ''lucida grande'', tahoma, verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;"><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5vnrNWyvI-U" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Scan.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a><br /></span></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Star Spangled Banner" - 1:10</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Father Norman O''Connor Introduces Duke & the Orchestra / Duke Introduces Tune & Anderson, Jackson & Procope - 3:36</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Black and Tan Fantasy" - 6:21</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Duke Introduces Cook & Tune - 0:26</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Tea for Two" - 3:34</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Duke & Band Leave Stage / Father Norman Talks About The Festival - 2:30</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Take the ''A'' Train" - 4:27</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Duke Announces Strayhorn''s A Train & Nance / Duke Introduces Festival Suite, Part I & Hamilton - 0:41</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Part I - Festival Junction" - 8:10</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Duke Announces Soloists; Introduces Part II - 0:38</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Part II - Blues to Be There" - 7:09</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Duke Announces Nance & Procope; Introduces Part III - 0:19</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Part III - Newport Up" - 5:33</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Duke Announces Hamilton, Gonsalves & Terry / Duke Introduces Carney & Tune - 0:25</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Sophisticated Lady" - 3:52</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Duke Announces Grissom & Tune - 0:17</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Day In, Day Out" - 3:50</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Duke Introduces Tune(s) and Paul Gonsalves Interludes - 0:23</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Diminuendo In Blue and Crescendo In Blue" - 14:20</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Announcements, Pandemonium - 0:44</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Pause Track - 0:06</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Duke Introduces Johnny Hodges - 0:18</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"I Got It Bad (and That Ain''t Good)" - 3:38</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Jeep''s Blues" - 4:36</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Duke Calms Crowd; Introduces Nance & Tune - 0:42</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Tulip or Turnip" - 2:49</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Riot Prevention - 1:08</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Skin Deep" - 9:13</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Mood Indigo" - 1:30</span></li>\r\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 53, '2014-07-13 04:25:37', 62, '', '2018-04-16 23:44:12', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-07-07 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 11, 0, 2, 'on this day in jazz, Duke Ellington', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 17153, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(100, 'On this day in jazz (July 13)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-july-13', '', '<p>On this day in 1960,   <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Mingus" target="_blank">Charles Mingus</a>''<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mingus_at_Antibes" target="_blank">Mingus at Antibes</a> was recorded. The album features Charles playing double bass and piano, Ted Curson on trumpet, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eric_Dolphy" target="_blank">Eric Dolphy</a> on alto sax (bass clarinet on track 3), Booker Ervin on tenor sax, and Dannie Richmond on drums. Bud Powell even joined in on "I''ll Rember April" (track 4).</p>\n<p>Here''s Charles playing both bass and piano on:<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=23gg1WZnNmE" target="_blank">"Better Get Hit In Yo Soul"</a></p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=23gg1WZnNmE" target="_blank"></a>The above version of Better Get is much faster than my favorite version, which can be found on <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Z-R11B7EGt0" target="_blank">Mingus Ah Um</a>. If this song isn''t soulful enough for you, also check out <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6OCrWScxtmA" target="_blank">"Wednesday Night Prayer Meeting"</a>.</p>\n<p><img src="images/tdij/220px-Charles_Mingus_1976.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></p>\n<p>If you want to know more about Charles, he wrote a 4000 bar piece called "Epitaph" which can be found on the internet. It takes over 2 hours to play and was found while cataloging his works after his death. He called it "Epitaph" because he felt no one would ever play or record it while he was alive.</p>\n<p>From wiki:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><a class="mw-redirect" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Epitaph_(Mingus)" title="Epitaph (Mingus)" style="color: #0b0080; background: none;">Epitaph</a> is considered one of Charles Mingus''s masterpieces. The composition is 4,235 measures long, requires two hours to perform, and is one of the longest jazz pieces ever written. Epitaph was only completely discovered during the cataloging process after his death, by musicologist Andrew Homzy.</p>\n<p>With the help of a grant from the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ford_Foundation" title="Ford Foundation">Ford Foundation</a>, the score and instrumental parts were copied, and the piece itself was premiered by a 30-piece orchestra, conducted by <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gunther_Schuller" title="Gunther Schuller">Gunther Schuller</a>. This concert was produced by Mingus''s widow, Sue Graham Mingus, at Alice Tully Hall on June 3, 1989, ten years after his death. It was performed again at several concerts in 2007. The performance at Walt Disney Concert Hall is available on <a class="external text" href="http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=92884124" rel="nofollow">NPR</a>. The complete score was published in 2008 by Hal Leonard.</p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 53, '2014-07-13 04:40:59', 62, '', '2016-08-20 01:11:26', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-07-13 04:27:45', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 6, 0, 27, '', '', 0, 5147, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(465, 'On this day in jazz (July 08)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-july-08', '', '<p>On this day in 1975, pianist <a href="http://newarkwww.rutgers.edu/ijs/mlw/intro2.html" target="_blank">Mary Lou Williams</a> recorded the album <em>Free Spirits</em>. Joining Mary on the album were Buster Williams on bass and Mickey Rocker on the drums. Although Mary recorded over 100 records in her career, this was only the ninth that she recorded as a leader.</p>\r\n<p>Mary was born Mary Elfrieda Scruggs in Atlanta, GA, but grew up in Pittsburgh, PA. She taught herself to play the piano and made her first public performance at six years old. She started playing professionally with Duke Ellington at the age of 12, and once at the ripe old age of 15, Louis Armstrong heard her playing in Harlem, and after the song he went up to her, picked her up and gave her a kiss. At 17, she married saxophonist John Williams and moved to Memphis, TN. In 1942, divorced from her husband, she returned to Pittsburgh for a while before moving to Europe for two years in 1952. In 1956 she became a Roman Catholic, quit performing and dedicated her time to the Bel Canto Foundation which helped musicians with drug addictions quit and return to performing. However, two priests and Duke Ellington convinced her to start performing again...and that brings you up with her history leading into yesterday''s profiled album, <em>Ellington at Newport</em>. <span style="white-space: pre;"> </span></p>\r\n<p>Some of the awards and honors she received over her career were the following:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Guggenheim Fellowships in both 1972 and 1977</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Nominee in the 1971 Grammy''s for Best Jazz Performance - Group</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Founded the Mary Lou Williams Foundation in 1980</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Duke University''s Duke''s Trinity Award for service to the university in 1981; in 1983 Duke established the Mary Lou Williams Center for Black Culture</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">In 1996, The Kennedy Center in Washington, D.C. established the annual Mary Lou Williams Women in Jazz Festival</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Another interesting bit of trivia for this day...it''s the day I published my last blog post for <strong>On this day in jazz</strong>. I started a year ago, profiling Miles Davis and Charles Mingus'' <em>Blue Moods</em>. While I admit the first few points left something to be desired, I think that I hit my stride by the end of the first month. I hope that you have enjoyed the journey and have learned a thing or two about this great art form.</p>\r\n<p>Here''s Mary with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9yfqBhxqwZA" target="_blank">Ode to St. Cecile</a>":</p>\r\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9yfqBhxqwZA" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/mlw-fs-f.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /></a></p>\r\n<p>Track listing:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Dat Dere (Bobby Timmons) 4:48</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Baby Man, No.2 (John Stubblefield) 7:56</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Baby Man (John Stubblefield) 8:31</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">All Blues (Miles Davis) 6:59</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Tempatation (Lew Brown) 5:08</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Pale Blue (Buster Williams) 4:27</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Free Spirits #2 (John Stubblefield) 5:04</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Free Spirits (John Stubblefield) 5:25</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Blues for Timme (Mary Lou Williams) 5:37</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Ode to Saint Cecile (Mary Lou Williams) 5:55</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Surrey With the Fringe on Top (Oscar Hammerstein II / Richard Rodgers) 2:58</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Gloria (Mary Lou Williams) 5:31</span></li>\r\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 53, '2015-07-05 19:17:43', 62, '', '2018-04-16 23:47:19', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-07-08 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 6, 0, 1, 'on this day in jazz, Mary Lou Williams', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 19358, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(101, 'On this day in jazz (July 14)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-july-14', '', '<p>On this day in 1964,   <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a> recorded Miles In Tokyo at<span style="font-family: arial,   <a href="href">the Kohseinenkin Hall,   Shinjuku, Tokyo. This is the first recording of Miles playing in Japan. It was released in 1969 in Japan, but it took until 2005 for the CD to be released in the US. </span><span style="font-family: arial, sans-serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 17px;">Besides </span><span style="font-family: arial, sans-serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 17px;">Miles on trumpet, <a href="http://www.herbiehancock.com/home.php" target="_blank">Herbie Hancock</a> is at the Piano, <a href="http://roncarter.net/JazzMaster/" target="_blank">Ron Carter</a> is on double base, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tony_Williams_(drummer)" target="_blank">Tony Williams</a> is at the drums and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sam_Rivers" target="_blank">Sam Rivers</a> was on tenor sax. What a lineup!</span></p>\n<p><span style="font-family: arial, sans-serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 17px;">As some of you may know, Don Cheadle and Ewan McGregor started filming <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/news/photos-miles-ahead-filming-begins-cincinnati-usa-today">Miles Ahead </a>last week in Cincinnati.</span></p>\n<p><span style="font-family: arial, sans-serif;"><span style="line-height: 17px;">Here''s a link to <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-xkiPPSVRvE" target="_blank">If I Were A Bell</a></span></span></p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-xkiPPSVRvE" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/milestokyo.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Set List</p>\n<ol style="line-height: 22.399999618530273px; margin: 0.3em 0px 0px 3.2em; padding: 0px; list-style-image: none;">\n<li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">"Introduction by Teruo Isono" - 1:10</li>\n<li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">"<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/If_I_Were_a_Bell" title="If I Were a Bell" style="color: #0b0080; background: none;">If I Were a Bell</a>" (<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frank_Loesser" title="Frank Loesser" style="color: #0b0080; background: none;">Frank Loesser</a>)  10:14</li>\n<li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">"<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/My_Funny_Valentine" title="My Funny Valentine" style="color: #0b0080; background: none;">My Funny Valentine</a>" (<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Rodgers" title="Richard Rodgers" style="color: #0b0080; background: none;">Richard Rodgers</a>,<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lorenz_Hart" title="Lorenz Hart" style="color: #0b0080; background: none;">Lorenz Hart</a>)  12:45</li>\n<li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">"So What" (<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miles_Davis" title="Miles Davis" style="color: #0b0080; background: none;">Miles Davis</a>)  8:02</li>\n<li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">"Walkin''" (Richard H. Carpenter)  9:11</li>\n<li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">"<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/All_of_You_(Cole_Porter_song)" title="All of You (Cole Porter song)" style="color: #0b0080; background: none;">All of You</a>" (<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cole_Porter" title="Cole Porter" style="color: #0b0080; background: none;">Cole Porter</a>)  11:18</li>\n<li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">"Go-Go [Theme] + closing announcement" (<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miles_Davis" title="Miles Davis" style="color: #0b0080; background: none;">Miles Davis</a>) - (1:19)</li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 53, '2014-07-13 16:07:57', 62, '', '2016-08-16 21:32:21', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-07-14 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 6, 0, 26, '', '', 0, 5069, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(102, 'On this day in jazz (July 15)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-july-15', '', '<p>On this day in 1954,   the first <a href="http://www.newportjazzfest.org/" target="_blank">Newport Jazz Festival</a> started. That makes this year''s festival the 60th anniversary of this great event. Just some of the acts performing this year are:Bobby McFerrin,   Jazz at Lincoln Center Orchestra (with Wynton Marsalis),   David Sanborn & Joey DeFrancesco, Dr. John, Ron Carter,<span style="line-height: 1.3em;">John Zorn, Lee Konitz Quartet with Grace Kelly, Ravi Coltrane, Mingus Big Band and The Brubeck Brothers. This year''s festival runs August 1 - August 3. </span></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">One of the most famous performances at the festival was Miles Davis'' cover of ''round About Midnight in 1955 with a truly all-star band which included </span>saxophonists <a href="http://www.zootsims.org/" target="_blank">Zoot Sims</a> and <a href="http://www.gerrymulligan.com/" target="_blank">Gerry Mulligan</a>, pianist <a href="http://www.monkzone.com/" target="_blank">Thelonious Monk</a>, bassist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Percy_Heath" target="_blank">Percy Heath</a>, and drummer <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Connie_Kay" target="_blank">Connie Kay</a>.</p>\n<p>Here''s a <a href="http://iisaphd.subsonic.org/share/ESQNT" target="_blank">link</a> to that performance.</p>\n<p><a href="http://iisaphd.subsonic.org/share/ESQNT" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/mdavis1957.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>See the post from<a href="index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=99:on-this-day-in-jazz-july-08&catid=53:july&Itemid=41" target="_self"> July 08</a> for info on<a href="http://paulgonsalves.org/" target="_blank"> Paul Gonsalves''s</a> famous performance a year later that literally had people running back in to the festival.</p>\n<p>Also of note on this day, <a href="http://www.bluenote.com/artists/bobby-hutcherson">Bobby Hutcherson</a> recorded <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/San_Francisco_(Bobby_Hutcherson_album)" target="_blank">San Francisco</a>. Check out TGP''s remix of "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=93wZYPAY6aY&feature=kp" target="_blank">A Night In Barcelona</a>". There''s more of Bobby on <a href="index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=95:on-this-day-in-jazz-july-12&catid=53:july&Itemid=41" target="_self">July 12</a>.</p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 53, '2014-07-13 16:34:17', 62, '', '2016-08-20 01:10:48', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-07-15 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 10, 0, 25, '', '', 0, 5008, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(105, 'On this day in jazz (July 18)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-july-18', '', '<p>On this day in 1942,   Helen O''Connell and Bob Eberly recorded Brazil. It was their last duet together. Her best selling records were: "Green Eyes", "Amapola," "Tangerine" and "Yours". Like with "Brazil", Bob Eberly sang the song first and Helen reprized in an up-tempo arrangement.</p>\n<p>O''Connell was selected by Down Beat readers as best female singer in 1940 and 1941 and won the 1940 Best Female Vocalist from Metronome magazine. She also co-hosted the Miss USA/Universe pageants from 1972 until 1980.</p>\n<p>Here''s one of my favorite songs: "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Mgi1o5gVDXM&feature=kp" target="_blank">Brazil</a>" (it''s also one of my favorite <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4Wh2b1eZFUM" target="_blank">movies</a> by <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4Wh2b1eZFUM" target="_blank">Terry Gilliam</a>):</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Mgi1o5gVDXM&feature=kp" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/250px-Helen_Oconnell.jpg" border="0" height="250" /> </a></p>\n<p>Also on this day, Charles Mingus who was honored on <a href="index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=100:on-this-day-in-jazz-july-13&catid=53:july&Itemid=41" target="_self">July 13</a>, recorded <a href="http://www.amazon.com/New-Tijuana-Moods-Charles-Mingus/dp/B000003G58" target="_blank">New Tijuana Moods</a>.</p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 53, '2014-07-14 22:26:06', 62, '', '2016-08-16 21:35:44', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-07-18 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 7, 0, 22, '', '', 0, 3034, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(103, 'On this day in jazz (July 16)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-july-16', '', '<p>On this day in 1961,   <a href="http://www.ericdolphy.net/" target="_blank">Eric Dolphy</a> was recorded live at the Five Spot by legendary engineer <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rudy_Van_Gelder" target="_blank">Rudy Van Gelder</a>. The whole concert is available in two volumes. The performance below is from volume 2. The session was played by Eric Dolphy on alto saxophone,   bass clarinet and flute; Booker Little on the trumpet; and a rhythm section consisting of Mal Waldron at the piano, Richard Davis playing double bass, and Ed Blackwell on drums. Make sure to check out the song "Bee Vamp".</p>\n<p>It took me a while to really appreciate Eric''s style, and this <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FvXICIZ_vZE" target="_blank">performance</a> is one that I enjoy:</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FvXICIZ_vZE" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/ed5s.jpg" border="0" width="300" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Complete set list:</p>\n<p>Volume one</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">"Fire Waltz" (Waldron)  13:44</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">"Bee Vamp" (Little)  12:30</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">"The Prophet" (Dolphy)  21:22</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">"Bee Vamp" (Alternate Take)  9:27</p>\n<p>Volume two</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">"Aggression" (Little)  17:21</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">"Like Someone in Love" (Jimmy Van Heusen)  19:58</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">"Number Eight (Potsa Lotsa)" (Dolphy)  15:33</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">"Booker''s Waltz" (Little)  14:39</p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 53, '2014-07-13 17:20:38', 62, '', '2016-08-16 21:34:21', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-07-16 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 8, 0, 24, '', '', 0, 6860, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(104, 'On this day in jazz (July 17)', 'bill-evans', '', '<p>On this day in 1962,  <a href="http://www.billevanswebpages.com/" target="_blank">Bill Evans</a> completed recording<a href="http://www.allmusic.com/album/interplay-mw0000188120" target="_blank">Interplay</a>.The all-star cast includes Bill Evans at the piano,   <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Percy_Heath" target="_blank">Percy Heath</a> on bass,   <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philly_Joe_Jones" target="_blank">Philly Joe Jones </a>on drums, <a href="http://www.jimhallmusic.com/" target="_blank">Jim Hall</a> playing guitar and <a href="http://www.freddiehubbardmusic.com/" target="_blank">Freddie Hubbard</a> on trumpet. I first got acquainted with Bill by listening to Miles Davis'' <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kbxtYqA6ypM" target="_blank">Kind of Blue</a> and quickly discovered many of Bill''s other great recordings.</p>\n<p>The song highlighted below is "You And The Night And The Music" which was originally writtenas part of the the Broadway show "Revenge with Music". Thus musical was an artistic failure, but did produce two hits, one of which ("You And The Night") has endured as a jazz standard. Justine "<span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Baby" Washington even recorded a pop version of this song in 1963--in fact, she''s still performing in 2014.</span></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Anyway, here''s Bill Evans with "</span><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bxKo7kp5a6Y" target="_blank" style="line-height: 1.3em;">You And The Night And The Music</a><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">":</span></p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bxKo7kp5a6Y" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/hqdefault.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 53, '2014-07-13 17:34:01', 62, '', '2016-08-16 21:34:54', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-07-17 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 10, 0, 23, '', '', 0, 8416, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(106, 'On this day in jazz (July 19)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-july-19', '', '<p>On this day in 1939,   tenor saxophonist and clarinet player <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bud_Freeman" target="_blank">Bud Freeman</a> recorded "The Eel" with his Summa Cum Laude Orchestra. Freeman''s nickname, in fact, was "The Eel", which he got for his long eel-like improvisations. Freeman played with Tommy Dorsey and Benny Goodman''s orchestras before forming his Summa Cum Laude Orchestra.</p>\n<p>"The Eel" is a prime example of Chicago style dixieland jazz. Chicago style replaces the tuba and banjo found in New Orleans style with the bass and guitar; it''s also usually played at a faster pace then New Orleans style. Chicago style is also the direct precursor to <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Swing_(jazz_performance_style)" target="_blank">Swing</a> jazz (swing was responsible for initiating the "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mBdAuXr4ssQ" target="_blank">Lindy Hop</a>" dance craze in Harlem).</p>\n<p>Here is "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-fMj4ktY_Go&feature=kp" target="_blank">The Eel</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-fMj4ktY_Go&feature=kp" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Bud_Freeman%2C_Marty_Marsala_%28Gottlieb_02951%29.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 53, '2014-07-14 22:48:15', 62, '', '2016-08-20 01:07:26', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-07-19 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 5, 0, 21, '', '', 0, 6108, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(114, 'On this day in jazz (July 27)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-july-27', '', '<p>On this day in 1956,   <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jackie_McLean" target="_blank">Jackie McLean</a> recorded his second session as a leader at the <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/rudy-van-gelder-mn0000305301/biography" target="_blank">Van Gelder Studio in Hackensack,  </a>NJ.<span style="line-height: 1.3em;"> The </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">work includes three original songs by Jackie, including the title song "Light''s Out" which you can hear below. </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">McLean is supported on this album by trumpeter </span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Donald_Byrd" target="_blank" style="line-height: 1.3em;">Donald Byrd</a><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">, and a rhythm section of pianist </span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elmo_Hope" target="_blank" style="line-height: 1.3em;">Elmo Hope</a><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">, </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">drummer </span><a href="http://www.drummerworld.com/drummers/Art_Taylor.html" target="_blank" style="line-height: 1.3em;">Art Taylor</a>, and<span style="line-height: 1.3em;">bassist </span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doug_Watkins" style="line-height: 1.3em;">Doug Watkins</a><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">. </span></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">An aside on Doug Watkins: Doug died tragically in 1962 when he fell asleep at the wheel while driving </span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roland_Hanna" title="Roland Hanna">Sir Roland Hanna</a> and trumpeter <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bill_Hardman" title="Bill Hardman">Bill Hardman</a> to San Francisco from Arizona to meet drummer <a href="http://www.drummerworld.com/drummers/Philly_Joe_Jones.html" target="_blank">Philly Joe Jones </a>for a concert. Although he was only 27 at the time, he had recorded of 350 studio albums. His best friend from high school onward was legendary bassist <a href="http://musicians.allaboutjazz.com/paulchambers">Paul Chambers</a>.</p>\n<p>But, back to Jackie... If you''ve seen Ken Burn''s<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jazz_(TV_series)" target="_blank"> 2000 Jazz documentary</a>, you''ve seen a bit of Jackie as he was a major contributor (along with Wynton Marsalis--who was also the art director and had a co-producer''s credit). Jackie passed away in 2006. There''s a funny story about Jackie McLean''s saxophone and Charlie Parker on the <a name="http://caitlain.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=107:on-this-day-in-jazz-july-20&catid=53:july&Itemid=41"></a>July 20 page.</p>\n<p>Here''s Jackie and his band playing "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cGiUD4t7rr0" target="_blank">Light''s Out</a>":<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cGiUD4t7rr0" target="_blank"><br /><img src="images/tdij/MI0001420115.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Lights Out" (McLean) - 12:57</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Up" (McLean) - 4:47</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Lorraine" (Donald Byrd) - 6:26</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"A Foggy Day" (Gershwin, Gerswhin) - 6:24</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Kerplunk" (Byrd) - 8:51</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Inding" (McLean) - 6:30</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 53, '2014-07-18 18:43:11', 62, '', '2016-08-20 01:09:14', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-07-18 18:43:11', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 6, 0, 13, '', '', 0, 3020, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(107, 'On this day in jazz (July 20)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-july-20', '', '<p>On this day in 1973 <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jackie_McLean" target="_blank">Jackie McLean</a> (and <a href="http://www.dextergordon.com/" target="_blank">Dexter Gordon</a>) recorded a concert live at "Montmartre Jazzhus" in Copenhagen that was later released as an album entitled "The Source".</p>\n<p>Jackie is sort of the "<a href="http://oracleofbacon.org/" target="_blank">6 Degrees of Kevin Bacon</a>" of jazz music,   having played with <a href="http://sonnyrollins.com/" target="_blank">Sonny Rollins</a>,   <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a> (at 19 years of age), <a href="http://mingusmingusmingus.com/" target="_blank">Charles Mingus</a>, <a href="http://www.artblakey.com/" target="_blank">Art Blakey</a>, <a href="http://www.monkzone.com/" target="_blank">Thelonious Monk</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sonny_Clark" target="_blank">Sonny Clark</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lee_Morgan" target="_blank">Lee Morgan</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ornette_Coleman" target="_blank">Ornette Coleman</a>, <a href="http://www.freddiehubbardmusic.com/" target="_blank">Freddie Hubbard</a>, <a href="http://www.bluenote.com/artists/bobby-hutcherson" target="_blank">Bobby Hutcherson</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tony_Williams_(drummer)" target="_blank">Tony Williams</a> and many others. Jackiereceived an American Jazz Masters fellowship from the National Endowment for the Arts in 2001.</p>\n<p>One time,<span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Jackie McLean lent<a href="http://www.cmgww.com/music/parker/home.html" target="_blank"> Charlie Parker</a> his alto sax whileC</span>harlie''s<span style="line-height: 1.3em;"> sax was in hock (pawned to get cash to support his heroin habit). Unfortunately, this sax didn''t have any better luck than Charlie''s original and was also pawned by Charlie. Luckily, the pawn shop owner generously gave it back to Jackie. Although Charlie Parker never repaid the debt, Jackie McLean went back to settle it some years later. This story is covered in one of the episodes of Ken Burn''s Jazz--which can be found on Netflix.</span></p>\n<p>Here''s Jackie and Dexter playing "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Y--rya5fg1I" target="_blank">I Can''t Get Started</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Y--rya5fg1I" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/JackieMcLean.jpg" border="0" height="250" /><img src="images/tdij/513.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 53, '2014-07-14 23:56:24', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:54:36', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-07-20 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 5, 0, 20, '', '', 0, 3629, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(108, 'On this day in jazz (July 21)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-july-21', '', '<p>On this day in 1957,   pianist <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/sonny-clark-mn0000036934">Sonny Clark</a> recorded "Dial ''S'' For Sonny" at the legendary <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Van_Gelder_Studio" target="_blank">Van Gelder Studio</a> in Hackensack, NJ,for <a href="http://www.bluenote.com/" target="_blank">Blue Note Records</a>. This was Clark''s first recording a a band leader. The album also features the talents of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Art_Farmer" target="_blank">Art Farmer</a> and <a href="http://www.hankmobley.net/" target="_blank">Hank Mobley</a>.</p>\n<p>Here''s Sonny playing "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vYLZj9gC3fg">It Could Happen To You</a>". This is a song that singer<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jo_Stafford" target="_blank">Jo Stafford</a> had a top 10 Billboard hit with the song in 1944. It''s also been covered byShirley Bassey, Miles Davis, Chet Baker, Red Garland, Erroll Garner, Bud Powell, Ahmad Jamal, Art Garfunkel, Frank Sinatra, Doris Day, Rosemary Clooney, June Christy, Robert Palmer, Keith Jarrett, Diana Krall, Barry Manilow, Nat King Cole, Dinah Washington, Barbra Streisand, Dave Brubeck, and Andy Williams just to name a few.</p>\n<p>Here''s "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vYLZj9gC3fg" target="_blank">It Could Happen to You</a>" from "Dial ''S'' For Sonny":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vYLZj9gC3fg" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/220px-Sonny_Clark.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing for "Dial ''S'' For Sonny":</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Dial "S" for Sonny" - 7:26</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Bootin'' It" - 5:17</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"It Could Happen to You" (Johnny Burke, James Van Heusen) - 6:59</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Sonny''s Mood" - 8:38</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Shoutin'' on a Riff" - 6:45</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Love Walked In" (George Gershwin, Ira Gershwin) - 5:50</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Bootin'' It" [Alternate Take] - 5:15 Bonus track on CD</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 53, '2014-07-15 00:26:07', 62, '', '2016-08-16 21:37:10', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-07-21 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 6, 0, 19, '', '', 0, 2897, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(109, 'On this day in jazz (July 22)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-july-22', '', '<p>On this day in 1966 John Coltrane''s concert "Live in Japan" was recorded. It consists of two songs,   "P<span style="line-height: 1.3em;">eace On Earth" and "Meditations/Leo".</span></p>\n<p>"Peace on Earth" is a 25-minute ballad that Coltrane wrote to express his empathy and sympathy for the nuclear attacks that Japan experienced during the second world war. Coltrane was in the navy during WWII,   having enlisted on August 6, 1945 (the day the first U.S. atomic bomb was dropped on Japan). He was trained as an apprentice seaman at Sampson Naval Training Station in upstate New York and later served at Pearl Harbor at the Manana Barracks (the largest posting of African-American servicemen in the world).</p>\n<p>Here''s "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pqyznfmsPuk" target="_blank">Peace on Earth</a>" (with some pretty cool <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fractal" target="_blank">fractal graphics</a>):</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pqyznfmsPuk" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/John_Coltrane_1963.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Also appearing on this work:<span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Alice Coltrane on piano, </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Pharoah Sanders on alto and tenor saxophones, bass clarinet, percussion, </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Jimmy Garrison on bass and </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Rashied Ali on drums.</span></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 53, '2014-07-15 00:58:44', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:54:17', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-07-22 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 7, 0, 18, '', '', 0, 2926, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(110, 'On this day in jazz (July 23)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-july-23', '', '<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">On (or around) this day in 1956,   </span><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chet_Baker" target="_blank" style="line-height: 1.3em;">Chet Baker</a><span style="line-height: 1.3em;"> completed recording of "Chet Baker Sings". In 2001,   the album received the Grammy Hall of Fame Award. At first I really didn''t like Chet''s voice, but it''s grown on me over time. Chet was somewhat of a tortured soul. </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Here''s an interesting story about Chet that is documented on Wikipedia:</span></p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">In 1968, Baker was savagely beaten (allegedly while attempting to buy drugs) after a gig in The Trident restaurant in Sausalito, California sustaining severe cuts on the lips and broken front teeth, which ruined his embouchure. He stated in the film Let''s Get Lost (<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QOR3Bg_BNSo" target="_blank">full movie here</a>) that an acquaintance attempted to rob him one night but backed off, only to return the next night with a group of several men who chased him. He entered a car and became surrounded. Instead of rescuing him, the people inside the car pushed him back out onto the street, where the chase by his attackers continued, and subsequently he was beaten to the point that his teeth, never in good condition to begin with, were knocked out, leaving him without the ability to play his horn. He took odd jobs, among them pumping gas. Meanwhile he was fitted for dentures and worked on his embouchure. Three months later he got a gig in New York (<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chet_Baker#Drug_addiction_and_decline" target="_blank">link</a>)</p>\n<p>Here he is singing one of my favorite jazz standards: "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3xpcBx1Gm-c" target="_blank">There Will Never Be Another You</a>":</p>\n<p><img src="images/tdij/The+Best+of+Chet+Baker+Sings+Chet+Baker++The+Best+of+Chet+B.png" border="0" height="250" /><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3xpcBx1Gm-c" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Chet675.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><em>There will be other lips that I may kiss</em></p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><em>But they won''t thrill me like yours used to do</em></p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><em>Yes, I may dream a million dreams</em></p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><em>But how can they come true</em></p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><em>If there will never ever be another you?</em></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 53, '2014-07-15 01:12:30', 62, '', '2016-08-16 21:38:17', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-07-23 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 4, 0, 17, '', '', 0, 2769, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(111, 'On this day in jazz (July 24)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-july-24', '', '<p>While this isn''t history (until later tonight),   on July 24, 2014, the 10th annual<strong>Made in Chicago: World Class Jazz</strong> festival beings at <a href="http://www.cityofchicago.org/city/en/depts/dca/supp_info/millennium_park.html" target="_blank">Millennium Park</a> with a six-concert series featuring Chicagos leading jazz artists. This year, the concerts will focus on Africa, the Middle East and the rhythm and roots of the South. It will also include tribute concerts / retrospectives.</p>\n<p>The series is free and will start tonight with a short set by young, aspiring musicians from Chicago-area high schools as part of the <a href="http://www.jazzinchicago.org/" target="_blank">Jazz Institute of Chicago</a>s Jazz Links Student Ensembles. The series goes<span style="line-height: 1.3em;"> through August 28, 2014 on which day </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">the <a href="http://www.cityofchicago.org/city/en/depts/dca/supp_info/chicago_jazz_festival.html" target="_blank">36th Annual Chicago Jazz Festival</a> will start.</span></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;"><a href="http://www.jazzinchicago.org/presents/made-chicago/made-chicago-world-class-jazz" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Made%20in%20Chicago%20web%20banner.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></span></p>\n<p></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;"><br /></span></p>\n<p><img src="images/tdij/pbh650.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></p>\n<p>Preston Bradley Hall in the Chicago Cultural Center</p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 53, '2014-07-16 19:41:00', 62, '', '2016-08-16 21:38:50', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-07-16 19:41:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 4, 0, 16, '', '', 0, 2951, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(112, 'On this day in jazz (July 25)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-july-25', '', '<p>On this day in 1962,   <a href="http://www.wesmontgomery.com/" target="_blank">Wes Montgomery</a> recorded "<a href="http://www.allmusic.com/album/full-house-mw0000056997" target="_blank">Full House</a>"at Tsubo in Berkeley,   California.The original album was released on <a href="http://www.concordmusicgroup.com/labels/Riverside/" target="_blank">Riverside</a>,   but it has been reissued several times, many that included alternate takes of several tracks. Notable about the recording is that it included the famous Miles Davis rhythm section of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wynton_Kelly" target="_blank">Wynton Kelly</a> (piano), <a href="http://musicians.allaboutjazz.com/paulchambers" target="_blank">Paul Chambers</a> (bass) and <a href="http://www.jimmycobb.net/" target="_blank">Jimmy Cobb</a>(drums). Johnny Griffin plays tenor.</p>\n<p>Here''s Wes and the band performing "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Sxg-oMz8rI4" target="_blank">I''ve Grown Accustomed To Her Face</a>" (which is a song from the 1956 musical "My Fair Lady"--I think Sideshow Bob also parodied it on "The Simpsons"):</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Sxg-oMz8rI4" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Wes_Montgomery_Full_House.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Full House" (Wes Montgomery)  9:14</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I''ve Grown Accustomed to Her Face" (Alan Jay Lerner, Frederick Loewe)  3:18</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Blue ''n'' Boogie" (Dizzy Gillespie, Frank Paparelli)  9:31</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Cariba (Montgomery)"  9:35</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Come Rain or Come Shine" (Johnny Mercer, Harold Arlen)  6:49</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"S.O.S." (Montgomery)  4:57</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Born To Be Blue" (Mel Torm, Robert Wells)  7:23</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 53, '2014-07-16 19:58:07', 62, '', '2016-08-16 21:39:33', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-07-16 19:58:07', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 6, 0, 15, '', '', 0, 3053, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(113, 'On this day in jazz (July 26)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-july-26', '', '<p>On this day in 1968,   <a href="http://www.drummerworld.com/drummers/Max_Roach.html" target="_blank">Max Roach</a> finshed recording the album "Members,   Don''t Get Weary" in New York City. Max was heavily instrumental in shaping bebop of the 1940s,   he often played modal / post-bop and avant-garde later in the 1960s. You''ll see that modal style on "Equipoise," "Libra," "Absolutions." Although the title song includes vocals by Andy Bey, all other songs are sans voice.</p>\n<p>Maxplayed for quite a number of jazz greats before becoming a band leader himself. Here''s a small list of those leaders and the great works he appeared on: <a href="http://www.dizzygillespie.com/" target="_blank">Dizzy Gillespie</a> ("Diz And Getz"), <a href="http://www.cmgww.com/music/parker/home.html" target="_blank">Charlie Parker </a>("Bird On 52nd Street"), <a href="http://www.monkzone.com/" target="_blank">Thelonious Monk</a> ("Brilliant Corners"), <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coleman_Hawkins" target="_blank">Coleman Hawkins</a> ("Body And Soul"), <a href="http://www.budpowelljazz.com/" target="_blank">Bud Powell</a> ("The Amazing Bud Powell"), <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis </a>("Birth of the Cool"), and<a href="http://sonnyrollins.com/" target="_blank">Sonny Rollins</a> ("Saxophone Colossus"). For further listening, check out an early Max Roach on Charlie Parker''s Savoy November 1945 session which can be found on "The Complete Savoy Studio Recordings".</p>\n<p>Regading "Members, Don''t Get Weary", it is one of Max''s better recordings from the late 60s and features Gary Bartz on alto sax, Charles Tolliver on trumpet, Stanley Cowell on piano, and Jymie Merritt on electric bass.</p>\n<p>Here''s "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NzLDHfBTT2k" target="_blank">Libra</a>" from "Members, Don''t Get Weary":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NzLDHfBTT2k" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/maxroach.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Abstrutions" - 3:40</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Libra" (Gary Bartz) - 4:58</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Effi" - 6:15</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Equipoise" - 6:22</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Members, Don''t Git Weary" (Max Roach) - 5:32</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Absolutions" (Jymie Merritt) - 4:39</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 53, '2014-07-17 20:11:25', 62, '', '2016-08-16 21:40:18', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-07-17 18:58:24', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 6, 0, 14, '', '', 0, 2981, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(115, 'On this day in jazz (July 28)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-july-28', '', '<p>On this day in 1953,   Charlie Parker recorded "Now''s The Time" at Fulton Recording Studios in New York City. Appearing with Charlie on this session was the all-star rhythm section of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Al_Haig" target="_blank">Al Haig</a> (piano), <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/percy-heath-mn0000256575/biography" target="_blank">Percy Heath</a> (bass) and <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/max-roach-mn0000396372/biography" target="_blank">Max Roach</a> (drums). Although most jazz experts say the only way to rally experience Charlie is to hear him play live, I submit that this one is very worth listening to.</p>\n<p>Although Charlie only recorded a small number of studio albums in his life, you can find over 200 recordings at <a href="rhapsody.com" target="_blank">rhapsody.com</a> listed as "Main Releases" (and over 500 total releases). Believe me when I say that building a Charlie Parker collection is very challenging. Luckily, there''s a few good starting points. I would start with "<a href="http://www.allmusic.com/album/birds-best-bop-on-verve-mw0000176045" target="_blank">Bird''s Best Bop on Verve</a>". Follow that up with the 10 CD "<a href="http://www.allmusic.com/album/bird-the-complete-charlie-parker-on-verve-mw0000196450" target="_blank">Bird The Complete Charlie Parker On Verve (Box Set)</a>" if you haven''t gotten enough. After that, check out "<a href="http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-complete-savoy-and-dial-master-takes-mw0000228243" target="_blank">The Complete Savoy & Dial Master Takes</a>".</p>\n<div>Here''s the greatest alto saxophonist who has every lived playing "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ryNtmkfeJk4" target="_blank">Now''s The Time</a>":</div>\n<div><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ryNtmkfeJk4" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/MI0002750232.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></div>', '', 1, 8, 0, 53, '2014-07-18 20:14:44', 62, '', '2016-08-16 21:41:21', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-07-18 20:14:44', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 6, 0, 12, '', '', 0, 2659, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(116, 'On this day in jazz (July 29)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-july-29', '', '<p>On this day in 1962,   <a href="http://sonnyrollins.com/" target="_blank">Sonny Rollins</a> completed recording "Our Man In Jazz". It features performances recorded over a four day period. On this album you''ll find two songs that were original compositions by Sonny. The selection below,   "Doxy", first appeared on wax eight years earlier in 1954 when <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a> recorded it for his album "Bags'' Groove". Sonny also played on that Davis recording along with a rhythm section of <a href="http://www.horacesilver.com/" target="_blank">Horace Silver</a> (piano), <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/percy-heath-mn0000256575/biography" target="_blank">Percy Heath</a> (bass) and <a href="http://www.drummerworld.com/drummers/Kenny_Clarke.html" target="_blank">Kenny Clarke</a> (drums).</p>\n<p>Also of note, when Rollins created his own record label, he named it Doxy Records. "Doxy" is a jazz standard and was supposedly written by Sonny in England on a stopover during a European tour. Doxy was the name of a bread-spread that the band was eating in the hotel. I guess they liked it.</p>\n<p>Here''s "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_3mYUY6_H3A" target="_blank">Doxy</a>" from 1962''s "Our Man In Jazz" (just click Meryl Streep''s face...or Sonny''s, whichever):</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_3mYUY6_H3A" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/sonny-meryl2-960x350.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">The above photo is from the 2011 Kennedy Center Honors where Sonny was honored along with </span>singer Barbara Cook, singer and songwriter Neil Diamond, cellist Yo-Yo Ma, and actress Meryl Streep.</p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 53, '2014-07-18 20:45:40', 62, '', '2016-08-16 21:41:51', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-07-29 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 4, 0, 11, '', '', 0, 2632, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(117, 'On this day in jazz (July 30)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-july-30', '', '<p>On this day <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Art_Pepper" target="_blank">Art Pepper</a> recorded "Saturday At The Village Vanguard". This album includes a 16 minute version of "Cherokee" that is well worth the listen. In fact,   listen the whole thing--it received 4.5 starts from All Music and peaked at #41 on the Billboard charts when it was first released in 1982.</p>\n<p>Art was always well regarded in jazz circles and even finished second to Charlie Parker in a Best Alto Saxophonist poll in Down Beat magazine. "Art Pepper Meets the Rhythm Section" and "Art Pepper + Eleven" are probably the two albums of Art''s that I listen to the most.</p>\n<p>Like many of his contemporaries, Art struggled with heroin addiction and was in and out of prison several times (four times, I think) including two stints at San Quentin.</p>\n<p>Here''s Art playing "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mTx7xiVcmc8" target="_blank">Cherokee</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mTx7xiVcmc8" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/pepper2.png" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">You Go to My Head 11:35</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">The Trip 12:25</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Cherokee 15:57</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">For Freddie 10:35</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 53, '2014-07-20 18:22:24', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:53:14', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-07-30 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 7, 0, 10, 'This day in jazz, July 31, Art Pepper', 'This day in jazz', 0, 2500, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(118, 'On this day in jazz (July 31)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-july-31', '', '<p>On this day in 1956,   Chet Baker finished recording tracks that would later become the album "Chet Baker & Crew". <span style="line-height: 1.3em;">These sessions were recorded soon after an extended European tour and they were held each day from July 23rd until July 31st. From this tremendously prolific set of recordings the following albums were produced: "The Route", "Chet Baker Sings", "Chet Baker Quintet at the Forum" (aka "Young Chet"), and the aforementioned "Chet Baker & Crew". The crew are: Chet on trumpet, <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/phil-urso-mn0000285461/biography" target="_blank">Phil Urso</a> on tenor sax, and a rhythm section of <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/bobby-timmons-mn0000765435/biography" target="_blank">Bobby Timmons</a> on piano, Jimmy Bond playing bass, and Peter Littman on the drums.</span></p>\n<p>You can also find Chet on the July 23rd page of this blog.</p>\n<p>Here''s Chet (and crew) playing "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7s8mU2NUk0g" target="_blank">To Mickey''s Memory</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7s8mU2NUk0g" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Chet+Baker++Crew.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"To Mickey''s Memory" (Harvey Leonard) - 5:12</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Slightly Above Moderate" (Bob Zieff) - 6:59</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Halema" (Phil Urso) - 3:51</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Revelation" (Gerry Mulligan) - 3:58</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Something For Liza" (Al Cohn) - 4:05</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Lucius Lu" (Urso) - 5:34</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Worryin'' the Life Out of Me" (Miff Mole, Bob Russell, Frank Signorelli) - 2:59</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Medium Rock" (Zieff) - 5:30</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 53, '2014-07-20 18:44:07', 62, '', '2016-08-16 21:43:12', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-07-31 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 6, 0, 9, 'This day in jazz, August 10, Chet Baker', 'This day in jazz', 0, 3015, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(119, 'On this day in jazz (August 01)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-august-01', '', '<p>On this day in 1939,   <a href="http://glennmillerorchestra.com/" target="_blank">Glenn Miller</a> recorded "In the Mood" at the Victor Studios in New York City. Although the song is much older,   it has since become synonymous with the Big Band Era of the 1940s and World War II. It was a hit not only in 1940 but also in 1943. The song is actually one of the first "mash-ups", consisting of riffs from three other songs: Tar Paper Stomp, Hot and Anxious, and Theres a Rhythm.</p>\n<p>Here''s Glenn Miller with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=c2aqHGaSxRI" target="_blank">In the Mood</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=c2aqHGaSxRI" target="_blank"><img src="http://broeder10.files.wordpress.com/2014/05/glenn-miller-military-photo.jpg" border="0" width="284" height="360" /></a></p>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 54, '2014-07-25 13:44:12', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:39:32', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-08-01 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 5, 0, 31, 'This day in jazz, August 1, Glenn Miller', 'This day in jazz', 0, 2147, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(120, 'On this day in jazz (August 02)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-august-02', '', '<p style="text-align: justify;">On this day in 1954,   <a href="http://cliffordbrown.net/" target="_blank">Clifford Brown</a> and <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/max-roach-mn0000396372/biography" target="_blank">Max Roach</a> began recording "Clifford Brown & Max Roach". The album was well received and includes two tracks that have become jazz standards ("Daahoud" and "Joy Spring")." Another track,   "Delilah", was selected by the Village Voice as the outstanding jazz track of 1954. The album is part the Grammy Hall of Fame and is #34 in "Jazz: A Critic''s Guide to the 100 Most Important Recordings". Along with Clifford and Max, <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/george-morrow-mn0000654031/biography" target="_blank">George Morrow</a> (bass), <a href="http://www.haroldland.net/" target="_blank">Harold Land</a> (tenor sax) and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richie_Powell" target="_blank">Richie Powell</a> (drums) also appear on this work.</p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Joy Spring", mentioned above, was written by Clifford for his wife, whom he referred to as "Joy Spring". An interesting story about the couple: she was introduced to Clifford (by Max) while she was working on a student thesis that "jazz was inferior to her field of classical music". Clifford and her somehow got past this and were married. </span></p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Unlike many of his contemporaries, Brown did not use drugs and was somewhat </span>abstemious<span style="line-height: 1.3em;"> with alcohol. Other jazz </span>musicians<span style="line-height: 1.3em;"> of the time found him a great influence during their drug recovery. It seems that many were under the belief that you had to use drugs to find that artistic </span>breakthrough<span style="line-height: 1.3em;">. </span></p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Clifford Brown died in a fatal automobile accident in 1956. Brown and Richie Powell were being driven to Chicago late one night when Powell''s wife lost control of the car during a torrential rainstorm on the Pennsylvania Turnpike, and all three lost their lives. A very tragic story and a great loss for jazz music. In memory of Clifford, Benny Golson wrote "I Remember Clifford", which has also become a jazz standard.</p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Brown''s influence lives on through the Clifford Brown Jazz Foundation, a 501(c)(3) organization founded by his widow, LaRue Brown Watson. The mission of the foundation is to inspire a love for jazz among young people. The Foundation is currently directed by Brown''s grandson, Clifford Brown III, who is a respected Bay Area trumpeter and music producer.</p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Here''s Clifford with Max Roach with "<a href="http://lh6.ggpht.com/-k_9ekSRIuJM/SCxjZ-T-RaI/AAAAAAAABjY/dXr5wNcvo7I/CliffordBrown020.jpg" target="_blank">Joy Spring</a>".</p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=g8kvsLBoGWM" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/CliffordBrown020.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Delilah" (Victor Young)  8:06</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Parisian Thoroughfare" (Bud Powell)  7:19</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Daahoud"  4:05</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Joy Spring"  6:50</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Jordu" (Duke Jordan)  7:50</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Blues Walk" (Chris Woods)  6:47</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"What Am I Here For?" (Duke Ellington, Frankie Laine)  3:11</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 54, '2014-07-25 14:08:40', 62, '', '2017-04-07 18:04:55', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-08-02 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 9, 0, 30, 'This day in jazz, August 2, Clifford Brown, Max Roach', 'This day in jazz', 0, 2432, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(293, 'On this day in jazz (January 18)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-january-18', '', '<p>On this day in 1955,   trumpeter <a href="http://cliffordbrown.net/" target="_blank">Clifford Brown</a> began recording Clifford Brown with Strings. The personnel backing Clifford on this album were Richie Powell on piano,   George Morrow on bass,   Barry Galbraith on guitar and, as always, <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/max-roach-mn0000396372/biography" target="_blank">Max Roach</a> on drums.<span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Neal Hefti arranged and conducted the music. While more laid back listeners may really enjoy this album, I''m not as quite drawn to these arrangements as am I to his other works with Max Roach.</span></p>\n<p>Unfortunately, Clifford would only survive this recording for 17 months, when a car accident would cut short a brilliant four year career. See my <a href="index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=120:on-this-day-in-jazz-august-02&catid=54:august&Itemid=41" target="_self">August 2nd page</a> where I talk more about Clifford.</p>\n<p>Here''s Clifford with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RG6sbJhtJEs" target="_blank">Laura</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RG6sbJhtJEs" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/CliffordBrown020.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Yesterdays" (Otto Harbach, Jerome Kern)  2:59</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Laura" (Johnny Mercer, David Raksin)  3:26</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"What''s New?" (Johnny Burke, Bob Haggart)  3:23</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Blue Moon" (Lorenz Hart, Richard Rodgers)  3:13</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Can''t Help Lovin'' Dat Man" (Oscar Hammerstein II, Kern)  3:43</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Embraceable You" (George Gershwin, Ira Gershwin)  3:00</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Willow Weep for Me" (Ann Ronell)  3:24</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Memories of You" (Eubie Blake, Andy Razaf)  3:31</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Smoke Gets in Your Eyes" (Harbach, Kern)  3:14</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Portrait of Jenny" (Irving Burgie, Jessie Mae Robinson)  3:24</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Where or When" (Hart, Rodgers)  3:26</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Stardust" (Hoagy Carmichael, Mitchell Parish)  3:23 </span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 59, '2015-01-02 21:10:11', 62, '', '2016-08-16 21:57:02', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-01-18 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 15, 'jazz, Clifford Brown', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1685, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(121, 'On this day in jazz (August 03)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-august-03', '', '<p>On this day in 1964,   <a href="http://www.wayneshorter.com/" target="_blank">Wayne Shorter</a> recorded "JuJu". "Juju" is different from many of Wayne''s other works--you can really sense the heavy influence of <a href="http://www.johncoltrane.com/" target="_blank">John Coltrane</a> on Wayne''s playing on this one. Joining Wayne on this album is the rhythm section of <a href="http://mccoytyner.com/" target="_blank">McCoy Tyner</a> (piano), <a href="http://sculpturedsounds.com/" target="_blank">Reggie Workman</a> (bass) and<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elvin_Jones" target="_blank" style="line-height: 1.3em;">Elvin Jones</a><span style="line-height: 1.3em;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;"> (drums)--</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">this is the same rhythm section that played with Coltrane on the 1961 Africa/Brass recording. Each piece has a limited number of scales and is very modal in nature. All compositions on the album were written by Wayne. </span></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Here''s Wayne Shorter with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=k0q8mGUHJVQ" target="_blank">Yes or No</a>":</span></p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=k0q8mGUHJVQ" target="_blank"><img src="http://music.ckut.ca/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/jazz_csg_041_wayne_shorter.jpg" border="0" width="256" height="192" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"JuJu" 8:30</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Deluge" 6:49</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"House of Jade" 6:49</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Mahjong" 7:39":</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Yes or No" 6.34</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Twelve More Bars to Go" 5:26</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 54, '2014-07-25 17:03:18', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:40:19', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-08-03 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 5, 0, 29, 'This day in jazz, August 3, Wayne Shorter', 'This day in jazz', 0, 2346, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(122, 'On this day in jazz (August 05)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-july-04', '', '<p>On this day in 1958,   <a href="http://www.thecountbasieorchestra.com/" target="_blank">Count Basie</a> recorded "Jazz in the Round" with his orchestra. If you are not familiar with the Count,  he was primarily known as a jazz pianist and bandleader.Basie formed his jazz orchestra in 1935 and a year later went to Chicago for their first recording. He continued to lead the group for almost 50 years while innovating the use of two "split" tenor saxophones and placing an emphasis on the rhythm section. Some of the notable musicians who played under his direction were tenor saxophonist Lester Young,   the guitarist Freddie Green, trumpeter Buck Clayton and singer Joe Williams.</p>\n<p>Basie''s best known songs are "One O''Clock Jump," and "April In Paris" (which can be seen in Mel Brooks'' irreverent <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=N2xYaL_Mheg" target="_blank">Blazing Saddles</a> movie)</p>\n<p>Here''s a non-Mel Brooks version of "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wCmcoZktZG4" target="_blank">April In Paris</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wCmcoZktZG4" target="_blank"><img src="http://www.latimes.com/includes/projects/hollywood/portraits/count_basie.jpg" border="0" width="280" height="350" /></a></p>\n<p>There''s also another good jazz scene in Blazing Saddles in which Cleavon Little sings a hilarious version of "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=k0jDUV4fu_0">I Get A Kick Out of You</a>". If you look it up on youtube, be warned there is some harsh language in the scene.</p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 54, '2014-07-25 17:39:55', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:40:40', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-08-05 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 10, 0, 27, 'This day in jazz, August 4, Count Basie', 'This day in jazz', 0, 19311, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(123, 'On this day in jazz (August 04)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-august-04', '', '<p>On this day in 1901,   Louis Armstrong was born in,   where else,   NOLA. Although he was a virtuoso on trumpet, and probably the first renowned jazz soloist, he''s very popular in due to his stage presence and unique voice. If you''re looking for some of his music, try and find his "Hot Fives" and "Hot Sevens''" recordings.</p>\n<p>Here''s his most famous song, "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2nGKqH26xlg" target="_blank">What a Wonderful World</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2nGKqH26xlg" target="_blank"><img src="http://lifeinthetwenties.wikispaces.com/file/view/hot_five.jpg/297785176/410x314/hot_five.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="201" /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 54, '2014-07-27 16:46:10', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:51:44', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-08-04 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 6, 0, 28, 'This day in jazz, August 4, Louis Armstrong', 'This day in jazz', 0, 2223, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(124, 'On this day in jazz (August 06)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-august-06', '', '<p>On this day in 1954,   Clifford Brown and Max Roach finished recording of the studio album, "Brown and Roach, Incorporated" at Capitol Studios in Los Angeles.<span style="line-height: 1.3em; text-align: justify;">Along with Clifford and Max, </span><a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/george-morrow-mn0000654031/biography" target="_blank" style="line-height: 1.3em; text-align: justify;">George Morrow</a><span style="line-height: 1.3em; text-align: justify;"> (bass), </span><a href="http://www.haroldland.net/" target="_blank" style="line-height: 1.3em; text-align: justify;">Harold Land</a><span style="line-height: 1.3em; text-align: justify;"> (tenor sax) and </span><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richie_Powell" target="_blank" style="line-height: 1.3em; text-align: justify;">Richie Powell</a><span style="line-height: 1.3em; text-align: justify;"> (drums) also appear on this work. More on Clifford and the band can be found on the August 02 page on this site. </span></p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Here''s "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VcQmn5d9-b4" target="_blank">Stompin'' at the Savoy</a>":</p>\n<p><span style="text-align: justify;"><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VcQmn5d9-b4" target="_blank"><img src="https://jazzinphoto.files.wordpress.com/2011/12/clifford-brown-max-roach-by-herman-leonard.jpg" border="0" width="212" height="262" /></a><br /></span></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Sweet Clifford" (Clifford Brown) - 6:41</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I Don''t Stand a Ghost of a Chance with You" (Bing Crosby, Ned Washington, Victor Young) - 7:19</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Stompin'' at the Savoy" (Benny Goodman, Andy Razaf, Edgar Sampson Chick Webb) - 6:23</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I''ll String Along with You" (Al Dubin, Harry Warren) - 4:09</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Mildama" (Max Roach) - 4:30</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Darn That Dream" (Eddie DeLange, Jimmy Van Heusen) - 4:02</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I Get a Kick out of You" (Cole Porter) - 7:36</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 54, '2014-07-27 16:54:21', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:41:15', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-08-06 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 8, 0, 26, 'This day in jazz, August 6, Clifford Brown, Max Roach', 'This day in jazz', 0, 2147, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(125, 'On this day in jazz (August 07)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-august-07', '', '<p>On this day in 1958,   <a href="http://www.monkzone.com/" target="_blank">Thelonious Monk</a> recorded "Thelonious In Action". The concert was recorded live at The Five Spot. Joining Monk on this album are <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/johnny-griffin-mn0000213510/biography" target="_blank">Johnny Griffin </a>(saxophone),   <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/ahmed-abdul-malik-mn0000602006/biography" target="_blank">Ahmed Abdul-Malik</a> (bass), and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roy_Haynes" target="_blank">Roy Haynes</a> (drums). Unfortunately, the group did not stay together long, but the album ''Misterioso" also contains songs from this same date.</p>\n<p>Here'' s Monk, with his composition "<a href="ttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6Di_mswqhLU" target="_blank">Rhythm-A-Ning</a>":</p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;"><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6Di_mswqhLU" target="_blank"><img src="http://jazzalljazz.it/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/JazzAllJazz_Thelonious_Monk3.jpg?w=192&h=193" border="0" width="220" height="220" /></a></span></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Light Blue" - 5:14</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Coming on the Hudson" - 5:24</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Rhythm-A-Ning" - 9:25</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Epistrophy (Theme)" - 1:05</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Blue Monk" - 8:31</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Evidence" - 8:48</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Epistrophy (Theme)" - 1:05</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 54, '2014-07-27 17:09:07', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:41:32', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-08-07 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 5, 0, 25, 'This day in jazz, August 7, Thelonious Monk', 'This day in jazz', 0, 2042, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(126, 'On this day in jazz (August 08)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-august-08', '', '<p>On this day in 1956,   Lester Young (The Pres),   recorded "Live at Bridland'' live at Bridland. Birdland is still around today,   if you are in NYC, check it out. Lester has several "Live at Birdland'' recordings. A 2007 CD packaged several of these recordings together. On this specific date, the following songs were played:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Lullabye of Birdland/Lester Leaps In</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Polka Dots & Moonbeams</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Up N Adam</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">In a Little Spanish Town</span></li>\n</ol>\n<div>Here''s The Pres with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=euAreOZqHO8" target="_blank">Lester Leaps In</a>":</div>\n<div><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=euAreOZqHO8" target="_blank"><img src="http://marcmyers.typepad.com/.a/6a00e008dca1f08834019aff0adeda970d-500wi" border="0" width="301" height="301" /></a></div>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 54, '2014-07-27 17:26:15', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:41:47', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-08-08 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 5, 0, 24, 'This day in jazz, August 8, Lester Young', 'This day in jazz', 0, 2162, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(127, 'On this day in jazz (August 09)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-august-09', '', '<p>On this day in 1948,   <a href="http://www.budpowelljazz.com/" target="_blank">Bud Powell</a> recorded many of the songs that would later be issued on "The Amazing Bud Powell". Bud is at his peak on these recordings, and is joined by<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fats_Navarro" target="_blank">Fats Navarro</a> on trumpet, <a href="http://sonnyrollins.com/">Sonny Rollins</a> on tenor sax, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tommy_Potter" target="_blank">Tommy Potter</a> on bass, and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roy_Haynes" target="_blank">Roy Haynes</a> on drums. If possible, get the Rudy Van Gelder version of this recording. Bud was extremely important in the development of bebop. Although he was trained in classic piano from age 5, his father played in the Stride style and Bud quickly developed jazz tastes, even becoming a neighborhood legend by age 10.</p>\n<p>Unfortunately, in November 1947, Bud was involved in an altercation at a Harlem nightclub in which he was struck in the eye with a bottle. At the hospital he was incoherent and was sent to Bellevue and subsequently to Creedmore State Hospital for 11 months where he was subjected to electroconvulsive therapy. The story is covered in Ken Burns'' Jazz documentary.</p>\n<p>Despite his tough life and repeated stints in mental hospitals, he was a true genius. Bill Evans, one of the greatest jazz pianists in the 50s and 60s, said this of Bud:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">If I had to choose one single musician for his artistic integrity, for the incomparable originality of his creation and the grandeur of his work, it would be Bud Powell. He was in a class by himself.</p>\n<p>Here''s "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=msaSi5dZBLo" target="_blank">Bouncing With Bud</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=msaSi5dZBLo" target="_blank"><img src="http://www.budpowelljazz.com/img/core/bud_index_at_piano.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="310" /></a></p>\n<p></p>\n<p></p>\n<p></p>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 54, '2014-07-27 17:41:03', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:42:29', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-08-09 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 6, 0, 23, 'This day in jazz, August 9, Bud Powell', 'This day in jazz', 0, 2221, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(128, 'On this day in jazz (August 10)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-august-10', '', '<p>On this day in 1964,   <a href="http://www.archieshepp.net/" target="_blank">Archie Shepp</a> recorded "Four for Trane". This album is the first one that Archie recorded as a band leader. It has been selected as part the "Core Collection" by "The Penguin Guide to Jazz" and was given a 5-star rating by <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/album/four-for-trane-mw0000197826" target="_blank">Allmusic</a>. As suggested by the title, the album features four <a href="http://www.johncoltrane.com/" target="_blank">John Coltrane</a> songs which have been rearranged by Archie and Roswell Budd. The major importance of the album is that it demonstrates how John''s revolutionary sound from the late 50s (literally, the last month of 1959) and early 60s could sound under different arrangements.</p>\n<p>Archie was born in 1937 and is still active today (2014). He was born in Fort Lauderdale, FL, but raised from an early age in Philadelphia, PA. Although he studied piano, flute and alto sax, he settled on tenor sax as his instrument of choice. He also studied drama at Goddard College from 1955 to 1959 but quickly decided to make a career in music. In 1971 he started a 30-year tenure as music professor at the University of Massachusetts Amhurst. His latest recording was from 2011 entitled "Wo!man".</p>\n<p>Here''s Archie and band playing "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SzxbPtkhzWA" target="_blank">Cousin Mary</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SzxbPtkhzWA" target="_blank"><img src="http://www.archieshepp.net/public/img/pg/03.jpg" border="0" width="215" height="208" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Syeeda''s Song Flute"  8:30</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Mr. Syms"  7:41</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Cousin Mary"  7:14</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Naima"  7:09</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Rufus (Swung His Face At Last To The Wind, Then His Neck Snapped)" (Shepp)  6:24</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 54, '2014-07-31 11:19:02', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:43:05', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-08-10 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 22, 'Archie Shepp, John Coltrane', 'This day in jazz, August 10', 0, 2076, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(129, 'On this day in jazz (August 11)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-august-11', '', '<p>On this day in 1980,   tenor saxophonist <a href="http://www.dextergordon.com/" target="_blank">Dexter Gordon</a> began recording Gotham City (it was completed a day later). This recording features a great rhythm section consisting of <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/cedar-walton-mn0000741325/biography" target="_blank">Cedar Walton</a> on piano, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Percy_Heath" target="_blank">Percy Heath</a> on bass and the great Art Blakey on drums. Trumpeter Woody Shaw and guitarist George Benson also make guest appearances. It''s a rather short recording with only four songs, but at 37 minutes across the four, you get some great solos.</p>\n<p>Here''s Dexter with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yLcL79e9RKg" target="_blank">Gotham City</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yLcL79e9RKg" target="_blank"><img src="http://www.canarypromo.com/sites/default/files/wgordd18.jpg" border="0" width="229" height="225" /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 54, '2014-08-03 14:53:28', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:43:44', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-08-11 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 21, 'This day in Jazz, Dexter Gordon', 'This day in jazz', 0, 2187, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(130, 'On this day in jazz (August 12)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-august-12', '', '<p>On this day in 1959,   <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/wynton-kelly-mn0000684253/biography" target="_blank">Wynton Kelly</a> recorded "Kelly Great". Appearing with Wynton on this work are all jazz legends, too: <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lee_Morgan" target="_blank">Lee Morgan</a> on trumpet, <a href="http://www.wayneshorter.com/" target="_blank">Wayne Shorter</a> on tenor sax, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Chambers" target="_blank">Paul Chambers</a> on bass and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philly_Joe_Jones">Philly Joe Jones</a> on drums. Unlike <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a>'' "Kind of Blue" which was recorded earlier in the year with several of the same musicians, this album is definitely in the hard bop genre.</p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Wynton was American jazz pianist of Jamaican descent who grew up in Brooklyn and is regarded as one the best pianists in jazz. Somewhat of a child prodigy, he made his first professional recording at 12 years of age. It took him a whopping four years, though, to score his first #1 hit (<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hal_Singer" target="_blank">Hal Singer''s</a> "Cornbread"). He started recording as a leader only three years later while also regularly accompanying singer <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dinah_Washington" target="_blank">Dinah Washington</a>. He was also a member of <a href="http://www.dizzygillespie.com/" target="_blank">Dizzy Gillespie''s</a> band and also played with <a href="http://mingusmingusmingus.com/" target="_blank">Charles Mingus</a>.</span></p>\n<p>Here''s Wynton with "<a href="http://iisaphd.subsonic.org/share/KIeiK" target="_blank">June Night</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="http://iisaphd.subsonic.org/share/KIeiK" target="_blank"><img src="http://www.soundstagedirect.com/media/wynton_kelly_kelly_great.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Wrinkles (Wynton Kelly)  8:05</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Mama "G"" (Wayne Shorter)  7:42</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">June Night" (Abel Baer, Cliff Friend)  8:23</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">What I Know" (Lee Morgan)  8:01</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Sydney" (Shorter)  3:55</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 54, '2014-08-03 15:20:36', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:44:08', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-08-12 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 5, 0, 20, '', '', 0, 2306, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(131, 'On this day in jazz (August 13)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-august-13', '', '<p>On this day in 1957,   <a href="http://www.gerrymulligan.com/" target="_blank">Gerry Mulligan</a> and <a href="http://www.monkzone.com/">Thelonious Monk</a> completed recording "Mulligan Meets Monk". Typically,   you wouldn''t think of the mellow west coast style of Mulligan blending well with the driving east coast style of Monk. However,   on this work, it is the contrast between their styles that makes it so interesting. Assisting with the recording were Wilbur Ware on bass Shadow Wilson on drums.</p>\n<p>The original release of the album featured four songs written by Monk and one by Mulligan ("Decidedly") and one cover "Sweet and Lovely". I prefer the Monk tunes, and three of the four are pretty much standards: "''round Midnight", "Rhythm-a-Ning" and the song below. "I Mean You" which Monk wrote with <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coleman_Hawkins" target="_blank">Coleman Hawkins</a> isn''t too bad, either.</p>\n<p>Here''s Gerry and Thelonious with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=X7pNrV4cAgs" target="_blank">Straight, No Chaser</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=X7pNrV4cAgs" target="_blank"><img src="http://eil.com/images/main/Gerry+Mulligan+-+''Round+Midnight+-+DOUBLE+LP-532854.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="252" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"''Round Midnight"  8:29</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Rhythm-a-Ning"  5:19</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Sweet and Lovely"  7:17</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Decidedly"5:54</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Straight, No Chaser"  7:00</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I Mean You"  6:53</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 54, '2014-08-03 15:56:14', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:44:25', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-08-13 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 2, 0, 19, '', '', 0, 2006, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(132, 'On this day in jazz (August 14)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-august-14', '', '<p>On this day in 1947,   <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a> recorded his first session on Savoy as leader with Charlie Parker''s band. The session wasn''t released until 1990,   but also includes Miles'' first recording session where he backs singer Rubberlegs Wilson. That session was recorded on April 24, 1945 and comprises the final eight songs on the album. Savoy titled the compilation, "First Miles".</p>\n<p>Although the album never got much praise, it is interesting historically. On the tracks with Rubberlegs, Miles only plays in ensemble mode, but on the one''s with Parker''s band, he plays strongly. You''ll notice all the songs are quite short--that''s because the LP had not been created yet (it came a year later in 1948), so all songs had to fit on a <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gramophone_record" target="_blank">78 rpm record</a> which limited songs to about three and a half minutes.</p>\n<p>Here''s Miles with "<a href="http://iisaphd.subsonic.org/share/ApOQ" target="_blank">Half Nelson</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="http://iisaphd.subsonic.org/share/ApOQ" target="_blank"><img src="http://www.israbox.com/uploads/posts/2012-07/1342286763_cover1fi.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Milestones" [First Take/Master Take 2] [First Take] (Davis)  2:45</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Mile Stone" [Take 3] [Take 3] (Davis)  2:47</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Little Willie Leaps" [First Take 1/Alt. Take 2] [First Take 1] (Davis)  3:57</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Little Willie Leaps" [Master Take 3] [Master Take 3] (Davis)  2:53</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Half Nelson" [Alt. Take 1] [Alternate Take 1] (Davis)  2:53</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Half Nelson" [Master Take 2] [Master Take 2] (Davis)  2:47</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Sippin'' At Bells" [First Take1/Master Take 2] [First Take 1] (Davis)  3:18</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Sippin'' At Bells" [First Take3/Alt. Take 4] [First Take 3] (Davis)  2:36</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"That''s the Stuff You Gotta Watch" [Alt. Take 1] [Alternate Take 1] (Battles, Meredith, Ram, Sissle)  3:05</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"That''s the Stuff You Gotta Watch" [Alt. Take 2] [Alternate Take 2] (Battles, Meredith, Ram, Sissle)  3:13</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"That''s the Stuff You Gotta Watch" [Master Take 3] [Master Take] (Battles, Meredith, Ram, Sissle)  3:17</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Pointless Mama Blues" (Reig, Williams)  2:51</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Deep Sea Blues" (Reig, Williams)  3:16</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Bring It On Home" [First and second Take] [First and second Take] (Reig, Williams)  3:06</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Bring It On Home" [Master Take 3] [Master Take 3] (Reig, Williams)  2:48</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Now''s The Time"[7] [Master Take 4] [Master Take 4] (Charlie, Parker)  3:15</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 54, '2014-08-03 16:42:27', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:44:40', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-08-14 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 3, 0, 18, '', '', 0, 1926, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(133, 'On this day in jazz (August 15)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-august-15', '', '<p>On this day in 1958,   <a href="http://moseallison.com/" target="_blank">Mose Allison</a> recorded "Creek Bank" at Rudy Van Gelder''s studio in Hackensack,   NJ. Mose was born in Tippo,   MS on his grandfather''s farm. He started playing piano at age five and occasionally plays the trumpet. He attended the University of Mississippi and LSU, where he earned a degree in English. He was in the army for two years before moving to New York City to start his professional career. Early in his career, Mose played with jazz greats such as <a href="http://www.stangetz.net/" target="_blank">Stan Getz</a>, <a href="http://www.gerrymulligan.com/" target="_blank">Gerry Mulligan</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Al_Cohn" target="_blank">Al Cohn</a> and <a href="http://www.zootsims.org/">Zoot Sims </a>before forming his own trio.</p>\n<p>Mose is a very hard person to categorize. Although I consider him jazz, others consider him blues. In fact, <a href="http://www.npr.org/ramfiles/jazz/jp.mose4.ram" target="_blank">"Jet" magazine tried to interview him</a>, thinking he was a black blues musician. Singer <a href="http://www.vanmorrison.com/index.html" target="_blank">Van Morrison</a> considers him to be one of the great songwriters of our time and on January 14, 2013, he was honored as a <a href="http://arts.gov/art-works/2013/click-click-photos-2013-nea-jazz-masters-awards" target="_blank">Jazz Master by the National Endowment for the Arts</a> which is the nation''s highest honor in jazz.</p>\n<p>Mose is probably as well-known for his comical lyrics as for his outstanding blusey jazz piano. Check out <a href="http://iisaphd.subsonic.org/share/Nijjm" target="_blank">other songs</a> by him such as "Parchman Farm" ("I''m gonna be here for the rest of my life / And all I did was shoot my wife"), "Foolkiller" ("Now, if you never been a fool / Then you don''t have to worry / But if you have / You better get in a hurry / And just to be on the safe side / Get yourself a little place to hide") or "One of these Days" ("One of these days I''ve got to get things straight / I''m gonna stop hangin'' out with jail bait").</p>\n<p>Here''s Mose with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Z5kVoTbDcns">Seventh Son</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Z5kVoTbDcns" target="_blank"><img src="http://marcmyers.typepad.com/.a/6a00e008dca1f088340133f4012958970b-350wi" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><a style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Seventh Son" (Willie Dixon) - 2:36</a></li>\n<li><a style="line-height: 1.3em;">"If I Didn''t Care" (Jack Lawrence) - 4:25</a></li>\n<li><a style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Cabin in the Sky" (Vernon Duke, John La Touche) - 4:04</a></li>\n<li><a style="line-height: 1.3em;">"If You Live" - 2:31</a></li>\n<li><a style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Yardbird Suite" (Charlie Parker) - 3:21</a></li>\n<li><a style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Creek Bank" - 4:34</a></li>\n<li><a style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Moon and Cypress" - 4:00</a></li>\n<li><a style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Mule" - 3:51</a></li>\n<li><a style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Dinner on the Ground" - 3:14</a></li>\n<li><a style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Prelude to a Kiss" (Duke Ellington, Irving Gordon, Irving Mills) - 4:12</a></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 54, '2014-08-03 17:17:36', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:45:08', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-08-15 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 4, 0, 17, '', '', 0, 2189, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(134, 'On this day in jazz (August 16)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-august-16', '', '<p>On this day in 1929,   pianist <a href="http://www.billevanswebpages.com/" target="_blank">Bill Evans</a> was born in Plainfield,   NJ. I first heard Bill play on Miles Davis'' "Kind of Blue" (the same way I was introduced to John Coltrane and Cannonball Adderley). Unfortunately Bill passed away in 1980,   but had a quite prolific career in the 60s and 70s.</p>\n<p>I''m highlighting Bill today instead of John Coltrane (who recorded some of "Lush Life" and "The Last Trane" on this day in 1957) mainly because my wife likes his music so much. In honor of him and her, I''ve decided to share my wife''s favorite Bill Evans song "<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peace_Piece" target="_blank">Peace Piece</a>".</p>\n<p>Peace piece is performed in ostinato (if you''re familiar with Ravel''s "Bolero", you''re familiar with ostinato--and oh, by the way, if you''ve never seen<a href="http://www.zbigvision.com/" target="_blank">Zbigniew Rybczy?ski''s</a> "Stairway to Lenin" (which features "Bolero"), make sure to watch it ASAP--it can be found at amazon.com).</p>\n<p>Anyway, back to "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Nv2GgV34qIg" target="_blank">Peace Piece</a>". It can be found on ''Everybody Digs Bill Evans":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Nv2GgV34qIg" target="_blank"><img src="http://mediad.publicbroadcasting.net/p/kcur/files/201309/Bill_Evans.jpg" border="0" width="200" height="200" /></a></p>\n<p></p>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 54, '2014-08-03 18:46:00', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:45:22', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-08-16 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 3, 0, 16, '', '', 0, 2018, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(135, 'On this day in jazz (August 17)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-august-17', '', '<p>On this day in 1959,   <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a> <span style="text-decoration: underline;"><em>released</em></span> his seminal work, "Kind of Blue". The album remains one of my favorites and was the first jazz album that I ever listened to (as well as the first SACD format disc I ever bought. The album was recorded in two sessions March 2 and April 22 of the same year of its release. An all-star cast accompanies Miles: <a href="http://www.johncoltrane.com/" target="_blank">John Coltrane</a> and <a href="http://www.cannonball-adderley.com/" target="_blank">Cannonball Adderley</a> on saxophone and the rhythm section of <a href="http://www.billevanswebpages.com/" target="_blank">Bill Evans</a> on piano, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Chambers">Paul Chambers </a> on bass and <a href="http://www.jimmycobb.net" target="_blank">Jimmy Cobb</a> on drums on all songs but "Freddie Freeloader". The rhythm section on "FF" features <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/wynton-kelly-mn0000684253/biography" target="_blank">Wynton Kelly</a> <span style="line-height: 1.3em;">on the piano. </span></p>\n<p>The album is certified quadruple platinum (4,000,000+ in sales) and was selected by the Library of Congress to be added to the National Recording Registry. Rolling Stone ranks the album #12 on its list of the 500 greatest albums of all time. There''s a <a href="http://www.amazon.com/Kind-Blue-Making-Miles-Masterpiece/dp/0306815583" target="_blank">book</a> dedicated to the album with some great photographs. If you are new to jazz, pick it up.</p>\n<p>It''s not possible for me to pick a favorite song, so here''s a <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kbxtYqA6ypM" target="_blank">link</a> to the entire album:</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kbxtYqA6ypM" target="_blank"><img src="https://jazzinphoto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/dennis-stockmagnum-photos-1958-miles-davisleft-cannonball-adderley-and-john-coltrane-right.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"So What" </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Miles Davis</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">9:22</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Freddie Freeloader" </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Miles Davis</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">9:46</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Blue in Green" </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Miles Davis, Bill Evans</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">5:37</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"All Blues" </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Miles Davis</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">11:33</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Flamenco Sketches" Miles Davis, Bill Evans</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">9:26</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 54, '2014-08-08 18:01:51', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:45:43', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-08-17 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 6, 0, 15, 'jazz, miles davis, bill evans, cannonball adderley, john coltrane, paul chambers, jimmy cobb, wynton kelly', 'On this day in jazz', 0, 1890, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(136, 'On this day in jazz (August 18)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-august-18', '', '<p>On this day in 1959,   <a href="http://www.davebrubeck.com/live/" target="_blank">Dave Brubeck</a> recorded "Blue Rondo  la Turk". The song is part of the legendary album "Time Out" which was recorded at the same studio that yesterday''s feature,   "Kind of Blue", was recorded at: Columbia''s 30th Street studio in NYC. The album reached #2 on the pop charts (very odd for an instrumental jazz LP) and the song "Time Out" reached #25 on the pop singles chart. Joining Dave on this album were <a href="http://www.puredesmond.ca/" target="_blank">Paul Desmond</a> on alto sax, Eugene Wright on bass and Joe Morello on drums.</p>\n<p>"Blue Rondo" has a compound meter (9/8) which is actually compound triple meter (which means it has a triple pulse in each beat) as well as swing 4/4 timing (for the piano and sax solos). Dave said that he got the idea of from Turkish street musicians.</p>\n<p>Here''s Dave Brubeck with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PD21CBN6KkE" target="_blank">Blue Rondo  la Turk</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PD21CBN6KkE" target="_blank"><img src="http://www.ssgmusic.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/brubeck1.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 54, '2014-08-08 18:41:38', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:46:02', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-08-18 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 3, 0, 14, '', '', 0, 2081, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(137, 'On this day in jazz (August 19)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-august-19', '', '<p>On this day in 1969,   <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a> began recording the double album "Bitches Brew" which features jazz fusion and avant-garde styles of jazz. The importance of the album is that it was the third major turning point in jazz that Miles ushered in during his life: first with cool jazz (listen to the album "Birth of the Cool") and next with modal jazz ("Kind of Blue"). In 2012, Rolling Stone listed it as #95 in its list of greatest albums of all time. It also won the 1971 Grammy for "Best Large Jazz Ensemble Album".</p>\n<p>Here''s Miles with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9hU6G6hmt2k" target="_blank">Miles Runs the Voodoo Down</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9hU6G6hmt2k" target="_blank"><img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/7/72/Bitches_brew.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Pharaoh''s Dance" (Joe Zawinul) </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">20:00</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Bitches Brew" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">26:59</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Spanish Key" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">17:29</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"John McLaughlin" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">4:26</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Miles Runs the Voodoo Down" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">14:04</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Sanctuary" (Wayne Shorter) 10:52</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 54, '2014-08-08 18:44:55', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:46:25', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-08-19 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 3, 0, 13, '', '', 0, 2142, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(138, 'On this day in jazz (August 20)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-august-20', '', '<p>On this day in 1905,   <a href="http://www.jackteagarden.info/" target="_blank">Jack Teagarden</a> was born in Vernon,   TX. Although he was considered by many to be the greatest jazz trombonist of his era,   his unusual style prevented most other''s from trying to copy it.</p>\n<p>Jack grew up in an area with a large African-American population and quickly developed an appreciation of blues and gospel music and was one of the first jazz musicians to incorporate the blues into his playing. Jack was also one of the first white jazz musicians to record with non-white players.</p>\n<p>Primarily known as a contributor to the Dixieland style of Jazz, "Basin Street Blues" and "Beale Street Blues" are two of his best known works. He was also in a few movies, most notably the 1940 Bing Crosby film "The Birth of the Blues". Bing was a good friend to Jack and even helped him to avoid bankruptcy.</p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Here''s Jack and Louis Armstrong playing "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eOxx1-LIAWA" target="_blank">Old Rockin'' Chair</a>":</span></p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eOxx1-LIAWA" target="_blank"><img src="http://sdjrcdn.chribomedia.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/Jack-Teagarden-Portrait.jpeg" border="0" width="224" height="224" /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 54, '2014-08-08 19:15:54', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:47:11', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-08-20 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 4, 0, 12, '', '', 0, 1903, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(139, 'On this day in jazz (August 21)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-august-21', '', '<p>On this day in 1976,   bassist <a href="http://www.charliehadenmusic.com/" target="_blank">Charlie Haden</a> completed recording the album "As Long As There Is Music". The album is a series of duets with legendary west coast pianist <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/hampton-hawes-mn0000558596/biography" target="_blank">Hampton Hawes</a>. Sadly, Charlie passed away on July 11th this year (2014). He left behind his wife, Ruth, son Josh, triplet daughters named Petra, Rachel and Tanya. Oh and also son-in-law, <a href="https://www.facebook.com/JackBlack" target="_blank">Jack Black</a>.</p>\n<p>Charlie was well known for his work with avant-garde artists like <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ornette_Coleman" target="_blank">Ornette Coleman</a> and <a href="http://www.keithjarrett.org/" target="_blank">Keith Jarrett</a> as well as his work with Quartet West and The Liberation Music Orchestra. Charlie was somewhat of a political activist, and was often anti-US government when it came to its stance with Latin America. While playing in Portugal in 1971, he was arrested at the request of the fascist led dictatorship for playing the song "Song for Che". The American cultural attache was able to get him released. While back in the US, the FBI went to his apartment to ask why he would do such a thing. He stated simply that he didn''t agree with the Portuguese government. In 2006, he gave an interview and discussed the events stating that:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">I later learned that they put it into the school books of the schools in Portugal, what I did. And there was a revolution in 1974 of the young enlisted officers, and they overthrew Caetano. He fled the country. And I think it was a gentleman named Duarte [Soares] that took over, socialist government. They invited me to come back, and I came back and I played. And there were 40,000 people in this big meadow in Lisbon, and they were all chanting, "Charlie! Charlie! Charlie!" And I had goose bumps all over. It made me feel so good.</p>\n<p>Here''s Charlie and Hampton with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XancdiYwrDs" target="_blank">Irene</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XancdiYwrDs" target="_blank"><img src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/ed/Charlie_Haden_1981.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Irene" (Hampton Hawes) - 7:58</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Rain Forest" (Hawes) - 5:34</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Turnaround" (Ornette Coleman) - 7:52 Bonus track on CD reissue</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"As Long as There''s Music" (Sammy Cahn, Jule Styne) - 8:11</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"This Is Called Love" - 9:12</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Hello/Goodbye" - 8:05</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Irene" (Hawes) - 8:39 Bonus track on CD reissue</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Turnaround" (Coleman) - 6:35 Bonus track on CD reissue</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"As Long as There''s Music" (Cahn, Styne) - 7:32 </span>Bonus track on CD reissue</li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 54, '2014-08-09 18:10:55', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:47:28', 62, 62, '2016-08-20 00:50:30', '2014-08-21 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 6, 0, 11, 'On this day in jazz, Charlie Haden, Hampton Hawes, August 21', 'On this day in jazz', 0, 2054, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(150, 'On this day in jazz (September 01)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-september-01', '', '<p>On this day in 1957,   pianist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sonny_Clark" target="_blank">Sonny Clark</a> recorded Sonny''s Crib at Rudy Van Gelder''s studio in Hackensack,   NJ. <a href="http://www.johncoltrane.com/" target="_blank">John Coltrane</a> tenor sax,   Donald Byrd played trumpet, Curtis Fuller was on trombone, and the rhythm section was rounded out by <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Chambers" target="_blank">Paul Chambers</a> on bass and <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/art-taylor-mn0000505154/biography" target="_blank">Art Taylor</a> on drums--what an impressive ensemble!</p>\n<p>Sonny''s Crib is true hard-bop, and this recording is one of the better one''s in the genre. Thom Jurek said of the album that it "drew deft, imaginative performances from all its players". I agree. By the way, you can find more of Sonny on my <a href="index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=108:on-this-day-in-jazz-july-21&catid=53:july&Itemid=41" target="_self">July 21st page</a> where I profiled "Dial ''S'' For Sonny" which was recorded a month and a half earlier.</p>\n<p>Here''s Sonny playing Richard Rogers'' "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z3DzPNQjR10" target="_blank">With A Song In My Heart</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z3DzPNQjR10" target="_blank"><img src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/b/bf/Sonny_Clark.jpg/220px-Sonny_Clark.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"With a Song in My Heart" (Richard Rodgers, Lorenz Hart) - 7:54</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Speak Low" (Kurt Weill) - 6:50</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Come Rain or Come Shine" (Harold Arlen) - 7:29</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Sonny''s Crib" - 13:31</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"News for Lulu" - 8:34</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 55, '2014-08-24 14:36:10', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:59:17', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-09-01 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 4, 0, 30, 'jazz, Sonny Clark, John Coltrane, Paul Chambers, Art Taylor', 'On this day in jazz', 0, 1635, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(140, 'On this day in jazz (August 22)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-august-22', '', '<p>On this day in 1938,   <a href="http://www.thecountbasieorchestra.com/" target="_blank">Count Basie</a> recorded the hit "Jumpin'' at the Woodside". Besides the Count on piano, the song also features <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buck_Clayton" target="_blank">Buck Clayton</a> and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lester_Young" target="_blank">Lester Young</a>. See the <a href="index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=122:on-this-day-in-jazz-july-04&catid=54:august&Itemid=41" target="_blank">August 05 page</a> on this blog for more on the Count.</p>\n<p>Here''s Count Basie and Orchestra playing "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NeVfd5_6fcc" target="_blank">Jumpin'' at the Woodside</a>" live:</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NeVfd5_6fcc" target="_blank"><img src="http://www.latimes.com/includes/projects/hollywood/portraits/count_basie.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p></p>\n<p>...and how could I leave out Eugene Patton as <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cj4jN-T5g8M" target="_blank">"Gene, </a>Gene, the Dancing Machine" dancing to "Jumpin'' at the Woodside"?</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cj4jN-T5g8M" target="_blank"><img src="https://i.ytimg.com/vi/IAsnN-J2Pxs/hqdefault.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 54, '2014-08-09 18:28:46', 62, '', '2016-08-20 18:22:53', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-08-22 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 5, 0, 10, 'On this day in jazz, August 22, Count Basie, Jumpin'' at the Woodside', 'On this day in jazz', 0, 2339, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(384, 'On this day in jazz (April 19)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-april-19', '', '<p>On this day in 1956,   pianist <a href="http://www.davebrubeck.com/live/" target="_blank">Dave Brubeck</a> started recording the album <em>Brubeck plays Brubeck</em> for Columbia at his house. All compositions are by Brubeck,   and all songs are solos. Dave provided excellent liner notes for the album and talked about each song. Here''s Dave giving you the idea of the whole album in a nutshell:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">The "compositions" in this album are not composed in the usual sense of the term. They are primarily sketches - a skeletal framework upon which improvise, to express a mood or emotion or stimulate musical ideas. These little offerings make no pretense as "composition", but at the same time I have tried to construct melody lines which have a certain value of their own, and above all to offer as "original" something more unique than a new version of the blues." "I am grateful for the challenge and the opportunity this solo album of "originals" has afforded me. The challenge lay in improvising on new themes and new chord structures without the rehearsal experience of years of performance."</p>\n<p>Here''s Dave with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SIACaR_N3mw" target="_blank">Swing Bells</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SIACaR_N3mw" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/5103KNQC9WL.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Swing Bells" 3:39</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Walkin'' Line" 2:47</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"In Your Own Sweet Way" 5:01</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Two-Part Contention" 5:39</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Weep No More" 3:59</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Duke" 2:54</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"When I Was Young" 3:19</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"One Moment Worth Years" 4:55</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Waltz" 3:49</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;"> </span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 62, '2015-04-10 14:38:53', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:33:03', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-04-19 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 12, 'on this day in jazz, Dave Brubeck', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1610, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(141, 'On this day in jazz (August 23)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-august-23', '', '<p>On this day in 1946,   pianist <a href="http://www.budpowelljazz.com/" target="_blank">Bud Powell</a> recorded the jazz standard "Bouncing with Bud". Saxophonist <a href="http://www.sonnystitt.com/" target="_blank">Sonny Stitt</a> and trumpeter <a href="http://www.kennydorham.net/biography/" target="_blank">Kenny Dorham</a> join Bud on the recording.</p>\n<p>Bud was very close to fellow pianist<a href="http://www.monkzone.com/" target="_blank">Thelonious Monk</a> and also played with <a href="http://www.cmgww.com/music/parker/home.html" target="_blank">Charlie Parker</a>,   <a href="http://www.dizzygillespie.com/" target="_blank">Dizzy Gillespie</a>, <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a>, <a href="http://sonnyrollins.com/" target="_blank">Sonny Rollins</a>, <a href="http://www.dextergordon.com/">Dexter Gordon</a>, <a href="http://mingusmingusmingus.com/" target="_blank">Charles Mingus</a> and <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/max-roach-mn0000396372/biography">Max Roach</a>. For more on Bud''s life, see the <a href="index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=127:on-this-day-in-jazz-august-09&catid=54:august&Itemid=41" target="_self">August 09 page</a> of this blog.</p>\n<p>Here''s Bud playing "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=msaSi5dZBLo" target="_blank">Bouncing with Bud</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=msaSi5dZBLo" target="_blank"><img src="http://www.bluenote.com/cdn/mceuploads/artists/bud-powell.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 54, '2014-08-09 18:43:03', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:48:10', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-08-23 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 9, 'jazz, bud powell', 'This day in jazz', 0, 2219, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(142, 'On this day in jazz (August 24)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-august-24', '', '<p>On this day in 1951,   vibraphonist <a href="http://www.pas.org/experience/halloffame/JacksonMilt.aspx" target="_blank">Milt Jackson</a> recorded "Between the Devil and the Deep Blue Sea". The rhythm section consisted of pianist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Lewis_(pianist)" target="_blank">John Lewis</a>,   bassist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ray_Brown_(musician)" target="_blank">Ray Brown</a> and drummer <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kenny_Clarke" target="_blank">Kenny Clarke</a>. All four men were once part of <a href="http://www.dizzygillespie.com/" target="_blank">Dizzy Gillepsie</a>''s big band and called themselves, "The Quartet". A year later, Milt and John would join with bassist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Percy_Heath" target="_blank">Percy Heath</a> and drummer <a href="http://www.drummerworld.com/drummers/Connie_Kay.html" target="_blank">Connie Kay</a> to form the Modern Jazz Quartet, a band that played together regularly until the 1970s and intermittently until the 1990s. Note, that there are also some recordings released as the "Milt Jackson Quartet". These recordings feature the great <a href="http://www.horacesilver.com/" target="_blank">Horace Silver</a> on the piano instead of John Lewis.</p>\n<p>Milt was a consummate professional heavily influenced by classical music who was probably more at home playing in front of a large tuxedoed crowd at Carnegie Hall than at a small mid-town jazz club.</p>\n<p>Here''s "The Quartet" with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VqbYTvf4qFQ" target="_blank">Between the Devil and the Deep Blue Sea</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VqbYTvf4qFQ" target="_blank"><img src="http://blog.roopevintage.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/1770-050-CB9CFD0F.jpg" border="0" width="241" height="191" /></a></p>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 54, '2014-08-09 19:10:21', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:48:31', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-08-24 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 8, 'jazz, milt jackson', 'On this day in jazz', 0, 2191, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(143, 'On this day in jazz (August 25)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-august-25', '', '<p>On this day in 1957,   <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jimmy_Smith_(musician)" target="_blank">Jimmy Smith</a>,   king of the Hammond B-3, recorded "J. O. S." with trumpeter <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lee_Morgan" target="_blank">Lee Morgan</a>. This is the second track off the studio album, "The Sermon". Interestingly enough, some of the tracks on his previously released album, "House Party", were also recorded on this day: "Lover Man" and "Just Friends". This wasn''t the last time that he would record multiple albums on a single day, either. "Open House" and "Plain Talk" were both recorded on March 22, 1960, and one month later he recorded "Midnight Special" and "Back at the Chicken Shack" on April 25. If that''s not impressive enough, just consider this: in the first two years of his recording career, he produced 13 albums.</p>\n<p>Here''s Jimmy with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zL_Z5_3_7X" target="_blank">J. O. S.</a>" (which I assume stands for James Oscar Smith):</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zL_Z5_3_7X" target="_blank"><img src="http://cps-static.rovicorp.com/3/JPG_400/MI0001/436/MI0001436815.jpg?partner=allrovi.com" border="0" width="200" height="200" /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 54, '2014-08-16 17:22:31', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:48:59', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-08-25 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 7, 'jazz, jimmy smith', 'On this day in jazz', 0, 2298, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(144, 'On this day in jazz (August 26)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-august-26', '', '<p>On this day in 1956,   Memphis,   Tennessee''s own <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/sonny-criss-mn0000755431/biography" target="_blank">Sonny Criss</a> began recording the songs that would be released on "Sonny Criss Plays Cole Porter". <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sonny_Clark">Sonny Clark</a> also appears on this album,   playing both the piano and alto sax. Allmusic rates the album with 4.5 stars.</p>\n<p>Sonny was born on October 23, 1926 in Memphis, Tennessee, but moved to Los Angeles at the age of 15. He was active from 1946 until 1977 when he developed stomach cancer. Under the excruciating pain of the cancer, he took his life on November 19, 1977 via a self-inflicted gunshot wound. At the time, the public was unaware of the cancer and was surprised at hearing of the suicide as Sonny was in peak form and had just signed a contract with Muse Records just months earlier. It was Sonny''s mother who made it known that it was due to his stomach cancer.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Here''s Sonny with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jSJsdWeppKU" target="_blank">I Love You</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jSJsdWeppKU" target="_blank"><img src="http://hardbop.tripod.com/images/criss.jpg" border="0" width="150" height="199" /></a></p>\n<p></p>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 54, '2014-08-16 17:52:00', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:49:24', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-08-26 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 6, 'jazz, sonny criss', 'this day in jazz', 0, 2033, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(145, 'On this day in jazz (August 27)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-august-27', '', '<p>On this day in 1962,   <a href="http://www.dextergordon.com/," target="_blank">Dexter Gordon</a> one of my favorite tenor saxophonists, recorded "Go!". Allmusic gives the album 5 stars, and I wholeheartedly agree. At 6''6" tall, "Long, Tall Dexter" was both a giant physically and musically. He was one of the first tenors to take up the bebop style on the instrument and was the son of a doctor who counted <a href="http://www.dukeellington.com/" target="_blank">Duke Ellington</a> and <a href="http://www.uiweb.uidaho.edu/hampton/bio.html" target="_blank">Lionel Hampton</a> as patients. Dexter switched from clarinet to sax at 15 and started playing in bands with <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/chico-hamilton-mn0000776301/biography" target="_blank">Chico Hamilton</a> and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buddy_Collette" target="_blank">Buddy Collette</a> (one of my favorite clarinetists) while he was still in high school.</p>\n<p>Dexter Gordon''s best year was probably 1986 in which he was inducted into the French Order of Arts and Letters by the Ministry of Culture in France was nominated for an Academy Award for Best Leading Role<span style="line-height: 1.3em;">his acting performance in "Round Midnight" </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">(he didn''t win the Oscar, but he did win a Grammy for Best Soundtrack for this film). Also starring in "Round Midnight" were Franois Cluzet and <a href="http://www.herbiehancock.com/home.php" target="_blank">Herbie Hancock</a> (Martin Scorsese, Philippe Noiret and <a href="http://www.wayneshorter.com/" target="_blank">Wayne Shorter</a> have cameos). The movie received excellent reviews from critics and has a 100% rating at Rotten Tomatoes.</span></p>\n<p>Here''s Dexter with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hkyJQcmVtZQ" target="_blank">Cheese Cake</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hkyJQcmVtZQ" target="_blank"><img src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/f/f1/Go_album_cover.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Cheese Cake" </span><span style="white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Dexter Gordon</span><span style="white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">6:33</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Guess I''ll Hang My Tears Out to Dry" </span><span style="white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Jule Styne, Sammy Cahn</span><span style="white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">5:23</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Second Balcony Jump" </span><span style="white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Billy Eckstine, Gerald Valentine</span><span style="white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">7:05</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Love for Sale" </span><span style="white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Cole Porter</span><span style="white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">7:40</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Where Are You?" </span><span style="white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Jimmy McHugh, Harold Adamson</span><span style="white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">5:21</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Three O''Clock in the Morning" </span><span style="white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Dorothy Terris, Julian Robledo</span><span style="white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">5:42</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 54, '2014-08-16 18:16:56', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:49:41', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-08-27 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 5, 0, 5, 'jazz, dexter gordon', 'this day in jazz', 0, 2118, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(146, 'On this day in jazz (August 28)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-august-28', '', '<p>On this day in 1956,   the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modern_Jazz_Quartet" target="_blank">Modern Jazz Quartet</a> recorded "The Modern Jazz Quartet At Music Inn". This album also features <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jimmy_Giuffre" target="_blank">Jimmy Giuffre</a> on several of the tunes,   including the one below which was written by Jimmy. It''s nice that they brought Jimmy onto this album,   as the MJQ consisted only of non-wind instruments (<a href="http://www.pas.org/experience/halloffame/JacksonMilt.aspx" target="_blank">Milt Jackson</a> on vibraphone and a rhythm section of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Lewis_(pianist)" target="_blank">John Lewis</a><span style="line-height: 1.3em;"> on piano, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Percy_Heath" target="_blank">Percy Heath</a> on bass and <a href="http://www.drummerworld.com/drummers/Connie_Kay.html" target="_blank">Connie Kay</a> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">on drums).</span></p>\n<p>Here''s the MJQ and Jimmy Guiffre with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hEYP2__SYYc" target="_blank">Fun</a>"</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hEYP2__SYYc" target="_blank"><img src="http://www.theweejun.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/03/MJQ.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Oh Bess, Oh Where''s My Bess" (George Gershwin) - 4:27</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"A Fugue for Music Inn" - 4:42</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Two Degrees East, Three Degrees West" - 7:04</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Serenade" (David Raksin) - 2:55</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Fun" (Jimmy Giuffre) - 5:30</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Sun Dance" - 4:14</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Man That Got Away" (Harold Arlen, Ira Gershwin) - 3:32</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"A Morning in Paris" - 2:51</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Variation No. 1 on "God Rest Ye Merry, Gentlemen" - 5:00</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 54, '2014-08-16 18:30:24', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:50:10', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-08-28 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 4, 'jazz, MJQ, modern jazz quartet, jimmy guiffre', 'this day in jazz', 0, 2290, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(147, 'On this day in jazz (August 29)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-august-29', '', '<p>August 29th is a pretty special day when it comes to jazz. It is the day upon which alto saxophonist <a href="http://www.cmgww.com/music/parker/home.html" target="_blank">Charlie Parker</a> (1920) and vocalist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dinah_Washington" target="_blank">Dinah Washington</a> (1924) were born. Additionally,   <a href="http://www.dextergordon.com/" target="_blank">Dexter Gordon</a> (whom I featured 2 days ago) recorded "A Swingin'' Affair" in 1962.</p>\n<p>I don''t often profile jazz vocalists,   but will make an exception for the exceptional Dinah Washington.<span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Dinah was the self-proclaimed "Queen of the Blues" and was inducted into the Alabama Jazz Hall of Fame in 1986 as well as the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame in 1993. She was born in Tuscaloosa but moved to Chicago as a child. Unfortunately she died at the early age of 39. She was found dead in bed by her 7th husband (pro football Hall of Famer, Dick "Night Train" Lane) having probably died due to taking a combination of secobarbital and amobarbital. Yes, I said, 7th husband. Read all about them <a href="http://illkeepyouposted.typepad.com/ill_keep_you_posted/2012/01/t.html" target="_blank">here</a>.</span></p>\n<p>Here''s Dinah singing "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OmBxVfQTuvI" target="_blank">What a Difference a Day Makes</a>":</p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;"><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OmBxVfQTuvI" target="_blank"><img src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/4a/Dinah_Washington_1952.jpg" border="0" width="239" height="282" /></a><img src="http://www.possumsal.com/CharlieParker/Charlie_Parker.jpg" border="0" width="230" height="282" /></span></p>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 54, '2014-08-16 18:52:51', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:50:33', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-08-29 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 3, 'jazz, dinah washington', 'this day in jazz', 0, 2189, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(148, 'On this day in jazz (August 30)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-august-30', '', '<p>On this day in 1979,   drummer Max Roach and tenor saxophonist Archie Shepp played both as soloists and as a duet at the Willisau Jazz Festival. The show was released by Hat records of Switzerland and is somewhat hard to find. Troy Collins said this about the album:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">Despite a generational divide,   Roach and Shepp share a similar revolutionary ideology,   finding common accord in an artistic aesthetic motivated by socio-political concerns. Advocates of positive political change through activism, their mutual respect for jazz tradition informs and enriches their progressive stance, making this meeting especially pointed.</p>\n<p>Both Max and Archie were outspoken civil rights activists. For example, in 1972 Archie released "Attica Blues" (relating to the Attica Prison riots) and "The Cry of My People". Shepp also wrote several theatrical plays that were professionally performed ("The Communist" and "Lady Day: A Musical Tragedy" were produced by Robert Kalfin and the Chelsea Theater Center). For more on Max, see the <a href="index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=113:on-this-day-in-jazz-july-26&catid=53:july&Itemid=41" target="_self">July 26 page</a> of this blog .</p>\n<p>Here''s Max and Archie with "<a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Max+Roach+&+Archie+Shepp/The+Long+March+Part+1" target="_blank">The Long March</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Max+Roach+&+Archie+Shepp/The+Long+March+Part+1" target="_blank"><img src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/7/7a/The_Long_March_(album).jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"J.C. Moses" - 5:52</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Sophisticated Lady" (Duke Ellington, Irving Mills, Mitchell Parish) - 5:46</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Long March" - 26:17</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"U-Jaa-Ma" (Archie Shepp) - 12:30</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Triptych" - 7:26</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Giant Steps" (John Coltrane) - 5:35</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"South Africa Goddamn" - 20:09</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"It''s Time" - 9:36</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 54, '2014-08-17 16:07:14', 62, '', '2016-08-20 01:03:50', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-08-30 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 5, 0, 2, 'jazz, Max Roach, Archie Shepp', 'On this day in jazz', 0, 2031, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(149, 'On this day in jazz (August 31)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-august-31', '', '<p>On this day in 1958,   the Modern Jazz Quartet with <a href="http://sonnyrollins.com/" target="_blank">Sonny Rollins</a> recorded <em>At Music Inn,   Volume 2</em> (<em>Volume 1</em> was recorded two years earlier and my discussion about it can be found <a href="index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=146:on-this-day-in-jazz-august-28&catid=54:august&Itemid=41" target="_self">here</a>). Thom Jurek said this of the two tunes that Sonny joins in on:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">As on the previous volume, the Modern Jazz Quartet are joined by a guest for the final two cuts; ace saxophonist Sonny Rollins digs in on both the classic "Bags Groove," composed by Jackson, and Dizzy Gillespie''s bebop anthem "Night in Tunisia." ... Rollins understands the MJQ''s use of tension and dynamics beautifully. His big, warm tone above Lewis and Jackson on the former is sweet, relaxed, and in-the-pocket. On the latter, the knotty melodic frame is played a little slower, but is a tough fingerpopper nonetheless, with Rollins playing accents in the opening vamps and the just gliding into his big bluesy solo. This is a welcome addition to volume one, and a larger study in contrasts given Rollins propensity to really blow, as opposed Giuffre''s lower key approach on the first volume. To say that this set works is an understatement. It is a highlight of the group''s storied career on Atlantic.</p>\n<p>Here MJQ joined by Sonny Rollins with "<a href="http://iisaphd.subsonic.org/share/TtasM" target="_blank">Bag''s Groove</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="http://iisaphd.subsonic.org/share/TtasM" target="_blank"><img src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/0/06/The_Modern_Jazz_Quartet_at_Music_Inn_Volume_2.jpg" border="0" width="199" height="200" /></a></p>\n<p>For more on Sonny, see the <a href="index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=116:on-this-day-in-jazz-july-29&catid=53:july&Itemid=41" target="_self">July 29 page</a> or just follow him on <a href="https://www.facebook.com/officialsonnyrollins" target="_blank">facebook</a></p>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 54, '2014-08-17 16:29:15', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:52:49', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-08-31 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 1, 'jazz, Modern Jazz Quartet, MJQ, Sonny Rollins', 'On this day in jazz', 0, 1961, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(151, 'On this day in jazz (September 02)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-september-02', '', '<p>On this day in 1969,   <a href="http://www.wayneshorter.com/" target="_blank">Wayne Shorter</a> completed recording his twelfth studio album entitled "Supernova". This album fits into the jazz fusion genre that <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a> ushered in with <a href="index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=137:on-this-day-in-jazz-august-19&catid=54:august&Itemid=41" target="_self">Bitches Brew</a>. All songs are originals, except for "Dindi" which was a tune written by the great Brazilian composer <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/antonio-carlos-jobim-mn0000781837/biography" target="_blank">Antonio Calos Jobim</a>. Jobim ("the Gershwin of Brazil") is one of my favorite bossa nova genre artists, and I must warn you that the cover of "Dindi" is about as far away from the easy going bossa nova version as you can get.</p>\n<p>At the time of this writing (2014), Wayne is still with us, and has been described by Ben Ratliff in 2008 as "jazz''s greatest living small-group composer and a contender for greatest living improviser". He has won 10 Grammy Awards and was "Down Beat" magazine''s annual poll winner for best soprano saxophone player from 1970 to 1979 (critic''s poll) and from 1970 to 1987 (reader''s poll). Very impressive. He also was the founder of the band "Weather Report". Note, if jazz fusion isn''t your style, you should check out the works he composed in the 50''s for the Jazz Messengers.</p>\n<p>Here''s Wayne with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zMqKup6dK9c" target="_blank">More Than Human</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zMqKup6dK9c" target="_blank"><img src="http://www.downtownmagazinenyc.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/Wayne_Shorter_01.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Supernova" - 4:52</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Swee-Pea" - 4:36</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Dindi" (Jobim) - 9:35</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Water Babies" - 4:53</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Capricorn" - 7:47</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"More Than Human" - 6:12</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 55, '2014-08-24 06:00:00', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:58:26', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-09-02 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 4, 0, 29, 'Wayne Shorter, jazz', 'On this day in jazz', 0, 1652, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(152, 'On this day in jazz (September 03)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-september-03', '', '<p>On this day in 1957,   double bassist <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/curtis-counce-mn0000785964/biography" target="_blank">Curtis Counce</a> completed the recording of "You Get More Bounce With Curtis Counce". The album covers almost one year of Curtis'' recording history having started in October of 1956.</p>\n<p>Curtis was born in Kansas City, Missouri in 1926 and moved to California at the age of 19. He began recording several years later with <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shelly_Manne" target="_blank">Shelly Manne</a>, <a href="http://www.teddy-charles.com/" target="_blank">Teddy Charles</a>, <a href="http://cliffordbrown.net/" target="_blank">Clifford Brown</a>, and <a href="http://lmgtfy.com/?q=many+others" target="_blank">many others</a>. In fact, he was one of the first African American artists to be in demand on the West Coast jazz movement. Despite being known as an in-demand session artist, he started is own quintet starting in 1956 and recorded several albums as a leader until his unfortunate early passing from a heart attack in 1963. All of these albums were reissued in 2006 on a double CD by Gambit Spain. In fact, "You Get More Bounce" was originally entitled "Councellation".<span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Most of the songs on the album are jazz standards, but there are a couple of originals also. </span></p>\n<p>Here''s Curtis with the standard "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uYZr2E27WBs" target="_blank">Stranger in Paradise</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uYZr2E27WBs" target="_blank"><img src="https://jazzinphoto.files.wordpress.com/2012/02/curtis-counce-william-claxton.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 55, '2014-08-24 15:29:14', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:00:41', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-09-03 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 3, 0, 28, 'jazz, curtis counce', 'This day in jazz', 0, 1760, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(153, 'On this day in jazz (September 04)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-september-04', '', '<p>On this day in 1958,   <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/max-roach-mn0000396372/biography" target="_blank">Max Roach</a> and his quintet recorded "Deeds, Not Words".Along with Max on the drums, we find trumpeter Booker Little, Ray Draper on tuba, tenor saxophonist George Coleman and bassist Art Davis.</p>\n<p>Max, who passed away in 2007, was one of the greatest drummers in world. In fact, in the early 80''s, Roach played entire concerts solo. You can find one of these solo on a Japanese label called Baystate and if you look around enough, you can probably even fine one of these solo concerts on video.</p>\n<p>Here''s "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zxe__B9IuQQ" target="_blank">You Stepped Out Of A Dream</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zxe__B9IuQQ" target="_blank"><img src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/2/26/Deeds%2C_Not_Words.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"You Stepped Out of a Dream" (Nacio Herb Brown, Gus Kahn) - 7:46</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Filide" (Ray Draper) - 7:06</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"It''s You or No One" (Sammy Cahn, Jule Styne) - 4:14</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Jodie''s Cha-Cha" (Bill Lee) - 4:56</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Deeds, Not Words" (Lee) - 4:34</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Larry-Larue" (Booker Little) - 5:13</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Conversation" (Max Roach) - 3:48</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"There Will Never Be Another You" (Mack Gordon, Harry Warren) - 5:50</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 55, '2014-08-24 17:09:52', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:01:17', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-09-04 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 27, 'jazz, Max Roach', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1701, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(154, 'On this day in jazz (September 05)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-september-05', '', '<p>On this day in 1959,   <a href="http://www.puredesmond.ca/" target="_blank">Paul Desmond</a> recorded "First Place Again" in NYC with <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Percy_Heath" target="_blank">Percy Heath</a> and <a href="http://www.drummerworld.com/drummers/Connie_Kay.html" target="_blank">Connie Kay</a> of the Modern Jazz Quartet, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jimmy_Giuffre" target="_blank">Jimmy Giuffre</a> (who played on "<a href="index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=146:on-this-day-in-jazz-august-28&catid=54:august&Itemid=41" target="_blank">At Music Inn</a>" with MJQ) and <a href="http://www.jimhallmusic.com/" target="_blank">Jim Hall</a>. In his review, Thom Jurek states that the musicians just all happened to be in NYC at the time and decided to make an after-hours recording.</p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">The album has a very sophisticated and relaxed moon, and was entitled "First Place Again" due to Paul finishing first place (again) in Down Beat magazine''s alto saxophone poll. You might find this album also entitled "East of the Sun". </span></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">If you are not familiar with Paul Desmond, he''s probably most famous for writing "Take Five" (still today, the greatest selling jazz single of all time) which can be found on the <a href="http://www.davebrubeck.com/live/" target="_blank">Dave Brubeck</a> Quartet album "<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Time_Out_(album)" target="_blank">Time Out</a>".</span></p>\n<p>Here''s Paul and the guys playing "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=03_GtIkX4e8" target="_blank">I Get A Kick Out Of You</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=03_GtIkX4e8" target="_blank"><img src="http://cps-static.rovicorp.com/3/JPG_400/MI0001/325/MI0001325333.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 55, '2014-08-24 17:35:01', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:02:21', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-09-05 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 4, 0, 26, 'jazz, Paul Desmond', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1824, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(155, 'On this day in jazz (September 06)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-september-06', '', '<p>On this day in 1973,   the <a href="http://www.artensembleofchicago.com/" target="_blank">Art Ensemble of Chicago</a> began recording "Fanfare For The Warriors" at Paragon Studios in Chicago,   Illinois. It features music by Lester Bowie, Joseph Jarman, Roscoe Mitchell, Malachi Favors Maghostut, Don Moye and Muhal Richard Abrams.</p>\n<p>Muhal was a co-founder of the <a href="http://www.aacmchicago.org/" target="_blank">AACM</a> which stands for the Association for the Advancement of Creative Musicians. The association was formed in 1965 and its purpose is to help in the recording of "serious, original music". Muhal and others founded the organization to provide a commitment to avant garde jazz during a time where there was a serious lack of performance venues and recording opportunities. Starting in 1969, the association has presented a music education program for inner-city youth in Chicago.</p>\n<p>Here''s the Art Ensemble of Chicago with "<a href="Fanfare For The Warriors" target="_blank">Fanfare For The Warriors</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nWjp-eE1RY4&index=3&list=ALBTKoXRg38BAmyrll-KNP0zXxenQVffiE" target="_blank"><img src="http://www.jazzhouse.org/jpg/farber/enid3.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Illistrum" (Favors) - 8:17</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Barnyard Scuffel Shuffel" (Bowie) - 5:12</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Nonaah" (Mitchell) - 5:44</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Fanfare for the Warriors" (Jarman) - 7:58</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"What''s to Say" (Jarman) - 4:02</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Tnoona" (Mitchell) - 6:25</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Key" (Mitchell) - 1:15</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 55, '2014-08-24 18:10:45', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:03:49', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-09-06 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 25, 'jazz, Art Ensemble of Chicago', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1759, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(156, 'On this day in jazz (September 07)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-september-07', '', '<p>On this day in 1956,   "Tenor Conclave" was released. This work features the four saxophonists <a href="http://www.johncoltrane.com/" target="_blank">John Coltrane</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Al_Cohn" target="_blank">Al Cohn</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hank_Mobley" target="_blank">Hank Mobley</a> and <a href="http://www.zootsims.org/" target="_blank">Zoot Sims</a> who were accompanied by a rhythm section of <a href="Red_Garland" target="_blank">Red Garland</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Chambers" target="_blank">Paul Chambers</a> and <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/art-taylor-mn0000505154/biography" target="_blank">Art Taylor</a>. What a group of jazz legends!</p>\n<p>The four songs on the album are "Tenor Conclave", "Just You, Just Me", "Bob''s Boys" and "How Deep Is The Ocean".</p>\n<p>Lindsay Planner said of the album that despite the greatness of these four tenors individually, "the whole tends to be greater than the sum of the parts."</p>\n<p>The entire album is <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7fLnT0KwJTI" target="_blank">here</a>:</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7fLnT0KwJTI" target="_blank"><img src="http://cps-static.rovicorp.com/3/JPG_500/MI0002/331/MI0002331580.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Tenor Conclave" (Mobley)  11:05</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Just You, Just Me" (Jesse Greer, Raymond Klages)  9:29</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Bob''s Boys" (Hank Mobley)  8:26</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"How Deep Is the Ocean" (Irving Berlin)  15:04</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 55, '2014-08-24 18:37:33', 62, '', '2016-08-20 01:06:50', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-09-07 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 5, 0, 24, 'JAZZ, john coltrane, hank mobley, zoot sims, art taylor, paul chambers, red garland, al cohn', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1820, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(157, 'On this day in jazz (September 18)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-september-18', '', '<p>On this day in 1966,   saxophonist <a href="http://www.charleslloyd.com/" target="_blank">Charles Lloyd</a> recorded <em>Forest Flower</em> which was a recording of his concert at the Monterey Jazz Festival. It features very strong performances by the rest of the quartet: <a href="http://www.keithjarrett.org/" target="_blank">Keith Jarrett</a> on piano, <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/cecil-mcbee-mn0000739015/biography" target="_blank">Cecil McBee</a> on bass, and <a href="http://www.jackdejohnette.com/" target="_blank">Jack DeJohnette</a> on drums.</p>\n<p>Thom Jurek gives a great review of the album on <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/album/forest-flower-charles-lloyd-at-monterey-mw0000120169" target="_blank">allmusic.com</a>:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">...the opening two title tracks, which form a kind of suite (one is "Forest Flower-Sunrise," the other "Sunset"), showcased the already fully developed imagination of Jarrett as a pianist....Lloyd''s own solos are demonstrative of his massive melodic gift....By the time the band reaches its final number, a sky-scorching version of Brooks Bowman''s "East of the Sun," they have touched upon virtually the entire history of jazz and still pushed it forward with seamless aplomb. Forest Flower is a great live record.</p>\n<p>Here''s Charles with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CnYoFF8DHu0" target="_blank">Forest Flower</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CnYoFF8DHu0" target="_blank"><img src="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-fz5OPkpxWHI/UJbpjCvhNtI/AAAAAAAABF0/d_WcapXHsbs/s1600/charles_lloyd.jpg" border="0" width="560" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Forest Flower: Sunrise" - 7:17</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Forest Flower: Sunset" - 10:19</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Sorcery" (Keith Jarrett) - 5:11</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Song of Her" (Cecil McBee) - 5:16</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"East of the Sun" (Brooks Bowman) - 10:20</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 55, '2014-08-30 16:52:26', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:07:49', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-09-17 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 5, 0, 13, 'jazz, Charles Lloyd, Keith Jarrett', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1803, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(158, 'On this day in jazz (September 08)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-september-08', '', '<p>On this day in 1972,   <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rahsaan_Roland_Kirk" target="_blank">Rahsaan Roland Kirk</a> recorded the album <em>Blacknuss</em>. Rahsaan played several instruments (some even with his nose),   but was known most for tenor sax and flute--and there are some great flute numbers on this album. Although most of his playing seems to be influenced primarily by hard bop and soul jazz,   Rahsaan understood the importance of all jazz forms from ragtime and swing to free jazz. Aside from jazz influences, you can hear pop influences by composers such as Smokey Robinson and Burt Bacharach in his music.</p>\n<p>Like several other jazz giants of the 60s and 70s, Kirk was outspoken when it cam to both black history and civil rights--often breaking into monologue between songs. Jay Leno who opened for Rahsaan on one of his tours said that Kirk would introduce him by saying, "I want to introduce a young brother who knows the black experience and knows all about the white devils .... Please welcome Jay Leno!".</p>\n<p>On other bit of trivia: Jimi Hendrix, arguably the greatest rock guitarist of all time, had hoped to record with Rahsaan (source: William Saunders'' 2010 book Jimi Hendrix London).</p>\n<p>Here''s Rahsaan playing the great Marvin Gaye tune, "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kcSGxq7DKUs">Ain''t No Sunshine</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kcSGxq7DKUs" target="_blank"><img src="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-9hrC06ApHQw/UJwwtKHVn7I/AAAAAAAAAGM/FdN-LsWd3wA/s1600/777939d1746331804873795292b7c.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Ain''t No Sunshine" (Bill Withers)  2:26</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"What''s Goin'' On/Mercy Mercy Me (The Ecology)" (Renaldo Benson, Al Cleveland, Marvin Gaye)  3:47</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I Love You, Yes I Do" (Chris Allen, Johnny Cameron)  2:49</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Take Me Girl, I''m Ready" (Johnny Bristol, Pam Sawyer, LaVerne Ware)  3:18</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"My Girl" (Smokey Robinson, Ronald White)  3:06</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Which Way Is It Going" Rahsaan Roland Kirk  2:26</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"One Nation" (Princess Patience Burton)  3:41</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Never Can Say Goodbye" (Clifton Davis)  4:02</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Old Rugged Cross" (Trad.)  7:15</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Make It With You" (David Gates)  4:50</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Blacknuss" (Kirk)  5:12</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 55, '2014-08-30 17:58:08', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:08:09', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-09-08 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 22, 'jazz, Rahsaan Roland Kirk', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1686, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(159, 'On this day in jazz (September 09)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-september-09', '', '<p>On this day in 1958,  <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a><span style="line-height: 1.3em;"> recorded <em>Jazz At The Plaza</em> in the Persian Room at the Plaza Hotel in New York City. The album is important because it features the same sextet that would go on to record <em>Kind of Blue</em> six months later: <a href="http://www.johncoltrane.com/" target="_blank">John Coltrane</a> on tenor sax,   <a href="http://www.cannonball-adderley.com/" target="_blank">Cannonball Adderley</a> on alto sax, and a rhythm section of <a href="http://www.billevanswebpages.com/" target="_blank">Bill Evans</a> on piano, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Chambers" target="_blank">Paul Chambers</a> on bass, and <a href="http://www.jimmycobb.net/" target="_blank">Jimmy Cobb</a> on the drums. </span></p>\n<p>Irving Townsend, in the liner notes, said this of the recording event: "it was a party. We taped it because we wanted to remember it, in case it never happened again." That is, it was a party thrown by Columbia in celebration of their jazz division--not an intended recording session. Columbia didn''t release the album until 1973. Bill Evans noted that they were paid at the 1958 scale instead of at the 1973 scale, which doesn''t seem right unless the album was sold at 1958 rates...</p>\n<p>Here''s Miles and sextet with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4FLAtqo57sA" target="_blank">Oleo</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4FLAtqo57sA" target="_blank"><img src="http://img13.imageshack.us/img13/9509/3ktg.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"If I Were a Bell"  8:31</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Oleo"  10:39</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"My Funny Valentine"  10:19</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Straight, No Chaser  10:56 including "The Theme"</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 55, '2014-08-30 18:04:28', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:08:32', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-09-09 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 5, 0, 23, '', '', 0, 1683, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(160, 'On this day in jazz (September 10)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-september-10', '', '<p>On this day in 1954,   drummer <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shelly_Manne" target="_blank">Shelly Manne</a> released <em>The Three and the Two</em>. Allmusic calls these recordings "most unusual". The "three" are Manne,   trumpeter Shorty Rogers,   and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jimmy_Giuffre" target="_blank">Jimmy Giuffre</a> playing clairnet, tenor & baritone sax. The "two" and Manne and pianist Russ Freeman.<span style="line-height: 1.3em;">The importance of the album is that it records some of the first free jazz ever recorded: it is believed that the first was Lennie Tristano in 1949, and then Manne with these recordings. </span></p>\n<p>A little bit about Shelly: in 1943 he married Florence Butterfield (known affectionately to family and friends as "Flip"). The song, "Flip" is also on this recording. They were married for the rest of Manne''s life (41 years). Shelly was also a big factor in keeping jazz going in Los Angeles during the late 60''s and 70''s by having many of the world''s prominent jazz musicians play at his Manne-Hole on North Cahuenga Boulevard in Hollywood (now Kitchen 24).</p>\n<p>Here''s Shelly with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jnJOJJoAXLY" target="_blank">Abstract No. 1</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jnJOJJoAXLY" target="_blank"><img src="http://s3.amazonaws.com/drumlessonscom/00-drummers/shelly-manne-7.jpg" border="0" width="254" height="300" /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 55, '2014-08-30 18:25:26', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:08:50', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-09-10 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 21, 'jazz, Shelly Manne', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1775, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(161, 'On this day in jazz (September 11)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-september-11', '', '<p>On this day in 1979,   <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/max-roach-mn0000396372/biography" target="_blank">Max Roach</a> began recording the album "Pictures In A Frame" at Barigozzi Studio in Milano,  Italy. It would be completed on September 17. Called a gap-filler between the genres of hard bop and avant-garde,   this is a very strong recording. The group included <a href="http://www.cecilbridgewater.com/Main/Home.htm" target="_blank">Cecil Bridgewater</a> on trumpet, <a href="http://www.odeanpope.com/" target="_blank">Odean Pope</a> on tenor sax/flute/oboe, and Calvin Hill on bass and features originals songs from the band members.</p>\n<p>Here''s Max with "<a href="http://24.192.96.124:4040/share/vXOeq" target="_blank">Magic</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="http://24.192.96.124:4040/share/vXOeq" target="_blank"><img src="http://www.drummerworld.com/pics/drum/dpa52/maxroach.jpg" border="0" width="214" height="260" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Reflections" (Max) - 3:36</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Mwalimu" (Odean Pope) - 8:16</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"A Place of Truth" (Max) - 4:11</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"China''s Waltz" (Calvin Hill) - 4:27</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Mail Order" (Pope) - 3:26</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Japanese Dream" (Clifford Jordan) - 3:40</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 55, '2014-08-30 18:42:03', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:15:17', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-09-11 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 20, 'jazz, Max Roach', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1763, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(162, 'On this day in jazz (September 12)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-september-12', '', '<p>On this day in 1963,   baritone saxophonist <a href="http://www.gerrymulligan.com/" target="_blank">Gerry Mulligan</a> began recording the album <em>Night Lights</em>. The album includes several other great jazz musicians who had played with Gerry earlier in their careers: trombonist <a href="http://www.bobbrookmeyer.com/" target="_blank">Bob Brookmeyer</a>,  guitarist <a href="http://www.jimhallmusic.com/" target="_blank">Jim Hall</a>,   and trumpeter <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/art-farmer-mn0000502199/biography" target="_blank">Art Farmer</a> just to name a few.</p>\n<p>The recording includes both new songs, some older songs and a couple of covers. He even arranges Chopin''s "Prelude in E minor" to round out the really relaxed feeling of the recording.</p>\n<p>Here''s "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0cK_AIpmejs" target="_blank">Night Lights</a>" with one of my favorite Van Gogh paintings ("Starry Night Over the Rhone") in the background:</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0cK_AIpmejs" target="_blank"><img src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/0c/Gerry_Mulligan_1972_%28Heinrich_Klaffs_Collection_78%29.jpg" border="0" width="180" height="256" /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 55, '2014-09-04 10:42:11', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:14:58', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-09-12 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 3, 0, 19, 'jazz, Gerry Mulligan', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1640, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(163, 'On this day in jazz (September 13)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-september-13', '', '<p>On this day in 1961,   <a href="http://www.puredesmond.ca/" target="_blank">Paul Desmond</a> recorded "My Funny Valentine" in New York City. The song would later become part of the album <em>Desmond Blue</em>. This song features Paul on alto saxophone,   Albert Richman on French horn,   <a href="http://www.jimhallmusic.com/" target="_blank">Jim Hall</a> on guitar, Gene Cherico on bass, <a href="http://www.drummerworld.com/drummers/Connie_Kay.html" target="_blank">Connie Kay</a> on drums, and Phil Bodner and Romeo Penque on woodwinds. Bob Prince conducts.</p>\n<p>Paul had never been recorded with the backing of a string orchestra. The album also includes the jazz standards "I''ve Got You Under My Skin," and "Body and Soul,". Shawn M. Haney on allmusic.com describes the album as: "a highly innovative and meticulously crafted work, reflecting the ongoing success of both Desmond and Hall within the 1960s and the cool jazz period."</p>\n<p>For more on Paul, see my<a href="index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=154:on-this-day-in-jazz-september-05&catid=55:september&Itemid=41" target="_self">September 05 "On this day in jazz" page</a>.</p>\n<p>Here''s Paul and orchestra with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_2cTgUK3MQY" target="_blank">My Funny Valentine</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_2cTgUK3MQY" target="_blank"><img src="http://cps-static.rovicorp.com/3/JPG_400/MI0001/325/MI0001325333.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 55, '2014-09-04 10:59:08', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:14:42', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-09-13 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 18, 'jazz, Paul Desmond', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1718, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(164, 'On this day in jazz (September 14)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-september-14', '', '<p>On this day in 1960,   avant-garde jazz saxophonist <a href="http://www.ayler.co.uk/" target="_blank">Albert Ayler</a> was recorded rehearsing "Tenderly" and "Leap Frog" which would later be released on the album: <em>Holy Ghost: Rare And Unissued Recordings</em>.</p>\n<p>Ayler rose to prominence in 1964 when he recorded and released "Spiritual Unity" with bassist Gary Peacock and percussionist Sunny Murray. Valerie Wilmer called SU "shockingly different",   while Ekkehard Jost said that the music the three played created "three independent rhythmic planes". Ayler himself said that the group wasn''t really playing the music together,   rather they were responding to listening to each other play. The album is part of "The Penguin Guide to Jazz"''s core collection.</p>\n<p>Here''s Albert with "Tenderly" and "Leap Frog":</p>\n<p><img src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/8/89/Albert_Ayler.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 55, '2014-09-06 16:56:28', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:14:25', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-09-14 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 17, 'jazz, Albert Ayler', 'On this day in jazz', 0, 1685, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(165, 'On this day in jazz (September 15)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-september-15', '', '<p>On this day in 1957,   <a href="http://www.johncoltrane.com/" target="_blank">John Coltrane </a> recorded the album <em>Blue Train</em> at Rudy Van Gelder''s studio in Hackensack, NJ. Joining John on this work are <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lee_Morgan" target="_blank">Lee Morgan</a> (trumpet), Curtis Fuller (trombone), and the rhythm section of Kenny Drew (piano), Paul Chambers (bass), and Philly Joe Jones (drums). With a collection of musicians like that, how could you not produce a classic?</p>\n<p>After this (his 4th studio) album, John would go on to record two more studio albums as a leader and the classic <em>Kind of Blue</em> with Miles Davis before recording the ground breaking <em>Giant Steps</em> in 1960. Although, <em>Blue Train</em> isn''t quite ground breaking itself, it is quite worth a listen to.</p>\n<p>Here''s the full album, starting with the title song "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Lr1r9_9VxQA" target="_blank">Blue Train</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Lr1r9_9VxQA" target="_blank"><img src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/6/68/John_Coltrane_-_Blue_Train.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Blue Train" </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">John Coltrane</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">10:43</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Moment''s Notice" </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">John Coltrane</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">9:10</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Locomotion" </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">John Coltrane</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">7:14</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I''m Old Fashioned" </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Johnny Mercer, Jerome Kern</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">7:58</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Lazy Bird" John Coltrane</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">7:00</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 55, '2014-09-06 17:07:58', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:13:55', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-09-15 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 16, 'John Coltrane, jazz', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1513, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(166, 'On this day in jazz (September 16)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-september-16', '', '<p>On this day in 1976,   <a href="http://straightlife.info/apbio.html" target="_blank">Art Pepper</a> completed recording the album entitled <em>The Trip</em>. Art,   who played tenor saxophone,   was joined by a rhythm section of George Cables (piano), Davis Williams (bass) and Elvin Jones (drums).</p>\n<p>The song "The Trip" was actually written in 1963 while Art was imprisoned in San Quentin (for the first time). Due to his heroin addition, Art actually served sentences from 1954-1956, 1960-1961, 1961-1964 and 1964-1965. Finally, in the late 1960s he tried drub rehabilitation and finally kicked the habit in the mid 70s via methadone therapy. He died in 1982 at the age of 56 and was laid to rest in the Hollywood Forever Cemetery. Dee Dee and Johnny Ramone would join him later as will, unfortunately, Morrissey some day (<a href="http://metro.co.uk/2007/02/08/grave-morrissey-picks-burial-spot-64290/" target="_blank">Morrissey picked a plot next to Johnny</a> which goes to show that music transcends political and ideological boundaries).</p>\n<p>Here''s Art with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oRq61VypkLk" target="_blank">The Trip</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oRq61VypkLk" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/artpepper200x150.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Trip" (Art Pepper)  8:55</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"A Song For Richard" (Joe Gordon)  6:17</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Sweet Love Of Mine" (Woody Shaw)  6:34</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Junior Cat" (Art Pepper)  7:46</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Summer Knows" (Michel Legrand, Marilyn & Alan Bergman)  7:09</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Red Car" (Art Pepper)  5:45</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 55, '2014-09-06 17:13:36', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:13:42', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-09-16 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 5, 0, 15, 'jazz, Art Pepper', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1863, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(167, 'On this day in jazz (September 17)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-september-17', '', '<p>On this day in 1970,   organist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Earland" target="_blank">Charles Earland</a> ("The Mighty Burner") recorded a concert at The Key Club in New Jersey which would later be released as the album <em>Living Black!</em>. Joining Charles were Gary Chandler on trumpet,   <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grover_Washington,  _Jr.">Grover Washington, Jr.</a> on tenor saxophone, Maynard Parker on guitar, Jesse Kilpatrick on drums and Buddy Caldwell on the congas.</p>\n<p>Here''s a review from allmusic.com, which awards the recording 5 stars:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">Living Black! is notable for many reasons, not the least of which is that it showcased Earland in a live setting at his most inspired. From choosing his sidemen to material to reading the audience to pure instrumental execution, there isn''t a weak moment on this date, nor a sedentary one... Everybody who was there, no doubt -- as well as any listener with blood instead of sawdust in her or his veins -- had their minds blown long before.</p>\n<p>Here''s Charles with the Benny Golson''s song "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sKDdMmLqfd0" target="_blank">Killer Joe</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sKDdMmLqfd0" target="_blank"><img src="http://cps-static.rovicorp.com/3/JPG_400/MI0000/136/MI0000136969.jpg?partner=allrovi.com" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Key Club Cookout" - 9:31</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Westbound No. 9" (Daphne Dumas, Ronald Dunbar, Edith Wayne) - 8:19</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Killer Joe" (Benny Golson) - 14:28</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Milestones" (Miles Davis) - 4:34</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 55, '2014-09-06 17:29:08', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:13:30', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-09-17 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 14, 'jazz, Charles Earlund', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1610, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(168, 'On this day in jazz (September 19)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-september-19', '', '<p>On this day in 1955,   pianist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Erroll_Garner" target="_blank">Erroll Garner</a> recorded <em>Concert By The Sea</em> in lovely Carmel, California. The concert was actually recorded inside of a church on a military base. Eddie Calhoun provided bass and Denzil Best played the drums. The album is highly rated by sites such as allmusic.com and jazz encyclopedia''s such as "<a href="http://www.amazon.com/s/?ie=UTF8&keywords=the+penguin+guide+to+jazz&tag=googhydr-20&index=stripbooks&hvadid=18838984109&hvpos=1t1&hvexid=&hvnetw=g&hvrand=15685964154790875757&hvpone=&hvptwo=&hvqmt=b&hvdev=c&ref=pd_sl_4y9hzs7kz6_b." target="_blank">The Penguin Guide To Jazz</a>"</p>\n<p>Errol is an interesting character. He couldn''t read music, but composed many songs including the standard, "Misty". He was short in stature (5''2") and would sit on multiple telephone directories while playing. As you might expect, he also had small hands that could barely span an octave, but could move them very quickly. C. Michael Bailey said that due to having no formal training, "Garner was not encumbered by theory or common performance practice, thereby making his music quite uncommon." Of the album itself, <a href="http://www.allaboutjazz.com/erroll-garner-concert-by-the-sea-by-c-michael-bailey.php#.VAxuT2BdU8o" target="_blank">Bailey says</a>:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">Concert By The Sea is a flawed monument of perfection. This recording was a dichotomy, a paradox, where the unlearned not only prevail, but create art of a lasting quality. This is the art.</p>\n<p>Here''s Erroll with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Jt8U9H3xXg4&list=ALBTKoXRg38BCk39LAPVb7LE4ZBxKx29pn&index=1" target="_blank">I''ll Remember April</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Jt8U9H3xXg4&list=ALBTKoXRg38BCk39LAPVb7LE4ZBxKx29pn&index=1" target="_blank"><img src="http://crooksandliars.com/files/vfs/2011/06/Erroll-Garner---resized.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I''ll Remember April" (Gene de Paul, Patricia Johnston, Don Raye)  4:14</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Teach Me Tonight" (Sammy Cahn, de Paul)  3:37</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Mambo Carmel-by-the-sea" (Erroll Garner)  3:43</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Autumn Leaves" (Joseph Kosma, Jacques Prvert, Johnny Mercer)  6:27</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"It''s All Right with Me" (Cole Porter)  3:21</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Red Top" (Lionel Hampton, Ben Kynard)  3:11</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"April in Paris" (Vernon Duke, Yip Harburg)  4:47</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"They Can''t Take That Away from Me" (George Gershwin, Ira Gershwin)  4:08</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"How Could You do a Thing Like That to Me" (Tyree Glenn, Allan Roberts)  3:59</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Where or When" (Richard Rodgers, Lorenz Hart)  3:06</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Erroll''s Theme" (Garner)  0:46</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 55, '2014-09-07 14:55:10', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:13:16', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-09-19 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 12, 'jazz, Erroll Garner', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1647, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(169, 'On this day in jazz (September 20)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-september-20', '', '<p>On this day in 1963,   <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jackie_McLean" target="_blank">Jackie McLean</a> recorded the album <em>Destination... Out!</em> at the Van Gelder Studio at Englewood Cliffs. The album consists of four songs, one of the a McLean original ("Kahlil the Prophet")--the other three were written by the session''s trombonist, Granchan Moncur III. <a href="http://www.bluenote.com/artists/bobby-hutcherson" target="_blank">Bobby Hutcherson</a> is also featured on this set playing the vibes, Larry Ridley is on the bass and Roy Haynes plays the drums. The album garners a 5-star rating from allmusic.com where Thom Jurek states: "<a href="http://www.allmusic.com/album/destination-out!-mw0000124614" target="_blank">If there was a perfect Blue Note session after John Coltrane''s Blue Train, this was it.</a>"</p>\n<p>Check out the <a href="index.php/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=107:on-this-day-in-jazz-july-20&catid=53:july&Itemid=41" target="_self">July 20 page</a> of my blog for an interesting story regarding Jackie and <a href="http://www.cmgww.com/music/parker/home.html" target="_blank">Charlie Parker</a>.</p>\n<p>Here''s Jackie with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=y8woYxaDjAM" target="_blank">Love and Hate</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=y8woYxaDjAM" target="_blank"><img src="http://jazzinphoto.files.wordpress.com/2013/10/a-profile-of-alto-saxophonist-jackie-mclean-during-the-recording-session-for-lee-morgans-leeway-album-1960.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Love and Hate" (Grachan Moncur III) - 8:25</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Esoteric" (Moncur) - 9:02</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Kahlil the Prophet" (Jackie McLean) - 10:23</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Riff Raff" (Moncur) - 7:07</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 55, '2014-09-07 15:25:30', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:12:49', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-09-20 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 4, 0, 11, '', '', 0, 1806, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(170, 'On this day in jazz (September 21)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-september-21', '', '<p>On this day in 1966,   organist<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jimmy_Smith_(musician)" target="_blank">Jimmy Smith</a> and guitarist<a href="http://www.wesmontgomery.com/" target="_blank">Wes Montgomery</a> began recording their third and forth collaboration,   <em>Jimmy & Wes: The Dynamic Duo</em> and <em>Further Adventures of Jimmy and Wes</em>. The album reached #1 on the jazz charts in 1967 and was as high as 129 on the Billboard charts. allmusic.com gives the album 5 stars.</p>\n<p>For more on Jimmy,   see the <a href="index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=143:on-this-day-in-jazz-august-25&catid=54:august&Itemid=41" target="_self">August 25th page</a>.</p>\n<p>Here''s Jimmy and Wes with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=blwgAhA5VZA" target="_blank">Down by the Riverside</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=blwgAhA5VZA" target="_blank"><img src="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/_hLY9DmXXlH4/TT7XsIA_fxI/AAAAAAAACbA/LApJTn9eeAA/s1600/capa.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Down by the Riverside" (Traditional) - 10:02</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Night Train" (Duke Ellington) - 6:46</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"James and Wes" (Jimmy Smith) - 8:13</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"13 (Death March)" (Gary McFarland) - 5:22</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Baby, It''s Cold Outside" (Frank Loesser) - 6:05</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"O.G.D. (aka Road Song)" (Wes Montgomery) - Alternative Take - 5:13</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 55, '2014-09-07 16:00:40', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:12:33', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-09-21 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 3, 0, 10, '', '', 0, 1934, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(171, 'On this day in jazz (September 22)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-september-22', '', '<p>On this day in 1953,   <a href="http://www.cmgww.com/music/parker/home.html" target="_blank">Charlie Parker</a> recorded music that would later be released as the album <em>At Storyville</em>. The album consists of two broadcasts: one while he was accompanied by the Red Garland Trio and the other features trumpeter Herb Pomeroy and pianist Sir Charles Thompson. The album features Bird in top form playing some of his favorite songs.</p>\n<p>Charlie Parker is one of jazz all-time greatest saxophonists. He was awarded 4 Grammys during his life,   has been inducted into numerous hall of fames posthumously,   and has even had a recording selected by the Library of Congress to be part of the National Recording Registry. In 1995, he sas one of several jazz musicians to see their likenesses on USA postage stamps.</p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Here''s Bird with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vnFgaZt2E-s" target="_blank">Moose the Mooche</a>":</span></p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vnFgaZt2E-s" target="_blank"><img src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/6/61/Charlie_Parker%2C_Tommy_Potter%2C_Miles_Davis%2C_Max_Roach_%28Gottlieb_06941%29.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Moose The Mooche  Charlie Parker 5:05</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">I''ll Walk Alone  Styne, Cahn 4:53</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Ornithology  Harris, Parker 4:23</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Out Of Nowhere  Heyman, Green 4:34</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Now''s The Time  Charlie Parker 4:11</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Don''t Blame Me  Fields, McHugh 4:58</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Dancing On The Ceiling  Rodgers-Hart 2:29</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Cool Blues  Charlie Parker 4:44</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Groovin'' High  Gillespie 5:04</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 55, '2014-09-18 20:25:39', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:12:20', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-09-22 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 3, 0, 9, 'jazz, Charlie Parker', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1599, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(172, 'On this day in jazz (September 23)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-september-23', '', '<p>On this day in 1971,   <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Mingus" target="_blank">Charles Mingus</a> (my favorite bassist) began recording <em>Let My Children Hear Music</em> which is a studio album arranged for large ensemble. Mingus thanked produced Teo Macero afterwards for "his untiring efforts in producing the best album I have ever made". Allmusic gives the album 5 stars and says: <em>Let My Children Hear Music</em> is a towering achievement and a must for any serious jazz fan." Take a listen to this,   Mingus'' favorite album, and you will realize why Charles was one of America''s greatest composers.</p>\n<p>For more on Charles, see the <a href="index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=100:on-this-day-in-jazz-july-13&catid=53:july&Itemid=41" target="_self">July 13th page</a>.</p>\n<p>The entire album is <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TKd_f2QBpvQ" target="_blank">here</a>:</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TKd_f2QBpvQ" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/6a00e008dca1f08834017d3e649175970c-500wi.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Shoes of the Fisherman''s Wife Are Some Jiveass Slippers"  9:34</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Adagio ma Non Troppo"  8:22</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Don''t Be Afraid, the Clown''s Afraid Too"  9:26</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Taurus in the Arena of Life"  4:17</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Hobo Ho"  10:07</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Chill of Death"  7:38</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The I of Hurricane Sue"  10:09</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 55, '2014-09-18 20:29:09', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:12:06', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-09-23 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 4, 0, 8, 'jazz, Charles Mingus', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1616, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(173, 'On this day in jazz (September 24)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-september-24', '', '<p>On this day in 1984,   Memphis, Tennessee''s own <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frank_Lowe" target="_blank">Frank Lowe</a> began recording <em>Decision In Paradise</em>. Frank was joined on this recording by trumpeter Don Cherry, trombonist Grachan Moncur III, pianist Geri Allen, bassist Charnette Moffett and drummer Charles Moffett. Scott Yanow said this of the album:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">Although a touch more conservative than one might expect (more of an open-minded straightahead set than music emphasizing sound explorations), all six group originals are of interest including Lowe''s unaccompanied performance on Butch Morris''s "I''ll Whistle Your Name" and Moncur''s whimsical "You Dig."</p>\n<p>Frank, as mentioned above, was born and raised in Memphis. He later moved to San Francisco and began playing the tenor saxophone. He recorded with Sun Ra and Alice Coltrane early in his career, and was an important part of the free jazz movement in the late 60s and 70s. He died on September 19, 2003 of lung cancer.</p>\n<p>Here''s Frank with "<a href="https://play.spotify.com/trackset/mediabar/3L2lXTAIwBWnWFwjnfxyXH%2C0OHW17JuFH1se1a8x1qug3%2C5MWChx6qtIgTMPrlo9pSpt%2C3MxvwbBFx5q8HjZfMBNq6B%2C7CPRXDXiY9gDBAfJJJA7JS%2C7wpmVxfHsfIgFfiBcXmfkP%2C4cux1d4jol59ZCe0awlijo%2C4c6h8eOYIE5DvO5hjBjsi2%2C38rIS7iqkJelEK9asRwqg1%2C5aYKVD1bsu83Vd839Jop2u%2C1I6DeVJO4IHxl5AP5x6J0x%2C3fJMHKWp1iM5PF0gzCuGen%2C4U6X0lb7TgHr4Q2NIe2DEn/%23/4" target="_blank">Decision in Paradise</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://play.spotify.com/trackset/mediabar/3L2lXTAIwBWnWFwjnfxyXH%2C0OHW17JuFH1se1a8x1qug3%2C5MWChx6qtIgTMPrlo9pSpt%2C3MxvwbBFx5q8HjZfMBNq6B%2C7CPRXDXiY9gDBAfJJJA7JS%2C7wpmVxfHsfIgFfiBcXmfkP%2C4cux1d4jol59ZCe0awlijo%2C4c6h8eOYIE5DvO5hjBjsi2%2C38rIS7iqkJelEK9asRwqg1%2C5aYKVD1bsu83Vd839Jop2u%2C1I6DeVJO4IHxl5AP5x6J0x%2C3fJMHKWp1iM5PF0gzCuGen%2C4U6X0lb7TgHr4Q2NIe2DEn/%23/4" target="_blank"><img src="http://bells.free-jazz.net/files/2007/08/lowe.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Decision in Paradise - 5:05</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I''ll Whistle Your Name" (Butch Morris) - 3:27</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Cherryco" (Don Cherry) - 6:03</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Lowe-Ologie" - 5:28</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"You Dig!" (Grachan Moncur III) - 8:23</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Dues and Don''ts" - 10:57</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 55, '2014-09-18 20:34:47', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:11:49', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-09-24 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 3, 0, 7, 'jazz, Frank Lowe', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1965, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(174, 'On this day in jazz (September 25)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-september-25', '', '<p>On this day in 1970,   tenor saxophonist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joe_Henderson" target="_blank">Joe Henderson</a> recorded two tracks that would be later released on his album <em>In Pursuit of Blackness</em>. These tracks were recorded at the Lighthouse Cafe in Hermosa Beach and feature Woody Shaw on trumpet,   Ron McClure on bass and Lenny White on drums. The rest of the album was recorded on May 12, 1971 at the Decca Studios in NYC.</p>\n<p>While "Gazelle" is featured below, you might also want to check out "Mind Over Matter". Vincent Thomas said this of the song:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">free-form, expressionist, abstract improv and then, in a short contained explosion, Henderson starts blowing his tenor like he''s spitting out rounds of bullets from a gun. A torrent solo follows and, just when you think the song won''t let up, in comes Curtis Fuller''s trombone and then Pete Yellen''s flute. The song ends with what almost sounds like the soundtrack to an absurd dream. It''s a 13-minute tune broken up into suites and, although it may not be the album''s best, it''s possibly its most enthralling, and it typifies this album''s place in Henderson''s Milestone discography -- not his best, but enthralling</p>\n<p>Here''s Joe with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=n6ELKlpmItY" target="_blank">Gazelle</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=n6ELKlpmItY" target="_blank"><img src="http://www.melmartin.com/gifs_jpegs/j_hender.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"No Me Esqueca" - 7:08</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Invitation" (Bronislau Kaper) - 7:34</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"A Shade of Jade" - 7:45</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Gazelle" - 7:33</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Mind Over Matter" - 13:19</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 55, '2014-09-18 20:40:24', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:11:33', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-09-25 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 3, 0, 6, 'jazz', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1695, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(175, 'On this day in jazz (September 26)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-september-26', '', '<p>On this day in 1962,   Duke Ellington and John Coltrane recorded an eponymous album at Rudy Van Gelder''s studio in Englewood Cliffs at the paladromic ages of 63 and 36. Mostly, we hear Duke playing backed by a big band, but here we have a more intimate quartet setting. John Coltrane said this of the recording:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">I was really honored to have the opportunity of working with Duke. It was a wonderful experience. He has set standards I haven''t caught up with yet. I would have liked to have worked over all those numbers again, but then I guess the performances wouldn''t have had the same spontaneity. And they mightn''t have been any better!</p>\n<p>Coltrane was in the height of his form playing both tenor and soprano saxophone. Jimmy Garrison and Aaron Bell played bass while Elvin Jones and Sam Woodyard played drums.</p>\n<div>Here''s Duke and Trane with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sCQfTNOC5aE" target="_blank">In A Sentimental Mood</a>":</div>\n<div><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sCQfTNOC5aE" target="_blank"><img src="http://www.stockplay.es/WebRoot/StoreLES/Shops/62028221/4D20/CE22/0E89/587A/B31A/C0A8/28B8/2EB9/LP-39_056.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></div>\n<div>Track listing:</div>\n<div>\n<div><ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"In a Sentimental Mood"  4:14</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Take The Coltrane"  4:42</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Big Nick"  4:30</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Stevie"  4:22</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"My Little Brown Book"  5:20</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Angelica"  6:00</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Feeling of Jazz"  5:34</span></li>\n</ol></div>\n</div>', '', 1, 8, 0, 55, '2014-09-18 20:46:08', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:11:15', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-09-26 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 5, 0, 5, 'jazz, Duke Ellington, John Coltrane', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1629, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(176, 'On this day in jazz (September 27)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-september-27', '', '<p>On this day in 1967,   <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joe_Henderson" target="_blank">Joe Henderson</a> began recording the studio album,   <em>Tetragon</em>.</p>\n<p>Joe was born into a large family of 9 brothers and 5 sisters. His musical studies were strongly supported by his parents,and he quickly took up several instruments. Before turning professional, he was in the army from 1960 until 1962 where he won first place in a talent show and was later chosen to embark on a world tour to entertain soldiers. During this tour he met Kenny Drew and Kenny Clarke in Paris which further encouraged him to become a professional musician. Upon being discharged he moved to New York where he met trumpeter Kenny Dorham who took him to see Dexter Gordon at Birdland. That night, Gordon invited Henderson to play him. Thus began a very successful career.</p>\n<p>Here''s Joe with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BJHmeDn9h80" target="_blank">I''ve Got You Under My Skin</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BJHmeDn9h80" target="_blank"><img src="http://www.thepianoshed.com/uploads/2/0/1/1/20117713/3769447_orig.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Invitation" (Kaper, Webster) - 6:18</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"R.J." (Carter) - 5:38</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Bead Game" (Henderson, Konitz) - 8:39</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Tetragon" - 5:40</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Waltz for Zweetie" (Bishop) - 4:29</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"First Trip" (Carter) - 5:15</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I''ve Got You Under My Skin" (Porter) - 4:59</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 55, '2014-09-18 21:00:23', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:10:56', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-09-27 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 3, 0, 4, 'jazz, Joe Henderson', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1920, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(177, 'On this day in jazz (September 28)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-september-28', '', '<p>On this day in 1968,   <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prince_Lasha" target="_blank">Prince Lasha</a> (alto saxophone,   flute, alto clarinet) and <a href="http://www.sonnysimmons.org/" target="_blank">Sonny Simmons</a> (alto saxophone, english horn) recorded their second album together: <em>Firebirds</em>. They are joined on the album by Bassist Buster Williams, drummer Charles Moffett and the great vibraphonist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bobby_Hutcherson" target="_blank">Bobby Hutcherson</a>.</p>\n<p>The album is an "Album Pick" at allmusic.com. Scott Yanow describes the album as "<span style="line-height: 1.3em;">influenced by (but not too derivative of) Ornette Coleman''s free jazz style, and the improvisations are pretty advanced and sometimes quite emotional. Lasha and Simmons made for a potent team, making one wish that they would have a reunion someday. An underrated classic of its kind."</span></p>\n<p>Here''s Prince and Sonny with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ubKOPZmyl3E" target="_blank">Firebirds</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ubKOPZmyl3E" target="_blank"><img src="http://www.sonnysimmons.org/images/Sonny08.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Island Song" </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">8:47</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Psalm of Solomon" </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">10:45</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Prelude to Bird" </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">3:53</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Loved Ones" </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">5:21</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Firebirds" 10:05</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 55, '2014-09-18 21:15:46', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:10:16', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-09-28 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 3, 0, 3, 'jazz, Prince Lasha, Sonny Simmons', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1743, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(178, 'On this day in jazz (September 29)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-september-29', '', '<p>On this day in 1984,   jazz violinist<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Billy_Bang" target="_blank"> Billy Bang</a> completed recording of the studio album "The Fire From Within". The album has been called "the perfect entree for Billy Bang newcomers". Joining Billy on the album are Ahmed Abdullah on trumpet,   Oscar Sanders on guitar, William Parker on bass, Thurman Barker playing the marimbas, and John Betsch on drums and (give me more) <a href="http://www.hulu.com/watch/536145" target="_blank">cowbell</a>. By the way, if you try to find the album on rhapsody.com, it''s listed under Ahmed''s name instead of Billy''s.</p>\n<p>A little about Billy: his family moved to the Bronx while he was still an infant. He attended a special school for musicians in Harlem where students were first assigned instruments based on their size. The small Billy Bang was assigned the violin and the rest is history.</p>\n<p>Here''s Billy with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-kAyOqw1nwY" target="_blank">Inorganic Beings</a>"</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-kAyOqw1nwY" target="_blank"><img src="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/-0JujZBlkBb0/TaRVlkUpyuI/AAAAAAAAAU4/t0XbfibKLjw/s320/billy%2Bbang.jpg" border="0" width="200" height="200" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Glow of Awareness" - 5:38</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Nagual Julian" - 5:46</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Shift Below" - 6:24</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Petty Tyrants" - 5:32</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The New Seers" - 10:41</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Mold of Man" - 7:34</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Inorganic Beings" - 5:29</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>\n<p></p>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 55, '2014-09-18 21:28:39', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:10:02', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-09-29 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 3, 0, 2, 'jazz, Billy Bang', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1736, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(395, 'On this day in jazz (April 30)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-april-30', '', '<p>On this day in 1974,   saxophonist Jan Garbarek (with the assistance of the Sdfunk-Sinfonieorchester conducted by Mladen Gutesha) recorded the album <em>Luminessence</em> at Tonstudio Bauer, Ludwigsburg. The album consists of three songs all written by the wonderful pianist <a href="http://www.keithjarrett.org/" target="_blank">Keith Jarrett</a> (the real reason for me highlighting this album). The songs have been described as "angst-ridden" pieces. The songs were actually written to be played by string orchestra (Jarrett is just as good of a classical musician as he is jazz--just don''t listen to his folk rock stuff!) and Jan Garbarek improvises on both tenor and soprano saxes.</p>\n<p>Richard Ginell, writing for allmusic.com said this of the album:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">The concept is not unlike that of Stan Getz''s Focus, but this music is far more static, downcast, and free of the pulse of jazz. As was characteristic of his writing then, Jarrett''s string parts are mostly turgid and thick-set, indulging in weird, sliding microtones on "Windsong," weighted down by some kind of emotional burden.</p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Here''s Jan with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wz9RbPqATrs" target="_blank">Numinior</a>":</span></p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wz9RbPqATrs" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/5696.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Numinor" - 13:49</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Windsong" - 6:32</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Luminessence" - 15:23</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 62, '2015-04-26 15:08:02', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:37:50', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-04-30 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 1, 'on this day in jazz', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1969, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(179, 'On this day in jazz (September 30)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-september-30', '', '<p>On this day in 1966,   the great pianist <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/wynton-kelly-mn0000684253/biography" target="_blank">Wynton Kelly</a> completed his penultimate album as a leader. It was entitled <em>Full View</em> and featured <a href="http://www.jimmycobb.net/" target="_blank">Jimmy Cobb</a> on drums and Ron McClure on bass. The album contains mostly standards such as "Autumn Leaves",   but also includes the Burt Bacharach hit "Walk on By" as well as one original from Wynton, "Scufflin''".</p>\n<p>For more about Wynton, see the <a href="index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=130:on-this-day-in-jazz-august-12&catid=54:august&Itemid=41" target="_self">August 12 page</a> of my blog.</p>\n<p>Here''s Wynton with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jdQpVXyEYTk" target="_blank">What a Diff''rence a Day Made</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jdQpVXyEYTk" target="_blank"><img src="http://www.weblo.com/music/images/artists/full/Wynton_Kelly_48f71b9653460.jpg" border="0" width="260" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I Want a Little Girl" (Murray Mencher, Billy Moll) - 4:42</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I Thought" (Rudy Stevenson) - 4:51</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"What a Diff''rence a Day Made" (Stanley Adams, Mara Grever) - 4:47</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Autumn Leaves" (Joseph Kosma, Johnny Mercer, Jacques Prvert) - 3:51</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Don''t Cha Hear Me Callin'' to Ya" (Stevenson) - 4:27</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"On a Clear Day (You Can See Forever)" (Burton Lane, Alan Jay Lerner) - 3:14</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Scufflin''" (Wynton Kelly) - 3:02</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Born to Be Blue" (Mel Torm, Robert Wells) - 4:07</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Walk on By" (Burt Bacharach, Hal David) - 3:15</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 55, '2014-09-20 16:28:55', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:39:56', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-09-30 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 4, 0, 1, 'Wynton Kelly, jazz', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1712, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(180, 'On this day in jazz (October 01)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-october-01', '', '<p>On this day in 1965,   the great pianist <a href="http://www.horacesilver.com/" target="_blank">Horace Silver</a> began recording <em>The Cape Verdean Blues</em> with his quartet and the wonderful trombonist <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/jj-johnson-mn0000119111/biography" target="_self">J. J. Johnson</a>. The title of the album,   as well as the music, was inspired by John Tavares Silva (Horace''s father), who was born in Maio, Cape Verde. The album would be completed 3 weeks later on October 22. If you are unfamiliar with Hoarace''s quartet, it included legends<a href="http://www.woodyshaw.com/" target="_blank">Woody Shaw</a> on trumpet and<a href="http://www.joehendersonsax.com/" target="_blank">Joe Henderson</a> on tenor saxophone. The rhythm section was rounded out with Ben Cranshaw on bass and Roger Humphries on the drums. See my <a href="index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=176:on-this-day-in-jazz-september-27&catid=55:september&Itemid=41" target="_self">September 27 page</a> for more on Joe Henderson.</p>\n<p>I''ll say more about Horace later in the month when I profile "Song for My Father", which is probably his most famous album.</p>\n<p>Here''s Horace with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0gt7QXwYpZo" target="_blank">The Cape Verdean Blues</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0gt7QXwYpZo" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/horace-silver.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Cape Verdean Blues" - 4:59</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The African Queen" - 9:36</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Pretty Eyes" - 7:30</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Nutville" - 7:15</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Bonita" - 8:37</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Mo'' Joe" (Joe Henderson) - 5:46</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 56, '2014-09-20 16:32:04', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:16:12', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-10-01 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 4, 0, 35, 'jazz, Horace Silver', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2630, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(181, 'On this day in jazz (October 02)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-october-02', '', '<p>On this day in 1939,   the great Charlie Christian was first recorded with the Benny Goodman sextet. Charlie was the first jazz virtuoso of the electric guitar who was a key figure in the transition of jazz from swing to bebop. Charlie was quite a bit ahead of him time, and Goodman has been quoted as saying "Who the hell wants to hear an electric guitar player?" before granting Charlie his audition.</p>\n<p>Charlie was born into a musical family in which his mother and father were said to have accompanied silent films at a local movie theater. The family moved to Oklahoma City (which was a major stopping point for bands traveling from the east coast to west coast) were he was exposed to musicians such as Louie Armstrong, Count Basie, Cab Calloway, Duke Ellington, Fletcher Henderson, Earl Hines and Chick Webb. Charlie was inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame in 1990.</p>\n<p>Here''s Charlie and Benny with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gT-fQDn0ebs" target="_blank">Stardust</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gT-fQDn0ebs" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/charlie-christian.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 56, '2014-09-20 16:51:05', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:16:37', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-10-02 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 3, 0, 34, 'Charlie Christian, jazz', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2052, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(182, 'On this day in jazz (October 03)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-october-03', '', '<p>On this day in 1969,   <a href="http://www.herbiehancock.com/home.php">Herbie Hancock</a> released <em>Fat Albert Rotunda</em>. The music was made for the TV special "Hey,   Hey, Hey, It''s Fat Albert", which, of course, inspired the creation of the "<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fat_Albert_and_the_Cosby_Kids" target="_blank">Fat Albert and the Cosby Kids</a>" TV show which would play on Saturday mornings throughout my early childhood.</p>\n<p>The album in important in that Herbie changed his style significantly from his earlier recordings. On this album, you will hear soul music rather than jazz as the basis of the works and foreshadow his upcoming jazz/funk style that he would play a few years later. The whole album is available on youtube, but here''s one of my favorites, "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4wNY9JFR-KY" target="_blank">Fat Mama</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4wNY9JFR-KY" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/herbie-hancock-synth.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Wiggle-Waggle" - (5:51)</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Fat Mama" - (3:49)</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Tell Me a Bedtime Story" - (5:01)</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Oh! Oh! Here He Comes" - (4:08)</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Jessica" - (4:13)</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Fat Albert Rotunda" - (6:29)</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Lil'' Brother" - (4:26)</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 56, '2014-09-20 17:07:31', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:16:47', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-10-03 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 4, 0, 33, 'jazz, Herbie Hancock', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2034, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(183, 'On this day in jazz (October 04)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-october-04', '', '<p>On this day in 1972,   trumpeter <a href="http://www.freddiehubbardmusic.com/" target="_blank">Freddie Hubbard</a> started recording <em>Sky Dive</em> at the Van Gelder Studios in Englewood Cliffs, NJ. Freddie was joined by a stellar line up including <a href="http://www.keithjarrett.org/" target="_blank">Keith Jarrett</a> on piano, <a href="http://www.georgebenson.com/" target="_blank">George Benson</a> on guitar, <a href="http://roncarter.net/JazzMaster/" target="_blank">Ron Carter</a> on the bass, and <a href="http://www.billycobham.com/" target="_blank">Billy Cobham</a> on drums (just to name a few). The album includes a couple of originals by Freddie (including the title track) as well as "In the Mist" by the great Bix Beiderbecke and the theme from "The Godfather". Strings also accompany the band on the album with arrangements by Don Sebesky.</p>\n<p>Freddie hailed from Indianapolis and played early in his career with jazz legends such as <a href="http://www.artblakey.com/" target="_blank">Art Blakey</a>, <a href="http://www.johncoltrane.com/" target="_blank">John Coltrane</a> and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ornette_Coleman" target="_blank">Ornette Coleman</a>. In 1961, he recorded a very influential album "Ready for Freddie" with <a href="http://www.wayneshorter.com/" target="_blank">Wayne Shorter</a>. He was awarded a Jazz Master Award (the nation''s highest jazz honor) in 2006 by the National Endowment for the Arts.</p>\n<p>Here''s Freddie with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_z3mNMsro0U" target="_blank">Sky Dive</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_z3mNMsro0U" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Freddie_Hubbard1_medium.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Povo" (Hubbard) - 14:46</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"In a Mist" (Beiderbecke) - 7:05</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Naturally" (Adderley) - 5:56</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Godfather (Theme)" (Rota) - 7:23</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Sky Dive" (Hubbard) - 7:37</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Naturally" [Alternate Take] - 5:03 Bonus track on CD</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 56, '2014-09-21 17:51:48', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:16:57', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-10-04 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 3, 0, 32, 'jazz, Freddie Hubbard', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2045, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(184, 'On this day in jazz (October 05)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-october-05', '', '<p>On this day in 1951,   the great <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a> recorded <em>Dig</em> at Apex Stdio in New York City. The importance of the album is the fact that despite Miles'' creation of cool jazz just a couple of years earlier, he became indifferent to it and changed his style almost immediately and tinkered with styles that would eventually lead to the modal movement of the late fifties. Also of note, this was the first jazz recording of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jackie_McLean" target="_blank">Jackie McLean</a>. Joining Miles and Jackie was a rhythm section consisting of pianist Walter Bishop, bassist Tommy Potter and legendary drummer <a href="http://www.artblakey.com/" target="_blank">Art Blakey</a>. Saxophone colossus <a href="http://sonnyrollins.com/" target="_blank">Sonny Rollins</a> also joined in as a member of the sextet.</p>\n<p>Here''s Miles with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1F75XdUYYHo" target="_blank">Dig</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1F75XdUYYHo" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/220px-Dig_MilesDavis.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Dig" (7:33)</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"It''s Only A Paper Moon" (5:23)</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Denial" (5:39)</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Bluing" (9:55)</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Out of the Blue" (6:15)</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Conception" (4:01)</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"My Old Flame" (6:34)</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 56, '2014-09-21 17:57:53', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:17:23', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-10-05 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 3, 0, 31, 'Miles Davis, jazz', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2070, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(185, 'On this day in jazz (October 06)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-october-06', '', '<p>On this day in 1960,   multi-instrumentalist <a href="http://www.yuseflateef.com/" target="_blank">Dr. Yusef Lateef</a> began recording <em>The Centaur and the Phoenix</em>. Yusef plays arghul,   flute, oboe and tenor saxophone, and was joined by Richard Williams on trumpet, the great <a href="http://clarkterry.com/" target="_blank">Clark Terry</a> on flugelhorn and trumpet, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Curtis_Fuller" target="_blank">Curtis Fuller</a> on trombone and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joe_Zawinul" target="_blank">Joe Zawinul</a> at the piano on this visionary recording.</p>\n<p>He was born William Emanuel Huddleston but converted to Islam in 1950 and took the name Yusef Lateef. He passed away in December of 2013. Although he played tenor sax and flute which, of course, were common to jazz, he also added oboe, bassoon, bamboo flute, shanai, shofar, xun, arghul and koto to his recordings and was one of the first jazz musicians to add Eastern influences to the repertoire. In addition to being a great musician, he was also a writer who wrote several books (including two novellas and two short story collections).</p>\n<p>Here''s Yusef Lateef with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IwB1Vrqs51Q" target="_blank">The Centaur and the Pheonix</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IwB1Vrqs51Q" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Yusef_Lateef_1971_Hamburg_%28Heinrich_Klaff_Collection_2%29.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Revelation" (Kenny Barron) - 6:02</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Apathy" - 5:25</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Ev''ry Day (I Fall in Love)" (Sammy Fain, Irving Kahal) - 6:59</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Centaur and the Phoenix" (Charles Mills) - 5:37</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Iqbal" - 4:51</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Summer Song" (Mills) - 5:26</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Philanthropist" - 4:02</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Jungle Fantasy" (Esy Morales) - 2:42</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Titora" (Billy Taylor) - 2:25</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 56, '2014-09-21 18:44:35', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:17:37', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-10-06 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 3, 0, 30, 'jazz, Yusef Lateef', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1934, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(305, 'On this day in jazz (January 30)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-january-30', '', '<p>On this day in 1956,  the one and only <a href="http://mingusmingusmingus.com/" target="_blank">Charles Mingus</a> recorded <em>Pithecanthropus Erectus</em>. Playing with Charles on the album were <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jackie_McLean" target="_blank">Jackie McLean</a> on alto saxophone,   J. R. Monterose on tenor saxophone, Mal Waldron on piano and Willie Jones on the drums. The album has received the highest rating possible by virtually all rating services and magazines, was selected to be part of the Penguin Guide to Jazz''s Core Collection and sits comfortably inside the top 100 jazz albums rated at <a href="http://jazz100.sffjazz.com/top100.html" target="_blank">sffjazz.com</a>.</p>\n<p>The title refers to species of humans also known as "java man". The song "Pithecanthropus Erectus" is an "epical" recording lasting over 10 minutes long whose aim was to depict the rise of man from PE to the modern day. PE is essentially translated as "Upright Apeman". Mingus played the upright bass, so his probably making a joke here, too.</p>\n<p>Here''s Charles with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QUo5gD6WlyA" target="_blank">A Foggy Day</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QUo5gD6WlyA" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/6a00e008dca1f08834017d3e649175970c-500wi.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing (songs by Charles except for #2):</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Pithecanthropus Erectus"  10:36</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"A Foggy Day"  7:50 (George Gershwin)</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Profile of Jackie"  3:11</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Love Chant"  14:59</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 59, '2015-01-09 18:13:38', 62, '', '2016-08-16 22:02:32', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-01-30 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 3, 'on this day in jazz, Charles Mingus', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2418, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(186, 'On this day in jazz (October 07)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-october-07', '', '<p>On this day in 1962,   <a href="http://www.ericdolphy.net/" target="_blank">Eric Dolphy</a> recorded <em>At the Gaslight Inn</em> with pianist <a href="http://www.herbiehancock.com/home.php" target="_blank">Herbie Hancock</a>.This recording was made shortly after Dolphy invited Hancock to join his band. The association was short and produced only a couple of live recordings; however, despite the brevity of the collaboration, both were innovative geniuses and the result was this historic recording. Dolphy played several instruments (alto saxophone, flute, and bass clarinet). In fact, he is considered to be the first important bass clarinet soloist in jazz. I have always enjoyed listening to the flute, and Eric is certainly one of my favorites along with <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buddy_Collette" target="_blank">Buddy Collette</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Herbie_Mann" target="_blank">Herbie Mann</a> and <a href="http://www.yuseflateef.com/" target="_blank">Yusef Lateef</a>.</p>\n<p>Unfortunately, Eric would only live another year and a half after this recording was made. He died in Berlin on June 29, 1964. The details of his death are disputed, but it is generally believed that he died due falling into a diabetic coma (this condition had not been diagnosed previously). Some said that he collapsed in this hotel room; however, others state that he collapsed on stage and the attending physicians believed the collapse was related to substance abuse (as was common to jazz musicians of that time) and was left in a hospital bed for the drugs to run their course which caused his death.</p>\n<p>He is remembered for a style which used wide intervals on the twelve tone scale and for reproducing human and animal-like effects which seemed to make his instruments speak. Dolphy usually is classified as an avant-garde improviser whose compositions "had a logic uncharacteristic of many other free jazz musicians of the day".</p>\n<p>Here''s Eric with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aNjy0G_lnMY" target="_blank">Miss Ann</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aNjy0G_lnMY" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/426x500xeric-dolphy-val-wilmer.jpg.pagespeed.ic.WcLh1q5NDH.jpg" border="0" width="213" height="250" /><br /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 56, '2014-09-26 21:27:39', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:17:58', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-10-07 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 29, 'Eric Dolphy, jazz', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1983, '');
