INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(189, 'On this day in jazz (October 08)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-october-08', '', '<p>On this day in 1965,   <a href="http://www.andrewhilljazz.com/" target="_blank">Andew Hill</a> recorded <em>Compulsion!!!!</em> at the Van Gelder Studios in Englewood Cliffs,   NJ (Van Gelder would remaster this album in 2006). Joining the pianist on the album were <a href="http://www.freddiehubbardmusic.com/" target="_blank">Freddie Hubbard</a> who played trumpet and flugelhorn, John Gilmore on tenor saxophone and bass clarinet, <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/cecil-mcbee-mn0000739015/biography" target="_blank">Cecil McBee</a> on the bass, and Joe Chambers on drums.</p>\n<p>Hill was born in Chicago in 1931 where he took up the piano at age 13 and attended the University of Chicago Experimental School. As a teenager he joined legends such as<a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a> and <a href="http://www.cmgww.com/music/parker/home.html" target="_blank">Charlie Parker</a> when their tours came to town. In the 1950s he played with jazz greats such as <a href="http://www.ericdolphy.net/" target="_blank">Eric Dolphy</a>, <a href="http://www.bluenote.com/artists/bobby-hutcherson" target="_blank">Bobby Hutcherson</a>, <a href="http://www.joehendersonsax.com/" target="_blank">Joe Henderson</a>, <a href="http://www.freddiehubbardmusic.com/" target="_blank">Freddie Hubbard</a>, <a href="http://www.woodyshaw.com/" target="_blank">Woody Shaw</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hank_Mobley" target="_blank">Hank Mobley</a> and Tony Williams (just to name a few). In 1961, while he was an accompanist for <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dinah_Washington" target="_blank">Dinah Washington</a>, he moved to New York City and shortly thereafter primarily recorded as a leader.</p>\n<p>Don''t think that Andrew''s career ended in the 1960s--he continued recording until his death in 2007. In fact, just in the years 2000-2008, he won the following awards:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">2008: National Endowment for the Arts (NEA) Jazz Master (our nation''s highest jazz honor)</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">2007: election to the Downbeat Hall of Fame; Jazz Journalist Association Pianist of the Year, Composer of the Year and Lifetime Achievement Award; conferred an honorary Doctorate of Music-Berklee College of Music</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">2006: Jazz Journalist Composer of Year Awards (as well as in 2000, 2001 and 2003); "Time Lines" was Down Beat Album of the Year; Playboy Jazz Artist of the Year</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">2001: "Dusk" was the Down Beat Album of the Year; Down Beat Winner Critics Poll Jazz (also in 2000)</p>\n<p>Here''s Andrew with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SJa-62A0Ogg" target="_blank">Compulsion</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SJa-62A0Ogg" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/HILLportrait1970.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Compulsion" - 14:15</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Legacy" - 5:50</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Premonition" - 10:32</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Limbo" - 10:17</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 56, '2014-09-26 21:54:39', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:18:34', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-10-08 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 28, 'jazz, Andrew Hill', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2176, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(188, 'On this day in jazz (October 07)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-october-07', '', '<p>On this day in 1962,   <a href="http://www.ericdolphy.net/" target="_blank">Eric Dolphy</a> recorded <em>At the Gaslight Inn</em> with pianist <a href="http://www.herbiehancock.com/home.php" target="_blank">Herbie Hancock</a>.This recording was made shortly after Dolphy invited Hancock to join his band. The association was short and produced only a couple of live recordings. Despite the brevity of the collaboration,   both were innovative geniuses,   making this an historic recording. Dolphy played several instruments (alto saxophone, flute, and bass clarinet). In fact, he is considered to be the first important bass clarinet soloist in jazz. I have always enjoyed listening to the flute, and Eric is certainly one of my favorites along with <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buddy_Collette" target="_blank">Buddy Collette</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Herbie_Mann" target="_blank">Herbie Mann</a> and <a href="http://www.yuseflateef.com/" target="_blank">Yusef Lateef</a>.</p>\n<p>Unfortunately, Eric would only live another year and a half after this recording was made. He died in Berlin on June 29, 1964. The details of his death are disputed, but it is generally believed that he died due falling into a diabetic coma (this condition had not been diagnosed previoously). Some said that he collapsed in this hotel room; however, others state that he collapsed on stage and the attending physicians believed the collapse was related to substance abuse (as was common to jazz musicians of that time) and was left in a hospital bed for the drugs to run their course which caused his death.</p>\n<p>He is remembered for a style which used wide intervals on the twelve tone scale and for reproducing human and animal-like effects which seemed to make his instruments speak. Dolphy usually is classified as an avant-garde improviser whose compositions "had a logic uncharacteristic of many other free jazz musicians of the day".</p>\n<p>Here''s Eric with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aNjy0G_lnMY" target="_blank">Miss Ann</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aNjy0G_lnMY" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/426x500xeric-dolphy-val-wilmer.jpg.pagespeed.ic.WcLh1q5NDH.jpg" border="0" width="213" height="250" /><br /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 56, '2014-09-26 21:39:01', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:18:21', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-10-07 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 4, 0, 16, 'Eric Dolphy, jazz', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2058, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(190, 'On this day in jazz (October 09)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-october-09', '', '<p>On this day in 1956,   pianist <a href="http://www.monkzone.com/" target="_blank">Thelonious Monk</a> began recording his studio album <em>Brilliant Corners</em>. The title track is one of Monk''s more complex songs,   and took a dozen takes (exceptionally strange for that time) before he was happy with the result. A great supporting cast including <a href="http://sonnyrollins.com/" target="_blank">Sonny Rollins</a> on tenor saxophone, <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/oscar-pettiford-mn0000896298/biography" target="_blank">Oscar Pettiford</a> on double bass, <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/max-roach-mn0000396372/biography" target="_blank">Max Roach</a> on drums and <a href="http://clarkterry.com/" target="_blank">Clark Terry</a> on trumpet make this one of the greatest jazz albums of all time. The album was recorded in three separate sessions and even includes Paul Chambers on the song "Bemsha Swing". In fact, the highly renowned <a href="http://www.downbeat.com/" target="_blank">Down Beat</a> magazine considered it the best album of the year (1957).</p>\n<p>With respect to other accolades, the album was one of fifty recordings chosen by the Library of Congress to be added to the National Recording Registry in 2003. The reference book <em>1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die</em> includes it also; and, in 1999, it was inducted into the Grammy Hall of Fame. sffjazz, which has been tracking the top 200 jazz albums of all time for several years now, lists it at #16. Check out their list <a href="http://jazz100.sffjazz.com/top100.html" target="_blank">here</a> (I find the list agrees pretty well with my estimations).</p>\n<p>Here''s Thelonious with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0TLEPQZIVOg" target="_blank">Brilliant Corners</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0TLEPQZIVOg" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Thelonious-Monk-008.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Brilliant Corners" </span><span style="white-space:pre"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">7:42</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Ba-Lue Bolivar Ba-Lues-Are" </span><span style="white-space:pre"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">13:24</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Pannonica" </span><span style="white-space:pre"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">8:50</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I Surrender, Dear" (Barry Harris)</span><span style="white-space:pre"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">5:25</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Bemsha Swing" (Thelonious Monk, Denzil Best)</span><span style="white-space:pre"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">7:42</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 56, '2014-09-28 16:31:08', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:19:16', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-10-09 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 27, 'jazz, Thelonious Monk', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2163, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(191, 'On this day in jazz (October 10)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-october-10', '', '<p>On this day in 1957,   <a href="http://www.stangetz.net/" target="_blank">Stan Getz</a> joined with the <a href="http://www.oscarpeterson.com/" target="_blank">Oscar Peterson</a> trio (Herb Ellis played guitar and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ray_Brown_(musician)" target="_blank">Ray Brown</a> played bass) to record <em>Stan Getz and the Oscar Peterson Trio</em>. If you''re not a big fan of jazz, you probably have still heard of Stan as he popularized the song "The Girl From Impanea" in 1964 with the great <a href="http://www.astrudgilberto.com/" target="_blank">Astrud Gilberto</a>. Getz became well known playing in Woody Herman''s big band in the 1940s before becoming a leader in the 1950s. Getz'' style definitely changed with the years as he moved from big band to bebop to cool jazz to third stream (a synthesis of jazz and classical music) and, of course, bossa nova--in fact he is a very large reason why you''ve heard the words "bossa nova" if you live in the USA.</p>\n<p>Here''s Stan with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FOXFG4YoSVM" target="_blank">I Want To Be Happy</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FOXFG4YoSVM" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/61prnekxfzL.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I Want to Be Happy" (Irving Caesar, Vincent Youmans)  7:35</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Pennies from Heaven" (Arthur Johnston, Johnny Burke)  5:16</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Ballad Medley: "Bewitched, Bothered and Bewildered"/"I Don''t Know Why (I Just Do)"/"How Long Has This Been Going On?"/"I Can''t Get Started"/"Polka Dots and Moonbeams" (Richard Rodgers, Lorenz Hart)/(Fred E. Ahlert, Roy Turk)/(George Gershwin, Ira Gershwin)/(Vernon Duke, I. Gershwin)/(Jimmy Van Heusen, Burke)  10:10</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I''m Glad There Is You" (Jimmy Dorsey, Paul Mertz)  4:38</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Tour''s End" (Stan Getz)  4:55</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I Was Doing All Right" (G. Gershwin, I. Gershwin)  4:08</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Bronx Blues" (Getz)  5:31</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 56, '2014-09-28 16:46:17', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:19:29', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-10-10 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 26, 'jazz, Stan Getz, Orcar Peterson', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2149, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(192, 'On this day in jazz (October 11)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-october-11', '', '<p>On this day in 1957,   drummer <a href="http://www.artblakey.com/" target="_blank">Art Blakey</a> finshed recording <em>Hard Drive</em> in New York City. Six of the seven songs on the album were recorded on this day--only "Deo-X" was recorded in the previous session. Joining Art on the session were Bill Hardman on trumpet,   Johnny Griffin on the tenor saxophone, Junior Mance on piano and Spanky DeBrest on bass.</p>\n<p>This album is just one of about seven or eight that Art recorded that year and precedes the legendary album "Moanin''" from 1958. The cover to the album says that the music "Is out of this world...and the next world, too". That may be a bit of hyperbole, but there are some rather good songs on it.</p>\n<p>If you are wondering if the title is anachronistic, it''s not. The hard drive was created a year before in 1956.</p>\n<p>Here''s Art with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lMNyZEIxO4Q" target="_blank">For Minors Only</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lMNyZEIxO4Q"><img src="images/tdij/art-blakey.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"For Minors Only" (Jimmy Heath) - 5:49</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Right Down Front" (Johnny Griffin) - 4:31</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Deo-X" (Bill Hardman) - 5:50</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Sweet Sakeena" (Hardman) - 5:06</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"For Miles and Miles" (Heath) - 5:24</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Krafty" (Griffin) - 6:35</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Late Spring" (Leon Mitchell) - 5:36</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 56, '2014-09-28 17:00:07', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:19:44', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-10-11 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 24, 'jazz, Art Blakey', 'ON THIS DAY IN JAZZ', 0, 19028, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(193, 'On this day in jazz (October 12)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-october-12', '', '<p>On this day in 1959,   pianist <a href="http://www.oscarpeterson.com/" target="_blank">Oscar Peterson</a> and his trio (i.e.,   bassist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ray_Brown_(musician)" target="_blank">Ray Brown</a> and drummer Ed Thigpen) recorded <em>Oscar Peterson Plays Porgy & Bess</em>. Oscar wasn''t the first jazz leader to record Porgy & Bess tunes--Miles Davis recorded an album a year earlier--but this recording is definitely worth the listen. allmusic.com considers "It Ain''t Necessarily So" and "I Got Plenty O'' Nuttin''" as the best tunes, but "Summertime" is pretty good too (maybe not as good as Miles''). Also, even though Oscar recorded the album just a year after Miles, the sound is definitely OP--so you definitely get a totally different feel than you get with Davis''. Personally, I''m looking forward to seeing "Porgy & Bess" performed by the <a href="http://www.lyricopera.org/porgy/" target="_blank">Chicago Symphony Opera this November</a>.</p>\n<p>A little about OP: Oscar was born in the West Indies, but moved to Montreal as a young child. The neighborhood he lived in (Little Burgundy) had a strong jazz culture, and Peterson picked up both the trumpet and piano at the age of five. He is considered one of the greatest jazz pianist of all time--so add a few of his recordings to your collection. If you like what you hear below, pick up the 5 CD set "The Complete Oscar Peterson Trio At The London House" as it features the same three musicians.</p>\n<p>Here''s Oscar with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Qka-UuXC79Q" target="_blank">(I Wants To Stay Here) I Love You, Porgy</a>"</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Qka-UuXC79Q" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/oscar-peterson-03.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I Got Plenty O'' Nuttin''"  6:26</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I Wants to Stay Here"  6:22</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Summertime"  3:50</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Oh, Dey''s So Fresh and Fine"  0:55</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Oh, Lawd, I''m on My Way!"  2:35</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"It Ain''t Necessarily So" (George Gershwin, Ira Gershwin)  4:01</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"There''s a Boat Dat''s Leavin'' Soon for New York"  7:13</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Oh Bess, Oh Where''s My Bess?"  4:56</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Here Come de Honey Man"  1:11</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Bess, You Is My Woman Now"  3:28</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 56, '2014-10-07 00:29:11', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:20:04', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-10-12 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 3, 0, 23, 'jazz, Oscar Peterson', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2132, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(194, 'On this day in jazz (October 13)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-october-13', '', '<p>On this day in 1954,   pianist <a href="http://www.davebrubeck.com/live/" target="_blank">Dave Brubeck</a> recorded "Stompin'' for Mili" and "Brother, Can You Spare A Dime" which would appear on his studio album <em>Brubeck Time</em>. Joining Dave on the album were alto saxophonist <a href="http://www.puredesmond.ca/" target="_blank">Paul Desmond</a>, Bob Bates on bass and Joe Dodge on drums. Dave was always interesting with respect to his experimentation to alternate time signatures, so his recording always come off having a sophisticated feel to them. I''ll do a page on "Time Out" next year, which is his most famous album.</p>\n<p>A little bit about "Stompin'' For Mili": first, Mili refers to photographer <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gjon_Mili" target="_blank">Gjon Mili</a> (famous Life magazine photographer who photographed some of the most famous artists in history like Pablo Picasso--google it). Here''s the story regarding the performance: Mili was somewhat reluctant to photograph the band during their session, and the band was somewhat intimidated by his presence. The first take of this song was very tentative and Mili''s opinion regarding it was quite dismissive. According to the liner notes on the album, this caused Brubeck''s "blood to boil" which led to the next take, which you can hear below, that Dave says was an "expression of rage and frustration".</p>\n<p>Here''s Dave Brubeck with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4Q__a39yWsg" target="_blank">Stompin'' for Mili</a>" (filmed by Gjon Mili, no less):</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4Q__a39yWsg" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/albumcoverDaveBrubeck-BrubeckTime.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Audrey" (Brubeck, Desmond)  3:35</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Jeepers Creepers" (Johnny Mercer, Harry Warren)  4:57</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Pennies From Heaven" (Johnny Burke, Arthur Johnston)  6:28</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Why Do I Love You?" (Jerome Kern, Oscar Hammerstein II)  5:42</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Stompin'' for Mili" (Brubeck, Desmond)  5:27</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Keepin'' Out of Mischief Now" (Andy Razaf, Fats Waller)  5:06</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"A Fine Romance" (Jerome Kern, Dorothy Fields)  3:48</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Brother, Can You Spare a Dime?" (Edgar Yipsel Harburg, Jay Gorney)  5:17</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 56, '2014-10-07 00:35:36', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:20:26', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-10-13 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 3, 0, 22, 'jazz, Dave Brubeck', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2158, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(304, 'On this day in jazz (January 29)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-january-29', '', '<p>On this day in 1968,   <a href="http://www.archieshepp.net/" target="_blank">Archie Shepp</a> recorded the album <em>The Way Ahead</em> for Impluse! Records at Rudy Van Gelder''s studio in Englewood Cliffs,  NJ. On this album you''ll hear Archie on his tenor sax,   Jimmy Owens on trumpet, <a href="http://www.grachanmoncur.com/" target="_blank">Granchan Moncur III</a> on the trombone, and a rhythm section of Walter Davis, Jr. on piano, <a href="http://roncarter.net/JazzMaster/" target="_blank">Ron Carter</a> on bass, and both <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roy_Haynes" target="_blank">Roy Haynes</a> and Beaver Harris on drums. The album is composed of four songs by Davis Jr., Moncur II, Shepp and one Duke Ellington/Irving Mills cover, "Sophisticated Lady".</p>\n<p>Archie was born in 1937 and is still active today (2015). He was born in Fort Lauderdale, FL, but raised from an early age in Philadelphia, PA. Although he studied piano, flute and alto sax, he settled on tenor sax as his instrument of choice. He also studied drama at Goddard College from 1955 to 1959 but quickly decided to make a career in music. In 1971 he started a 30-year tenure as music professor at the University of Massachusetts Amhurst.</p>\n<p>Here''s Archie with his original, "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rTio2HNRHxA" target="_blank">Fiesta</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rTio2HNRHxA" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/04.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Damn If I Know (The Stroller)" (Walter Davis Jr.) - 6:16</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Frankenstein" (Grachan Moncur III) - 13:50</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Fiesta" (Archie Shepp) - 9:54</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Sophisticated Lady" (Duke Ellington, Irving Mills, Mitchell Parish) - 7:08</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 59, '2015-01-09 17:57:15', 62, '', '2016-08-16 22:01:58', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-01-29 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 4, 'on this day in jazz, Archie Shepp', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2098, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(195, 'On this day in jazz (October 14)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-october-14', '', '<p>On this day in 1965,   <a href="http://www.johncoltrane.com/" target="_blank">John Coltrane</a> recorded <em>Kulu S Mama (Juno S Mama)</em> which would be the title track for his album"Kulu S Mama"--during a session where a large ensemble cast supported the saxophonist (for this track and the track "Selflessness"). The rest of the album was recorded with his standard quartet (i.e., a rhythm section featuring the great <a href="http://mccoytyner.com/" target="_blank">McCoy Tyner</a> on piano, Jimmy Garrison on bass, and Elvin Jones on drums).</p>\n<p>This album was the last one released in John''s lifetime as he passed away on July 17, 1967. John became very religious during the later years of his short life, and has actually been sainted by the African Orthodox Church. He is part of the 3,000 square foot <a href="http://www.allsaintscompany.org/dancing-saints-all-icons" target="_blank">painting of the Dancing Saints</a> of St. Gregory of Nyssa Episcopal Church in San Francisco. If this sounds strange to you, here''s what Samuel Freeman said regarding it in <em>The New York Times</em>:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">In both implicit and explicit ways, Coltrane also functioned as a religious figure. Addicted to heroin in the 1950s, he quit cold turkey, and later explained that he had heard the voice of God during his anguishing withdrawal. [...] In 1966, an interviewer in Japan asked Coltrane what he hoped to be in five years, and Coltrane replied, "A saint."</p>\n<p>Here''s John with "<span style="line-height: 15.8079996109009px;"><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ryMLO7Ed4d8" target="_blank">Kulu S Mama (Juno S Mama)</a>":</span></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 15.8079996109009px;"><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ryMLO7Ed4d8" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/JohnColtraneWiki.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></span></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 15.8079996109009px;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Kulu S Mama (Juno S Mama)" - 18:50</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Vigil" - 9:51</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Welcome" - 5:34</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 56, '2014-10-08 10:52:08', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:20:49', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-10-14 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 21, 'jazz, John Coltrane', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1988, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(196, 'On this day in jazz (October 15)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-october-15', '', '<p>On this day in 1957,   tenor saxophonist <a href="http://www.benwebster.dk/" target="_blank">Ben Webster</a> recorded <em>Soulville</em> with the Oscar Peterson Trio (<a href="http://www.oscarpeterson.com/" target="_blank">Oscar</a> on piano,   and the trio of Herb Ellis on guitar, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ray_Brown_(musician)" target="_blank">Ray Brown</a> on bass and Stan Levy on drums). The album would definitely be in my top 50 (if I had such a list) and even features some songs with Ben playing the piano instead of Oscar. allmusic.com said "Newcomers shouldn''t hesitate to start here.", so check it out if you''re still in the early stages of building your jazz collection.</p>\n<p>Here''s a great version of "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=X_dMvId7H-c" target="_blank">Makin'' Whoopie</a>" from Ben Webster:</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=X_dMvId7H-c" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Ben_Webster_1271_18x24_Dig_Ins_Gal_Final_copy.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Soulville" (Ben Webster)  8:03</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Late Date" (Webster)  7:13</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Time on My Hands" (Harold Adamson, Mack Gordon, Vincent Youmans)  4:16</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Lover, Come Back to Me" (Oscar Hammerstein II, Sigmund Romberg)  8:26</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Where Are You?" (Adamson, Jimmy McHugh)  4:41</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Makin'' Whoopee" (Walter Donaldson, Gus Kahn)  4:29</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Ill Wind (Harold Arlen, Ted Koehler)  3:30</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 56, '2014-10-08 11:08:36', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:21:01', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-10-15 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 20, 'jazz, Ben Webster', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2043, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(197, 'On this day in jazz (October 16)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-october-16', '', '<p>On this day in 1957,   Coleman Hawkins joined <a href="index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=196:on-this-day-in-jazz-october-15&catid=56:october&Itemid=41" target="_self">yesterday''s profiled artist</a>,   <a href="http://www.benwebster.dk/" target="_blank">Ben Webster</a> (with <a href="http://www.oscarpeterson.com/" target="_blank">Oscar Peterson</a> and the Oscar Peterson Trio),   to record "Coleman Hawkins Encounters Ben Webster".</p>\n<p>Hawkins, who was best known by his jazz friends as "Bean" (but sometimes referred to as "Hawk") was one of the first great tenor saxophonists. Hawkins was somewhat of a child prodigy, playing the piano and cello in his youth, picked up the saxophone at the ripe old age of nine and was playing concerts throughout his home state of Kansas by fourteen. As an adult, he moved to NYC and played with greats such as <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a>, <a href="http://www.monkzone.com/" target="_blank">Thelonious Monk</a> and <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/max-roach-mn0000396372/biography" target="_blank">Max Roach</a>, just to name a few. He also appeared on the great "Thelonious Monk with John Coltrane" album in 1957.</p>\n<p>Here''s the wonderful, slow, somewhat sad, "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hi8NtRBfrAc" target="_blank">It Never Entered My Mind</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hi8NtRBfrAc" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Coleman_Hawkins_(Gottlieb_03991).jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Blues for Yolande" (Coleman Hawkins)  6:44</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"It Never Entered My Mind" (Richard Rodgers, Lorenz Hart)  5:47</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"La Rosita" (Paul Dupont, Allan Stuart)  5:02</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"You''d Be So Nice to Come Home To" (Cole Porter)  4:15</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Prisoner of Love" (Russ Columbo, Clarence Gaskill, Leo Robin)  4:13</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Tangerine" (Johnny Mercer, Victor Schertzinger)  5:21</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Shine On, Harvest Moon" (Jack Norworth, Nora Bayes)  4:49</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 56, '2014-10-08 23:10:09', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:21:17', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-10-16 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 19, 'jazz, Coleman Hawkins', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1998, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(198, 'On this day in jazz (October 17)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-october-17', '', '<p>On this day in 1952,   the one and only <a href="http://www.cmgww.com/music/parker/home.html" target="_blank">Charlie Parker</a> was recorded live at the Howard Theater in Washington, DC. This recording can now be found on the remastered 6-CD set: <em>The Washington Concerts</em>. During this performance trombonists Kai Winding and Earl Swope, tenor saxophonist <a href="http://www.zootsims.org/" target="_blank">Zoot Sims</a>, trumpeter Charlie Walp and guitarist Charlie Byrd joined the big Bird.</p>\n<p>For more on Charley Parker, just use the search box on this site. Or click this <a href="index.php?searchword=charlie+parker&ordering=&searchphrase=all&Itemid=1&option=com_search" target="_self">link</a> if you''re lazy.</p>\n<p>Here''s "<a href="http://iisaphd.subsonic.org/share/FGPMj" target="_blank">Melody Out Of Nowhere</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="http://iisaphd.subsonic.org/share/FGPMj" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/MI0002750232.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 56, '2014-10-08 23:21:37', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:21:33', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-10-17 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 4, 0, 18, 'jazz, Charlie Parker', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1960, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(199, 'On this day in jazz (October 18)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-october-18', '', '<p>On this day in 1967,   alto saxophonist <a href="http://www.sonnystitt.com/" target="_blank">Sonny Stitt</a> recoded <em>Sonny Stitt And The Giants</em> in Zurich. Sonny is joined by trumpeter Howard McGhee and a rhythm section of pianist Walter Bishop,   Jr.,   bassist Tommy Potter and drummer <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kenny_Clarke" target="_blank">Kenny Clarke</a>. allmusic.com says it "is state of the art for bop of the period."</p>\n<p>Sonny came from a family with a strong musical background: his father, Edward Boatner, was baritone singer/composer/college music professor; his brother was a classically trained pianist; his mother was a piano teacher. I haven''t been able to track down the details, but for some reason, Sonny was given up for adoption and that''s how he came to receive the surname, Stitt. Sonny''s earliest recordings were made in 1945 with the great <a href="http://www.stangetz.net/" target="_blank">Stan Getz</a> and legend <a href="http://www.dizzygillespie.com/" target="_blank">Dizzy Gillespie</a>. Later he would also play with <a href="http://www.dextergordon.com/" target="_blank">Dexter Gordon</a>, Gene Ammons, and <a href="http://www.budpowelljazz.com/" target="_blank">Bud Powell</a>, just to name a few. Later in life, he would join the all-star group "Giants of Jazz" which featured <a href="http://www.artblakey.com/" target="_blank">Art Blakey</a>, Dizzy Gillespie, <a href="http://www.monkzone.com/" target="_blank">Thelonious Monk</a>, Kai Winding and bassist Al McKibbon, and his catalog would eventually reach over 100 albums--which is very impressive for someone of his period (he began recording in the 1940s).</p>\n<p>Here''s a video of Sonny with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PgaTwCNizRc">Lover Man</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PgaTwCNizRc" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/6a00e008dca1f088340162fe0fa2fa970d-500wi.jpg" border="0" width="350" height="268" /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 56, '2014-10-10 18:57:57', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:21:45', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-10-18 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 17, 'jazz, Sonny Stitt', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2026, '');
