j/6a00e008dca1f088340162fe0fa2fa970d-500wi.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="268" /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 56, '2014-10-10 18:57:57', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:22:01', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-10-18 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 15, 'jazz, Sonny Stitt', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2083, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(201, 'On this day in jazz (October 19)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-october-19', '', '<p>On this day in 1972,   Sun Ra began recording <em>Space Is The Place</em> (it would be finished the next day). The album was a soundtrack to a film of the same name and contains some of his most ambitious works. There are a significant amount of vocals on the album, but with Sun Ra, like always, this album is about avant-garde, free-form jazz music. The film, which stars Sun Ra (I''ve never seen it), is described as "an 85-minute blaxploitation science fiction film made in 1972". I''m sure there''s a better review, but you''ll have to google for it.</p>\n<p>Additionally, I must say that I would do a disservice to Sun Ra if I attempted to try and explain him in a paragraph, so I''ll just get on with his music (instead of talking about his abduction by aliens and trip to Saturn)...</p>\n<p>Here''s Sun Ra with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ef3rh2qRJvo" target="_blank">Space Is The Place</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ef3rh2qRJvo" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/rc2013037_530.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"It''s After the End of the World"  3:25</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Under Different Stars"  3:55</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Discipline 33"  3:22</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Watusa"  7:11</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Calling Planet Earth"  3:04</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I Am the Alter-Destiny"  1:08</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Satellites Are Spinning"  2:33</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Cosmic Forces"  3:09</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Outer Spaceways Incorporated" 3:00</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"We Travel the Spaceways"  2:28</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Overseer"  3:04</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Blackman/Love in Outer Space"  16:53</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Mysterious Crystal"  5:53</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I Am the Brother of the Wind"  5:54</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"We''ll Wait for You"  4:11</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Space Is the Place"  4:23</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 56, '2014-10-10 19:22:08', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:22:21', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-10-19 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 5, 0, 14, 'jazz, Sun Ra', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2025, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(202, 'On this day in jazz (October 20)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-october-20', '', '<p>What a treat we have today,   as it was the same day that <a href="http://www.cannonball-adderley.com/" target="_blank">Cannonball Adderley</a> recorded "Mercy,   Mercy,   Mercy" in 1966 at "The Club" (Capitol Records studio in Hollywood with an invited audience). The song was written by his pianist, Austrian composer<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joe_Zawinul" target="_blank">Joe Zawinul</a> (Za-Ve-Nool). The song reached #2 on the soul charts and #11 on the Billboard hot 100. Not bad for a "live" jazz recording. It was also covered by a band called "The Buckinghams" who added lyrics and took it to #5 on the charts. What you''ll really love on this song is Joe''s Wurlitzer electric piano. If you like Ray Charles, you''ll melt hearing Joe play...and Cannonball ain''t too shabby either.</p>\n<p>This song is definitely one of my favorites, and I''ve probably heard it hundreds of times. So...set aside 5 minutes and have a listen yourself. If you want to hear more of Cannonball, I would suggest starting with "Somethin'' Else" which includes Miles Davis and Art Blakey--it''s a great great album, too.</p>\n<p>Here''s Cannonball with Joe''s song "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pRrFWp4DUho" target="_blank">Mercy, Mercy, Mercy</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pRrFWp4DUho" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/joe-n-cannonball.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 56, '2014-10-10 19:39:38', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:23:23', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-10-20 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 13, 'jazz, Joe Zawinul, Cannonball Adderley', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2011, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(203, 'On this day in jazz (October 21)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-october-21', '', '<p>On this day in 1961,   <a href="http://www.johncoltrane.com/" target="_blank">John Coltrane</a> began recording <em>My Favorite Things</em>. The rhythm section joining John were <a href="http://mccoytyner.com/" target="_blank">McCoy Tyner</a> on the piano,   Steve Davis on bass and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elvin_Jones" target="_blank">Elvin Jones</a> on the drums. The album consists only of standards written by the likes of Rogers and Hammerstien and Ira and George Gershwin. If you''ve ever worked next to the train station on Adams street in Chicago, you probably hate "My Favorite Things" due having to hear the guy on the street playing it several times a day.</p>\n<p>But, I digress, "My Favorite Things" is indeed one of my favorite things. It features John playing the soprano saxophone (in fact, this was the first album upon which John was recorded on the instrument) instead of his usual choice of alto or tenor. If you get a chance to see John''s son, <a href="http://www.ravicoltrane.com/" target="_blank">Ravi Coltrane</a>, play--take it as he''s pretty good on the soprano, too. I was lucky enough to catch him (Ravi) at the <a href="http://villagevanguard.com/" target="_blank">Village Vanguard</a> on October 4, 2014; however, I wasn''t lucky enough to talk to him in person--that would have been my wife that got to chat with him after the show while I was in the men''s room.</p>\n<p>Here''s John with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qWG2dsXV5HI" target="_blank">My Favorite Things</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qWG2dsXV5HI" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/John_Coltrane_1963.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"My Favorite Things" </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Oscar Hammerstein II,Richard Rodgers</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">13:41</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Everytime We Say Goodbye" </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Cole Porter</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">5:39</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Summertime" </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Ira Gershwin, DuBose Heyward, George Gershwin</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">11:31</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"But Not for Me" </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Ira Gershwin, George Gershwin</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">9:34</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 56, '2014-10-11 17:29:43', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:23:45', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-10-21 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 12, 'jazz, John Coltrane', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2099, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(204, 'On this day in jazz (October 21)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-october-21', '', '<p>On this day in 1961,   <a href="http://www.johncoltrane.com/" target="_blank">John Coltrane</a> began recording <em>My Favorite Things</em>. The rhythm section joining John were <a href="http://mccoytyner.com/" target="_blank">McCoy Tyner</a> on the piano,   Steve Davis on bass and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elvin_Jones" target="_blank">Elvin Jones</a> on the drums. The album consists only of standards written by the likes of Rogers and Hammerstien and Ira and George Gershwin. If you''ve ever worked next to the train station on Adams street in Chicago,   you probably hate "My Favorite Things" due having to hear the guy on the street playing it several times a day.</p>\n<p>But, I digress, "My Favorite Things" is indeed one of my favorite things. It features John playing the soprano saxophone (in fact, this was the first album upon which John was recorded on the instrument) instead of his usual choice of alto or tenor. If you get a chance to see John''s son, <a href="http://www.ravicoltrane.com/" target="_blank">Ravi Coltrane</a>, play--take it as he''s pretty good on the soprano, too. I was lucky enough to catch him (Ravi) at the <a href="http://villagevanguard.com/" target="_blank">Village Vanguard</a> on October 4, 2014; however, I wasn''t lucky enough to talk to him in person--that would have been my wife that got to chat with him after the show while I was in the men''s room.</p>\n<p>Here''s John with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qWG2dsXV5HI" target="_blank">My Favorite Things</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qWG2dsXV5HI" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/John_Coltrane_1963.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"My Favorite Things" </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Oscar Hammerstein II,Richard Rodgers</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">13:41</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Everytime We Say Goodbye" </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Cole Porter</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">5:39</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Summertime" </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Ira Gershwin, DuBose Heyward, George Gershwin</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">11:31</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"But Not for Me" </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Ira Gershwin, George Gershwin</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">9:34</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 56, '2014-10-11 17:29:43', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:24:40', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-10-21 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 11, 'jazz, John Coltrane', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2076, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(205, 'On this day in jazz (October 22)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-october-22', '', '<p>On this day in 1975,   Frank Lowe completed recording of his studio album <em>The Flam</em>. Frank Lowe plays tenor saxophone on this album and Leo Smith adds trumpet,   flugelhorn and wood flute. Joseph Bowie is on the trombone while bass and drums were added by Alex Blake and Charles Shaw, respectively. Frank Lowe''s main genre was free jazz, which is something I''ve yet to really find a strong taste for, but it''s good in small doses. Scott Yanow reviewed the album for allmusic.com and said "These heated performances are better heard than described."</p>\n<p>There''s more about Frank on my <a href="index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=173:on-this-day-in-jazz-september-24&catid=55:september&Itemid=41" target="_blank">September 24 page</a>, so check that page out, too.</p>\n<p>Here''s Frank with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v1pC4I_EaZU" target="_blank">Third St. Stomp</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v1pC4I_EaZU" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/lowe.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Sun Voyage" (Joseph Bowie) - 7:35</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Flam" (Frank Lowe) - 14:03</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Be-Bo-Bo-Be" (Chales Bobo Shaw) - 10:53</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Third St. Stomp" (Alex Blake, Joseph Bowie, Frank Lowe, Charles Bobo Shaw, Leo Smith) - 10:21</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"U.B.O." (Leo Smith) - 0:45</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 56, '2014-10-12 16:20:14', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:24:59', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-10-22 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 10, 'jazz, Frank Lowe', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2246, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(206, 'On this day in jazz (October 23)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-october-23', '', '<p>On this day in 1962,   the great <a href="http://www.artblakey.com/" target="_self">Art Blakey</a> began recording his studio album <em>Caravan</em> at the Plaza Sound Studio in NYC. Besides Art sitting at the drums,   the album features some great performances by his Jazz Messengers: <a href="http://www.wayneshorter.com/" target="_blank">Wayne Shorter</a> on the tenor saxophone, <a href="http://www.freddiehubbardmusic.com/" target="_blank">Freddie Hubbard</a> on trumpet and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Curtis_Fuller" target="_blank">Curtis Fuller</a> on the trombone; <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/cedar-walton-mn0000741325/biography" target="_blank">Cedar Walton</a> (piano) and <a href="http://sculpturedsounds.com/" target="_blank">Reggie Workman</a> (bass) rounded out the rhythm section.</p>\n<p>For more on the album, see the extensive review by Lindsay Planner at <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/album/caravan-mw0000191511" target="_blank">allmusic.com</a>, or just go by their guide to jazz off <a href="http://www.amazon.com/All-Music-Guide-Jazz-Recordings/dp/0879305304/ref=sr_1_2?ie=UTF8&qid=1413131475&sr=8-2&keywords=all+music+guide+to+jazz" target="_blank">amazon.com</a>. I think I got mine for $1. Not bad for a book with 1,700 artists profiled and over 18,000 albums reviewed. It has a good rating system that can guide you to the more important works by each artist. I found it a must have.</p>\n<p>Here''s Art with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KkNfChkmTF4" target="_blank">Caravan</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KkNfChkmTF4" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/efce943472c8641e49cfa4c90c3f5.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Caravan" (Juan Tizol) - 9:46</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Sweet ''n'' Sour" (Shorter) - 5:30</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"In the Wee Small Hours of the Morning" (Mann, Hilliard) - 4:05</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"This Is for Albert" (Shorter) - 8:20</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Skylark" (Carmichael, Mercer) - 4:50</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Thermo" (Hubbard) - 6:45</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 56, '2014-10-12 16:34:01', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:25:21', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-10-23 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 9, 'jazz, Art Blakey', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2587, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(207, 'On this day in jazz (October 24)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-october-24', '', '<p>On this day in 1947,   the legendary <a href="http://www.monkzone.com/" target="_blank">Thelonious Monk</a> recorded his first trio session with drummer <a href="http://www.artblakey.com/" target="_blank">Art Blakey</a> and bassist Al McKibbon. The recordings can be found as part of the compilation,   <em>Thelonious Monk Blue Note Sessions</em> which is essentially a collection of several 78 RPM singles released between 1947 and 1952. The songs they recorded on this date were:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Nice Work If You Can Get It" (George Gershwin)</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Ruby My Dear"</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Well You Needn''t" </span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"April in Paris" (Vernon Duke) </span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Off Minor"</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Introspection"</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Thelonious had a very prolific career and wrote many songs that would become jazz standards ("''Round Midnight," "Blue Monk," "Ruby, My Dear," "In Walked Bud," and "Well, You Needn''t"). If you haven''t listened to him in detail, take a couple of hours and learn more about him as he is one of the great jazz musicians and composers of all time.</span></p>\n<p>Here''s Thelonious with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=40GSfcaka8E" target="_blank">Well, You Needn''t</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=40GSfcaka8E" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/theloniousmonk_600w.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 56, '2014-10-12 16:49:33', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:50:09', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-10-24 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 8, 'jazz, Thelonious Monk', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2519, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(208, 'On this day in jazz (October 25)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-october-25', '', '<p>On this day in 1960,   alto saxophonist <a href="http://straightlife.info/apbio.html" target="_blank">Art Pepper</a> recorded the studio album <em>Smack Up</em>. Joining Art were Jack Sheldon on trumpet and a rhythm section of Pete Jolly at the piano,   Jimmy Bond on bass and Frank Butler on the drums. It is a really fine album starting with the title song composed by Harold Land,   followed by an original by Art, "Las Cuevas de Mario" which leads into a song by my favorite clarinetists, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buddy_Collette" target="_blank">Buddy Collette</a>, entitled "A Bit of Basie"; and there''s even an <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ornette_Coleman" target="_blank">Ornette Coleman</a> song on the album: "Tears Inside".</p>\n<p>If you are unfamiliar with the phrase "Smack Up", it means to shoot up with heroin. Art would battle heroin addiction for several years. I cover this in a small amount of detail on the <a href="index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=166:on-this-day-in-jazz-september-16&catid=55:september&Itemid=41" target="_blank">September 16 page</a>.</p>\n<p>Here''s Art with a great version of "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=55iR50cyzfg" target="_blank">Smack Up</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=55iR50cyzfg" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/art_pepper_publicity_photo_1959_sml.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Smack Up" (Harold Land) 4:15</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Las Cuevas De Mario" (Art Pepper) 6:59</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"A Bit of Basie" (Buddy Collette) 7:21</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"How Can You Lose" (Benny Carter) 6:53</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Maybe Next Year" (Duane Tatro) 4:21</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Tears Inside" (Ornette Coleman) 7:43</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Solid Citizens" (Jack Monterose) -6:29</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Solid Citizens (alternate take)" -6:28</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 56, '2014-10-12 17:08:29', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:29:05', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-10-25 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 7, 'jazz, Art Pepper', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2658, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(209, 'On this day in jazz (October 26)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-october-26', '', '<p>On this day in 1964,   the great <a href="http://www.horacesilver.com/" target="_blank">Horace Silver</a> recorded one of the best songs ever,   "Song for My Father". Hoarce''s father was John Tavares Silva, who was born in Maio, Cape Verde. On the <a href="index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=180:on-this-day-in-jazz-october-01&catid=56:october&Itemid=41" target="_self">October 1 page</a> I covered another album that John inspired his son to create. Joining Horace on the song are Carmell Jones on the trumpet, <a href="http://www.joehendersonsax.com/" target="_blank">Joe Henderson</a> on tenor saxophone, Teddy Smith on the bass and Roger Humphries at the drums. It''s one of those few songs where every instrument acts in a synergistic effect to create something really magical.</p>\n<p>"Song for My Father" is a true jazz standard. It has a bossa nova style and has been either sampled, stolen or borrowed by many other musicians, many of them not even playing in the jazz genre. For example, the opening horns were borrowed by Stevie Wonder for his song "Don''t You Worry ''Bout a Thing"; the song supplied the chords for the Style Council''s 1984 song "Me Ship Came In!"; and it provided the basis for Steely Dan''s biggest pop hit "Rikki Don''t Lose That Number." Not too shabby.</p>\n<p>Here''s Horace with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=boVaez6rVNA" target="_blank">Song for My Father</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=boVaez6rVNA" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/horace-silver-jazz-pianist-2014-billboard-650.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">And here''s a </span>slightly<span style="line-height: 1.3em;"> faster, longer, more highly improvised <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=S1CilMzT55M" target="_blank">live version</a>.</span></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 56, '2014-10-12 17:31:01', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:30:00', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-10-26 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 6, 'jazz, Horace Silver', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2847, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(210, 'On this day in jazz (October 27)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-october-27', '', '<p>On this day in 1961,   trumpter/flugelhornist <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/art-farmer-mn0000502199/biography" target="_blank">Art Farmer</a> completed recording of the album "Perception". This was the first album upon which Art only played flugelhorn. Joining Art on this work were a rhythm section consisting of Harold Mabern on piano, Tommy Williams on bass and<span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Roy McCurdy on drums. All men were part of the Jazztet which was founded by Art and Benny Golson (the other two members of the sextet were pianist <a href="http://mccoytyner.com/" target="_blank">McCoy Tyner</a> and trombonist Grachan Moncur III). Although Art does not have a large catalog as a composer, this album features two originals: "Punsu" and "Kayin''".</span></p>\n<p>Art started playing professionally while still in high school. During this time he often appeared with his identical twin brother, bassist Addison Farmer. He went on to join Gerry Mulligan''s quartet before forming the Jazztet with Benny in 1959. Art continually developed his style throughout his life and switched from the trumpet to the flugelhorn in order to have a warmer feel to his sound. In fact, he''s one of the first people to solo on the instrument.</p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Here''s Art with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=B4BZOEr0Eio" target="_blank">Punsu</a>":</span></p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=B4BZOEr0Eio" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Art_Farmer_beim_MPS_Festival_1971_%28Heinrich_Klaffs_Collection_20%29.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Punsu"  5:14</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Day After" (Tom McIntosh)  2:25</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Lullaby of the Leaves" (Bernice Petkere, Joe Young)  4:18</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Kayin''"  3:57</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Tonk" (Ray Bryant)  4:37</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Blue Room" (Lorenz Hart, Richard Rodgers)  3:58</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Change Partners" (Irving Berlin)  5:23</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Nobody''s Heart" (Hart, Rodgers)  4:05</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 56, '2014-10-16 07:33:28', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:30:53', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-10-27 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 5, 'jazz, Art Farmer', 'On this day in jazz', 0, 2577, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(211, 'On this day in jazz (October 28)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-october-28', '', '<p>On this day in 1978,   tenor saxophonist <a href="http://www.zootsims.org/" target="_blank">Zoot Sims</a> completed recording of the album "If I''m Lucky". The album was recorded with pianist Jimmy Rowles. The CD is essentially a group of obscure,   not often heard songs that the two interpreted. Joining Jimmy in the rhythm section were bassist George Mraz and drummer Mousey Alexander. If you are looking for something both new and old, this is a great place to find it.</p>\n<p>Zoot is absolutely one of my favorite saxophonists and probably my favorite from the west coast style. If I was to go and buy one Zoot album to start a collection, I''d pick "<a href="http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-rare-dawn-sessions-mw0000086831" target="_blank">The Rare Dawn Sessions</a>".</p>\n<p>Here''s Zoot with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VBkiZdahsnc" target="_blank">If I''m Lucky</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VBkiZdahsnc" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/69.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">(I Wonder) Where Our Love Has Gone (Buddy Johnson) 4:54</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Legs (Neal Hefti) 6:31</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">If I''m Lucky (Eddie DeLange / Josef Myrow) 5:29</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Shadow Waltz (Al Dubin / Harry Warren) 5:34</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">You''re My Everything (Mort Dixon / Harry Warren / Joe Young) 5:26</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">It''s All Right With Me (Cole Porter) 6:54</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Gypsy Sweetheart (Mitchell Parish) 4:18</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">I Hear a Rhapsody (Jack Baker / George Fragos / Dick Gasparre) 6:28</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 56, '2014-10-16 07:51:35', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:31:43', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-10-28 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 4, 'jazz, Zoot Sims', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2516, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(212, 'On this day in jazz (October 29)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-october-29', '', '<p>On this day in 1929,   Boyd Senter recorded "Beale Street Blues" with his "Senterpedes". It was recorded in New York and released by Okeh (production ID: 40836). Boyd was born in Nebraska in 1898 to a farming family. After hearing the "Original Dixieland Jazz Band" on the Edison,   he decided that he wanted to play jazz also. Although he wasn''t a child prodigy by any means, he worked hard and learned to play trumpet, all the saxophones, various horns and the banjo. However, he was best known for the clarinet and became known as "The Jazzologist Supreme". With his clarinet he could mimic many of the farmyard sounds he grew up hearing, which endeared him to fans and other musicians as well.</p>\n<p>The song, "Beale Street Blues" was written by Florence Alabama''s (and later, Memphian) W. C. Handy (aka "The Father of the Blues") in 1916. Of course, the song refers the Beale Street in downtown Memphis, TN.</p>\n<p>W. C. Handy''s influence was far and wide and I was delighted to look up a couple of weeks ago and see that at the corner of 6th Avenue and 52nd Street the street sign declares it "W. C. Handy''s Place".</p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Here''s Boyd with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XQ7V3YcrrN8" target="_blank">Beale Street Blues</a>":</span></p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XQ7V3YcrrN8" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/senter2.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 56, '2014-10-16 18:30:08', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:32:26', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-10-29 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 4, 0, 3, 'jazz, Boyd Senter', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2638, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(213, 'On this day in jazz (October 30)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-october-30', '', '<p>On this day in 1958,   <a href="http://www.artblakey.com/" target="_blank">Art Blakey</a> recorded the studio album "Moanin''" at Van Gelder Studio in Hackensack,  NJ. Joining the legendary drummer on the album are the Jazz Messengers: legend <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lee_Morgan" target="_blank">Lee Morgan</a> on trumpet,   legend <a href="http://www.bennygolson.com/" target="_blank">Benny Golson</a> on tenor saxophone, <a href="http://bobbytimmons.jazzgiants.net/" target="_blank">Bobby Timmons</a> on piano and Jymie Merritt on bass (quite a lineup). The music was written by Golson except for the hit, "Moanin''" (Timmons) and the cover "Come Rain or Come Shine" (Johnny Mercer and Harold Arlen). If you''ve ever spent much time in terminal 3 of O''Hare International Airport in Chicago, you''ve heard the song "Moanin''" (they play jazz in over the speakers, and you can hear it best near the security lines and downstairs by the baggage claim.</p>\n<p>The album itself is a true classic. In addition to the title track, the song "Blues March" is also one of my favorites (and "Are You Real?" and "Along Came Betty" aren''t bad, either).</p>\n<p>Here''s Art and the Jazz Messengers with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cv9NSR-2DwM" target="_blank">Moanin''</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cv9NSR-2DwM" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/art-blakey-08.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Moanin''" (Bobby Timmons)  9:35</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Are You Real"  4:50</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Along Came Betty"  6:12</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Drum Thunder Suite"  7:33</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Blues March"  6:17</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Come Rain or Come Shine" (Harold Arlen, Johnny Mercer)  5:49</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 56, '2014-10-16 20:03:49', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:33:35', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-10-30 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 5, 0, 2, 'jazz, Art Blakey', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2722, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(214, 'On this day in jazz (October 31)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-october-31', '', '<p>On this day in 1956,   <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chet_Baker" target="_blank">Chet Baker</a> and <a href="http://straightlife.info/apbio.html" target="_blank">Art Pepper</a> recorded the studio album, "Playboys". Most of the songs were written by <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jimmy_Heath" target="_blank">Jimmy Heath</a> (brother of bassist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Percy_Heath" target="_blank">Percy Heath</a>). When the album was first released, the cover art featured a photo of a pinup model and the name of the album was shown in the same font used by the magazine, "Playboy". Despite being a big supporter of jazz over the years, the first "Playboy Jazz Festival" was still 3 years away, and I suppose Hugh Hefner wasn''t happy about the cover. He threatened to sue, but nothing ever came of it, except for this: when the album re-released in 1961 (as well as the 1989 CD format re-release), it was renamed "Pictures of Heath" and the cover was changed to be a picture of Art and Chet in the studio.</p>\n<p>Joining Chet''s trumpet and Art''s alto sax were Phil Urso on the tenor sax and a rhythm section of Carl Perkins on piano, Curtis Counce on bass and Larance Marable on the drums. Chet and Art do a great job of playing off of each other, and make this selection of songs quite enjoyable to listen to.</p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Here''s Chet and Art with "</span><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BcSxlN318RA" target="_blank" style="line-height: 1.3em;">For Minors Only</a><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">":</span></p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BcSxlN318RA" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/CBAP.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing (songs by Jimmy Heath, except where noted):</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"For Minors Only" - 4:00</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Minor-Yours " (Art Pepper) - 6:44</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Resonant Emotions" - 5:41</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Tynan Time" (Pepper) - 5:32</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Picture of Heath" - 6:44</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"For Miles and Miles" - 6:25</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"C.T.A." - 5:12</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 56, '2014-10-19 14:56:49', 62, '', '2016-08-18 20:28:28', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-10-31 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 1, 'jazz, Art Pepper, Chet Baker', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2374, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(215, 'On this day in jazz (November 01)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-november-01', '', '<p>On this day 1978,   <a href="http://www.billevanswebpages.com/" target="_blank">Bill Evans</a> was in the middle of recording his studio album, "Affinity". The album is interesting for a couple of reasons. First, Bill is heard playing (for the last time on a studio album) the Fender Rhodes electric piano on several of the tracks. Second, it features the Belgian harmonica player <a href="http://www.tootsthielemans.com/" target="_blank">Toots Thielmans</a> and was the recording debut for bassist Marc Johnson. Joining Bill, Toots and Marc were Larry Schneider (on flute, tenor and soprano saxophones) and Eliot Zigmund on the drums. The album only made it to the #18 position on the Billboard Jazz Albums charts (and allmusic only gave it 3 stars), so it''s definitely not one of his best, but worth hearing if you''ve never heard Bill play the electric piano.</p>\n<p>Here''s Bill and Toots with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lTHfeTvipZQ" target="_blank">Body and Soul</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lTHfeTvipZQ" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/1303407855_bill-evans-toots-thielemans.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I Do It for Your Love" (Paul Simon)  7:16</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Sno'' Peas" (Phil Markowitz)  5:51</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"This Is All I Ask" (Gordon Jenkins)  4:14</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Days of Wine and Roses" (Henry Mancini, Johnny Mercer)  6:40</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Jesus'' Last Ballad" (Gianni Bedori)  5:52</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Tomato Kiss" (Larry Schneider)  5:17</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Other Side of Midnight (Noelle''s Theme)" (Michel Legrand)  3:17</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Blue in Green" (Miles Davis, Bill Evans)  4:09</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Body & Soul" (Edward Heyman, Robert Sour, Frank Eyton, Johnny Green)  6:16</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 57, '2014-10-19 15:03:03', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:04:00', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-11-01 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 3, 0, 30, 'jazz, Bill Evans', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2548, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(216, 'On this day in jazz (November 02)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-november-02', '', '<p>On this day in 1966,   pianist <a href="http://www.horacesilver.com/" target="_blank">Horace Silver</a> recorded three songs for his album "The Jody Grind" (including the title song). The other three songs on the album were recorded on November 23. Joining Horace on the album were the great <a href="http://www.woodyshaw.com/" target="_blank">Woody Shaw</a> on trumpet,   James Spaulding on flute and alto sax,   Tyrone Washington on tenor sax, Larry Ridley on bass and Roger Humphries on the drums.</p>\n<p>The album was very popular in 1967 when it was released by Blue Note and reached #8 on the Billboard Jazz Albums chart. allmusic.com gives it 4 1/2 stars, saying this in Steve Huey''s review: "Silver''s playing is at its rhythmic, funky best throughout, brimming over with confidence and good cheer, and evoking memories of the classic feel of his early-''60s quintet."</p>\n<p>Here''s Horace with finger popping, foot tapping title song, "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cIrE6sZduWo" target="_blank">The Jody Grind</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cIrE6sZduWo" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/The_Jody_Grind_Cover.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Jody Grind"  5:50</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Mary Lou"  7:09</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Mexican Hip Dance"  5:53</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Blue Silver"  5:59</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Grease Piece"  7:31</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Dimples"  7:17</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 57, '2014-10-19 15:32:02', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:04:24', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-11-02 05:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 29, 'jazz, Horace Silver', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2498, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(217, 'On this day in jazz (November 03)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-november-03', '', '<p>On this day in 1961,   <a href="http://www.johncoltrane.com/" target="_blank">John Coltrane</a> recorded "Live! at the Village Vanguard". On this album,   <a href="http://mccoytyner.com/" target="_blank">McCoy Tyner</a> (piano),   Jimmy Garrison (bass) and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elvin_Jones" target="_blank">Elvin Jones</a> (drums) formed the rest of what would be called "The Classic Quartet". <a href="http://www.ericdolphy.net/" target="_blank">Eric Dolphy</a> (bass clarinet) joined in for the song, "Spiritual". Rudy Van Gelder was picked to engineer the recordings.</p>\n<p>During the period during which the recording occurred, magazine articles were highly critical of the direction that John was taking his music. Some even called it "musical non-sense" and "horrifying". John would prove them wrong in the long run, but it was tough sledding back in 1961. In his book "Coltrane: The Story of A Sound" (2007), Ben Ratliff called the performance of "Chasin'' the Trane" on the more important jazz recordings due to its ability to unify the approaches of free jazz, jamming, and neoclassicism.</p>\n<p>By the way, the Village Vanguard is alive and well, so if you get a chance to go, take it--it''s really a great place to see live jazz due to the intimate atmosphere. My wife even got to talk to Ravi Coltrane between sets the last time we were there.</p>\n<p>Here''s John with "<a href="http://iisaphd.subsonic.org/share/grHmG" target="_blank">Chasin'' the Trane</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="http://iisaphd.subsonic.org/share/grHmG" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Jazz-player-John-Coltrane-006.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 57, '2014-10-26 16:44:08', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:04:56', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-11-03 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 27, 'jazz, John Coltrane', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2487, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(218, 'On this day in jazz (November 04)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-november-04', '', '<p>On this day in 1964,   guitarist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grant_Green" target="_blank">Grant Green</a> began recording the studio album "Idle Moments". An all-star group joined Grant,   including <a href="http://www.joehendersonsax.com/" target="_blank">Joe Henderson</a> on the tenor saxophone,   Duke Pearson playing the piano, the great <a href="http://www.bluenote.com/artists/bobby-hutcherson" target="_blank">Bobby Hutcherson</a> on the vibraphone, Bob Cranshaw on bass and Al Harewood on the drums.</p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Grant is definitely my favorite jazz guitarist. If you''re wondering why Grant''s sound sounds the way it does, fellow guitarist George Benson said the Grant would turn off the bass and treble settings of his amplifier allowing the midband frequencies to be accentuated, creating a punchy, biting tone.</span></p>\n<p>Here'' Grant with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gwaFDFP7m_E" target="_blank">Idle Moments</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gwaFDFP7m_E" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Grant_Green_guitarist.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Idle Moments" (Pearson)  14:56</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Jean De Fleur" (Green)  6:49</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Django" (John Lewis)  8:44</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Nomad" (Pearson)  12:16</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 57, '2014-10-26 16:57:40', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:05:10', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-11-04 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 4, 0, 28, 'jazz, Grant Green', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2829, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(219, 'On this day in jazz (November 05)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-november-05', '', '<p>On this day in 1969,   <a href="http://www.oscarpeterson.com/" target="_blank">Oscar Peterson</a> began recording the album "Hello Herbie". The reason for the title was guitarist <a href="http://classicjazzguitar.com/artists/artists_page.jsp?artist=12" target="_blank">Herb Ellis</a> who joined OPs trio for this set. The album contains some great tunes by other jazz greats such as <a href="http://www.wesmontgomery.com/" target="_blank">Wes Montgomery</a>,   Benny Goodman/Charlie Christian,   and <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/hampton-hawes-mn0000558596/biography" target="_blank">Hampton Hawes</a>. In fact, Herb even considered the album to be one of his favorite recordings.</p>\n<p>Here''s OP with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=J73KJJJ7aYk&index=4&list=PLB70DAE80E873BB75" target="_blank">Hamp''s Blues</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=J73KJJJ7aYk&index=4&list=PLB70DAE80E873BB75" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/herb-ellis_1609798f.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Naptown Blues" (Wes Montgomery)  5:20</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Exactly Like You" (Dorothy Fields, Jimmy McHugh)  4:50</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Seven Come Eleven" (Charlie Christian, Benny Goodman, Fletcher Henderson)  5:06</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Hamp''s Blues" (Hampton Hawes)  3:46</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Blues for H.G." (Oscar Peterson)  6:05</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"A Lovely Way to Spend an Evening" (Harold Adamson, McHugh)  8:23</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Day by Day" (Sammy Cahn, Axel Stordahl, Paul Weston)  4:44</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 57, '2014-10-26 17:17:22', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:05:27', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-11-05 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 4, 0, 26, 'jazz, Oscar Peterson', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2837, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(220, 'On this day in jazz (November 06)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-november-06', '', '<p>On this day in 1962,   the great <a href="http://mingusmingusmingus.com/" target="_blank">Charles Mingus</a> recorded "Oh Yeah". Mingus is most famous for being one of the greatest bassists and composers in history; however,   on this album,   he plays no bass, sings on three of the songs and plays the piano on all. The album also features jazz multi-musician <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rahsaan_Roland_Kirk" target="_blank">Rahsaan Roland Kirk</a> who plays the flute, siren, and the tenor, manzello and stritch saxophones.</p>\n<p>Steve Huey gives a great review of the album on allmusic.com, saying this of the addition of "mad genius" Roland Kirk to Mingus'' band:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">His chemistry with Mingus is fantastically explosive, which makes sense -- both were encyclopedias of jazz tradition, but given over to oddball modernist experimentation. It''s a shame Kirk only spent three months with the band, because his solo interpretations are such symbiotic reflections of Mingus'' intent as a composer. Look no further than "Hog Callin'' Blues," a stomping "Haitian Fight Song" descendant where Kirk honks and roars the blues like a man possessed.</span></p>\n<p>Here''s Charles and Roland with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=donDOIiuWc0" target="_blank">Hog Callin'' Blues</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=donDOIiuWc0" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/charles-mingus-05.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=donDOIiuWc0" target="_blank"> </a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Hog Callin'' Blues"  7:27</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Devil Woman"  9:42</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Wham Bam Thank You Ma''am"  4:43</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Ecclusiastics"  6:59</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Oh Lord Don''t Let Them Drop That Atomic Bomb on Me"  5:43</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Eat That Chicken"  4:38</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Passions of a Man"  4:56</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 57, '2014-10-26 17:39:59', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:05:42', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-11-06 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 4, 0, 25, 'jazz, Charles Mingus', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 20668, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(221, 'On this day in jazz (November 07)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-november-07', '', '<p>On this day in 1940,   <a href="http://www.dukeellington.com/" target="_blank">Duke Ellington</a> recorded on of the great live performances in jazz history in Fargo,   ND. Joining the Duke were some of the best jazz soloists of the day, including <a href="http://www.benwebster.dk/" target="_blank">Ben Webster</a>, Jimmy Blanton, Johnny Hodges, Rex Stewart, and Tricky Sam Nanton. The reason why the performance was recorded was because two South Dakota State students asked for permission to do so, and Duke and the venue''s manager OKd the request. The recording was recorded via a portable turntable which cut the sound onto 16" acetate covered aluminum disks which sat next to Duke''s piano.</p>\n<p>If you go to buy the recording, you''ll probably find it on this format: "The Duke at Fargo, 1940: Special 60th Anniversary Edition" or the "Complete Legendary Fargo Concert", although it was originally released as three LP records by "Book of the Month Records" as "Duke Ellington At Fargo, 1940". The original recording won the 1980 Grammy for "Best Jazz Instrumental Performance, Big Band". The original disks were donated to the Archives Center of the Smithsonian Institution''s National Museum of American History where they reside today.</p>\n<p>Here''s Duke and Ben Webster with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RDtBsBX7KoY" target="_blank">Stardust</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RDtBsBX7KoY" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/MTE5NDg0MDU0OTU5ODUxMDIz.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 57, '2014-10-26 18:00:33', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:05:57', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-11-07 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 24, 'jazz, Duke Ellington', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 3204, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(222, 'On this day in jazz (November 08)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-november-08', '', '<p>On this day in 1957,   pianist/singer <a href="http://moseallison.com/" target="_blank">Mose Allison</a> recorded his second studio album, "Local Color". The album contains only a rhythm section with Addison Farmer on the bass and Nick Stabulas on the drums. When I covered Mose on August 15, I said this about him:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">Mose is a very hard person to categorize. Although I consider him jazz, others consider him blues. In fact, "Jet" magazine tried to interview him, thinking he was a black blues musician. Singer Van Morrison considers him to be one of the great songwriters of our time and on January 14, 2013, he was honored as a Jazz Master by the National Endowment for the Arts which is the nation''s highest honor in jazz.</p>\n<p>Here''s Mose with the satirical "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v5hw9T9Ozv4" target="_blank">Parchman Farm</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v5hw9T9Ozv4" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/mose-allison_1.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Carnival" - 2:59</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Parchman Farm" - 3:17</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Crepuscular Air" - 3:43</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Mojo Woman" - 4:04</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Town" - 3:21</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Trouble in Mind" (Richard M. Jones) - 3:13</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Lost Mind" (Percy Mayfield) - 3:31</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I''ll Never Be Free" (Bennie Benjamin, George David Weiss) - 5:36</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Don''t Ever Say Goodbye" (Duke Ellington) - 3:12</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Ain''t You a Mess" - 2:40</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 57, '2014-10-26 18:09:43', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:06:09', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-11-08 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 22, 'jazz, Mose Allison', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2676, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(223, 'On this day in jazz (November 09)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-november-09', '', '<p>On this day in 1969,   saxophonist <a href="http://www.archieshepp.net/" target="_blank">Archie Shepp</a> recorded the song "Pitchin'' Can". The song features Shepp with Clifford Thornton on trumpet,   Noah Howard on alto sax, Julio Finn on harmonica, Leroy Jenkins on viol, Dave Burrell on piano, Earl Freeman on bass, Sunny Murray on drums and Chicago Beau with vocals. If you are looking for the album this song is on, you can look for "Black Gypsy" if you can''t find the original album to which this was the title song.</p>\n<p>Archie is best known for his Afrocentric music of the late 1960s. He was raised in Philadelphia where he first learned to play the piano. He also studied clarinet and alto sax before focusing on the tenor sax. If you''re interested in more by Archie, check out his album "Four for Trane". Archie is still active today (2014) and you can find more about him on my August 10th page.</p>\n<p>Here''s Archie with "<a href="http://iisaphd.subsonic.org/share/thtKg" target="_blank">Pitchin'' Can</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="http://iisaphd.subsonic.org/share/thtKg" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/04.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 57, '2014-10-30 15:14:30', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:06:23', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-11-09 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 5, 0, 23, 'jazz, Archie She', 'on this day in hazzpp', 0, 2609, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(224, 'On this day in jazz (November 10)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-november-10', '', '<p>On this day in 1956,   the great <a href="http://www.horacesilver.com/" target="_blank">Horace Silver</a> recorded the studio album <em>Six Pieces of Silver</em>. Donald Byrd (trumpet),   <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hank_Mobley" target="_blank">Hank Mobley</a> (tenor sax),   Doug Watkins (bass) and Louis Hayes (drums) join Horace on this recording. The original album featured seven songs (six by Silver, hence the title) of which two were big hits for Horace: "Seor Blues" and "Cool Eyes".</p>\n<p>If you''re familiar with Art Blakey''s Jazz Messengers, you''ve got the same band here (i.e., the 1955 version), just with Louis Hayes on drums instead of Art. In fact, this was the first album released by "The Horace Silver Quintet" which would feature many of the same players over the coming years. For more on Horace, check out my <a href="index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=180:on-this-day-in-jazz-october-01&catid=56:october&Itemid=41" target="_self">October 01</a> or <a href="index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=209:on-this-day-in-jazz-october-26&catid=56:october&Itemid=41" target="_self">October 26</a> pages.</p>\n<p>Here''s Horace with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iRdlvzIEz-g" target="_blank">Seor Blues</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iRdlvzIEz-g" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Horace_Silver_by_Dmitri_Savitski_1989.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Cool Eyes" </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">5:55</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Shirl" </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">4:16</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Camouflage" </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">4:25</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Enchantment" </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">6:22</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Seor Blues" </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">7:01</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Virgo" </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">5:49</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"For Heaven''s Sake" (Elise Bretton, Donald Meyer, Edwards Sherman)</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 57, '2014-10-30 15:20:35', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:06:52', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-11-10 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 21, 'jazz, Horace Silver', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2815, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(225, 'On this day in jazz (November 11)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-november-11', '', '<p>On this day in 1968,   <a href="http://www.bluenote.com/artists/bobby-hutcherson" target="_blank">Bobby Hutcherson</a>,   on of my favorite vibraphonists,   recorded the studio album "Spiral". Joining Bobby were the great <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harold_Land" target="_blank">Harold Land</a> on saxophone, Stanley Cowell on piano, Reggie Johnson on bass and <a href="http://www.josephachambers.com/" target="_blank">Joe Chambers</a> on drums. All members of the group submitted compositions for the album, and what you get is a true group effort.</p>\n<p>If you notice that the release date of the album was 1979, you might ask why this album wasn''t released for 11 years. Steve Huey''s (of allmusic.com) opinion is that its sound did not fit the late-''60s music spirit as it wasn''t fusion, nor "aggressively far-out"...however, the music is still really good with a modal post-bop sound. I agree...although, to me, it is non-aggressively far-out compared to the modal works of 1959.</p>\n<p>Here''s Bobby with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YkoiFfmf5r0" target="_blank">Jasper</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YkoiFfmf5r0" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/bobby-hutcherson-2008.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Ruth" (Chambers) - 7:52</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Wedding March" (Cowell) - 3:54</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Poor People''s March" (Land) - 6:18</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Spiral" (Chambers) - 6:15</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Visions" (Hutcherson) - 3:50</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 57, '2014-10-30 15:37:48', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:07:10', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-11-11 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 20, 'jazz, Bobby Hutcherson', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 20019, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(226, 'On this day in jazz (November 12)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-november-12', '', '<p>On this day in 1925,   <a href="https://www.louisarmstronghouse.org/louie_armstrong/overview.htm" target="_blank">Louis Armstrong</a> recorded his first session as a leader. The name chosen for the band was "Louis Armstrong and His Hot Five". The band would continue recording together until 1927. In 1928 other records were recorded by a band with the same name, but Louis was the only member who played in both incarnations. The original Hot Five were Louis, Louis'' wife, Lil Hardin Armstrong (piano), the great Kid Ory (trombone), Johnny Dodds (clarinet) and Johnny St. Cyr (guitar and banjo). All of the recordings were made in Chicago for Okeh records.</p>\n<p>In 2002, the recordings were added to the National Recording Registry in the organization''s inaugural year. They said this about the recordings:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">Louis Armstrong was jazz''s first great soloist and is among American music''s most important and influential figures. These sessions, his solos in particular, set a standard musicians still strive to equal in their beauty and innovation.</p>\n<p>Here''s Louis with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ksmGt2U-xTE" target="_blank">Heebie-Jeebies</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ksmGt2U-xTE" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/orig_Louis_Armstrong_s_Hot_Five_02.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 57, '2014-11-01 16:13:18', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:07:24', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-11-12 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 19, 'jazz, Louis Armstrong', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2943, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(227, 'On this day in jazz (November 13)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-november-13', '', '<p>On this day in 1960,   tenor saxophonist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hank_Mobley" target="_blank">Hank Mobley</a> recorded the album "Roll Call" at Van Gelder Studio in Englewood Cliffs,   NJ. Assisting Hank on this recording were <a href="http://www.freddiehubbardmusic.com/" target="_blank">Freddie Hubbard</a> on trumpet and a rhythm section of <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/wynton-kelly-mn0000684253/biography" target="_blank">Wynton Kelly</a> on piano, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Chambers" target="_blank">Paul Chambers</a> on bass and <a href="http://www.artblakey.com/" target="_blank">Art Blakey</a> on drums--all legends. Although I like his album "Soul Station" the best (I''ll feature it in February), this one is next on my list.</p>\n<p>Stacia Proefrock, writing for allmusic.com, said that "Mobley''s performance throughout the recording is stylish without being restrained, and the strength of his songwriting shines on five of the album''s six songs." Check it out, it''s definitely a classic hard bop set.</p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 15.8079996109009px;">Here''s Hank with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OgmEYz56gBE" target="_blank">Roll Call</a>":</span></p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OgmEYz56gBE" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/hank_mobley.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Roll Call" - 10:33</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"My Groove Your Move" - 6:07</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Take Your Pick" - 5:27</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"A Baptist Beat" - 8:54</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The More I See You" (Warren, Gordon) - 6:47</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Breakdown" - 4:57</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 57, '2014-11-01 16:57:46', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:07:49', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-11-13 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 18, 'jazz, Hank Mobley', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 22389, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(228, 'On this day in jazz (November 14)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-november-14', '', '<p>On this day in 1971,   <a href="http://www.artblakey.com/" target="_blank">Art Blakey</a>,   <a href="http://www.dizzygillespie.com/" target="_blank">Dizzy Gillespie</a>,   Al McKibbon, <a href="http://www.monkzone.com/" target="_blank">Thelonious Monk</a>, <a href="http://www.sonnystitt.com/" target="_blank">Sonny Stitt</a> and <a href="http://www.bjbear71.com/Winding/Kai.html" target="_blank">Kai Winding</a> were recorded live in England under the billing "The Giants of Jazz". Hopefully you''re familiar with these greats, but you may not have ever heard them play together. Dizzy still played a great trumpet, Art is amazing on the drums, Thelonious is perfect on the piano, Sonny sizzles on both the tenor and alto saxophone, Kai clobbers it on trombone and Al McKibbon belts out the bass.</p>\n<p>I was able to find this concert on Amazon <a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B000DZIGGW/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o01_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1" target="_blank">here</a>. The first couple of songs are filled with some incredible solos, and the version of "A Night in Tunia" is probably the best that I have ever heard--due in large part to a wonderful drum solo by Art Blakey mid way through the song. The second CD is less about the solos and more about the synergy of all the artists. I consider it a must have.<span style="line-height: 1.3em;">In addition to this recording, many of their other concerts during this tour are available on CD, DVD and even <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VUVuX3lLrdg" target="_blank">youtube</a> so check them out.</span></p>\n<p>Here''s the Giants with "<a href="http://iisaphd.subsonic.org/share/GxiGh" target="_blank">A Night In Tunisia</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="http://iisaphd.subsonic.org/share/GxiGh" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/51JJFjzgHCL.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Tin Tin Deo" (Gil Fuller, Chano Pozo)  11:42</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Night in Tunisia" (Dizzy Gillespie, Felix Paparelli)  10:22</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Woody ''n'' You" (Gillespie)  8:34</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Tour de Force" (Gillespie)  13:22</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Allen''s Alley (Be Bop Tune)" (Denzil Best)  8:38</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Blue ''n'' Boogie" (Gillespie)  13:50</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Everything Happens to Me" (Tom Adair, Matt Dennis)  4:52</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Dizzy''s Rap  1:09</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Blue Monk" (Thelonious Monk)  9:44</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"''Round Midnight" (Monk)  8:19</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 57, '2014-11-01 17:34:07', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:08:04', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-11-14 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 5, 0, 17, 'jazz', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2640, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(229, 'On this day in jazz (November 15)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-november-15', '', '<p>On this day in 1957,   <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jimmy_Smith_(musician)" target="_blank">Jimmy Smith</a>,   the king of the Hammond B-3, recorded a live concert at Small''s Paradise in New York City. The album was titled "Groovin'' At Small''s Paradise". The recording featured Jimmy jamming through 13 songs with a slightly different sound than we''re used to. The reason for the different sound was because the power switch for the percussion setting on Jimmy''s organ was either turned off or broken (no one knows for sure). The effect of this was that the percussion sounds were not routed through the vibrato circuit like normal, instead it comes out straight without any decay due to the switch seemingly set <em>between</em> on and off.</p>\n<p>For more of Jimmy, you can find him on several of my other pages: <a href="index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=170:on-this-day-in-jazz-september-21&catid=55:september&Itemid=41" target="_self">July 16</a>, <a href="index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=143:on-this-day-in-jazz-august-25&catid=54:august&Itemid=41" target="_self">August 25</a>, and <a href="index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=170:on-this-day-in-jazz-september-21&catid=55:september&Itemid=41" target="_self">September 21</a> or just take a listen to The Beastie Boys'' song "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Xf1YF_MH1xc" target="_blank">Root Down</a>" in which they sample Jimmy and shout out to him.</p>\n<p>Here''s Jimmy with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HtUtaIPKz1Y" target="_blank">The Champ</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HtUtaIPKz1Y" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/jimmy%20smith%2001.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Imagination" (Johnny Burke, Jimmy Van Heusen) - 7:56</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Walkin''" (Richard Carpenter) - 11:41 Bonus track on CD reissue</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"My Funny Valentine" (Lorenz Hart, Richard Rodgers) - 11:03</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"It''s Only a Paper Moon" (Harold Arlen, E. Y. Harburg, Billy Rose) - 10:28 Bonus track on CD reissue</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I Can''t Give You Anything But Love" (Dorothy Fields, Jimmy McHugh) - 7:00 Bonus track on CD reissue</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Laura" (Johnny Mercer, David Raksin) - 10:28</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"(Back Home Again in) Indiana" (James F. Hanley, Ballard MacDonald) - 15:40</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Body and Soul" (Edward Heyman, Robert Sour, Frank Eyton, Johnny Green) - 10:03</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Champ" (Dizzy Gillespie) - 13:47 Bonus track on CD reissue</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Lover Man" (Jimmy Davis, Ram Ramirez, James Sherman) - 7:28</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Slightly Monkish" (Jimmy Smith) - 6:59</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"After Hours" (Erskine Hawkins, Avery Parrish) - 10:58</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Just Friends" (John Klenner, Sam M. Lewis) - 6:29</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 57, '2014-11-01 18:04:07', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:08:22', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-11-15 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 16, 'jazz, Jimmy Smith', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2550, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(230, 'On this day in jazz (November 16)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-november-16', '', '<p>On this day in 1964,   guitarist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grant_Green" target="_blank">Grant Green</a> recorded the studio album "Street of Dreams" in Rudy Van Gelder''s Englewood Cliffs studio. Besides regulars Larry Young on the organ and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elvin_Jones" target="_blank">Elvin Jones</a> on drums,   Grant is joined by the great vibraphonist <a href="http://www.bluenote.com/artists/bobby-hutcherson">Bobby Hutcherson</a>.</p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">The cover art for the album is interesting in that you might have actually walked by these signs if you walked down <a href="grantgreen.png" target="_self">Grant Steet in San Francisco</a>. For more on Grant, you can check out my <a href="index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=218:on-this-day-in-jazz-november-04&catid=57:november&Itemid=41" target="_blank">November 4 page</a>. </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span></p>\n<p>Here''s the third song on the album, "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=04HqZw-o6OM" target="_blank">Street of Dreams</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=04HqZw-o6OM" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Street_of_Dreams_%28Grant_Green_album%29.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I Wish You Love" (Chauliac, Trenet)  8:46</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Lazy Afternoon" (Latouche, Moross)  7:44</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Street of Dreams" (Young, Lewis)  9:03</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Somewhere in the Night" (Gordon, Myrow)  8:01</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 57, '2014-11-08 16:01:31', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:08:43', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-11-16 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 15, 'Jazz, Grant Green', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2804, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(231, 'On this day in jazz (November 17)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-november-17', '', '<p>On this day in 1935,   trombonist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roswell_Rudd" target="_blank">Roswell Rudd</a> was born in Sharon,   CT. Rudd is probably best known for his collaborations with <a href="http://www.archieshepp.net/" target="_blank">Archie Shepp</a> and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cecil_Taylor" target="_blank">Cecil Taylor</a>, and is regarded as a significant player in the free and avant-garde jazz movements of the 1960s.</p>\n<p>Roswell is a Yale graduate and taught ethnomusicology at Bard College in New York (Annandale-on-Hudson) and the University of Maine. Roswell has spent a significant time in the African nation Mali, Mongolia and Buryatia playing and recording with local musicians as well as conducting master classes and workshops around the world.</p>\n<p>Some of the honors bestowed on Roswell are:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Guggenheim Fellowship in composition (2000)</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Trombonist of the Year by the Jazz Journalists Association (2003, 2004, 2005, 2009 and 2010)</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Monk''s Dream" nominated for Grammy Awards in the categories of Best Vocal Performance Male and Best Jazz Instrumental Album (1999)</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Down Beat Magazine Critic''s Poll  No. 1 Trombonist (2010--46 years after the same forum voted him most likely to succeed, in 1964)</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Here''s Roswell performing "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dYvGncWTPLA" target="_blank">Steppes Song</a>" with the Mongolian Buryat Band:</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dYvGncWTPLA" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Roswell_Rudd.jpg" border="0" width="215" height="250" /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 57, '2014-11-08 16:22:33', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:09:00', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-11-17 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 14, 'jazz, Roswell Rudd', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2526, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(232, 'On this day in jazz (November 18)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-november-18', '', '<p>On this day in 1957,   bassist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wilbur_Ware" target="_blank">Wilbur Ware</a> would complete recording of his sole album as a leader, "The Chicago Sound". The album was recorded in New York City at Reeves Sound Studios and features Johnny Griffin on the tenor sax, John Jenkins on the alto sax, Junior Mance on the piano and a combination of Frankie Dunlop and Wilbur Campbell on the drums. To this date, it''s the only album I own featuring two Wilburs.</p>\n<p>Ware is best known for his collaborations with Thelonious Monk and Sonny Rollins, for possessing a unique perspective on time and space, and being able to play some of the most difficult jazz music at incredible speed.<span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Unfortunately, he struggled with a narcotics addiction that resulted in incarceration and costing him to lose six years musically. Wilbur passed away from emphysema in 1979.</span></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Here''s Wilbur with "</span><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-H_9hVOzC2E&list=PLZG8xAsenL8aSRz6NyOW90S2MOoVuSFgG&index=4" target="_blank" style="line-height: 1.3em;">The Man I Love</a><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">":</span></p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-H_9hVOzC2E&list=PLZG8xAsenL8aSRz6NyOW90S2MOoVuSFgG&index=4" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/wilbur_ware.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Mamma-Daddy" - 3:53</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Body and Soul" (Frank Eyton, Johnny Green, Edward Heyman, Robert Sour) - 3:15</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Desert Sands" (Paul Dunlap, Edward Heyman, Stuff Smith) - 5:28</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"31st and State" - 6:27</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Lullaby of the Leaves" (Bernice Petkere, Joe Young) - 2:56</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Latin Quarters" (John Jenkins) - 4:37</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Be-Ware" (Jenkins) - 4:28</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Man I Love" (George Gershwin, Ira Gershwin) - 7:21</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 57, '2014-11-08 17:05:36', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:09:13', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-11-18 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 5, 0, 13, 'jazz, Wilbur Ware', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2659, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(233, 'On this day in jazz (November 19)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-november-19', '', '<p>On this day in 1960,   flugelhornist <a href="http://clarkterry.com/" target="_blank">Clark Terry</a> recorded "Color Changes". It proved to be one of his finest albums and features arrangements by <a href="http://www.yuseflateef.com/" target="_blank">Yusef Lateef</a>,   Budd Johnson, and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Al_Cohn" target="_blank">Al Cohn</a>. Joining Clark on the album were Yusef Lateef (on tenor, flute, oboe, and English horn), Jimmy Knepper (on trombone), Julius Watkins (on French horn), Seldon Powell (on tenor saxophone and flute), and a rhythm section of Tommy Flanagan (piano), Joe Benjamin (bass), and Ed Shaughnessy (drums).</p>\n<p>Clark''s professional career has spanned over 70 years and over his long career Clark has become one of the most recorded and one of the most decorated musicians in jazz history (over 250 awards and counting). Some of the major awards bestowed on him are:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">The National Endowment for the Arts Jazz Master Award (1991)</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Inducted into the Jazz at Lincoln Center Nesuhi Ertegun Jazz Hall of Fame (2013)</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">The 2010 Grammy Lifetime Achievement Award, two Grammy certificates, three Grammy nominations</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">The French Order of Arts and Letters (2000)</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Sixteen honorary doctorates</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Here''s Clark with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uhDVTkPA5CE" target="_blank">No Problem</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uhDVTkPA5CE" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Clark_Mumbles_Terry.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 57, '2014-11-08 17:21:44', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:09:25', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-11-19 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 12, 'jazz, Clark Terry', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2391, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(234, 'On this day in jazz (November 20)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-november-20', '', '<p>On this day in 1959,   <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a> began recording "Sketches of Spain" at the Columbia 30th Street Studio in New York City. The style of the album is considered to be "Third Stream" due to the classical influences upon the music. The album features an extended version of the second movement of classical jazz guitarist Joaquin Rodrigo''s "Concierto de Aranjuez" along with "Will o'' the Wisp" which is from the ballet El Amor Brujo by Manuel de Falla.</p>\n<p>For the Rodrigo song,   Miles plays the flugelhorn which serves as a substitution for Rodrigo''s guitar and then later moves to the trumpet. When asked about his view of the work,   Rodrigo said that he was not impressed. In fact, at the time is was released there was little else to musically compare it to, so it caught the public quite by surprise. Despite the public reception, Gil Evans (arranger) and Davis won the 1961 Grammy Award for Best Original Jazz Composition. Over the years, it has come to be regarded as one of the top 50 albums in the overall jazz genre, and it was recently included the the Rolling Stone 500 greatest albums of all time at #358.</p>\n<p>Here''s "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9xBeqafxkE4" target="_blank">Will O the Wisp</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9xBeqafxkE4" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Miles_Davis_-_Sketches_of_Spain.png" border="0" width="250" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Concierto de Aranjuez" (Adagio) (Joaqun Rodrigo)  16:19</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Will o'' the Wisp" (Manuel de Falla)  3:47</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Pan Piper" (a.k.a. Alborada de Vigo) (traditional)  3:52</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Saeta" (Gil Evans)  5:06</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Solea" (Evans)  12:15</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 57, '2014-11-08 18:15:14', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:09:38', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-11-20 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 11, 'jazz, Miles Davis', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2404, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(235, 'On this day in jazz (November 21)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-november-21', '', '<p>On this day in 1963,   trombonist <a href="http://www.grachanmoncur.com/" target="_blank">Granchan Moncur III</a> recorded his first album, "Evolution" at Rudy Van Gelder''s Englewood Cliffs studio. The album was highly praised, but Granchan would only record eight more albums as a leader. Joining Granchan on this album were the great <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lee_Morgan" target="_blank">Lee Morgan</a> on trumpet, the legendary <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jackie_McLean" target="_blank">Jackie McLean</a> on saxophone, and a vrythm section featuring the legendary <a href="http://www.bluenote.com/artists/bobby-hutcherson" target="_blank">Bobby Hutcherson</a> on vibraphone, Bob Cranshaw on bass and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tony_Williams_(drummer)" target="_blank">Tony Williams</a> on drums.</p>\n<p>Granchan, the son of a jazz bassist, was born in New York City and raised in Newark, NJ. He picked up his first instrument (the cello) at age 9, but moved to the trombone at 11. He attended the Laurinburg Institute of North Carolina in high school and played with <a href="http://www.artblakey.com/" target="_blank">Art Blakey</a> and Jackie McLean (with whom he would later record two important albums: "One Step Beyond" and "Destination Out!") when they came to town.</p>\n<p>Here''s Granchan with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eHWhrigwG7I" target="_blank">Air Raid</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eHWhrigwG7I" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/515dc3d024424.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Air Raid" - 9:19</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Evolution" - 12:24</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Coaster" - 11:39</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Monk in Wonderland" - 7:54</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 57, '2014-11-08 18:57:54', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:09:54', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-11-21 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 10, 'jazz, Granchan Moncur III', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2541, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(236, 'On this day in jazz (November 22)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-november-22', '', '<p>On this day in 1985,   trumpeter <a href="http://www.freddiehubbardmusic.com/" target="_blank">Freddie Hubbard</a> and trumpeter <a href="http://www.woodyshaw.com/" target="_blank">Woody Shaw</a> completed recording of "Double Take". Joining them on the album were Kenny Garrett on the alto sax and a rhythm section of Mulgrew Miller (piano),   <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/cecil-mcbee-mn0000739015/biography" target="_blank">Cecil McBee</a> (bass) and Carl Allen (drums).</p>\n<p>The duo also recorded another collaboration a couple of years later ("The Eternal Triangle") and you can find them both on the CD "The Complete Freddie Hubbard and Woody Shaw Sessions". The songs they picked for this album include works by both men and also <a href="http://cliffordbrown.net/" target="_blank">Clifford Brown''s</a> "Sandu", <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fats_Navarro" target="_blank">Fats Navarro''s</a> "Boperation", <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lee_Morgan" target="_blank">Lee Morgan''s</a> "Desert Moonlight" and <a href="http://www.kennydorham.net/biography/" target="_blank">Kenny Dorham''s</a> "Lotus Blossom". Check it out, it''s really a great set.</p>\n<p>Here''s Freddie and Woody sounding great together playing "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OKRsO88JtD8" target="_blank">Boperation</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OKRsO88JtD8" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/freddie_woody.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Sandu" (Clifford Brown) - 4:28</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Boperation" (Howard McGhee, Fats Navarro) - 4:56</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Lament for Booker" (Freddie Hubbard, J. J. Johnson) - 6:22</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Hub-Tones" (Hubbard) - 6:25</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Desert Moonlight" (Lee Morgan) - 8:10</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Just a Ballad for Woody" (Woody Shaw) - 5:30</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Lotus Blossom" (Kenny Dorham) - 8:15</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 57, '2014-11-13 02:11:53', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:10:33', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-11-22 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 9, 'jazz, Woody Shaw, Freddie Hubbard', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2630, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(237, 'On this day in jazz (November 23)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-november-23', '', '<p>On this day in 1955,   <a href="http://www.artblakey.com/" target="_blank">Art Blakey</a> and his Jazz Messengers were recorded live at the Cafe Bohemia in Greenwich Village. During this performance, the Jazz Messengers consisted of the great <a href="http://www.horacesilver.com/" target="_blank">Horace Silver</a> on piano, <a href="http://www.kennydorham.net/biography/" target="_blank">Kenny Dorham</a> on trumpet, the wonderful <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hank_Mobley" target="_blank">Hank Mobley</a> on tenor sax, and Doug Watkins on bass. Eventually, Horace would steal the Jazz Messengers away from Art for a few albums, so it''s great to be able to hear both Horace and Art together on this one.</p>\n<p>The entire night''s work can be found on two CDs entitled "At the Cafe Bohemia, Vol. 1" and "At the Cafe Bohemia, Vol. 2".</p>\n<p>Here''s Art and the Jazz Messengers with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=d6GJzOPb8-k" target="_blank">Prince Albert</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=d6GJzOPb8-k" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/art-blakey.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p>CD 1</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Announcement by Art Blakey 1:32</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Soft Winds" 12:34</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Theme" 6:11</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Minor''s Holiday" 9:11</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Alone Together" 4:15</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Prince Albert" 8:51</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p>CD 2</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Sportin'' Crowd" 7:32</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Like Someone in Love" 9:18</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Yesterdays" </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">4:20</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Just One of Those Things" 9:29</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Hank''s Symphony" 4:44</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Gone with the Wind" 7:27</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Avila and Tequila" 12:49</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I Waited for You" </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">9:50</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 57, '2014-11-13 02:23:01', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:10:48', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-11-23 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 8, 'jazz, Art Blakey, Horace Silver', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2420, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(238, 'On this day in jazz (November 24)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-november-24', '', '<p>On this day in 1974,   trumpeter <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chet_Baker" target="_blank">Chet Baker</a> and baritone saxophonist <a href="http://www.gerrymulligan.com/" target="_blank">Gerry Mulligan</a> reunited for a concert at Carnegie Hall. Joining the duo was a rhythm section of Bob James on pianos, Dave Samuels on vibes, Ron Carter on bass and Harvey Mason on drums. Throw in <a href="http://www.johnscofield.com/" target="_blank">John Scofield</a> who is heard here in one of his first recordings and you have quite the lineup.</p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Check out more background on Chet Baker on my <a href="index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=110:on-this-day-in-jazz-july-23&catid=53:july&Itemid=41" target="_self">July 23rd page</a> and compare the song below to the song on that page. There''s 18 years between the recordings (and also the terrible attack that Chet suffered in 1968 where he lost his front teeth), but all in all I think the 1974 version sounds pretty much like the young Chet.</span></p>\n<p>Here''s Chet and Gerry with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lZw3jB17TrE" target="_blank">There Will Never Be Another You</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lZw3jB17TrE" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/df901b171b9e4d2531a8e2f5d9cc7.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing (songs by Mulligan unless noted):</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Line for Lyons 8:14</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">For an Unfinished Woman 8:48</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">My Funny Valentine (Hart / Rodgers) 8:40</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Song for Strayhorn 9:26</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">It''s Sandy at the Beach 9:08</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">K-4 Pacific 11:41</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">There Will Never Be Another You (Gordon / Warren) 6:53</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 57, '2014-11-13 11:27:18', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:11:02', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-11-24 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 7, 'jazz, Chet Baker, Gerry Mulligan', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2566, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(239, 'On this day in jazz (November 25)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-november-25', '', '<p>On this day in 1960,   the great <a href="http://www.cannonball-adderley.com/" target="_blank">Cannonball Adderley</a> was recorded live in concert at Salle Pleyel in Paris during his very first European tour. This is one of my favorite live performances and have listened to it more times than I can count. Joining Cannonball for the set were his brother, coronetist Nat Adderley, and a rhythm section of Victor Feldman (piano), Sam Jones (bass) and Louis Hayes (drums).</p>\n<p>Despite Cannonball not speaking French (which he apologizes for after the first song), he does talk a bit between the songs which makes the performance even more interesting. Two of the songs are absolute must hears: "Jeannine" and "Dis Here", but the rest are quite entertaining, too. It''s all classic hard bob with Cannball''s "exhuberent and happy" alto pacing the way (Scott Yanow with the quote).</p>\n<p>Here''s Cannonball with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=au9MWVPmcbE" target="_blank">Jeannine</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=au9MWVPmcbE" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/MI0000142390.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 57, '2014-11-15 17:14:28', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:11:17', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-11-25 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 6, 'jazz, Cannonball Adderley', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2688, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(240, 'On this day in jazz (November 26)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-november-26', '', '<p>On this day in 1956,   the great trombonist and band leader Tommy Dorsey passed away at his home in Connecticut. Although these days when people think of the Dorsey name,   they''re probably thinking about his his older brother,   Jimmy, Tommy was quite accomplished in his day. He racked up 286 Billboard chart hits including seventeen number one hits including: "On Treasure Island", "The Music Goes ''Round and Around", "You", "Marie", "Satan Takes a Holiday", "The Big Apple", "Once in a While", "The Dipsy Doodle", "Our Love", "All the Things You Are", "Indian Summer", and "Dolores". His biggest hit was "I''ll Never Smile Again" which featured Frank Sinatra on vocals and was number one for twelve weeks on the Billboard pop singles chart in 1940. It has been reported that over 110 million Tommy Dorsey records have been sold. That''s a lot.</p>\n<p>Here''s Tommy Dorsey with Edythe Wright with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q9CAMCP6VR8" target="_blank">The Music Goes Round and Round</a>" from 1935:</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q9CAMCP6VR8" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Tommy-Dorsey.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Although the above version is pretty good, I prefer <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hminkVMTgCc" target="_blank">Red Norvo and Mae ("Betty Boop") Questel''s version</a>:</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hminkVMTgCc" target="_blank"><img src="https://ia600408.us.archive.org/3/items/MaeQuestelTheVoiceOfBettyBoop/MaeQuestelAged16-17_thumb.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 57, '2014-11-15 17:36:50', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:11:30', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-11-26 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 5, 'jazz, Tommy Dorsey', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2449, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(241, 'On this day in jazz (November 27)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-november-27', '', '<p>On this day in 1973,   <a href="http://www.puredesmond.ca/" target="_blank">Paul Desmond</a> began recording the album "Skylark" at Rudy Van Gelder''s studio in Englewood Cliffs,   NJ. Joining Paul on the album were guitarists <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/G%C3%A1bor_Szab%C3%B3" target="_blank">Gbor Szab</a> and Gene Bertoncini, George Ricci on cello and a rhythm section consisting of <a href="http://www.bobjames.com/" target="_blank">Bob James</a> on piano / electric piano, <a href="http://roncarter.net/JazzMaster/" target="_blank">Ron Carter</a> on bass and percussion instuments provided by Jack DeJohnette and Ralph MacDonald.</p>\n<p>Paul was one of the great alto saxophonists of all time, most known for his collaborations with <a href="http://www.davebrubeck.com/live/" target="_blank">Dave Brubeck</a>. His style is typical west coast cool jazz, and the song below is a great example of that genre. The sax comes across a sultry, smoky and very vibrant. If you like Paul you''ll also like <a href="http://www.zootsims.org/" target="_blank">Zoot Sims</a> and <a href="http://www.stangetz.net/" target="_blank">Stan Getz</a> (both whom I consider to have had better careers than Paul).</p>\n<p>Here''s Paul with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=x_ZPceluIsY" target="_blank">Skylark</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=x_ZPceluIsY" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/maxresdefault.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Take Ten" (Paul Desmond) - 6:08</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Romance de Amor" (Traditional) - 9:40</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Was a Sunny Day" (Paul Simon) - 4:52</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Music for a While" (Henry Purcell) - 6:45</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Skylark" (Hoagy Carmichael, Johnny Mercer) - 5:21</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Indian Summer" (Al Dubin, Victor Herbert) - 4:00</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 57, '2014-11-15 17:53:01', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:11:43', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-11-27 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 4, 'jazz, Paul Desmond', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2506, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(242, 'On this day in jazz (November 28)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-november-28', '', '<p>On this day in 1974,   pianist <a href="http://www.oscarpeterson.com/" target="_blank">Oscar Peterson</a> and trumpeter <a href="http://www.dizzygillespie.com/" target="_blank">Dizzy Gillespie</a> began recording the eponymous album "Oscar Peterson & Dizzy Gillespie" (it would be completed the next day). The work features several songs by Gillespie,  two collaborations between the duo ("Mozambique" and "Blues for Bird") as well as songs by <a href="http://www.dukeellington.com/" target="_blank">Duke Ellington</a>,Johnny Mercer, et al. This album was actually the first of what would eventually be five collaborations between the two. If you''re wondering who else played on the album, don''t. These are all duets.</p>\n<p>The album, as you can imagine, is quite good and reached as high as #37 on the Billboard Jazz Albums charts when released. In fact, Dizzy won the Grammy for Best Jazz Instrumental Performance for 1975 because of his work here.</p>\n<p>Here''s OP and Dizz with the standard "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ozHyz_APWrg" target="_blank">Autumn Leaves</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ozHyz_APWrg" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/51NOvXecHYL._SL500_AA280_.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Caravan" (Duke Ellington, Irving Mills, Juan Tizol)  7:02</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Mozambique" (Dizzy Gillespie, Oscar Peterson)  7:08</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Autumn Leaves" (Joseph Kosma, Johnny Mercer, Jacques Prvert)  7:25</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Close Your Eyes" (Bernice Petkere)  5:26</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Blues for Bird" (Gillespie, Peterson)  12:32</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Dizzy Atmosphere" (Gillespie)  4:55</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Alone Together" (Howard Dietz, Arthur Schwartz)  5:16</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Con Alma" (Gillespie)  5:15</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 57, '2014-11-20 11:50:10', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:11:58', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-11-28 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 5, 0, 3, 'Oscar Peterson, Dizzie Gillepsie, jazz', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2532, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(243, 'On this day in jazz (November 29)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-november-29', '', '<p>On this day in 1957,   tenor saxophonist <a href="http://www.johncoltrane.com/" target="_blank">John Coltrane</a> and pianist <a href="http://www.monkzone.com/" target="_blank">Thelonious Monk</a> were recorded playing a benefit concert at "Carnegie Hall" in NYC. The title of the concert was "Thanksgiving Jazz" and the benefit was for the Morningside Community Center in Harlem. In addition to Coltrane and Monk,   other artists performing at the benefit were <a href="http://www.billieholiday.com/" target="_blank">Billie Holiday</a>,   <a href="http://www.dizzygillespie.com/" target="_blank">Dizzy Gillespie</a>, Ray Charles, <a href="http://sonnyrollins.com/" target="_blank">Sonny Rollins</a>, and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chet_Baker" target="_blank">Chet Baker</a> with <a href="http://www.zootsims.org/" target="_blank">Zoot Sims</a>--what a night it must have been!</p>\n<p>There are actually two sets in this recording: the first five songs are from their first set and the last four songs comprise an incomplete second set. Unfortunately, "Epistrophy" is cut off on the second set, but, luckily, it is recorded in full on the first set.<span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Aside from the fact that you''ve got two of the greatest Jazz musicians of all time playing here, the recording is interesting from a non-musical viewpoint as well. The recording was made by Voice of America and later made its way to the vaults of the Library of Congress. It sat there gathering dust for over 45 years when recording supervisor Larry Applebaum noticed a set of tapes which were labeled sp. Event 11/29/57 carnegie jazz concert (#1), and one labeled T. Monk.. The album was released in 2005 after being restored by producer Michael Cuscuna and Monk''s son, T.S. Monk. After release it became the #1 selling album on amazon.com, and Newsweek even called it the "musical equivalent of the discovery of a new Mount Everest". So take a listen and add it to your collection. For more on the story of the recording, see Monk''s site <a href="http://www.monkzone.com/story.html" target="_blank">here</a>.</span></p>\n<p>Here''s the full version of "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5cbm64xUWnE" target="_blank">Epistrophy</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5cbm64xUWnE" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/MonktraneWeb-1390497848.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Monk''s Mood"  7:52</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Evidence"  4:41</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Crepuscule With Nellie"  4:26</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Nutty"  5:03</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Epistrophy"  4:29</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Bye-Ya"  6:31</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Sweet & Lovely"  9:34</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Blue Monk"  6:31</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Epistrophy" (incomplete)  2:24</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 57, '2014-11-20 12:07:36', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:12:12', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-11-29 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 5, 0, 2, 'jazz, John Coltrane, Thelonious Monk', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2634, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(244, 'On this day in jazz (November 30)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-november-30', '', '<p>On this day in 1966,   pianist <a href="http://chickcorea.com/" target="_blank">Chick Corea</a> was recording his debut album as a leader,   "Tones for Joan''s Bones". The album featured an all-star cast supporting Chick: <a href="http://www.woodyshaw.com/" target="_blank">Woody Shaw</a> on trumpet,   <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joe_Farrell" target="_blank">Joe Farrell</a> on tenor saxophone and flute, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steve_Swallow" target="_blank">Steve Swallow</a> on bass and <a href="http://www.josephachambers.com/" target="_blank">Joe Chambers</a> on drums. All songs were written by Chick.</p>\n<p>The album is pretty hard to find as the labels decided, over the years, to include the works inside other albums. If you can''t find the original, you can find all the works (listed below) in Miroslav Vitou'' album "Mountain in the Clouds". If you''d rather get an album that includes <a href="http://www.herbiehancock.com/home.php" target="_blank">Herbie Hancock</a>, <a href="http://www.keithjarrett.org/" target="_blank">Keith Jarrett</a> and <a href="http://mccoytyner.com/" target="_blank">McCoy Tyner</a> also (man, I''m dropping names), get the compilation album "Chick Corea, Herbie Hancock, Keith Jarrett, McCoy Tyner" which you can easily find on <a href="http://www.amazon.com/Chick-Corea-Herbie-Hancock-Jarrett/dp/B000002I6H" target="_blank">amazon.com</a>. Or, as a third option, get his album "Inner Space" which includes all of these works on a 2 LP set (note, the CD reissue does not include "This is New" or "Tones"). If you get the "Inner Space" reissue, also pick up <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blue_Mitchell" target="_blank">Blue Mitchell''s</a> "Boss Horn" as it includes "Tones".</p>\n<p>If you like what you hear, check out Chick on <a href="https://www.facebook.com/chickcorea" target="_blank">facebook</a>--he''s still very active in 2014!</p>\n<p>Here''s Chick with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uALWPswGJeE" target="_blank">This is New</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uALWPswGJeE" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Chick-Corea-e1340641581845.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Litha" </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">13:33</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"This is New" </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">7:37</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Tones for Joan''s Bones" </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">6:11</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Straight Up and Down" </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">12:33</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 57, '2014-11-20 14:00:59', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:12:24', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-11-30 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 1, 'jazz, Chick Corea', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2787, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(245, 'On this day in jazz (December 01)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-december-01', '', '<p>On this day in 1967,   pianist <a href="http://mccoytyner.com/" target="_blank">McCoy Tyner</a> recorded his eighth studio album, "Tender Moments" at Van Gelder Studio in Englewood Cliffs, NJ. He was supported on the album by the great <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lee_Morgan" target="_blank">Lee Morgan</a> on trumpet, the wonderful <a href="http://www.josephachambers.com/" target="_blank">Joe Chambers</a> on drums, Herbie Lewis on bass, Julian Priester on trombone, Bob Northern on french horn, Howard Johnson on tuba, James Spaulding on alto saxophone and flute, and Bennie Maupin on tenor saxophone. That''s a lot of wind!</p>\n<p>All songs are originals by McCoy and Scott Yanow of allmusic.com states that "the music is quite colorful and advanced for the period. Well worth investigating". It is also one of the albums that <a href="http://www.concordmusicgroup.com/search/?Search_Type=album&Search=Rudy+Van+Gelder" target="_blank">Rudy Van Gelder chose to remaster in 24-bit resolution</a> from the original two-track tapes. If you get the chance to find a RVG remaster of an album, they are high suggested.</p>\n<p>Here''s McCoy with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yRErVHZG_rE" target="_blank">All My Yesterdays</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yRErVHZG_rE" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/mccoy-tyner-01.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Mode to John" - 5:42</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Man from Tanganyika" - 6:54</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The High Priest" - 6:08</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Utopia" - 7:37</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"All My Yesterdays" - 6:04</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Lee Plus Three" - 5:35</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 58, '2014-11-20 14:20:47', 62, '', '2016-08-20 01:02:54', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-12-01 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 31, 'jazz, McCoy Tyner', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1925, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(246, 'On this day in jazz (December 02)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-december-02', '', '<p>On this day in 1959,   two of the greatest cool jazz saxophonists of all time completed their collaboration "Gerry Mulligan Meets Ben Webster". <a href="http://www.gerrymulligan.com/" target="_blank">Gerry</a> is undoubtedly the best baritone saxophonist to have ever played the instrument and <a href="http://www.benwebster.dk/" target="_blank">Ben</a> was one of the leading tenor saxophonists of his time. The collaboration started on November 3rd and produced a tremendous amount of great music over the next month. The original LP issue featured 6 songs and the CD reissue contains 5 bonus tracks<span style="line-height: 15.8079996109009px;"> </span><span style="line-height: 15.8079996109009px;">(listed below)</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">. If you''re a "completeist",   Verve reissued "Gerry Mulligan Meets Ben Webster (Complete)" in 1997 which contains the aforementioned 11 songs along with 15 alternate takes. </span></p>\n<p>This album is quite good and is even part of NPR''s "Basic Jazz Library".allmusic.com gives it its highest "5-star" rating.</p>\n<p>Here''s "<a href="http://iisaphd.subsonic.org/share/FiGzn" target="_blank">The Cat Walk</a>" which is the only song on the album which the two shared writing credits for:</p>\n<p><a href="http://iisaphd.subsonic.org/share/FiGzn"><img src="images/tdij/Untitled-1_________coteb_article.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing (Gerry Mulligan composer unless otherwise noted):</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Chelsea Bridge" (Billy Strayhorn)  7:22</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Cat Walk" (Mulligan, Ben Webster)  5:47</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Sunday" (Chester Conn, Bennie Krueger, Nathan "Ned" Miller, Jule Styne)  7:25</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Who''s Got Rhythm"  7:42</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Tell Me When"  5:06</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Go Home"  10:04</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"In a Mellow Tone" (Duke Ellington, Milt Gabler)  6:57</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"What Is This Thing Called Love?" (Cole Porter)  7:28</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"For Bessie" (Webster)  5:41</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Fajista" (Webster)  5:50</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Blues in B Flat"  7:22</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 58, '2014-11-20 14:45:41', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:13:30', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-12-02 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 7, 0, 30, 'jazz, Ben Webster, Gerry Mulligan', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1855, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(247, 'On this day in jazz (December 03)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-december-03', '', '<p>On this day in 1957,   the great baritone saxophonist <a href="http://www.gerrymulligan.com/" target="_blank">Gerry Mulligan</a> (who was also highlighted yesterday) began recording "Reunion" with his old pal <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chet_Baker" target="_blank">Chet Baker</a>. Gerry and Chet performed some quite memorable work in the early fifties and then went their separate ways to become band leaders; this work is a continuation of that partnership. Gerry wrote the title song and the album also includes works by Hoagy Carmichael,   Cole Porter, Hammerstein & Rodgers, Johnny Mercer and <a href="http://www.cmgww.com/music/parker/home.html" target="_blank">Charlie Parker</a> (just to name a few). Henry Grimes and Dave Bailey joined the duo playing bass and drums, respectively.</p>\n<p>If you want to hear some of the earlier collaborations along with the reunion, you can find "The Complete Gerry Mulligan Quartet with Chet Baker The Original Sessions & Collaborations 1953 The Reunion 1957" at <a href="http://www.amazon.com/complete-Mulligan-Original-Sessions-Collaborations/dp/B005937TPW" target="_blank">amazon.com</a>.<span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Check out my blog for other interesting tidbits about both Gerry and Chet.</span></p>\n<p>Here''s Gerry and Chet with the title song, "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GtD7fY1057w" target="_blank">Reunion</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GtD7fY1057w" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/D-triochetgerry.JPG" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Reunion" (Gerry Mulligan) - 4:03</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"When Your Lover Has Gone" (Einar Aaron Swan) - 5:05</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Stardust" (Hoagy Carmichael, Mitchell Parish) - 4:42</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"My Heart Belongs to Daddy" (Cole Porter) - 4:11</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Jersey Bounce" (Tiny Bradshaw, Buddy Feyne, Eddie Johnson, Bobby Plater) - 4:25</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Surrey With the Fringe on Top" (Oscar Hammerstein II, Richard Rodgers) - 4:40</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Trav''lin'' Light" (Johnny Mercer, Jimmy Mundy, Trummy Young) - 3:40</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Ornithology" (Benny Harris, Charlie Parker) - 5:11</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 58, '2014-11-20 15:14:33', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:13:50', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-12-03 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 29, 'jazz, Gerry Mulligan, Chet Baker', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2329, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(248, 'On this day in jazz (December 11)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-december-11', '', '<p>On this day in 1949,   <a href="http://www.sonnystitt.com/" target="_blank">Sonny Stitt</a> recorded four songs with the great <a href="http://www.budpowelljazz.com/" target="_blank">Bud Powell</a> that would later be released as "All God''s Children Got Rhythm". Not sure why they didn''t call it "All God''s Chillun Got Rhythm"...but anyway, it''s a great recording. The first four songs listed below were recorded with Sonny on tenor sax, Bud at the piano, Curly Russell on bass, and the great <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/max-roach-mn0000396372/biography" target="_blank">Max Roach</a> on drums. Although the album is really a compilation of three different sets (one with J.J. Johnson, also), you could arguably call it Sonny''s first studio album-- some would argue that "Stitt''s Bits" (1950) was his first.</p>\n<p>Here''s the <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=blp_SDq98gQ" target="_blank">four songs recorded that day</a>:</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=blp_SDq98gQ" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Sonny+Stitt+c850675656745e230d54ca8e9235c5.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"All God''s Chillun Got Rhythm" (Walter Jurmann, Gus Kahn, Bronis?aw Kaper) - 2:57</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Sonnyside" - 2:21</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Bud''s Blues" - 2:32</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Sunset" - 3:44</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Fine and Dandy" (Paul James, Kay Swift) - 2:39</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Fine and Dandy" [alternate take] (James, Swift) - 2:38 Bonus track on CD reissue</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Strike Up the Band" (George Gershwin, Ira Gershwin) - 3:26</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I Want to Be Happy" (Irving Caesar, Vincent Youmans) - 3:09</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Taking a Chance on Love" (Vernon Duke, Ted Fetter, John Latouche) - 2:32</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Afternoon in Paris" (John Lewis) - 3:03</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Afternoon in Paris" [alternate take] (Lewis) - 2:59 Bonus track on CD reissue</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Elora" (J.J. Johnson) - 3:03</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Elora" [alternate take] (Johnson) - 3:07 Bonus track on CD reissue</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Teapot" (Johnson) - 2:43</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Teapot" [alternate take] (Johnson) - 3:01 Bonus track on CD reissue</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Blue Mode" (Johnson) - 3:45</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Blue Mode" [alternate take] (Johnson) - 2:49 Bonus track on CD reissue</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p style="line-height: 15.8079996109009px;">Songs 1-4: December 11, 1949; s<span style="line-height: 15.8079996109009px;">ongs 5-9: January 26, 1950; s</span><span style="line-height: 15.8079996109009px;">ongs 10-17: October 17, 1949</span></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 58, '2014-11-20 15:33:26', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:14:05', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-12-11 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 6, 0, 21, 'jazz, Sonny Stitt, Bud Powell, J.J. Johnson', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1584, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(249, 'On this day in jazz (December 04)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-december-04', '', '<p>On this day in 1964,   guitarist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kenny_Burrell" target="_blank">Kenny Burrell</a> began recording the studio album "Guitar Forms". The album features arrangements by Gil Evans on five of the nine tracks; three blues songs without the larger group and one solo performance ("Prelude #2"). The rhythm section joining Kenny on the album were Roger Kellaway on piano, Joe Benjamin on bass, Grady Tate on drums and Willie Rodriguez playing the congas. The orchestra included some jazz greats as well including <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lee_Konitz" target="_blank">Lee Konitz</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steve_Lacy" target="_blank">Steve Lacy</a>, <a href="http://roncarter.net/JazzMaster/" target="_blank">Ron Carter</a> and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elvin_Jones" target="_blank">Elvin Jones</a>.</p>\n<p>If you''re not familiar with Kenny, he is probably best known for his collaboration with organist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jimmy_Smith_(musician)" target="_blank">Jimmy Smith</a> on "Organ Grinder Swing" which was a top 20 hit. His first album as a leader was in 1956: "Introducing Kenny Burrell". His album "Midnight Blue" is his most notable album as a soloist and is part of NPR''s "Basic Jazz Library" collection. He currently is Director of Jazz Studies at UCLA''s Herb Alpert School of Music.</p>\n<p>Here''s Kenny with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Qp50jQ_mPAg" target="_blank">Downstairs</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Qp50jQ_mPAg" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/G-barrel.JPG" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Downstairs" (Elvin Jones)  2:53</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Lotus Land" (Cyril Scott)  9:38</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Terrace Theme" (Joe Benjamin)  4:02</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Prelude No. 2" (George Gershwin)  2:17</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Moon and Sand" (William Engvick, Morty Palitz, Alec Wilder)  4:16</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Loie" (Kenny Burrell)  3:19</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Greensleeves" (Traditional)  4:12</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Last Night When We Were Young" (Harold Arlen, Yip Harburg)  4:34</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Breadwinner" (Burrell)  3:00</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 58, '2014-11-23 16:27:28', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:14:38', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-12-04 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 28, 'jazz, Kenny Burrell', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1908, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(250, 'On this day in jazz (December 05)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-december-05', '', '<p>On this day in 1972,   the great <a href="http://www.dukeellington.com/" target="_blank">Duke Ellington</a> teamed up with bassist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ray_Brown_(musician)" target="_blank">Ray Brown</a> to recorded a series of duets that would be released as the studio album "This One''s For Blanton!". Blanton refers to Chattanooga,   Tennessee native <a href="http://www.jazz.com/encyclopedia/blanton-jimmy-james-h-jr" target="_blank">Jimmy Blanton</a> who played with Duke for a couple of years starting in 1939 and also recorded a series of duets with the Duke.</p>\n<p>Blanton is known for changing the way that the bass was played in jazz music. Prior to Jimmy,   the bass was simply an background instrument used for quarter notes and a rare solo. Jimmy introduced playing eighth and sixteenth notes, transforming the bass from just a rhythm instrument to an instrument worth of the same ground as the winds. Blanton is also remembered for being part of Duke''s big band at the same time as Ben Webster--if you''ve heard of "The Blanton-Webster Band", it refers to the recordings of the Duke Ellington Orchestra between 1940 and 1942 while the two were in the band. Unfortunately, Blanton contracted tuberculosis at the age of 23 and died shortly thereafter.</p>\n<p>Here''s the Duke and Ray Brown with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qZFTDxYV7ss" target="_blank">Sophisticated Lady</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qZFTDxYV7ss" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/56ec6ea19836e4a85f1bbfbd7d242.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Do Nothin'' Till You Hear from Me" (Ellington, Bob Russell) - 5:36</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Pitter Panther Patter" - 3:06</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Things Ain''t What They Used to Be" (Mercer Ellington) - 4:00</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Sophisticated Lady" (Ellington, Irving Mills, Mitchell Parish) - 5:30</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"See See Rider" (Traditional) - 3:07</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Fragmented Suite for Piano and Bass: First Movement" (Ray Brown, Ellington) - 4:51</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Fragmented Suite for Piano and Bass: Second Movement" (Brown, Ellington) - 5:11</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Fragmented Suite for Piano and Bass: Third Movement" (Brown, Ellington) - 3:40</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Fragmented Suite for Piano and Bass: Fourth Movement" (Brown, Ellington) - 4:58</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 58, '2014-11-23 17:10:22', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:15:07', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-12-05 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 27, 'jazz, Duke Ellington, Jimmy Blanton', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1791, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(251, 'On this day in jazz (December 06)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-december-06', '', '<p>On this day in 1996,   master guitarist <a href="http://www.jimhallmusic.com/" target="_blank">Jim Hall</a> was recorded live at the Village Vanguard in New York City performing songs that would be released on the album "Panorama: Live At The Village Vanguard". Joining Jim on the album were Greg Osby on alto saxophone, the great <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/art-farmer-mn0000502199/biography" target="_blank">Art Farmer</a> playing the flugelhorn, Slide Hampton on trombone, <a href="http://kennybarron.com/" target="_blank">Kenny Barron</a> and Geoff Keezer on pianos, Scott Colley on bass and Terry Clarke on drums.</p>\n<p>Hall had a long an storied career and was a great ambassador for jazz music. In 1957 he was part of the legendary trio of saxophonist <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jimmy_Giuffre" target="_blank">Jimmy Giuffre</a> and trombonist <a href="http://www.bobbrookmeyer.com/" target="_blank">Bob Brookmeryer</a> (note, a trio without piano, bass or drums) and was one of the first to play "Third Stream", recording with violinist Itzhak Perlman.</p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Here''s Jim with "</span><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D4L_jxx4pRg" target="_blank" style="line-height: 1.3em;">The Answer is Yes</a><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">":</span></p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D4L_jxx4pRg" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Jim-Hall-in-1955-770.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Pan-O-Rama</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">8:27</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Little Blues</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">9:05</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">The Answer is Yes</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">9:11</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Entre Nous</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">4:24</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;"> </span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Furnished Flats</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">6:50</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;"> </span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Something To Wish For</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">4:46</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;"> </span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">No You Don''t!</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">6:40</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;"> </span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Painted Pig</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">7:34</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Here Comes Jane 7:12</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 58, '2014-11-23 17:34:41', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:15:18', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-12-06 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 26, 'jazz, Jim Hall', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1942, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(252, 'On this day in jazz (December 07)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-december-07', '', '<p>On this day in 1956,   the legendary <a href="http://www.monkzone.com/" target="_blank">Thelonious Monk</a> completed the recording of his greatest album,   "Brilliant Corners". The album was inducted into the Grammy Hall of Fame in 1999; was chosen in 2003 as one of fifty recordings to be added to the National Recording Registry; and is one of the albums selected by Andrew Gilbert to be included in his book "1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die". Joining Thelonious on the work were an all-star cast including <a href="http://sonnyrollins.com/" target="_blank">Sonny Rollins</a> on tenor saxophone, <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/oscar-pettiford-mn0000896298/biography" target="_blank">Oscar Pettiford</a> and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Chambers" target="_blank">Paul Chambers</a> on bass, <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/max-roach-mn0000396372/biography" target="_blank">Max Roach</a> on drums, <a href="http://clarkterry.com/" target="_blank">Clark Terry</a> on trumpet and Ernie Henry on alto saxophone.</p>\n<p>There can be no hyperbole when talking about this album--that''s how great it is. From the complex title song to the concluding "Beshma Swing", the music is hard bob at its best. How complex was "Brilliant Corners"? Just let me put it this way: during a time where one or two takes were the norm for recording a song, the sidemen tried 25 takes over a four hour period, Ernie Henry nearly suffered a breakdown and Pettiford and Theolonious got into a shouting match. In fact, the legendary producer Orrin Keepnews thought that Pettiford''s microphone was broken at one point only to learn that Oscar was pantomiming playing--talk about passive aggressive! Thankfully, the song finally got pieced together from several takes by Keepnews.</p>\n<p>Here''s Thelonious with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NBzh-8SKB2U" target="_blank">Beshma Swing</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NBzh-8SKB2U" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Thelonious+Monk-courtsey-of-Konkapa-on-Last.fm_.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing (songs by Monk unless noted):</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Brilliant Corners" </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">7:42</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Ba-Lue Bolivar Ba-Lues-Are" </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">13:24</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Pannonica" </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">8:50</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I Surrender, Dear" (Barry Harris)</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">5:25</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Bemsha Swing" (Thelonious Monk, Denzil Best)</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">7:42</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 58, '2014-11-23 18:03:03', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:15:49', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-12-07 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 25, 'jazz, Thelonious Monk', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2125, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(253, 'On this day in jazz (December 08)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-december-08', '', '<p>In this day in 1970,   trumpeter <a href="http://www.woodyshaw.com/" target="_blank">Woody Shaw</a> began recording his landmark debut studio album "Blackstone Legacy". The album is quite a long one, clocking in at over 78 minutes. It was given a five star rating by allmusic.com which call it Woody''s answer to Miles Davis'' Bitches Brew.NPR has called Woody "the last great trumpet innovator". It is said that he had both a photographic memory and the gift of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Absolute_pitch" target="_blank">perfect pitch</a>.</p>\n<p>Here''s the liner notes which are very much (unfortunately) still true today:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">This album is dedicated to the youth who will benefit mankind. To the youth who are constantly aware of the turmoil in which the world is and who are trying to right all these wrongs  whether in music or in speech or in any other way of positive work.</span></p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">This album is dedicated to the freedom of Black people all over the world. And its dedicated to the people in the ghettos here. The stone in the title is the image of strength. I grew up in a ghetto  funky houses, rats and roaches, stinking hallways. Ive seen all of that, and Ive seen people overcome all of that. This music is meant to be a light of hope, a sound of strength and of coming through. Its one for the ghetto.</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">Were trying to express whats happening in the world today as we  a new breed of young musicians  feel it. I mean the different tensions in the world, the ridiculous war in Vietnam, the oppression of poor people in this, a country of such wealth. The cats on this date usually discuss these things, but were all also trying to reach a state of spiritual enlightenment in which were continually aware of whats happening but react in a positive way. The music in this album, you see, expresses strength  confidence that well overcome these things.</p>\n<p>Here''s Woody with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Wa_xpNs6djE" target="_blank">Think On Me</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Wa_xpNs6djE"><img src="images/tdij/woody-shaw-121208.png" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Blackstone Legacy" - 16:08</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Think On Me" (George Cables) - 10:45</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Lost and Found" - 11:57</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"New World" (Cables) - 18:30</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Boo-Ann''s Grand" - 14:25</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"A Deed for Dolphy" - 8:56</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 58, '2014-11-27 15:28:11', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:16:14', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-12-08 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 24, 'jazz, Woody Shaw', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1966, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(254, 'On this day in jazz (December 09)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-december-09', '', '<p>On this day in 1964,   saxophonist <a href="http://www.johncoltrane.com/" target="_blank">John Coltrane</a> recorded the groundbreaking album "A Love Supreme"--so...happy golden anniversary to this work! The importance of this work is that it creates a bridge between the modal/hard bop that was the rage of the late fifties and early sixties and the free jazz style which he was moving into for the rest of his life. If you love modal/bop styles but have a hard time accepting free/avant-garde jazz,   this is the perfect album for you to test the waters.</p>\n<p>This great album,   which is definitely one of the most important jazz albums ever recorded, was recorded in one session by John on soprano and tenor saxophones, <a href="http://mccoytyner.com/" target="_blank">McCoy Tyner</a> on piano, Jimmy Garrison on bass and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elvin_Jones" target="_blank">Elvin Jones</a> on drums--what a lineup. All music sites that provide 1 through 5 star ratings give this one a consensus five-star rating. If you are unfamiliar with jazz, but a fan of rock, you''ve probably heard a shout out to it (as well as <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a> and <a href="http://www.billieholiday.com/" target="_blank">Billy Holiday</a> in U2''s "Angel of Harlem":</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">Birdland on Fifty-Three<br /> The street sounds like a symphony<br /> We got John Coltrane and a love supreme<br /> Miles and she''s got to be an angel.<br /> Lady Day got diamond eyes<br /> She sees the truth behind the lies<br /> (Angel).</p>\n<p>Here''s John with part 1, "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5Pi5ZJZ07ME" target="_blank">Acknowledgement</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5Pi5ZJZ07ME" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/IMG_02412.jpg" border="0" height="250" /><img src="images/tdij/als-jc-rear.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Part 1: "Acknowledgement" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">7:47</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Part 2: "Resolution"</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">7:22</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Part 3: "Pursuance" 10:42</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Part 4: "Psalm" 7:05</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 58, '2014-11-27 15:46:03', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:18:13', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-12-09 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 8, 0, 23, 'jazz, John Coltrane', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1925, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(255, 'On this day in jazz (December 10)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-december-10', '', '<p>On this day in 1930,   <a href="http://www.dukeellington.com/" target="_blank">Duke Ellington</a> and his Cotton Club Orchestra recorded "Mood Indigo". Duke wrote the music for the song with Barney Bigard and Irving Mills provided the vocals. Originally,   the title of the song was an instrumental called "Dreamy Blues" and was the first song that Duke wrote especially for a live radio broadcast. After the live performance in October, tons of mail flowed in praising the song and Irving Mills penned lyrics to go with it. Once the lyrics were added, the title changed to "Mood Indigo".</p>\n<p>Take a listen to the song and see how Ellington gets Joe Nanton to play his trombone at the top of its register while having Barney play his clarinet at the lowest end of its register. This was the first time anyone had recorded in such a way (it was given the name "mike-tone") which essentially gives an illusion of a third instrument being played.</p>\n<p>Here''s Duke with "<a href="http://youtu.be/ojamSYmjEs0" target="_blank">Mood Indigo</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="http://youtu.be/ojamSYmjEs0" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/ellington.JPG" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 58, '2014-12-02 22:09:45', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:18:29', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-12-10 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 22, 'jazz, Duke Ellington', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1592, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(256, 'On this day in jazz (December 12)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-december-12', '', '<p>On this day in 1956,   drummer <a href="http://www.artblakey.com/">Art Blakey</a> recorded "Hard Bop" with his band,   The Jazz Messengers. At this time the Messengers consisted of Bill Hardman on trumpet,   the great <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jackie_McLean" target="_blank">Jackie McLean</a> on alto saxophone, Sam Dockery on piano and Spanky DeBrest on bass. Three of the five tracks were written by either Bill, Jackie or a collaboration thereof. Throw in the the standard "Stella by Starlight" and Richard Rogers'' "My Heart Stood Still" and you''ve got an excellent hard bop set.</p>\n<p>Although this version of the Jazz Messengers is not quite as strong as the original version which featured <a href="http://www.horacesilver.com/" target="_blank">Horace Silver</a> on piano, or the subsequent incarnation which included <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lee_Morgan" target="_blank">Lee Morgan</a>, <a href="http://www.bennygolson.com/" target="_blank">Benny Golson</a> and <a href="http://bobbytimmons.jazzgiants.net/" target="_blank">Bobby Timmons</a>, the music is still quite pleasing. As expected, Art, Jackie and Bill provide the strongest reason to listen to the music, but Sam and Spanky do a great job at rounding out the rhythm section.</p>\n<p>Speaking of Spanky, here''s Art and the Messengers with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=X2Thl9vIq10" target="_blank">Cranky Spanky</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=X2Thl9vIq10" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/7cda558f9d604506b33beecdbea9f.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Cranky Spanky" (Bill Hardman) - 4:45</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Stella by Starlight" (Ned Washington, Victor Young) - 8:50</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"My Heart Stood Still" (Lorenz Hart, Richard Rodgers) - 5:33</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Little Melonae" (Jackie McLean) - 8:20</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Stanley''s Stiff Chicken" (Hardman, McLean) - 9:25</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 58, '2014-12-02 22:16:21', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:18:42', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-12-12 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 20, 'jazz, Art Blakey', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1784, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(257, 'On this day in jazz (December 13)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-december-13', '', '<p>On this day in 1954,   pianist <a href="http://www.horacesilver.com/" target="_blank">Horace Silver</a> recorded half of the tunes that would be released on "Horace Silver and the Jazz Messengers". If you''ve been following my blog,   you''ll note that yesterday I featured <a href="http://www.artblakey.com/" target="_blank">Art Blakey</a> with the second incarnation of the Jazz Messengers. On this album you get the first incarntation: <a href="http://www.kennydorham.net/biography/" target="_blank">Kenny Dorham</a> on the trumpet, the great <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hank_Mobley" target="_blank">Hank Mobley</a> on tenor saxophone, Doug Watkins on the bass and, of course, the legendary Art Blakey at the drums. All of the songs were written by Horace except for one, "Hankerin''" which was written by Mobley.</p>\n<p>This album played an important role in setting the tone for the hard bop style that would flourish over the next decade. What is hard bop? The easiest way to explain it is that you start with bebop and infuse it with the blues and gospel to get to hard bop. Also, it was the first "Jazz Messengers" album, and Art Blakey would use this name for the name of his band for the rest of his career. allmusic.com gives it its highest five star rating.</p>\n<p>Here''s Horace and the Jazz Messengers with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tu4o65SwUIw" target="_blank">Doodlin</a>''":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tu4o65SwUIw" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/6c1985cd3f9bb62c514601e3b269e.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Room 608"  5:22</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Creepin'' In"  7:26</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Stop Time"  4:07</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"To Whom It May Concern"  5:11</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Hippy"  5:23</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Preacher"  4:18</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Hankerin''" (Mobley)  5:18</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Doodlin''"  6:45</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 58, '2014-12-02 22:22:03', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:18:54', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-12-13 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 5, 0, 19, 'jazz, Horace Silver', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1756, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(258, 'On this day in jazz (December 14)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-december-14', '', '<p>On this day in 1956,   piano legend <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Red_Garland" target="_blank">Red Garland</a> recorded two songs ("If I Were A Bell" and "I Know Why (And So Do You)") which would appear on the studio album "Red Garland''s Piano". The rest of the rhythm section joining Red were <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Chambers" target="_blank">Paul Chambers</a> on bass and <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/art-taylor-mn0000505154/biography" target="_blank">Art Taylor</a> on the drums.</p>\n<p>Red was born in Dallas, TX, in 1923 to a mother that played several instruments herself. Although he started with the clarinet and saxophone, he later decided to play the piano (in 1940). He actually considered a career in boxing, but a bout with Sugar Ray Robinson may have had a little bit of an impact on him deciding to make a career in music instead. Red was also part of the <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a> Quintet of 1955 which featured a young <a href="http://www.johncoltrane.com/" target="_blank">John Coltrane</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philly_Joe_Jones" target="_blank">Philly Joe Jones</a> and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philly_Joe_Jones" target="_blank">Paul Chambers</a>. Unfortunately, Miles and Red did not see eye to eye and by 1958 he was on his way out while <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/wynton-kelly-mn0000684253/biography" target="_blank">Wynton Kelly</a> and <a href="http://www.billevanswebpages.com/" target="_blank">Bill Evans</a> were on their way in to join up with Miles.</p>\n<p>Here''s Red with George and Ira Gershwin''s: "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AL3kbBw4dKM&list=PL70AD76A808813703&index=1" target="_blank">But Not For Me</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AL3kbBw4dKM&list=PL70AD76A808813703&index=1" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/redg.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Please Send Me Someone to Love" (Percy Mayfield) - 9:51</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Stompin'' at the Savoy" (Benny Goodman, Andy Razaf, Edgar Sampson, Chick Webb) - 3:12</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Very Thought of You" (Ray Noble) - 4:12</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Almost Like Being in Love" (Alan Jay Lerner, Frederick Loewe) - 4:52</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"If I Were a Bell" (Frank Loesser) - 6:41</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I Know Why (And So Do You)" (Harry Warren, Mack Gordon) - 4:50</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I Can''t Give You Anything but Love" (Dorothy Fields, Jimmy McHugh) - 5:05</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"But Not For Me" (George Gershwin, Ira Gershwin) - 5:52</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 58, '2014-12-02 22:29:43', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:19:11', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-12-14 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 18, 'jazz, Red Garland', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1828, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(259, 'On this day in jazz (December 15)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-december-15', '', '<p>On this day in 1958,   <a href="http://www.billevanswebpages.com/" target="_blank">Bill Evans</a> recorded his second album as a leader,   "Everybody Digs Bill Evans". It would feature his song "Peace Piece" along with several jazz standards such as "Minority",   "Night and Day" and "Oleo". Joining Bill on the album were bassist Sam Jones and drummer <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philly_Joe_Jones" target="_blank">Philly Joe Jones</a>. The interesting tie to yesterday''s artist, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Red_Garland" target="_blank">Red Garland</a>, is Bill''s use of block chords that Red had made famous in his recordings.</p>\n<p>The song highlighted below is "Peace Piece". It is one of my wife''s as well as one of my favorite songs. The same chords used for this song were also used as the basis for the song "Flamenco Sketches" which appeared the following year on <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a>'' "Kind of Blue". Although Evans had constant requests to play the piece live in his last years, he refused, believing that it would cause the song to lose its value.</p>\n<p>Here''s Bill with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=afwp5KR3r74">Peace Piece</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=afwp5KR3r74" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/evans-bill-4f8f713c2be56.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Minority" (Gryce)  5:23</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Young and Foolish" (Hague, Arnold B. Horwitt)  5:54</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Lucky to Be Me" (Bernstein, Comden, Green)  3:41</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Night and Day" (Porter)  7:35</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Tenderly" (Gross)  3:34</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Peace Piece" (Evans)  6:44</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"What Is There to Say?" (Duke, Harburg)  4:55</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Oleo" (Rollins)  4:09</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Epilogue" (Evans)  0:41</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 58, '2014-12-02 22:35:04', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:19:27', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-12-15 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 17, 'jazz, Bill Evans', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1763, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(260, 'On this day in jazz (December 16)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-december-16', '', '<p>On this day in 1955,   <a href="http://www.stangetz.net/" target="_blank">Stan Getz</a> recorded the music for the album "Stan Getz in Stockholm". The album was the first album recorded by Stan after a convalescence in North Africa due to cases of pleurisy and pneumonia. Luckily for us,  and for Stan, he made a full recovery as is proved here. On the album, Stan is joined by three Swedes: pianist Bengt Hallberg, bassist Gunnar Johnson, and drummer Anders Burman.</p>\n<p>Like always, Getz provides a rich warm sound as he plows through a series of ballads, standards and even some fast bop. You would never guess that he had only recently recovered from the aforementioned illness and had not recorded in four months. This is truly one of the best Getz albums, so if you''re new to Stan''s music feel free to start here. Be sure to check out <a href="http://www.stangetz.net/" target="_self">his website</a> which is run by his daughter, Beverly.</p>\n<p>Here''s Stan with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zY6lKsacq-A" target="_blank">I Don''t Stand a Ghost of a Chance With You</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zY6lKsacq-A" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/stangetz.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Indiana (Hanley-MacDonald)</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Without a Song (Eliscu-Rose-Youmans)</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">I Don''t Stand a Ghost of a Chance with You (Crosby-Washington-Young)</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">I Can''t Believe That You''re in Love with Me (Gaskill-McHugh)</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Everything Happens to Me (Adair-Dennis)</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Over the Rainbow (Arlen-Harburg)</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Get Happy (Arlen-Koehler)</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Jeepers Creepers (Mercer-Warren)</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 58, '2014-12-02 22:39:40', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:17:09', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-12-15 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 16, 'jazz, Stan Getz', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1684, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(261, 'On this day in jazz (December 17)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-december-19', '', '<p>On this day in 1958,   drummer <a href="http://www.artblakey.com/" target="_blank">Art Blakey</a> and his Jazz Messengers completed recording the songs that would be issued on the album: "1958-Paris Olympia". If you''re following my blog,   you''ll recall that on December 12th we looked at the second incarnation of the Jazz Messengers. Today, we''re looking at the third, and perhaps, most famous / talented of all of the versions of the Jazz Messengers as it included <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lee_Morgan" target="_blank">Lee Morgan</a> on trumpet, <a href="http://www.bennygolson.com/" target="_blank">Benny Golson</a> on tenor sax, <a href="http://bobbytimmons.jazzgiants.net/" target="_blank">Bobby Timmons</a> on piano and Jymie Merritt on bass.</p>\n<p>Not only was this a stellar lineup personnel-wise, it also features a great set of songs including "I Remember Clifford", "Moanin''" and "Blues March". Below is the song, "I Remember Clifford" which was written by Benny Golson for <a href="http://cliffordbrown.net/" target="_blank">Clifford Brown</a> who had died in 1956 in an auto wreck. Golson said that it took him several weeks to write the song and that he had written anything like it before, wanting to create a melody that was both memorable and true to Clifford''s memory. See my <a href="index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=120:on-this-day-in-jazz-august-02&catid=54:august&Itemid=41" target="_self">August 2nd post</a> for more on Clifford.</p>\n<p>Here''s Art and the Jazz Messengers with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=S9QMnLVSStY" target="_blank">I Remember Clifford</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=S9QMnLVSStY" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/522.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing (all by Benny Golson unless noted):</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Just by Myself" - 4:35</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I Remember Clifford" - 5:36</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Are You Real" - 10:17</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Moanin''" (Bobby Timmons) - 13:38</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Justice" (Thelonious Monk) - 9:17</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Blues March" - 5:46</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Whisper Not" - 7:11</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 58, '2014-12-02 22:47:12', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:19:42', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-12-17 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 6, 0, 15, 'jazz, Art Blakey', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1659, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(278, 'On this day in jazz (January 03)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-january-03', '', '<p>On this day in 1955,   <a href="http://clarkterry.com/" target="_blank">Clark Terry</a> began recording his debut album as a leader which would be later released as <em>Clark Terry</em>,  <em>Introducing Clark Terry</em> and even <em>Swahili</em>. The arrangements were provided by the great Quincy Jones, Jimmy Cleveland played trombone, Cecil Payne played the baritone saxophone, and the rhythm section consisted of an all-star cast: <a href="http://www.horacesilver.com/" target="_blank">Horace Silver</a> on piano, Wendell Marshall and <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/oscar-pettiford-mn0000896298/biography" target="_blank">Oscar Pettiford</a> on basses and cello, and <a href="http://www.artblakey.com/" target="_blank">Art Blakey</a> on the drums.</p>\n<p>The album consists of five songs by Clark and three by Quincy and was rated four stars (out of five) by allmusic.com. Clark, whom I have profiled before, was still playing in <a href="http://www.dukeellington.com/" target="_blank">Duke Ellington</a>''s orchestra at the time, but shows here that he was ready to lead. Although he only plays trumpet on this album, he was noted as the man who introduced the flugelhorn as a major instrument for jazz recordings. With a career that spans over 70 years, he has a huge catalog and has won more awards than can be mentioned in a short blog post. Check him out if you are unfamiliar with him. Also, search my site for more details.</p>\n<p>Here''s Clark with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kQiBsf2KO3c" target="_blank">Swahili</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kQiBsf2KO3c" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/2014-10-20-4E65E255EB4D46F189D1F9CFE3BE3487.JPG" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Swahili" (Quincy Jones) - 6:07</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Double Play" (Jones) - 3:33</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Slow Boat" - 4:28</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Co-Op" (Terry, Rick Henderson) - 3:45</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Kitten" - 5:35</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Countless" (Freddie Green, Terry) - 6:42</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Tuma" (Jones) - 3:06</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Chuckles" - 4:19</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 59, '2014-12-25 16:00:39', 62, '', '2016-08-16 21:51:40', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-01-03 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 29, 'jazz, Clark Terry', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1799, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(262, 'On this day in jazz (December 18)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-december-18', '', '<p>On this day in 1956,   <a href="http://www.zootsims.org/" target="_blank">Zoot Sims</a> completed recording the album "Zoot!". Nick Travis provides additional wind on trumpet and the rhythm section was comprised of George Handy on piano, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wilbur_Ware" target="_blank">Wilbur Ware</a> on bass and Osie Johnson on drums. There are several songs that are quite good on the album including Handy''s "Why Cry", Osie''s "Osmosis" and Johnny Mercer''s "Fools Rush In". Although Zoot is known for his virtuoso playing of the tenor saxophone, he is heard here playing the alto instead.</p>\n<p>Here''s Zoot with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0M8Vv6o-9po" target="_blank">Why Cry?</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0M8Vv6o-9po" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Lee-Tanner-Zoot-Sims.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing (songs by Handy unless noted):</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Why Cry?" - 5:54</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Echoes of You" - 7:12</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Swim, Jim" - 7:07</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Here and Now" - 4:55</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Fools Rush In (Where Angels Fear to Tread)" (Rube Bloom, Johnny Mercer) - 4:30</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Osmosis" (Osie Johnson) - 4:44</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Taking a Chance on Love" (Vernon Duke, Ted Fetter, John La Touche) - 6:01</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 58, '2014-12-03 16:54:36', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:19:59', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-12-18 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 14, 'jazz, Zoot Sims', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1719, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(263, 'On this day in jazz (December 19)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-december-19', '', '<p>On this day in 1957,   tenor saxophonists <a href="http://sonnyrollins.com/" target="_blank">Sonny Rollins</a> and <a href="http://www.sonnystitt.com/" target="_blank">Sonny Stitt</a> joined trumpeter <a href="http://www.dizzygillespie.com/" target="_blank">Dizzy Gillespie</a> to record "Sonny Side Up". There are four songs on the album including one original by Stitt ("The Eternal Triangle"). In addition to the leaders,   the rhythm section is provided by Ray Bryant on piano, Tommy Bryant on bass and Charlie Persip on drums.</p>\n<p>The mood of the album is quite upbeat and you could categorize this as either bebop or hard bop. allmusic.com calls the recording: "one of the most exciting "jam session" records in the jazz catalog" and a "highly enjoyable jazz set and something of an approximation of the music''s once-revered live cutting session." I agree. It is said that Dizzy actually stoked the fire with phone calls and gossip before the session to get Sonny & Sonny fired up for the recording. It really appears to work as the two seem to battle each other as they trade solos. Oh, by the way, Dizzy isn''t too bad either.</p>\n<p>Here''s Sonnys and Dizzy with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G4H9k-d9fBk" target="_blank">On the Sunny Side of the Street</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G4H9k-d9fBk" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/sonnysideup-cover-1600.jpg" border="0" height="250" /><img src="images/tdij/sonnysideup-rearcocver-1600.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"On the Sunny Side of the Street" (Jimmy McHugh, Dorothy Fields) - 5:43</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Eternal Triangle" (Stitt) - 14:10</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"After Hours" (Avery Parrish) - 12:21</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I Know That You Know" (Vincent Youmans) - 5:28</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 58, '2014-12-03 16:59:11', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:20:15', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-12-19 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 13, 'jazz, Sonny Rollins, Sonny Stitt, Dizzy Gillespie', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1859, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(264, 'On this day in jazz (December 20)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-december-20', '', '<p>On this day in 1960,   tenor saxophonist <a href="http://paulgonsalves.org/" target="_blank">Paul Gonsalves</a> recorded the studio album "Gettin'' Together". Joining Paul on the album were Cannonball Adderley''s brother,   Nat,   on the cornet and a rhythm section of <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/wynton-kelly-mn0000684253/biography" target="_blank">Wynton Kelly</a> at the piano, Sam Jones on bass and <a href="http://www.jimmycobb.net/" target="_blank">Jimmy Cobb</a> on drums. You might remember that Wynton and Jimmy were also part of the rhythm section on <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a>'' "Kind of Blue" which was recorded a couple of years earlier (along with <a href="http://www.cannonball-adderley.com/" target="_blank">Cannonball</a> on alto sax and <a href="http://www.johncoltrane.com/" target="_blank">John Coltrane</a> on tenor). There are two songs definitely worth listening to on this one: the first track "Yesterdays" and "I Cover the Waterfront".</p>\n<p>Paul is famously known for his association with <a href="http://www.dukeellington.com/" target="_blank">Duke Ellington</a> and especially for his performance at the 1956 Newport Jazz Festival where he played a 27-chorus solo during Ellington''s "Diminuendo and Crescendo in Blue". The performance can be found on youtube and also in Ken Burns'' jazz documentary--look it up, it''s quite incredible. Basically, everyone was starting to leave the festival for the day, but when Paul started playing his solo people started dancing in the aisles and people who had left started running back to hear him play. By the way, Duke''s 1966 album "Far East Suite" which also includes Paul was also recorded on this day and is well worth a listen.</p>\n<p>Here''s Paul with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gaL2Vuh_nlU" target="_blank">Yesterdays</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gaL2Vuh_nlU" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Paul_Gonsalves.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Yesterdays" (Otto Harbach/Jerome Kern)</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"J. And B. Blues"</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I Surrender, Dear"</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Hard Groove"</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Low Gravy"</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I Cover the Waterfront"</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Gettin'' Together"</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Walkin"''</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 58, '2014-12-03 17:04:37', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:20:30', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-12-20 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 12, 'jazz, Paul Gonsalves', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1723, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(265, 'On this day in jazz (December 21)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-december-21', '', '<p>On this day in 1963,   the great <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lee_Morgan" target="_blank">Lee Morgan</a> recorded his most popular album as a leader,   "The Sidewinder". The title track is one of the most famous soul jazz recordings to this date and was quite a hit when released. Although you might think of a snake when hearing the title, it was actually meant to refer to a bad guy on television according to Lee. The song was so popular that Chrysler used it in an unauthorized TV Commercial during the 1965 World Series. After Lee threatened to sue, the ad was pulled and not played again. Joining Lee''s trumpet on the album were the tenor saxophone of <a href="http://www.joehendersonsax.com/" target="_blank">Joe Henderson</a> and a rhythm section of Barry Harris on piano, Bob Cranshaw on bass and Billy Higgins on the drums.</p>\n<p>The album features five songs all written by Lee and is part of the Penguin Guide To Jazz''s Core Collection, recipient of a five-star rating at allmusic.com and one of the 17 recordings noted jazz reviewer Scott Yanow includes in his essay "Hard Bop" as Essential Hard Bop Recordings. Take a listen to it.</p>\n<p>Here''s Lee with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qJi03NqXfk8" target="_blank">The Sidewinder</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qJi03NqXfk8" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Lee_Morgan.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Sidewinder"  10:25</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Totem Pole"  10:11</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Gary''s Notebook"  6:03</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Boy, What a Night"  7:30</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Hocus Pocus"  6:21</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 58, '2014-12-03 17:08:03', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:20:43', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-12-21 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 11, 'jazz, Lee Morgan', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1740, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(266, 'On this day in jazz (December 22)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-december-22', '', '<p>On this day in 1965,   <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a> was recorded live at the Plugged Nickel in Chicago,   IL. The entire seven sets over the two nights of December 22 and 23rd were released as a box set "The Complete Live at the Plugged Nickel 1965". Unfortunately,   while the music survives, the venue does not. There is, however, a blog page dedicated to the Nickel <a href="http://plugged-nickel.blogspot.com/" target="_blank">here</a>.</p>\n<p>The music for the sets is mostly comprised of standards and Miles'' most important compositions. However, don''t expect straight ahead interpretations here. During the trip to Chicago, drummer<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tony_Williams_(drummer)" target="_blank">Tony Williams</a> challenged the band to play "anti-jazz", or "playing whatever one wished rather than the standard versions". The band followed suit and what you get here are the anti-standard Plugged Nickel performances. In addition to Miles and Tony, <a href="http://www.wayneshorter.com/" target="_blank">Wayne Shorter</a> joined in on tenor saxophone, the great <a href="http://www.herbiehancock.com/home.php" target="_blank">Herbie Hancock</a> was at the piano and <a href="http://roncarter.net/JazzMaster/" target="_blank">Ron Carter</a> played bass. Quite a stellar lineup!</p>\n<p>Here''s Miles with a <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nyAO3twW_Mk" target="_blank">sample</a> from the first disk:</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nyAO3twW_Mk"><img src="images/tdij/512BN9ACGSL.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 58, '2014-12-03 17:11:58', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:21:03', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-12-22 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 10, 'jazz, Miles Davis', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1713, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(267, 'On this day in jazz (December 23)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-december-23', '', '<p>On this day in 1954,   The Modern Jazz Quartet recorded their second session for the studio album "Django". The first session is actually from June 25th, 1953 and the last session was held January 9, 1955. The album has had a somewhat complicated lineage due to the fact that Prestige Records had yet to move into the LP era at the time of its original release. If you are looking for the work, I would suggest getting Rudy Van Gelder''s remastered version on CD which was reissued in 2006.</p>\n<p>As you might expect, the title of the album is in honor of gypsy jazz guitarist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Django_Reinhardt" target="_blank">Django Reinhardt</a>. The title song was written by <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Lewis_(pianist)" target="_blank">John Lewis</a> (pianist and music director of the band) and has since become a standard in the jazz repertoire. In fact, most of the songs on the album were written by Lewis with the exceptions being <a href="http://www.dizzygillespie.com/" target="_blank">Dizzy Gillespie</a>''s "One Bass Hit", George and Ira Gershwin''s "But Not for Me" and Vernon Duke''s "Autumn In New York". In fact, the longest song on the album, "La Ronde Suite", is actually a version of the jazz standard "Two Bass Hit" which Lewis wrote for Gillespie.</p>\n<p>Hopefully, you''re familiar with MJQ, but if not remember this:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;"><a href="http://www.pas.org/experience/halloffame/JacksonMilt.aspx" target="_blank">Milt Jackson</a> (aka "Bags") played the vibraphone, John, as mentioned, played piano, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Percy_Heath" target="_blank">Percy Heath</a> played bass and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kenny_Clarke" target="_blank">Kenny Clarke</a> played the drums </span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">they formed MJQ after being part of Dizzy Gillespie''s big band</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p>On a few occasions the band invited other artists to come in and add an additional instrument (e.g., guitarist <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jimmy_Giuffre" target="_blank">Jimmy Guiffre</a> or saxophonist <a href="http://sonnyrollins.com/" target="_blank">Sonny Rollins</a> on their "At Music Inn" albums), but most of the time you won''t hear wind breaking out from their songs.</p>\n<p>Here''s MJQ with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1z88Vc1oyvU" target="_blank">Django</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1z88Vc1oyvU" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/6a00d8341c85cd53ef016768bc4473970b-800wi.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Django" (John Lewis)  7:03</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"One Bass Hit" (Dizzy Gillespie)  2:59</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"La Ronde Suite" (Lewis)  9:38</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Queen''s Fancy" (Lewis)  3:12</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Delauney''s Dilemma" (Lewis)  4:01</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Autumn In New York" (Vernon Duke)  3:40</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"But Not for Me" (George Gershwin, Ira Gershwin)  3:44</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Milano" (Lewis)  4:23</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 58, '2014-12-03 17:22:46', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:21:19', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-12-23 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 9, 'jazz, Modern Jazz Quartet', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1775, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(268, 'On this day in jazz (December 24)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-december-24', '', '<p>On this day in 1954,   <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a> completed recording of the studio album,   Bags'' Groove at Rudy Van Gelder''s studio in Hackensack,   NJ. Bags, of course, refers to <a href="http://www.pas.org/experience/halloffame/JacksonMilt.aspx" target="_blank">Milt Jackson</a> who was probably the greatest vibraphone players in history. Joining Miles and Milt on the work were a group of men who would become legendary themselves: <a href="http://sonnyrollins.com/" target="_blank">Sonny Rollins</a> on tenor sax, <a href="http://www.horacesilver.com/" target="_blank">Horace Silver</a> on piano, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Percy_Heath" target="_blank">Percy Heath</a> on bass and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kenny_Clarke" target="_blank">Kenny Clarke</a> on drums.</p>\n<p>The title track is indeed one of the best songs on the work and was written by the vibraphonist. "Airegin", "Oleo" and "Doxy" were written by the 24 year-old Sonny Rollins and all four songs are now consensus-ly considered jazz standards. If you are wondering about the names of the songs, "Bags" was Milt''s Nickname; "Oleo" is a bread spread (margarine--of course), "Doxy" was a European bread spread that Sonny had tasted at a hotel in Europe (and would later become the name of Rollins'' own record label)...he seemed to have a thing for edible oils; and "Airegin" is simply Nigeria spelled backwards. One other notable thing about the album--Miles Davis used the Harmon mute on his trumpet for the first time on "Oleo". If you''ve ever seen Miles from 1954 onward, it''s likely you saw his trumpet with a mute on it.</p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Here''s Miles and Milt with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=I0d5LU6SCz8" target="_blank">Bag''s Groove</a>" (fyi, Bud Powell is also shown in the photo below):</span></p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=I0d5LU6SCz8" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/milt_miles_bud.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Bags'' Groove" (Milt Jackson) [Take 1]  11:16</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Bags'' Groove" (Milt Jackson) [Take 2]  9:24</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Airegin" (Sonny Rollins)  5:01</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Oleo" (Sonny Rollins)  5:14</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"But Not for Me" (George Gershwin, Ira Gershwin) [Take 2]  5:45</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Doxy" (Sonny Rollins)  4:55</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"But Not for Me" (George Gershwin, Ira Gershwin) [Take 1]  4:36</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 58, '2014-12-16 19:02:52', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:21:32', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-12-24 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 8, 'jazz, Miles Davis, Milt Jackson, Sonny Rollins', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1736, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(269, 'On this day in jazz (December 25)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-december-25', '', '<p>On this day in 1971,   the Modern Jazz Quartet recorded "Paul Desmond & Modern Jazz Quartet" with, who else, <a href="http://www.puredesmond.ca/" target="_blank">Paul Desmond</a>. It wasn''t uncommon for the MJQ to perform a Christmas performance, and this one occurred at the New York City Town Hall. After the first intermission, Paul Desmond (who very rarely played with any other groups) joined in--and this recording is that session.</p>\n<p>allmusic.com calls it "a fusion of cool classical modernists (MJQ) and a dry-martini altoist that works". One of the reasons Paul played with them was because bassist<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Percy_Heath" target="_blank">Percy Heath</a> and drummer <a href="http://www.drummerworld.com/drummers/Connie_Kay.html" target="_blank">Connie Kay</a> had supported him on previous albums. In fact, this was the only time the MJQ and Desmond ever performed in public.</p>\n<p>On this work you''ll find the traditional songs, "Greensleeves" and "La Paloma Azul" alongside Rice & Webber''s "Jesus Christ Superstar" and <a href="http://www.pas.org/experience/halloffame/JacksonMilt.aspx" target="_blank">Milt Jackson</a>''s (see yesterday''s post) "Bag''s New Groove".</p>\n<p>Here''s MJQ and Paul with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-brmiryqxxY" target="_blank">Greensleeves</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-brmiryqxxY" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Paul-Desmond-The-Only-Recorded-471485.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="245" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Greensleeves - Traditional - 3:10</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">You Go to My Head - J. Fred Coots / Haven Gillespie - 7:56</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Blue Dove (La Paloma Azul) - Traditional - 4:55</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Jesus Christ Superstar - Tim Rice / Andrew Lloyd Webber - 4:54</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Here''s That Rainy Day - Johnny Burke / James Van Heusen - 4:50</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">East of the Sun (And West of the Moon) - Brooks Bowman - 8:25</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Bags'' New Groove - Milt Jackson - 5:10</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 58, '2014-12-16 19:33:54', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:21:53', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-12-25 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 7, 'jazz, MJQ, Paul Desmond', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1840, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(270, 'On this day in jazz (December 26)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-december-26', '', '<p>On this day in 1992,   pianist and NEA Jazz Master <a href="http://arts.gov/honors/jazz/cedar-walton" target="_blank">Cedar Walton</a> recorded the studio album <em>Manhattan Afternoon</em> in New York City with Billy Higgins and David Williams (aka "The Cedar Walton Trio"). Cedar is one of my favorite later day hard bop jazz pianists. I take that back. He''s one of my favorite jazz pianists,   period.</p>\n<p>This album features a couple of originals by Cedar along with several jazz standards written by the likes of <a href="http://sonnyrollins.com/" target="_blank">Sonny Rollins</a> ("St. Thomas"), Johnny Mercer ("Skylark"), <a href="http://www.monkzone.com/" target="_blank">Thelonious Monk</a> ("I Mean You"), <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Lewis_(pianist)" target="_blank">John Lewis</a> ("Afternoon In Paris") and <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a> ("The Theme").</p>\n<p>Here''s Cedar with one of my favorite songs, "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MNnNMn_uXH4" target="_blank">St. Thomas</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MNnNMn_uXH4" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/52178173833dd.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">There Is No Greater Love (Jones / Symes)</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">St. Thomas (Sonny Rollins)</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Skylark (Johnny Mercer / Hoagy Carmichael)</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">The Newest Blues (Cedar Walton)</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">When Love Is New (Cedar Walton)</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">I Mean You (Thelonious Monk)</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Afternoon In Paris (John Lewis)</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">The Theme (Miles Davis)</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 58, '2014-12-16 19:52:23', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:22:09', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-12-26 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 6, 'jazz, Cedar Walton', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1804, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(271, 'On this day in jazz (December 27)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-december-27', '', '<p>On this day in 1960,   pianist Ray Charles completed recording the soul jazz album <em>Genius + Soul = Jazz</em>. Ray was accompanied by a foison of musicians including <a href="http://clarkterry.com/" target="_blank">Clark Terry</a>, Phillip Guilbeau, Jimmy Nottingham, Joe Wilder, John Frosk, Jimmy Cleveland, Urbie Green, Keg Johnson, George Matthews, George Dorsey, Earl Warren, Budd Johnson, Seldon Powell, Haywood Henry, Sam Herman, Joe Benjamin and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roy_Haynes" target="_blank">Roy Haynes</a>. You may notice some of the names as part of the crew hailed from Count Basie''s band (the rest were NYC session musicians). Quincy Jones and Ralph Burns provided the arrangements for the songs. Ray of course plays the Hammond B-3 on this one and sings vocals.</p>\n<p>The album which includes original songs by Ray also includes some Jazz standards such as Bobby Timmons'' "Moanin''", George and Ira Gershwin''s "Strike Up the Band" and Ray Henderson''s "Birth of the Blues". The album was inducted into the Grammy Hall of Fame in 2011.</p>\n<p>Here''s Ray with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jIQu1Zowe6M" target="_blank">Birth of the Blues</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jIQu1Zowe6M" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/ray-charles.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"From the Heart" (Ray Charles) arr. Quincy Jones  3:30</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I''ve Got News for You" (Ray Alfred) arr. Ralph Burns  4:28</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Moanin''" (Bobby Timmons) arr. Quincy Jones  3:14</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Let''s Go" (Charles) arr. Ralph Burns  2:39</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"One Mint Julep" (Rudy Toombs) arr. Quincy Jones  3:02</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I''m Gonna Move to the Outskirts of Town" (Andy Razaf, Casey Bill Weldon) arr. Quincy Jones  3:38</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Stompin'' Room Only" (Howard Marks) arr. Ralph Burns  3:35</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Mister C" (Charles) arr. Ralph Burns  4:28</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Strike Up the Band" (George Gershwin, Ira Gershwin) arr. Quincy Jones  2:35</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Birth of the Blues" (Ray Henderson, Buddy G. DeSylva, Lew Brown) arr. Ralph Burns  5:05</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 58, '2014-12-16 22:12:45', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:22:38', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-12-27 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 5, 0, 5, 'jazz, Ray Charles', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1713, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(272, 'On this day in jazz (December 28)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-december-28', '', '<p>On this day in 1959,   pianist <a href="http://www.billevanswebpages.com/" target="_blank">Bill Evans</a> recorded the studio album <em>Portrait in Jazz</em>. The album was recorded with just a rhythm section with Scott LaFaro on the bass and Paul Motian on the drums. The album is a very significant one in jazz as it continued the direction that <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a> and Bill started with "Kind of Blue".</p>\n<p>Famed critic Scott Yanow said this of the album: "the influential interpretations were far from routine or predictable at the time. LaFaro and Motian were nearly equal partners with the pianist in the ensembles... A gem.". Whether you are a fan of bop,   modal jazz improvisations, piano jazz, Miles Davis or Bill Evans, take a listen.</p>\n<p>Here''s Bill with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hu8NBvpOwn4" target="_blank">When I Fall In Love</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hu8NBvpOwn4" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/ac9a2aa302a3fdce1dcecabd3afc3.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Come Rain or Come Shine" (Harold Arlen, Johnny Mercer)  3:24</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Autumn Leaves" (Joseph Kosma, Jacques Prvert, Mercer  6:00</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Witchcraft" (Cy Coleman, Carolyn Leigh)  4:37</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"When I Fall in Love" (Victor Young, Edward Heyman)  4:57</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Peri''s Scope" (Bill Evans)  3:15</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"What Is This Thing Called Love?" (Cole Porter)  4:36</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Spring Is Here" (Richard Rodgers, Lorenz Hart)  5:09</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Someday My Prince Will Come" (Frank Churchill, Larry Morey)  4:57</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Blue in Green" (Miles Davis, Evans)  5:25</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 58, '2014-12-24 03:08:12', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:22:46', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-12-28 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 6, 0, 4, 'jazz, Bill Evans', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1740, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(273, 'On this day in jazz (December 29)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-december-29', '', '<p>On this day in 1958,   vibraphonist <a href="http://www.pas.org/experience/halloffame/JacksonMilt.aspx" target="_blank">Milt Jackson</a> completed recording <em>Bags'' Opus</em>. Joining Milt on the album were Art Farmer on trumpet,   <a href="http://www.bennygolson.com/" target="_blank">Benny Golson</a> on tenor sax,   Tommy Flanagan on the piano, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Chambers" target="_blank">Paul Chambers</a> on bass, and <a href="http://www.drummerworld.com/drummers/Connie_Kay.html" target="_blank">Connie Kay</a> on drums--quite an ensemble!</p>\n<p>Besides being joined by MJQ drummer Connie Kay on the performance, Milt also performs a song by MJQ member<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Lewis_(pianist)" target="_blank">John Lewis</a> (pianist and music director): "Afternoon in Paris". The album received 4.5 stars from allmusic.com and is definitely worth a listen.</p>\n<p>Here''s Bags with Benny Golson''s "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HcNqbywLRHw" target="_blank">Whisper Not</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HcNqbywLRHw" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Milt_Jackson_07.jpg" border="0" width="279" height="180" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Ill Wind" (Harold Arlen, Ted Koehler) - 4:28</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Blues for Diahann" - 7:25</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Afternoon in Paris" (John Lewis) - 6:02</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I Remember Clifford" (Benny Golson) - 5:55</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Thinking of You" (Bert Kalmar, Harry Ruby) - 4:23</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Whisper Not" (Golson) - 6:16</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 58, '2014-12-24 03:12:45', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:23:00', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-12-29 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 5, 0, 3, 'jazz, Milt Jackson', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1930, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(274, 'On this day in jazz (December 30)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-december-30', '', '<p>On this day in 1960,   <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coleman_Hawkins" target="_blank">Coleman Hawkins</a> and Eddie "Lockjaw" Davis recorded <em>Night Hawk</em> at Van Gelder Studios in Englewood Cliffs, NJ. Joining the two tenors was a rhythm section consisting of Tommy Flanagan on piano, the great <a href="http://roncarter.net/JazzMaster/" target="_blank">Ron Carter</a> on bass and Gus Johnson on drums.</p>\n<p>Coleman (aka Bean) was Eddie''s elder by 18 years, and Eddie considered Bean to be one of his greatest influences. If I am correct, this was only the second album that they recorded together with one of them as a leader (1959''s "Very Saxy" was the other and comes under Eddie''s name). The album consists of five songs and two are certainly worth giving a listen: the title track (which runs 10:30 long) and "In a Mellow Tone"--a Duke Ellington tune where the two tenors battle it out with Davis playing the higher registers and Bean the lower.</p>\n<p>Here''s Coleman and Eddie with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pKq0BfWcPSI" target="_blank">Night Hawk</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pKq0BfWcPSI" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Night_Hawk_(album).jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Night Hawk" (Coleman Hawkins) - 10:30</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"There Is No Greater Love" (Isham Jones, Marty Symes) - 8:15</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"In a Mellow Tone" (Duke Ellington, Milt Gabler) - 6:45</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Don''t Take Your Love from Me" (Henry Nemo) - 8:35</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Pedalin''" (Ken McIntyre) - 6:35</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 58, '2014-12-24 03:17:05', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:23:18', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-12-30 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 2, 'jazz, Coleman Hawkins', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1593, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(275, 'On this day in jazz (December 31)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-december-31', '', '<p>Happy New Year''s Eve! On this day in 1986,   <a href="http://www.branfordmarsalis.com/" target="_blank">Branford Marsalis</a> began recording his third studio album for Columbia,  entitled <em>Renaissance</em>. The album consists of some great tunes by jazz giants such as Cole Porter,   <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/jj-johnson-mn0000119111/biography" target="_blank">J. J. Johnson</a>, Jimmy Rowles, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tony_Williams_(drummer)" target="_blank">Tony Williams</a>, <a href="http://sonnyrollins.com/" target="_blank">Sonny Rollins</a> ("St. Thomas"!) as well as an original by Branford. Joining Branford''s saxophones was a rhythm section Tony Williams on drums and Bob Hurst on bass. If that''s not enough, add <a href="http://www.herbiehancock.com/home.php" target="_blank">Herbie Hancock</a> and Buster Williams on "The Peacocks" and you''ve got quite an extraordiary album.</p>\n<p>Here''s Branford with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DUD6WTLQ0uQ" target="_blank">The Peacocks</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DUD6WTLQ0uQ" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Tonight%20Show%20Branford%202_13.jpg" border="0" width="170" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Just One Of Those Things - C. Porter</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Lament - J.J. Johnson</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">The Peacocks - J. Rowles</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Love Stone - T. Williams</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Citadel - T. Williams</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">The Wrath (Structured Burnout) - B. Marsalis</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">St. Thomas - S. Rollins</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 58, '2014-12-24 03:22:00', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:17:54', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2014-12-31 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 1, 'jazz, Branford Marsalis', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1611, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(276, 'On this day in jazz (January 01)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-january-01', '', '<p>On this day in 1949,   <a href="http://www.cmgww.com/music/parker/home.html" target="_blank">Charlie Parker</a> was recorded for a WMCA radio broadcast. Charlie, the greatest alto saxophonist who ever lived, was joined by <a href="http://www.kennydorham.net/biography/" target="_blank">Kenny Dorham</a> on trumpet, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Al_Haig" target="_blank">Al Haig</a> on piano, Tommy Potter on bass and Joe Harris on the drums. The songs played ranged from <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lester_Young" target="_blank">Lester Young</a> tunes to <a href="http://www.dizzygillespie.com/" target="_blank">Dizzy Gillespie</a> standards to originals by Parker himself.</p>\n<p>Recorded at Royal Roost, these sessions can be found on the 4 disc <em>Complete Royal Roost Broadcasts</em> and the 4 disc <em>Complete Live Performances on Savoy: Sept. 29, 1947 - Oct. 25, 1950</em>. If you''ve never heard Bird play live, give this one a listen and you''ll get an idea why so many consider him the greatest jazz musician to have ever lived.</p>\n<p>Here''s Bird with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AaTTQZHFGw8" target="_blank">Groovin'' High</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AaTTQZHFGw8" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/charlie-parker-royal-roost-11-december-1948-1-d35.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Jumpin''</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Bebop</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Slow Boat to China</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Ornithology</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Groovin'' High</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">East of the Sun (And West of the Moon)</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Cheryl</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 59, '2014-12-25 03:57:53', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:48:57', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-01-01 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 6, 0, 31, 'jazz, Charlie Parker', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1792, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(279, 'On this day in jazz (January 04)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-january-04', '', '<p>On this day in 1965,   drummer <a href="http://www.joyousshout.com/" target="_blank">Chico Hamilton</a> began recording the album, <em>Chic Chic Chico</em>. Actually, all songs except the title song were recorded on this date--the title song was recorded on March 16, 1965. Chico was accompanied by trumpet, trombone, french horn, flute, piccolo, tenor saxophone, guitar and bass in this heavily arranged set. While the rhythm section was Chico''s normal group of Gbor Szab, Albert Stinson and Willie Bobo, the wind was special on this one and even included Harold Land.</p>\n<p>Chico rose to prominece backing jazz greats such as <a href="http://mingusmingusmingus.com/" target="_blank">Charles Mingus</a>, <a href="http://www.dextergordon.com/" target="_blank">Dexter Gordon</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buddy_Collette" target="_blank">Buddy Collette</a> and others and firmly established his career playing with stars such as <a href="http://www.dukeellington.com/" target="_blank">Duke Ellington</a>, Nat King Cole, Sammy Davis Jr., Billy Holiday, Bing Crosby, Bob Hope and Lena Horne.</p>\n<p>The core group of Lloyd, Szab and Stinson heard on this album had played with Chico since the early 1960s and were described as chamber jazz with avant-gardism by the critic Scott Yanow. He even played a significant part in the film arts, providing the soundtrack for the first Western film to be shown behind the Iron Curtain ("Litho", 1962) and scoring literally hundreds of commercials.</p>\n<p>For more on Chico, take a trip over to <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Chico+Hamilton" target="_blank">last.fm</a>:</p>\n<p><a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Chico+Hamilton" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/chicointhepark.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Chic Chic Chico" (Manny Albam) - 2:47</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Corrida De Torres" (Gbor Szab) - 5:35</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Tarantula" (Gbor Szab) - 3:03</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"What''s New?" (Bob Haggart, Johnny Burke) - 6:02</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"St. Paddy''s Day Parade" (Chico Hamilton) - 3:09</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Carol''s Walk" (Chico Hamilton) - 6:36</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Swampy" (Gbor Szab) - 2:45</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Fire Works" (Gbor Szab) - 5:52</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 59, '2014-12-28 15:09:35', 62, '', '2016-08-20 01:02:17', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-01-04 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 6, 0, 28, 'jazz, Chico Hamilton', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1934, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(277, 'On this day in jazz (January 02)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-january-02', '', '<p>On this day in 1956,  <a href="http://www.billytaylorjazz.com/" target="_blank">Billy Taylor</a> began recording <em>Evergreens</em> with his trio which consisted of Billy at the piano,   Earl May on the bass and Percy Brice on the drums. Billy Taylor is a bit more obscure compared to many of the musicians that I highlight in my blog,   but he did leave behind a large catalog of over 300 songs. On <em>Evergreens</em> you get an upbeat and happy interpretation of songs by the likes of Irving Berlin, <a href="http://www.dukeellington.com/" target="_blank">Duke Ellington</a>, George & Ira Gershwin, Oscar Hammerstein II and even a couple of originals.</p>\n<p>A little bit about the man: besides being a performer, he also was a composer, broadcaster and educator. As a composer, one of his most important songs was "I Wish I Knew How It Would Feel to Be Free", which had strong popularity during the civil rights movement. It was covered by <a href="http://www.ninasimone.com/" target="_blank">Nina Simone</a> on her album "Silk & Soul" and became famous in the UK as the music for BBC Television''s <em>Film programme</em>. It was also selected as "one of the greatest songs of the sixties" by the New York Times as well as being the theme music for the 1996 film <em>Ghosts of Mississippi</em>.</p>\n<p>As a broadcaster, he was NBC''s Musical Director for "The Subject Is Jazz", a 13 episode series which was the first dedicated solely to jazz. It''s guests included Duke Ellington, <a href="http://www.billevanswebpages.com/" target="_blank">Bill Evans</a>, <a href="http://www.cannonball-adderley.com/" target="_blank">Cannonball Adderley</a> and Langston Hughes. From 1969 to 1972 he was the music director for "The David Frost Show"--the first African American to lead a talk show band.</p>\n<p>As an educator, he was the Wilbur D. Barrett Chair of Music at the University of Massachusetts Amherst and a Duke Ellington Fellow at Yale. He published instructional books on jazz, taught jazz at several institutions (Howard University, Long Island University, the Manhattan School of Music, and the University of Massachusetts Amherst). He holds a Ph.D from UMA. He was elected to the Hall of Fame for the International Association for Jazz Education, served as the artistic director for jazz at the Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts (responsible for the Louis Armstrong Legacy series and the annual Mary Lou Williams Women in Jazz Festival). He was one of only three jazz musicians to be appointed to the National Council of the Arts.</p>\n<p>Here''s Billy''s "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5dlrXCYrNYI" target="_blank">I Wish I Knew How It Would Feel to Be Free</a>" performed by Nina Simone at Montreaux in 1976:</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5dlrXCYrNYI" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/6a00e008dca1f0883401156f14c28d970c-300wi.jpg" border="0" width="223" height="270" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Cheek To Cheek</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">It''s Too Late Now</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">I Only Have Eyes For You</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Then I''ll Be Tired Of You</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">All The Things You Are</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">But Not For Me</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">You Don''t Know What Love Is</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Satin Doll</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">More Than You Know</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Between The Devil And The Deep Blue Sea</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 59, '2014-12-25 14:42:27', 62, '', '2016-08-16 21:51:21', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-01-02 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 30, 'jazz, The Modern Jazz Quartet, MJQ, Paul Desmond', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1641, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(280, 'On this day in jazz (January 05)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-january-05', '', '<p>On this day in 1959,   trumpeter <a href="http://www.shout.net/~jmh/mitchell/index.htm" target="_blank">Blue Mitchell</a> recorded his second album as a leader,   <em>Out of the Blue</em>. The album features an all-star cast including <a href="http://www.bennygolson.com/" target="_blank">Benny Golson</a> on the tenor saxophone, <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/wynton-kelly-mn0000684253/biography" target="_blank">Wynton Kelly</a> (tracks 1-6) and <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/cedar-walton-mn0000741325/biography" target="_blank">Cedar Walton</a> (track 7) on the piano, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Chambers" target="_blank">Paul Chambers</a> (tracks 2 & 5-7) and Sam Jones (tracks 1, 3 & 4) on the bass, and <a href="http://www.artblakey.com/" target="_blank">Art Blakey</a> on drums.</p>\n<p>Blue got his start professionally after being noticed by <a href="http://www.cannonball-adderley.com/" target="_blank">Cannonball Adderley</a> in 1958. After recording with Cannonball, he joined the <a href="http://www.horacesilver.com/" target="_blank">Horace Silver</a> Quintet for the next 6 years until the band split up. Taking some of the members of that quintet, he formed his own band with a young <a href="http://chickcorea.com/" target="_blank">Chick Corea</a> at the piano. This group would last until 1969 at which time Blue began touring with Ray Charles.</p>\n<p>Here''s Blue with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=avGCBKAg2fY" target="_blank">It Could Happen To You</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=avGCBKAg2fY" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/BlueMitchell_sm.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Blues on My Mind" (Benny Golson) - 9:05</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"It Could Happen to You" (Johnny Burke, Jimmy Van Heusen) - 5:52</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Boomerang" (Clark Terry) - 5:01</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Sweet-Cakes" - 6:09</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Missing You" (Ronnell Bright) - 5:40</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"When the Saints Go Marching In" (Traditional) - 7:00</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Studio B" (Paul Chambers) - 7:18 Bonus track on CD reissue</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 59, '2014-12-28 16:30:07', 62, '', '2016-08-20 01:01:01', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-01-05 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 27, 'jazz, Blue Mitchell', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1986, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(281, 'On this day in jazz (January 06)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-january-06', '', '<p>On this day in 1955,   <a href="http://www.teddy-charles.com/" target="_blank">Teddy Charles</a> completed recording the songs that would be released on the studio album,   <em>Evolution</em>. The songs recorded this day were recorded at Rudy Van Gelder''s studio in Hackensack,   NJ. I''ve always enjoyed the vibes, and Teddy was an excellent, yet overlooked, vibraphonist. Music critics put Teddy in the "third stream" genre--which means that he took elements of classical music and infused them into the jazz styles of the day.</p>\n<p>This album features not only great vibraphone play but also some great wind from J. R. Monterose, strings from <a href="http://mingusmingusmingus.com/" target="_blank">Charles Mingus</a> (credited as "Charlie" on the album cover), and drums by Jerry Segal. On the two tracks recorded a couple of years earlier (songs 7 & 8), you''ll hear <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jimmy_Giuffre" target="_blank">Jimmy Giuffre</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Curtis_Counce" target="_blank">Curtis Counce</a> and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shelly_Manne" target="_blank">Shelly Manne</a>.</p>\n<p>Here''s Teddy with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8mCttVgPXQs" target="_blank">Ralaxo Abstracto</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8mCttVgPXQs" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/6a00e008dca1f088340168ea57f33f970c-500wi.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing (songs by Teddy except where noted):</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Violetta" - 3:37</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Night We Called It a Day" (Tom Adair, Matt Dennis) - 2:41</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Jay Walkin''" - 3:36</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Speak Low" (Ogden Nash, Kurt Weill) - 3:16</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Relaxo Abstracto" - 5:23</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I Can''t Get Started" (Vernon Duke, Ira Gershwin) - 7:10</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Free" (Shorty Rogers) - 4:18</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Evolution" (Jimmy Giuffre) - 4:13</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>\n<p>*note, songs 7&8 were recorded on August 31, 1953 in Los Angeles with Shorty Rogers on trumpet, Jimmy Giuffre on tenor and baritone sax, Curtis Counce on bass and Shelly Manne on drums.</p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 59, '2014-12-28 16:52:05', 62, '', '2016-08-20 01:06:18', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-01-06 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 26, 'jazz, Teddy Charles', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1872, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(282, 'On this day in jazz (January 07)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-january-07', '', '<p>On this day in 1957,   vibraphonist <a href="http://www.pas.org/experience/halloffame/JacksonMilt.aspx" target="_blank">Milt Jackson</a> completed the recording of the songs that would comprise <em>Plenty,   Plenty Soul</em>. Joining Milt on this day were: Joe Newman on trumpet,   Jimmy Cleveland on trombone, the great <a href="http://www.cannonball-adderley.com/" target="_blank">Cannonball Adderly</a> on alto sax, Frank Foster on tenor sax, Sahib Shihab on baritone sax, and a legendary rhythm section of <a href="http://www.horacesilver.com/" target="_blank">Horace Silver</a> at the piano, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Percy_Heath" target="_blank">Percy Heath</a> on the bass and <a href="http://www.artblakey.com/" target="_blank">Art Blakey</a> on the drums. For the songs recorded two days earlier, the band consisted of Milt, Joe, Lucky Thompson on tenor, Horace, <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/oscar-pettiford-mn0000896298/biography" target="_blank">Oscar Pettiford</a> on bass and <a href="http://www.drummerworld.com/drummers/Connie_Kay.html" target="_blank">Connie Kay</a> on drums. Quite a lineup! Quincy Jones provided arrangements for the songs recorded on this day, also.</p>\n<p>You''ll remember that Milt, Percy and Connie were all part of the Modern Jazz Quartet--<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Lewis_(pianist)" target="_blank">John Lewis</a> was the only member not to play on this album. The album has some really great tunes, especially the title track, Cannonball''s "Sermonette" and the final track by Quincy Jones, "Blues at Twilight". Give it a listen.</p>\n<p>Here''s Milt with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FcWMWa9RMYY" target="_blank">Plenty, Plenty Soul</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FcWMWa9RMYY" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/MJackson.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Tack listing (songs by Milt Jackson except as indicated):</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Plenty, Plenty Soul" (Milt Jackson, Quincy Jones) - 9:33</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Boogity Boogity" (Jones) - 4:55</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Heartstrings" - 4:53</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Sermonette" (Cannonball Adderley) - 5:23</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Spirit-Feel" - 4:22</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Ignunt Oil" - 5:35</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Blues at Twilight" (Jones) - 6:46</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p>*songs 4-7 were recorded on January 5, 1957.</p>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 59, '2014-12-28 17:25:14', 62, '', '2016-08-16 21:53:11', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-01-07 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 25, 'jazz, Milt Jackson', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1820, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(283, 'On this day in jazz (January 08)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-january-08', '', '<p>On this day in 1964,   pianist <a href="http://www.andrewhilljazz.com/" target="_blank">Andrew Hill</a> recorded the studio album <em>Judgement!</em> at Rudy Van Gelder''s studio in Englewood Cliffs,NJ.<span style="line-height: 15.8079996109009px;">All compositions on this work were composed by Andrew and played by Andrew, <a href="http://www.bluenote.com/artists/bobby-hutcherson" target="_blank">Bobby Hutcherson</a> on vibraphone, Richard Davis on bass and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elvin_Jones" target="_blank">Elvin Jones</a> on drums--an excellent line up. </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">For more on Andrew, check out the <a href="index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=189:on-this-day-in-jazz-october-08&catid=56:october&Itemid=41" target="_self">October 8th page</a> of my blog where I give some biographical information and a list of awards bestowed upon him. </span></p>\n<p>The liner notes were provided by Leonard Feather and explain this album excellently:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">The first track, "Siete Ocho", meaning "Seven Eight", is an intriguing 7/8 piece with a main theme about 20 measures long. "Flea Flop" was named "for the first notes of the melody, which seemed to suggest a jumping flea. This is also dedicated to the hotels and motels that jazz sidemen are obliged to stay in all over the country." The composition "Yokada Yokada" was named after the song "Yakety Yak", referring to "senseless dialogue between people," whilst "Alfred" was, of course, dedicated to producer Alfred Lion because of his "natural understanding of jazz in general," and because of the rapport that was established in the interpretation of Hill''s tunes. The title track "Judgment" was inspired by a poem written by Hill''s wife, Lavern. Ultimately, "Reconciliation" wants to represent "the adjustment every musician has to make to achieve unity and harmony with the rest of the group."</p>\n<p>Here''s Andrew with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Yb3sivDtZLI" target="_blank">Judgement!</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Yb3sivDtZLI" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/andrew-hill.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Siete Ocho" - 8:58</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Flea Flop" - 7:21</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Yokada Yokada" - 5:17</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Alfred" - 7:04</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Judgment" - 6:53</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Reconciliation" - 7:24</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Yokada Yokada" [alternate take] - 5:12 Bonus track on CD</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 59, '2014-12-28 17:39:29', 62, '', '2016-08-16 21:53:32', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-01-08 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 24, 'jazz, Andrew Hill', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1822, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(284, 'On this day in jazz (January 09)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-january-09', '', '<p>On this day in 1961,   pianist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cecil_Taylor" target="_blank">Cecil Taylor</a> began recording the studio album,   <em>Jumpin'' Punkins</em>. Cecil was one of the great pioneers of free jazz and is one of my favorite musicians from the genre (along with the star of <a href="index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=283:on-this-day-in-jazz-january-08&catid=59:january&Itemid=41" target="_self">yesterday''s blog post</a>,   Andrew Hill). Besides the work highlighted here, also check out Cecil''s 1956 album <em><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jazz_Advance" target="_blank">Jazz Advance</a>.</em></p>\n<p>Although the album was recorded in 1961, it did not get released until 1974 in Japan and 1987 in the United States. It features <a href="http://www.archieshepp.net/" target="_blank">Archie Shepp</a> on the tenor saxophone, Buell Neidlinger on bass and drums by Denis Charles and Billy Higgins. On "I Forgot", you''ll hear <a href="http://clarkterry.com/" target="_blank">Clark Terry</a> on trumpet, <a href="http://www.roswellrudd.com/docs/main/frame.htm" target="_blank">Roswell Rudd</a> on trombone, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steve_Lacy" target="_blank">Steve Lacy</a> on soprano saxophone and Charles Davis on baritone sax. What a wonderful group of musicians.</p>\n<p>Here''s Cecil with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BsLClgHFCf4" target="_blank">Jumpin'' Punkins</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BsLClgHFCf4" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/201008_CecilTaylor.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Jumpin'' Punkins" (Mercer Ellington) - 8:15</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"O.P." (Buell Neidlinger) - 7:35</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I Forgot" (Cecil Taylor) - 8:34</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Things Ain''t What They Used to Be" (Ellington, Ted Persons) - 8:55</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 59, '2014-12-28 17:55:48', 62, '', '2016-08-16 21:53:51', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-01-09 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 23, 'jazz, Cecil Taylor', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1734, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(285, 'On this day in jazz (January 10)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-january-10', '', '<p>On this day in 1958,   <a href="http://www.johncoltrane.com/" target="_blank">John Coltrane</a> recorded "Lush Life" at Rudy Van Gelder''s studio in Hackensack, NJ. The song would appear on the album of the same name which was released three years later in March 1961. Joining John''s tenor saxophone were Donald Byrd on trumpet and a rhythm section of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Red_Garland" target="_self">Red Garland</a> on piano, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Chambers" target="_blank">Paul Chambers</a> on bass and Louis Hayes on drums.</p>\n<p>The song was written by <a href="http://www.billystrayhorn.com/" target="_blank">Billy Strayhorn</a> who also wrote the standard "Take the ''A'' Train". Personally, I''ve never taken the ''A'' train, but I have watched it go by many times while waiting on the ''E''. <a href="http://www.dukeellington.com/">Duke Ellington</a> said this of Billy:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">He demanded freedom of expression and lived in what we consider the most important and moral of freedoms: freedom from hate, unconditionally; freedom from self pity (even through all the pain and bad news); freedom from fear of possibly doing something that might possibly help another more than it might himself and freedom from the kind of pride that might make a man think that he was better than his brother or his neighbor.</p>\n<p>Here''s John performing Billy Strayhorn''s "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=f3bWRnrWfZc" target="_blank">Lush Life</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=f3bWRnrWfZc" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/John_Coltrane_1963.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Like Someone in Love" (Jimmy Van Heusen, Johnny Burke)  5:00</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I Love You" (Cole Porter)  5:33</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Trane''s Slow Blues" (Coltrane)  6:05</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Lush Life" (Billy Strayhorn)  14:00</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I Hear a Rhapsody" (Jack Baker, George Fragos, Dick Gasparre)  6:01</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 59, '2014-12-28 19:33:19', 62, '', '2016-08-16 21:54:13', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-01-10 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 22, 'jazz, John Coltrane', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1707, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(286, 'On this day in jazz (January 11)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-january-11', '', '<p>On this day in 1962,   pianist <a href="http://mccoytyner.com/" target="_blank">McCoy Tyner</a> completed recording the studio album <em>Inception</em> at Rudy Van Gelder''s studio in Englewood Cliffs, NJ. All songs were played by the rhythm section of McCoy, Art Davis (bass) and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elvin_Jones" target="_blank">Elvin Jones</a> (drums). Most of the songs were composed by McCoy, including "Blues for Gwen" which was named after McCoy''s sister, and "Sunset" which was named by his wife, Aisha, who said that the song made her think of nature when she heard it.</p>\n<p>The importance of the album is that it gives the listener a chance to hear McCoy playing what meant most to him rather than following what <a href="http://www.johncoltrane.com/" target="_blank">John Coltrane</a> wished him to play in his quartets. Also, without any wind on the album, it gives one a chance to hear a more naked version of McCoy''s piano than you will hear on the quartet albums while staying within the modal genre made popular by <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a>, <a href="http://www.billevanswebpages.com/" target="_blank">Bill Evans</a> and Coltrane.</p>\n<p>Here''s McCoy with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sYvICoEVpCk" target="_blank">Inception</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sYvICoEVpCk" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/tumblr_lda5ts7Rmw1qzn0deo1_1280.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Inception" - 4:28</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"There Is No Greater Love" (Jones, Symes) - 6:21</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Blues for Gwen" - 4:27</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Sunset" - 4:41</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Effendi" - 6:39</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Speak Low" (Nash, Weill) - 6:18</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 59, '2014-12-28 19:49:01', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:58:30', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-01-11 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 5, 0, 21, 'jazz, McCoy Tyner', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1403, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(287, 'On this day in jazz (January 12)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-january-12', '', '<p>On this day in 1956,   saxophonist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lester_Young" target="_blank">Lester Young</a> recorded the album <em>The Jazz Giants ''56</em>. Joining Lester on the album were Roy Eldridge on trumpet, Vic Dickenson on trombone, Teddy Wilson at the piano, Freddie Green on guitar, Gene Ramey on bass and Jo Jones on drums.</p>\n<p>Lester Young (aka "Pres") became famous playing with <a href="http://www.thecountbasieorchestra.com/" target="_blank">Count Basie</a> in his orchestra. His take on the saxophone differed from many of his peers and can best be described as cool, relaxed and sophisticated (think of the West Coast jazz of the 1950s and 1960s--even though Lester predated those musicians by two decades).</p>\n<p>Lester was born in Woodville, MS in 1909 to a very musical family. The family moved from Woodville to New Orleans while he was still an infant and then to Minneapolis while he was a child. He started out professionally playing in the family band, but left in 1927 at the age of 18 because he refused to tour in the south where the Jim Crow laws were still in effect. In 1933 he joined Count Basie''s band and quickly gained stardom. Lester had a very interesting life, and I would urge you to learn more about the man as a short blog cannot do him justice.</p>\n<p>Here''s Lester with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=R8cFxKVYC7A" target="_blank">Gigantic Blues</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=R8cFxKVYC7A" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/lester-young-01.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">I Guess I''ll Have To Change My Plan (Schwartz, Dietz) - 9:35</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">I Didn''t Know What Time It Was (Rodgers, Hart) - 10:06</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Gigantic Blues" (Young) - 6:54</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"This Year''s Kisses" (Irving Berlin) - 6:49</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"You Can Depend on Me" (Charles Carpenter, Louis Dunlap, Earl Hines) - 9:06</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 59, '2014-12-28 20:11:46', 62, '', '2016-08-16 21:55:00', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-01-12 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 20, 'jazz, Lester Young', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1510, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(288, 'On this day in jazz (January 13)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-january-13', '', '<p>On this day in 1957,  tenor saxophonist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hank_Mobley" target="_blank">Hank Mobley</a> recorded the studio album <em>Hank Mobley and His All Stars</em> at Rudy Van Gelder''s studio in Hackensack, NJ. Hank was supported by an all star cast (hence, the name) which included <a href="http://www.pas.org/experience/halloffame/JacksonMilt.aspx" target="_blank">Milt Jackson</a> on the vibraphone, <a href="http://www.horacesilver.com/" target="_blank">Horace Silver</a> on piano, Doug Watkins on bass and <a href="http://www.artblakey.com/" target="_blank">Art Blakey</a> on drums.</p>\n<p>All songs were compositions by Hank himself and two of them are very good: "Don''t Walk" and "Mobley''s Musings". If you are a fan of bop, this one is sure to please as it''s essentially a who''s who of late 50''s boppers and their performances are very strong.</p>\n<p>Here''s Hank et al with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WTM7K6q_cEE" target="_blank">Mobley''s Musings</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WTM7K6q_cEE" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/hank_mobley.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Reunion" - 6:55</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Ultra Marine" - 6:39</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Don''t Walk" - 7:50</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Lower Stratosphere" - 10:38</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Mobley''s Musings" - 6:04</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 59, '2015-01-02 18:18:27', 62, '', '2016-08-16 21:54:37', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-01-13 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 6, 0, 2, 'jazz, Hank Mobley', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1717, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(289, 'On this day in jazz (January 14)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-january-14', '', '<p>On this day in 1963,   saxophonist <a href="http://www.ayler.co.uk/" target="_blank">Albert Ayler</a> recorder the free jazz album <em>My Name Is Albert Ayler</em> in Copenhagen. The album was Albert''s debut as a leader and fetaures Albert on playing both tenor and soprano saxophones (including voice on the first track),  Danish pianist Niels Brnsted,   Danish bassist Niels-Henning rsted Pedersen and drummer <a href="http://www.ronniegardiner.org.uk/Home.html" target="_blank">Ronnie Gardiner</a>.</p>\n<p>Thom Jurek reviewed the album for allmusic.com an said this of the work:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">This is a strange record, like a soloist mismatched with the recording of another band, but nonetheless there is that singular tenor voice to contend with, and, on "Summertime," it is unfathomably beautiful".</p>\n<p>Something also has to be said about the drummer, Ronnie Gardiner. Ronnie was engaged to be married but his fiance died before their wedding date. He was performing in the Canary Islands at the time and the onslaught of depression after her death led him to consider drowning himself. However, during one show he saw a quadriplegic teenage boy in the audience smiling at him. It totally changed his view on life and has led him to create a music therapy that would be used to treat people with Parkinson''s disease and stroke patients. See his site (link above) for more, but essentially the method is a way of teaching people to memorize a series of coordinated physical movements while music is playing with a steady beat. It is currently being used by more than 200 physical and occupational therapists in Sweden. There''s a longer story about it <a href="http://www.heraldtribune.com/article/20100222/article/2221044" target="_blank">here</a>.</p>\n<p>Here''s Albert with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4Id6N30MuII" target="_blank">Summertime</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4Id6N30MuII" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/albert-ayler.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Introduction by Albert Ayler - 1:15</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Bye Bye Blackbird" (Mort Dixon, Ray Henderson) - 7:19</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Billie''s Bounce" (Charlie Parker) - 5:59</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Summertime" (George Gershwin, Ira Gershwin, DuBose Heyward) - 8:46</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"On Green Dolphin Street" (Bronis?aw Kaper, Ned Washington) - 9:05</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"C.T." (Albert Ayler) - 12:01</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 59, '2015-01-02 18:41:59', 62, '', '2016-08-16 21:55:23', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-01-14 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 19, 'jazz, Albert Ayler', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1528, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(290, 'On this day in jazz (January 15)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-january-15', '', '<p>On this day in 1960,   the Modern Jazz Quartet completed recording the songs that would comprise the album <em>Pyramid</em>. Specifically,   "Vendrome" and "How High the Moon" were the songs that were recorded on January 15. Besides the aforementioned songs,   there is one other original, "Django", and 4 cover tunes (including Duke Ellington''s "It Don''t Mean a Thing"). allmusic.com gives the album 4 1/2 stars out of five, calling it "quite stimulating, enthusiastic, and fresh". I agree.</p>\n<p>So, check out <a href="http://www.pas.org/experience/halloffame/JacksonMilt.aspx" target="_blank">Milt Jackson</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Lewis_(pianist)" target="_blank">John Lewis</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Percy_Heath" target="_blank">Percy Heath</a> and <a href="http://www.drummerworld.com/drummers/Connie_Kay.html" target="_blank">Connie Kay</a> with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gSgQfkWqTmY" target="_blank">How High the Moon</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gSgQfkWqTmY" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/097bbff303751b716d592a92451d8.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Vendome" (John Lewis) - 2:30</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Pyramid (Blues for Junior)" (Ray Brown) - 10:46</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"It Don''t Mean a Thing (If It Ain''t Got That Swing)" (Duke Ellington, Irving Mills) - 5:02</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Django" (John Lewis) - 4:36</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"How High the Moon" (Nancy Hamilton, Morgan Lewis) - 6:15</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Romaine" (Jim Hall) - 7:28</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 59, '2015-01-02 19:50:59', 62, '', '2016-08-16 21:55:45', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-01-15 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 18, 'jazz, Modern Jazz Quartet', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1502, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(291, 'On this day in jazz (January 16)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-january-16', '', '<p>On this day in 1959,   free jazz saxophonist Ornette Coleman began recording his second studio album, <em>Tomorrow Is the Question</em> in Los Angeles, CA. Ornette was one of the most prominent innovators in the free jazz genre, and even coined the term "free jazz". On this work, he is accompanied by an all star cast including <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Don_Cherry_%28trumpeter%29" target="_blank">Don Cherry</a> on the trumpet, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Percy_Heath" target="_blank">Percy Heath</a> (songs 1-6) and Red Mitchell (songs 7-9) on bass and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shelly_Manne" target="_blank">Shelly Manne</a> on drums.</p>\n<p>The importance of this album lies not only in the fact that it was one of the early free jazz recordings, but it is the first on which Ornette removed the piano (he was contractually required to have a piano on his first album)--so you get the exact sound that Ornette was looking for (i.e., more freedom for the soloists).</p>\n<p>Here''s what a few of his peers said about him:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">Roy Eldridge: "I listened to him all kinds of ways. I listened to him high and I listened to him cold sober. I even played with him. I think he''s jiving, baby."</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">Theolious Monk: "Man, that cat is nuts!"</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">Don Cherry: (recalling the day he met Ornette) "it was about 90 degrees and he had on an overcoat. I was scared of him."</p>\n<p>Here''s Ornette with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7OwUEKGbCU4" target="_blank">Tomorrow Is the Question</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7OwUEKGbCU4" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/claxtoncolemanl.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Tomorrow Is the Question!"  3:09</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Tears Inside"  5:00</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Mind and Time"  3:08</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Compassion"  4:37</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Giggin''"  3:19</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Rejoicing"  4:01</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Lorraine"  5:55</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Turnaround"  7:58</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Endless"  5:18</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 59, '2015-01-02 20:11:29', 62, '', '2016-08-16 21:56:07', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-01-16 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 17, 'jazz, Ornette Coleman', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1492, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(292, 'On this day in jazz (January 17)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-january-17', '', '<p>On this day in 1951,   the great <a href="http://www.cmgww.com/music/parker/home.html" target="_blank">Charlie Parker</a> recorded songs for the album <em>Swedish Schnapps</em>. On the cover of the album,Verve called the band "Charlie Parker and his Orchestra". I think that is taking it a bit too far. The men who made up the quintet with Charlie on this day were <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a> on trumpet, Walter Bishop Jr. on piano, Teddy Kotick on bass and <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/max-roach-mn0000396372/biography" target="_blank">Max Roach</a> on drums. If you find the CD reissue, it adds 5 more songs which were recorded on August 8 of the same year and features a different quartet that included <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Lewis_(pianist)" target="_blank">John Lewis</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kenny_Clarke" target="_blank">Kenny Clarke</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ray_Brown_(musician)" target="_blank">Ray Brown</a> and Red Rodney.</p>\n<p>Here''s Charlie with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=F88Os7b-sxo" target="_blank">She Rote</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=F88Os7b-sxo" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Charlie-Parker-001.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 59, '2015-01-02 20:43:51', 62, '', '2016-08-16 21:56:37', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-01-17 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 16, 'jazz, Charlie Parker', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1571, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(294, 'On this day in jazz (January 19)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-january-19', '', '<p>On this day in 1957,   saxophonist<a href="http://straightlife.info/apbio.html" target="_blank">Art Pepper</a> recorded the classic album <em>Art Pepper Meets the Rhythm Section</em>. The rhythm section was <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Red_Garland" target="_blank">Red Garland</a> on piano,   <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Chambers" target="_blank">Paul Chambers</a> on bass and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philly_Joe_Jones" target="_blank">Philly Joe Jones</a> on the drums--all four are jazz legends and were,   at the time of recording, the rhythm section for the Miles Davis Quintet.</p>\n<p>There are some really good songs on this work including Cole Porter''s "You''d Be So Nice to Come Home To" and several songs by either Art, Art & Paul, or Red. For more on Art, search his name on my web site or check out my <a href="index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=166:on-this-day-in-jazz-september-16&catid=55:september&Itemid=41" target="_blank">September 16th blog entry</a>.</p>\n<p>Here''s Art with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zHuzH2FL1ww" target="_blank">Straight Life</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zHuzH2FL1ww" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/artpepper200x150.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"You''d Be So Nice to Come Home To" (Cole Porter)  5:25</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Red Pepper Blues" (Red Garland)  3:37</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Imagination" (Johnny BurkeJimmy Van Heusen)  5:52</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Waltz Me Blues" (Paul ChambersArt Pepper)  2:56</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Straight Life" (Art Pepper)  3:59</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Jazz Me Blues" (Delaney)  4:47</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Tin Tin Deo" (FullerPozo)  7:42</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Star Eyes" (Gene de PaulDon Raye)  5:12</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Birks'' Works" (Dizzy Gillespie)  4:17</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 59, '2015-01-04 17:42:11', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:47:40', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-01-19 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 5, 0, 14, 'on this day in jazz, Art Pepper', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1866, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(295, 'On this day in jazz (January 20)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-january-20', '', '<p>On this day in 1963,   the great <a href="http://mingusmingusmingus.com/" target="_blank">Charles Mingus</a> recorded <em>The Black Saint and the Sinner Lady</em>. The album is actually just one song divided into four tracks and six movements and was meant to be the music for a ballet. A line from a poem is quoted on the cover: "Touch my beloveds thought while her worlds affluence crumbles at my feet."</p>\n<p>The album is well regarded historically, being part of the "Crown Collection" from the <em>Penguin Guide to Jazz</em> and a five star selection from allmusic.com which says it is "one of the greatest achievements in orchestration by any composer in jazz history." The music was recorded with Charles on piano as well as bass and an accompanying tentet featuring alto,soprano, tenor and baritone saxophones, flutes, trumpets, trombones (standard and contrabass), tuba, piano, classical guitar and drums.</p>\n<p>Here''s Charles with <em><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zFA0FYQo0Gg" target="_blank">The Black Saint and the Sinner Lady</a></em>:</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zFA0FYQo0Gg" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/220px-Charles_Mingus_1976.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Stop! Look! And Listen, Sinner Jim Whitney!"</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">6:39</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Hearts'' Beat and Shades in Physical Embraces"</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">6:45</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"(Soul Fusion) Freewoman and Oh, This Freedom''s Slave Cries"</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">7:22</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Stop! Look! And Sing Songs of Revolutions!" /</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Saint and Sinner Join in Merriment on Battle Front" /</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Of Love, Pain, and Passioned Revolt, then Farewell, My Beloved, ''til It''s Freedom Day"</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">18:39</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 59, '2015-01-04 17:58:19', 62, '', '2016-08-20 01:09:59', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-01-20 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 5, 0, 13, 'on this day in jazz, Charles Mingus', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1943, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(296, 'On this day in jazz (January 21)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-january-21', '', '<p>On this day in 1949,   <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a> began recording the songs that would make up the seminal album <em>Birth of the Cool</em>. The album is a compilation of three recording sessions with an all star cast including <a href="http://www.bjbear71.com/Winding/Kai.html" target="_blank">Kai Winding</a> & <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/jj-johnson-mn0000119111/biography">J. J. Johnson</a> on trombones,   <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lee_Konitz" target="_blank">Lee Konitz</a> on alto saxophone,   <a href="http://www.gerrymulligan.com/" target="_blank">Gerry Mulligan</a> on baritone saxophone, <a href="http://www.jazzinchicago.org/educates/journal/articles/my-time-al-haig" target="_blank">Al Haig</a> and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Lewis_(pianist)" target="_blank">John Lewis</a> on piano, Al McKibbon on bass, and <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/max-roach-mn0000396372/biography" target="_blank">Max Roach</a> and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kenny_Clarke" target="_blank">Kenny Clarke</a> on drums.</p>\n<p>Miles Davis is considered to be not only the father of cool jazz but also the father of modal jazz (see <em>Kind of Blue</em>) and jazz fusion (see <em>Bitches Brew</em>).</p>\n<p>Because it is impossible for me to pick just one song from even the first recording date, here''s a <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TWK2pLW0Rdc" target="_blank">link to the entire album</a>.</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TWK2pLW0Rdc" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/miles-davis-nonet.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Move" (Denzil Best, arranged by John Lewis)  2:32</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Jeru" (Gerry Mulligan)  3:10</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Moon Dreams" (Chummy MacGregor, Johnny Mercer, arranged by Gil Evans)  3:17</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Venus de Milo" (Mulligan)  3:10</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Budo" (Miles Davis, Bud Powell, arranged by Lewis)  2:32</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Deception" (Davis, arranged by Mulligan)  2:45</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Godchild" (George Wallington, arranged by Mulligan)  3:07</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Boplicity" (Cleo Henry, i.e. Davis and Gil Evans, arranged by Evans)  2:59</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Rocker" (Mulligan)  3:03</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Israel" (Johnny Carisi)  2:15</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Rouge" (John Lewis)  3:13</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Darn That Dream" (Eddie DeLange, James Van Heusen, arranged by Mulligan)  3:26</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>\n<p>Tracks recorded on 21-JAN-1949: 1, 2, 5 & 7</p>\n<p>Tracks recorded on 22-APR-1949: 4, 8, 10 & 11</p>\n<p>Tracks recorded on 09-MAR-1950: 3, 6, 9 & 12</p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 59, '2015-01-04 18:19:58', 62, '', '2016-08-16 21:58:17', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-01-21 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 12, 'on this day in jazz, Miles Davis', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1961, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(297, 'On this day in jazz (January 22)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-january-22', '', '<p>On this day in 1956,   the Modern Jazz Quartet began recording their first studio album for Atlantic Records, <em>Fontessa</em>. As I''ve said many times before, the MJQ is one of my favorite jazz bands, especially because of <a href="http://www.pas.org/experience/halloffame/JacksonMilt.aspx" target="_blank">Milt Jackson</a>''s supreme command of the vibraphone. The album features several originals by both <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Lewis_(pianist)" target="_blank">John Lewis</a> (pianist and music director of the group) and Milt. However, it also contains several standards that shouldn''t be missed including "Angel Eyes", "Over the Rainbow", "Willow Weep for Me" and "Woody N You". Listen to some of the standards and then compare them to a version by <a href="http://www.zootsims.org/" target="_blank">Zoot Sims</a> and you''ll be amazed at both how different they sound from each other and how they both hold up in their own way.</p>\n<p>One other note on this album. It was released in both mono and stereo version by Atlantic, but the stereo version has a bad hiss at 60, 120 and 180 Hz, which makes it better to have the mono version. The theory is that stereo recordings where still somewhat experimental during this time and all the kinks had not been worked out.</p>\n<p>Here''s the MJQ with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LWU60se-U3o" target="_blank">Woody N You"</a>:</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LWU60se-U3o" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/1770-050-CB9CFD0F.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Versailles" (John Lewis) - 3:22</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Angel Eyes" (Earl Brent, Matt Dennis) - 3:48</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Fontessa" (Lewis) - 11:12</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Over the Rainbow" (Harold Arlen, E.Y. Harburg) - 3:50</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Bluesology" (Milt Jackson) - 5:04</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Willow Weep for Me" (Ann Ronell) - 4:47</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Woodyn You" (Dizzy Gillespie) - 4:25</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 59, '2015-01-05 19:06:14', 62, '', '2016-08-16 21:58:43', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-01-22 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 11, 'on this day in jazz, The Modern Jazz Quartet', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2199, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(298, 'On this day in jazz (January 23)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-january-23', '', '<p>On this day in 1960,   <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/sonny-red-mn0000038187/biography" target="_blank">Sonny Red</a> completed recording his album <em>Out of the Blue</em>. Assisting Sonny Red''s alto saxophone were <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/wynton-kelly-mn0000684253/biography" target="_blank">Wynton Kelly</a> on piano,   <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Chambers" target="_blank">Paul Chambers</a> (songs #1-6) and Sam Jones (songs #7-13) on bass, and Roy Brooks (songs #1-6) and <a href="http://www.jimmycobb.net/" target="_blank">Jimmy Cobb</a> (songs #7-13) on drums. The first six songs were recorded on December 5th of the previous year; hence, the reason for the different personnel on the last seven songs.</p>\n<p>Sonny has become quite obscure these days, and his albums are somewhat hard to find. He released just a handful of albums as a leader in the early 1960s and one other in 1971. He passed away at the age of 48.</p>\n<p>Here''s Sonny with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CjwxclTmAQQ" target="_blank">You''re Driving Me Crazy</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CjwxclTmAQQ" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/sonny-red-plays-the-alto-saxophone-during-the-recording-session-for-his-out-of-the-blue-album-1959.png" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing (Sonny Red composer unless otherwise noted):</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Bluesville" - 5:53</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Stay As Sweet As You Are" (Gordon, Revel) - 6:16</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I''ve Never Been in Love Before" (Loesser) - 5:24</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Nadia" - 4:10</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Blues in the Pocket" - 6:32</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Alone Too Long" (Fields, Schwartz) - 3:00</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Lope" - 5:16</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Stairway to the Stars" (Malneck, Parish, Signorelli) - 6:19</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Crystal" - 5:38</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Lost April" (DeLange, Newman, Hubert Spencer) - 6:49</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"You''re Sensational" (Porter) - 6:30</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Blues for Kokee" - 5:36</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"You''re Driving Me Crazy" (Donaldson) - 5:27</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 59, '2015-01-05 19:27:21', 62, '', '2016-08-16 21:59:08', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-01-23 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 10, 'on this day in jazz, Sonny Red', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2180, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(299, 'On this day in jazz (January 24)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-january-24', '', '<p>On this day in 1975,   the great <a href="http://www.keithjarrett.org/" target="_blank">Keith Jarrett</a> was recorded live at the Opera House in Cologne. The title of the work is <em>The Kln Concert</em> (Kln being the German word for the English Cologne). The album is a solo concert given by Keith late on January 24th after the opera had completed. This work is currently the best-selling solo album and the all-time best-selling piano album in jazz history (with more than 3.5 million units sold). Once you listen to the work,   you''ll understand why it sits at the top.</p>\n<p>A little bit about the performance: the concert was organized by a 17 year old who convinced both the opera house to have the concert and for Keith to play at it. When Keith got to the opera house for rehearsal,   the requested piano was not available and after seeing in what poor condition the piano was in, he almost cancelled the concert. Luckily for us, several hours of tuning made it playable and the concert was on. The album consists of essentially one song in four movements, and all of the music was improvised on the spot by Keith. No music had ever been written down and after the concert was heard by the masses, he was urged to publish the music for the work. Keith refused saying that it was improvised "on a certain night and should go as quickly as it comes." He finally submitted to the requests, but asked that any pianist only use it as a guide and not to play it note for note. You can read more about the concert at <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_K%C3%B6ln_Concert" target="_blank">wikipedia</a>.</p>\n<p>Here''s Keith with the first movement of <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eKNQSSNNag8" target="_blank"><em>The Kln Concert</em></a>:</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eKNQSSNNag8" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Keith-Jarrett-feat.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Part I"  26:01</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Part IIa"  14:54</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Part IIb"  18:13</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Part IIc"  6:56</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 59, '2015-01-05 19:42:50', 62, '', '2016-08-16 21:59:42', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-01-24 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 9, 'on this day in jazz, Keith Jarrett', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2128, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(300, 'On this day in jazz (January 25)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-january-25', '', '<p>On this day in 1960,   cornetist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nat_Adderley" target="_blank">Nat Adderley</a> began recording the studio album <em>Work Song</em>. This album was the sixth''s of Nat as a leader and features <a href="http://www.wesmontgomery.com/" target="_blank">Wes Montgomery</a> on guitar, <a href="http://bobbytimmons.jazzgiants.net/" target="_blank">Bobby Timmons</a> on piano, Sam Jones and Keter Betts on bass / cello, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Percy_Heath" target="_blank">Percy Heath</a> on bass and Louis Hayes on the drums.</p>\n<p>The title song is a jazz standard and was even given lyrics and covered by Oscar Brown. While Nat is not as famous as his brother, <a href="http://www.cannonball-adderley.com/" target="_blank">Julian "Cannonball" Adderley</a>, this album is excellent. allmusic.com gives it 4.5 stars and suggests tracks 1, 4 and 6 as must listens.</p>\n<p>Here''s Nat with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zz1vSRJiPAc" target="_blank">My Heart Stood Still</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zz1vSRJiPAc" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/b870f3654a84f838805e73677a346.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Work Song" - 4:15</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Pretty Memory" (Bobby Timmons) - 3:54</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I''ve Got a Crush on You" (George Gershwin, Ira Gershwin) - 2:55</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Mean to Me" (Fred E. Ahlert, Roy Turk) - 5:01</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Fallout" - 4:54</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Sack of Woe" - 4:28</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"My Heart Stood Still" (Lorenz Hart, Richard Rodgers) - 6:25</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Violets for Your Furs" (Tom Adair, Matt Dennis) - 3:50</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Scrambled Eggs" (Sam Jones) - 3:20</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 59, '2015-01-07 16:48:00', 62, '', '2016-08-16 22:00:11', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-01-25 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 8, 'on this day in jazz, Nat Adderley', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2033, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(301, 'On this day in jazz (January 26)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-january-26', '', '<p>On this day in 1985,   <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a> began recording the studio album<em>You''re Under Arrest</em>. Joining Miles on this work were such jazz greats <a href="http://www.johnmclaughlin.com/" target="_blank">John McLaughlin</a> and <a href="http://www.johnscofield.com/" target="_blank">John Scofield</a>. The album contains links to several pop stars of the day: "Time After Time" - <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VdQY7BusJNU" target="_blank">Cyndi Lauper</a>,   "Human Nature" - <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kql0ld02SS4" target="_blank">Michael Jackson</a>,   "You''re Under Arrest" - Gordon Matthew Thomas Sumner.</p>\n<p>In case that last one threw you for a loop, here''s the story: during the recording of the album, Miles'' bassist, Darryl Jones, brought in Gordon (stage name Sting) to meet his longtime idol (Miles Davis). Miles asked Sting if he knew French, and because he did, Miles had him translate the Miranda warning into French and yell it into the microphone during the track.</p>\n<p>Here''s Miles with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=23VCyohcUxg" target="_blank">Time After Time</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=23VCyohcUxg" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/MI0001540738.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"One Phone Call"/"Street Scenes" (Davis) 4:34</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Human Nature" (John Bettis, Steve Porcaro) 4:30</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Intro: MD 1"/"Something''s On Your Mind"/"MD 2" (Davis, Hubert Eaves III, James "D-Train" Williams) 7:17</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Ms. Morrisine" (Davis, Morrisine Tynes Irving, Robert Irving III) 4:57</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Katia Prelude" (Davis, Irving III) 0:40</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Katia" (Davis, Irving III) 7:37</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Time After Time" (Cyndi Lauper, Rob Hyman) 3:37</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"You''re Under Arrest" (John Scofield) 6:14</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Medley: Jean Pierre"/"You''re Under Arrest"/"Then There Were None" (Davis, Irving III, Scofield) 3:23</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 59, '2015-01-07 17:08:45', 62, '', '2016-08-16 22:00:38', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-01-26 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 7, 'on this day in jazz, Miles Davis', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1894, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(302, 'On this day in jazz (January 27)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-january-27', '', '<p>On this day in 1958,   pianist <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/hampton-hawes-mn0000558596/biography" target="_blank">Hampton Hawes</a> recorded the studio album Four!. Joining Hampton on the album were Barney Kessel on guitar, Red Mitchell on bass and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shelly_Manne" target="_blank">Shelly Manne</a> on the drums. There are so many great songs on this album--as well as all of his others in the 1950s--that you should listen to it from start to finish.</p>\n<p>Hampton is definitely one of my favorite pianists of all time. I find myself listening to his music on a weekly basis. In fact, when I look at my profile on <a href="http://www.last.fm/user/iisaphd" target="_blank">last.fm</a>, I see that he''s actually #1 on my most played artists list. While he did not play with the flair (or talent) of<a href="http://www.budpowelljazz.com/" target="_blank">Bud Powell</a>, <a href="http://www.keithjarrett.org/" target="_blank">Keith Jarrett</a> or <a href="http://www.horacesilver.com/" target="_blank">Horace Silver</a>, he plays with a gentle sophistication that is both stimulating and relaxing at the same time. Check him out!</p>\n<p>On other note: he wrote the classic jazz memoir, <em><a href="http://www.amazon.com/Raise-Up-Off-Me-Portrait/dp/1560253533" target="_blank">Raise Up Off Me</a></em>. This book won the Deems-Taylor Award for music writing in 1975.</p>\n<p>Here''s Hampton with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9cpGIa4pxy0" target="_blank">Yardbird Suite</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9cpGIa4pxy0" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/hampton_hawes_with_b.kessel._s.mane._r.mitchell-four.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Yardbird Suite" (Parker) - 6:40</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"There Will Never Be Another You" (Gordon, Warren) - 6:59</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Bow Jest" (Mitchell) - 6:31</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Sweet Sue" (Young, Harris) - 5:35</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Up Blues" (Hawes) - 5:09</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Like Someone in Love" (Burke, Van Heusen) - 3:21</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Love Is Just Around the Corner" (Gensler, Robin) - 5:42</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Thou Swell" (Hart, Rogers) - 4:54 (CD reissue bonus track)</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Awful Truth" (Hawes) - 8:09 (CD reissue bonus track)</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 59, '2015-01-07 17:24:37', 62, '', '2016-08-16 22:01:03', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-01-27 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 6, 'on this day in jazz, Hampton Hawes', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1997, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(303, 'On this day in jazz (January 28)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-january-28', '', '<p>On this day in 1970,   trumpeter <a href="http://www.freddiehubbardmusic.com/" target="_blank">Freddie Hubbard</a> recorded songs for the album <em>Red Clay</em> at Van Gelder Studios in Englewood Cliffs,   NJ. This album was the first that Freddie recorded on Creed Taylor''s new label,   CTI. Freddy recorded extensively for Blue Note in the early to mid 1960s and then started bouncing around between labels until settling at CTI. CTI also lured many other jazz greats of the day to record on the label including Stanley Turrentine, George Benson, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chet_Baker">Chet Baker</a>, <a href="http://www.gerrymulligan.com/" target="_blank">Gerry Mulligan</a>, Nina Simone, <a href="http://www.puredesmond.ca/" target="_blank">Paul Desmond</a>, <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/art-farmer-mn0000502199/biography">Art Farmer</a>, <a href="http://www.herbiehancock.com/home.php" target="_blank">Herbie Hancock</a> and <a href="http://roncarter.net/JazzMaster/" target="_blank">Ron Carter</a>.</p>\n<p>This album also was quite a shift in style for Hubbard who started playing in more of a fusion style on this record--a style he would continue to play over the rest of his life. The album received a 5-star rating from allmusic.com and is part of the top 200 jazz albums of all time at <a href="http://jazz100.sffjazz.com/index.html" target="_blank">sffjazz.com</a>, a great site for starting your jazz education. Joining Freddie on the album were <a href="http://www.joehendersonsax.com/" target="_blank">Joe Henderson</a> on tenor saxophone and flute, Herbie Hancock on electric piano and organ, Ron Carter on bass and electric bass and Lenny White on drums. Quite a strong lineup! All songs on the album were written by Freddie except for one: "Cold Turkey" by John Lennon. The song is one of my favorite John Lennon songs post Beatles.</p>\n<p>Here''s Fredie with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=P05saf1Yrbc" target="_blank">Cold Turkey</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=P05saf1Yrbc" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/300x300.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Red Clay" - 12:11</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Delphia" - 7:23</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Suite Sioux" - 8:38</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Intrepid Fox" - 10:45</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Cold Turkey" (Lennon) - 10:27</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 59, '2015-01-07 19:01:38', 62, '', '2016-08-16 22:01:31', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-01-28 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 5, 'on this day jazz, Freddie Hubbard', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2063, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(306, 'On this day in jazz (January 31)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-january-31', '', '<p>On this day in 1959,   <a href="http://www.horacesilver.com/" target="_blank">Horace Silver</a> recorded <em>Finger Popin''</em> with the Horace Silver Quintet at Rudy Van Gelder''s studio in Hackensack,   NJ. Joining Horace on the work were <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blue_Mitchell" target="_blank">Blue Mitchell</a> on the trumpet,   Junior Cook on tenor saxophone, Gene Taylor on bass and Louis Hayes on the drums.</p>\n<p>Like all of Horace''s Blue Note albums of the mid 50''s to early 60s, this album is a true classic. It received a 5 star rating from allmusic.com, and Steve Huey said this regarding the album:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">it''s electrifying and tightly knit, with a palpable sense of discovery and excitement at how well the music is turning out... Finger Poppin'' is everything small-group hard bop should be, and it''s a terrific example of what made the Blue Note label''s mainstream sound so infectious".</p>\n<p>Here''s Horace with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q0lnDlQW0Ro" target="_blank">Finger Poppin''</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q0lnDlQW0Ro" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/horacesilver_wolff1.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Finger Poppin''" - 4:47</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Juicy Lucy" - 5:46</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Swingin'' the Samba" - 5:17</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Sweet Stuff" - 5:32</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Cookin'' at the Continental" - 4:54</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Come on Home" - 5:30</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"You Happened My Way" - 5:29</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Mellow D" - 5:37</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 59, '2015-01-11 17:41:06', 62, '', '2016-08-16 22:03:13', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-01-31 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 1, 'on this day in jazz, Horace Silver', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2279, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(307, 'On this day in jazz (February 01)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-february-01', '', '<p>On this day in 1967,   Frank Sinatra and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ant%C3%B4nio_Carlos_Jobim" target="_blank">Antnio Carlos Brasileiro de Almeida Jobim</a> completed recording <em>Francis Albert Sinatra & Antnio Carlos Jobim</em>. The album was quite popular that year and reached #4 on the US jazz albums list and #19 on the general US albums lists. It was also nominated for the 1968 Grammy in the category of Album of the Year.<span style="line-height: 1.3em;">On this album Frank belts out the vocals,   Tom (Jobim) plays piano,   guitar and even provides some backing vocals and Dom Um Romo plays drums. The orchestra was conducted by Claus Ogerman. </span></p>\n<p>Jobim is one of my favorite musicians to listen to in the summer when I want to simply relax. Check out his albums <em>Wave</em>, <em>Tide</em> and <em>Stone Flower</em> to hear some of his best music. Frank also has a couple of good albums, too.<em>Sinatra And Sextet - Live In Paris</em> is an essential part of any music collection, especially due to the song "Night and Day".</p>\n<p>Here''s Frank and Tom with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KyP0vfXF-Qg" target="_blank">Baubles, Bangles and Beads</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KyP0vfXF-Qg" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/frank-sinatra-tom-jobim_sinatra-special-airdate-13-nov-1967_1_sh111.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a><span style="line-height: 1.3em;"> </span></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Girl from Ipanema" (Antonio Carlos Jobim, Norman Gimbel, Vincius de Moraes)  3:00</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Dindi" (Ray Gilbert, Jobim, Aloysio de Oliveria)  3:25</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Change Partners" (Irving Berlin)  2:40</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Quiet Nights of Quiet Stars (Corcovado)" (Jobim, Gene Lees)  2:45</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Meditation (Meditao)" (Jobim, Gimbel, Newton Mendona)  2:51</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"If You Never Come to Me" (Jobim, Gilbert, de Oliveira)  2:10</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"How Insensitive (Insensatez)" (Jobim, Gimbel, de Moraes)  3:15</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I Concentrate on You" (Cole Porter)  2:32</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Baubles, Bangles and Beads" (Robert C. Wright, George Forrest, Alexander Borodin)  2:32</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Once I Loved (O Amor em Paz)" (Jobim, Gilbert, de Moraes)  2:37</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 60, '2015-01-11 18:03:55', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:34:18', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-02-01 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 28, 'on this day in jazz, Frank Sinatra, Antonio Carlos Jobim', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2091, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(308, 'On this day in jazz (February 02)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-february-02', '', '<p>On this day in 1959,   bassist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Chambers" target="_blank">Paul Chambers</a> began recording <em>Go</em>. Joining Paul on the album were <a href="http://www.cannonball-adderley.com/" target="_blank">Cannonball Adderley</a> on alto saxophone, both <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philly_Joe_Jones" target="_blank">Philly Joe Jones</a> (tracks: 1-1 to 1-6, 2-1 to 2-5) and <a href="http://www.jimmycobb.net/" target="_blank">Jimmy Cobb</a> (tracks: 1-7 to 1-9, 2-6, 2-7) on drums,<a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/wynton-kelly-mn0000684253/biography" target="_blank">Wynton Kelly</a> on piano and <a href="http://www.freddiehubbardmusic.com/" target="_blank">Freddie Hubbard</a> on trumpet--what a lineup!</p>\n<p>The album is a collection of jazz standards and original compositions. The CD reissue contains a bonus disk with alternate takes which feature some extended solos. 1959 was truly a great year for jazz--just a month after this album was recorded, Paul, Cannonball, Wynton and Jimmy would enter Columbia Record''s 30th Street Studio to record the most important jazz album of all time, <em>Kind of Blue</em> with <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a>.</p>\n<p>Here''s Paul with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CkpEJ1vhLFI" target="_blank">I Heard That</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CkpEJ1vhLFI" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/PaulChambersNewtumblr.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing (first disk):</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Awful Mean </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">6:55</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Julie Ann</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">5:57</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">There Is No Greater Love </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">8:14</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">I Heard That </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">9:30</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Dear Ann </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">4:08</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Shades Of Blue </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">8:23</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Just Friends </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">5:15</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Ease It </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">6:56</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">I Got Rhythm 6:05</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 60, '2015-01-11 18:19:45', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:34:50', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-02-02 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 27, 'on this day in jazz, Paul Chambers', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1820, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(309, 'On this day in jazz (February 03)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-february-03', '', '<p>On this day in 1966,   saxohonist <a href="http://www.wayneshorter.com/" target="_blank">Wayne Shorter</a> started recording <em>Adam''s Apple </em>at Rudy Van Gelder''s studio in Englewood Cliffs, NJ. Joining in on the fun was a rhythm section of <a href="http://www.herbiehancock.com/home.php" target="_blank">Herbie Hancock</a> at the piano, <a href="http://sculpturedsounds.com/" target="_blank">Reggie Workman</a> on the bass and <a href="http://www.josephachambers.com/" target="_blank">Joe Chambers</a> on the drums. Although not quite as tight at 1965''s <em>Speak No Evil</em>, it''s still a very good album, well worth a listen. allmusic.com said this of the album: " Taken in isolation, this is one of the great works of mid-''60s jazz".</p>\n<p>From my September 2nd blog entry (but worth repeating):</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">At the time of this writing, Wayne is still with us, and has been described by Ben Ratliff in 2008 as "jazz''s greatest living small-group composer and a contender for greatest living improviser". He has won 10 Grammy Awards and was "Down Beat" magazine''s annual poll winner for best soprano saxophone player from 1970 to 1979 (critic''s poll) and from 1970 to 1987 (reader''s poll). Very impressive. He also was the founder of the band "Weather Report". Note, if jazz fusion isn''t your style, you should check out the works he composed in the 50''s for the Jazz Messengers.</p>\n<p>Here''s Wayne with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3XvJFW0DHbU" target="_blank">Footprints</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3XvJFW0DHbU" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/879920309379bd741bdb03a81f0a0.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing (written by Shorter unless noted):</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Adam''s Apple"  6:49</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"502 Blues (Drinkin'' and Drivin'')" (Jimmy Rowles)  6:34</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"El Gaucho"  6:30</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Footprints"  7:29</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Teru"  6:12</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Chief Crazy Horse"  7:34</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Collector" (Herbie Hancock)  6:54</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 60, '2015-01-12 18:55:40', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:35:10', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-02-03 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 26, 'on this day in jazz, Wayne Shorter', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1904, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(310, 'On this day in jazz (February 04)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-february-04', '', '<p>On this day in 1960,   pianist <a href="http://www.billytaylorjazz.com/" target="_blank">Billy Taylor</a> recorded the live album <em>Uptown</em> at The Prelude in New York City. The entire group was a rhythm section of Billy,   Henry Grimes on bass and Ray Mosca on drums. <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orrin_Keepnews" target="_blank">Orrin Keepnews</a> served as the producer, and pretty much everything Orrin touched turned to gold.</p>\n<p>Although allmusic.com only gives the album 3 stars, I consider it a four star piece and suggest listening to ErrollGarner''s "La Petite Mambo", Duke Jordon''s "Jordu", Billy''s "Soul Sisters" and Sara Cassey & Dotty Wayne''s "Warm Blue Stream"--although all the songs are pretty good.</p>\n<p>Here''s Billy with "<a href="http://iisaphd.subsonic.org/share/vxGGx" target="_blank">La Petite Mambo</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="http://iisaphd.subsonic.org/share/vxGGx" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/billy-taylor-round-frame.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a><span style="line-height: 1.3em;"> </span></p>\n<p>Track listing (written by Taylor unless noted):</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"La Petite Mambo" (Erroll Garner) - 5:45</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Jordu" (Duke Jordan) - 4:10</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Just the Thought of You" - 4:59</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Soul Sisters" - 5:36</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Moanin''" (Bobby Timmons) - 5:13</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Warm Blue Stream" (Sara Cassey, Dotty Wayne) - 4:55</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Biddy''s Beat" - 4:14</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Cu-Blu" - 4:01</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"''S Wonderful" (George Gershwin, Ira Gershwin) - 3:51</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 60, '2015-01-12 19:07:38', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:35:45', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-02-04 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 25, 'on this day in jazz, Billy Taylor', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1813, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(311, 'On this day in jazz (February 05)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-february-05', '', '<p>On this day in 1972,   Mal Waldron recorded Blues for Lady Day. Lady Day, of course, refers to Billie Holiday for whom Mal was her final regular accompanist. Mal recorded several tributes to the Lady, and this one is a nine song piano only tribute which consists of eight songs Mal and Billie played together plus "Blues for Lady Day" which Mal wrote himself.</p>\n<p>If you find the re-release on CD, there are actually some songs not related at all to Lady Day, but are interesting enough themselves as they include Mal playing with bassist Henk Haverhoek and drummer Pierre Courbois.</p>\n<p>Here''s Mal with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=21nOiIFyGuU" target="_blank">Blues for Lady Day</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=21nOiIFyGuU" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/photo_gallery872.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Blues for Lady Day" (Mal Waldron)  3:43</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Just Friends" (John Klenner, Sam M. Lewis)  4:04</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Don''t Blame Me" (Jimmy McHugh, Dorothy Fields)  3:20</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"You Don''t Know What Love Is" (Gene de Paul, Don Raye)  5:38</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Man I Love" (George Gershwin, Ira Gershwin)  3:01</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"You''re My Thrill" (Jay Gorney, Sidney Clare)  3:39</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Strange Fruit" (Abel Meeropol)  2:47</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Easy Living" (Ralph Rainger, Leo Robin)  4:48</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Mean to Me" (Fred E. Ahlert, Roy Turk)  3:01</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 60, '2015-01-18 19:02:16', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:36:07', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-02-05 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 24, 'on this day in jazz, Mal Waldron', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1685, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(312, 'On this day in jazz (February 06)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-february-06', '', '<p>On this day in 1959,   two of my personal favorite artists,   <a href="http://www.zootsims.org/" target="_blank">Zoot Sims</a> and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Al_Cohn" target="_blank">Al Cohn</a>, were recorded live at the Half Note in New York City. The title of the released work is <em>Jazz Alive! A Night at the Half Note</em>. In addition to the two being two of my favorite artists, this is one of my favorite two Zoot Sims albums--the other is <em>The Rare Dawn Sessions</em>.</p>\n<p>Joining the two sax players were pianist <a href="http://moseallison.com/" target="_blank">Mose Allison</a> (another one of my favorite artists), bassist Nabil Totah and accomplished drummer <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Motian" target="_blank">Paul Motian</a>. With such great musicians and such a great location, you can easily understand why this one of the best live jazz albums ever recorded.</p>\n<p>Here''s Art and Zoot with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=y99XAif1Wp0" target="_blank">Lover, Come Back To Me</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=y99XAif1Wp0" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/115852678.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Lover, Come Back to Me (Oscar Hammerstein II / Sigmund Romberg) 9:08</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">It Had to Be You (Isham Jones / Gus Kahn) 10:14</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Wee Dot (J.J. Johnson / Leo Parker) 8:50</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">After You''ve Gone (Henry Creamer / Turner Layton) 11:37</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 60, '2015-01-18 19:17:42', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:36:28', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-02-06 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 23, 'on this day in jazz, Al Cohn, Zoot Sims', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1539, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(313, 'On this day in jazz (February 07)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-february-07', '', '<p>On this day in 1960,   saxophonist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hank_Mobley" target="_blank">Hank Mobley</a> recorded one of the finest studio albums ever,   <em>Soul Station</em>. Most of the songs are originals by Mobley, but also included are Irving Berlin''s "Remember" and Ralph Rainger/Leo Robin''s "If I Should Lose You". Hank is assisted by a rhythm section consisting of hard bob royalty: <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/wynton-kelly-mn0000684253/biography" target="_blank">Wynton Kelly</a> on piano, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Chambers" target="_blank">Paul Chambers</a> on bass and <a href="http://www.artblakey.com/" target="_blank">Art Blakey</a> on drums.</p>\n<p>It''s really hard to pick only one song to feature, but I''ll go with song number four, "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IC3FHpSbKC4" target="_blank">Split Feelin''s</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IC3FHpSbKC4" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/2011011005355134f.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Remember" </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Irving Berlin</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">5:41</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"This I Dig of You" </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Hank Mobley</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">6:25</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Dig Dis" </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Hank Mobley</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">6:08</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Split Feelin''s" </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Hank Mobley</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">4:55</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Soul Station" </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Hank Mobley</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">9:06</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"If I Should Lose You" </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Ralph Rainger, Leo Robin</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">5:08</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 60, '2015-01-18 19:28:42', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:36:51', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-02-07 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 22, 'on this day in jazz, Hank Mobley', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1630, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(314, 'On this day in jazz (February 08)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-february-08', '', '<p>On this day in 1972,   the great <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jimmy_Smith_(musician)" target="_blank">Jimmy Smith</a> recorded the live album <em>Root Down</em> in Los Angeles, CA. Jimmy, of course, plays the Hammond B3 organ and is joined by Wilton Felder on bass, Arthur Adams on guitar, Steve Williams on harmonica, Paul Humphrey on drums and Buck Clarke on the congas and other percussion. Although the main reason to listen is for Jimmy''s work on the organ, I must say the Wilton and Arthur do a funky job on the guitars and Paul and Buck are great working the percussion.</p>\n<p>allmusic.com gives the album 5 stars and the <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Xf1YF_MH1xc" target="_blank">Beastie Boys</a> liked the title song so much that they sampled it for their iconic song, "Root Down". If you''ve heard only one of the versions, but not the other, take a listen to the one you haven''t heard.</p>\n<p>Here''s Jimmy with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DP4LGEAfUEY" target="_blank">Root Down</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DP4LGEAfUEY" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/51+hfUDc43L.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Sagg Shootin'' His Arrow"  7:09</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"For Everyone Under the Sun"  5:56</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"After Hours"  7:45</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Root Down (And Get It)"  7:44</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Let''s Stay Together" (Al Green)  6:30</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Slow Down Sagg"  6:43</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 60, '2015-01-18 21:28:15', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:37:10', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-02-08 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 2, 'on this day in jazz, Jimmy Smith', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1861, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(315, 'On this day in jazz (February 09)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-february-09', '', '<p>On this day in 1978,   <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clifford_Jordan" target="_blank">Clifford Jordan</a> recorded the album <em>The Adventurer</em>. On this work you''ll hear Clifford on both the tenor and alto saxophones as well as the flute. His rhythm section consisted of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tommy_Flanagan" target="_blank">Tommy Flanagan</a> at the piano,   Bill Lee on bass, and Grady Tate on the drums. The album includes three originals along with three covers. The album receives a four star rating from allmusic.com and sites two songs as essential listens: <a href="http://www.cmgww.com/music/parker/home.html" target="_blank">Charlie Parker</a>''s "Quasimodo" and Clifford''s "Adventurer". Clifford''s tone is very mellow, in line with some of my favorite saxophonists such as <a href="http://www.stangetz.net/" target="_blank">Stan Getz</a> and <a href="http://www.zootsims.org/" target="_blank">Zoot Sims</a>, so you can see why I like this album so much.</p>\n<p>Clifford Jordan was born in Chicago in 1931 and started his professional career in the Windy City, playing with jazz greats such as <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/max-roach-mn0000396372/biography" target="_blank">Max Roach</a> and <a href="http://www.sonnystitt.com/" target="_blank">Sonny Stitt</a>. Like most of the great jazz musicians of the time, he would end up living in New York and eventually became part of <a href="http://www.horacesilver.com/" target="_blank">Horace Silver</a>''s quartet as well as playing with <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/jj-johnson-mn0000119111/biography" target="_blank">J.J. Johnson</a> and <a href="http://www.kennydorham.net/biography/" target="_blank">Kenny Dorham</a> before joining <a href="http://mingusmingusmingus.com/" target="_blank">Charles Mingus</a>'' group where he would stand toe to toe with jazz great <a href="http://www.ericdolphy.net/" target="_blank">Eric Dolphy</a>.</p>\n<p style="line-height: 15.8079996109009px;">rhapsody.com says this of Clifford:</p>\n<p style="line-height: 15.8079996109009px; padding-left: 30px;">(he) didnt really straddle the fence between Bop and Avant Garde; he simply stepped around it. Perhaps his unique Post Bop style stemmed from his origins as a Chicago tenor, a tradition firmly rooted in the conventions of Swing and Bop harmony. Or perhaps its the result of his big, warm tone, which always made his abstract, meandering improvisational flights accessible and appealing. Whatever the cause, many musicians admired the effect, and Jordan was popular among the jazz community in the 1960s. Between 1960 and 1975, he recorded several acclaimed albums as a leader, backed by pianist Cedar Walton and a rotating rhythm section...</p>\n<p style="line-height: 15.8079996109009px;">In addition to the two songs mentioned above, also take a listen to this one, "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GEwRMYo2Xfw" target="_blank">He''s a Hero</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GEwRMYo2Xfw" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/clifford-jordan.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing (songs by Clifford unless otherwise noted):</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"He''s a Hero" - 5:19</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Quasimodo" (Charlie Parker) - 7:08</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"No More" (Tutti Camarata, Bob Russell) - 4:54</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Blues for Muse" - 5:06</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Adventurer" - 6:49</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I''ll Be Around" (Alec Wilder) - 5:55</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 60, '2015-01-24 19:41:29', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:37:40', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-02-09 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 21, 'on this day in jazz, Clifford Jordan', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1681, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(316, 'On this day in jazz (February 10)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-february-10', '', '<p>On this day in 1960,   trumpeter <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/art-farmer-mn0000502199/biography" target="_blank">Art Farmer</a> and saxophonist <a href="http://www.bennygolson.com/" target="_blank">Benny Golson</a> completed the recording of Meet the Jazztet in New York City. The Jazztet was a sextet that geatured Curtis Fuller on trombone and a rhythm section of <a href="http://mccoytyner.com/" target="_blank">McCoy Tyner</a> on the piano,   Addison Farmer on bass,   and Lex Humphries on the drums. The album received a five start rating from allmusic.com--take a listen and you''ll see why.</p>\n<p>At a time when most jazz musicians were taking advantage of the somewhat recently invented long playing album the producers of this album went in the opposite direction--having the band recording songs short enough to produce radio airplay and a hit single, "Killer Joe".</p>\n<p>However, I think the best song is Golson''s "<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/I_Remember_Clifford_%28song%29" target="_blank">I Remember Clifford</a>". Bob Blumenthal said this of the song: "(it is a) heartbreaking reading. The balance Farmer achieves between fealty to the melody and sympathetic variation make this (version) definitive."</p>\n<p>Here''s Art and Benny with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zj5ij9X2Af0&list=PLafagIBDy-VI9GFscc9rjYjBYnXgITc2C" target="_blank">I Rember Clifford</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zj5ij9X2Af0&list=PLafagIBDy-VI9GFscc9rjYjBYnXgITc2C" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Art-Farmer-Benny-Golson-resize-2.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Serenata" (Leroy Anderson, Mitchell Parish)  3:30</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"It Ain''t Necessarily So" (George Gershwin, Ira Gershwin)  4:26</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Avalon" (Buddy DeSylva, Al Jolson, Vincent Rose)  3:29</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I Remember Clifford"  3:10</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Blues March"  5:16</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"It''s All Right with Me" (Cole Porter)  3:53</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Park Avenue Petite"  3:41</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Mox Nix" (Art Farmer)  4:01</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Easy Living" (Ralph Rainger, Leo Robin)  3:33</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Killer Joe"  4:57</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 60, '2015-01-24 20:02:45', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:38:13', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-02-10 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 20, 'on this day in jazz, Art Farmer, Benny Golson', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1679, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(317, 'On this day in jazz (February 11)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-february-11', '', '<p>On this day in 1958,   living legend <a href="http://sonnyrollins.com/" target="_blank">Sonny Rollins</a> began recording the songs that would part of the album <em>Freedom Suite</em>. That is,   all the songs save for the title song were recorded on this date--the title song was recorded on March 7. Sonny''s tenor saxophone is joined by <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/oscar-pettiford-mn0000896298/biography" target="_blank">Oscar Pettiford</a> on the bass and <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/max-roach-mn0000396372/biography" target="_blank">Max Roach</a> on the drums--it should be noted that Sonny was the one who pioneered the pianoless trio form.</p>\n<p>Sonny was well know for his political activism, and this album firmly affirms his views. Take 20 minutes and listen to "The Freedom Suite" and you''ll understand how he expresses those view through music.</p>\n<p>Here''s Sonny with Noel Coward''s "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=P8TE-gc9WVc" target="_blank">Someday I''ll Find You</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=P8TE-gc9WVc" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/sonny-meryl2-960x350.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Freedom Suite" (Sonny Rollins) - 19:17</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Someday I''ll Find You" (Nol Coward) - 4:35</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Will You Still Be Mine?" (Tom Adair, Matt Dennis) - 2:54</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Till There Was You" (Meredith Willson) - 4:54</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Till There Was You" [alternate take] (Willson) - 4:55 Bonus track on CD rerelease</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Shadow Waltz" (Al Dubin, Harry Warren) - 4:08</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 60, '2015-01-24 20:53:57', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:38:39', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-02-11 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 19, 'on this day in jazz, Sonny Rollins', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1620, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(318, 'On this day in jazz (February 12)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-february-12', '', '<p>On this day in 1960,   trumpeter <a href="http://www.kennydorham.net/biography/" target="_blank">Kenny Dorham</a> completed recording the studio album <em>Jazz Contemporary</em>. Kenny was assisted by Charles Davis on baritone saxophone, Steve Kuhn on piano, Jimmy Garrison and Butch Warren on bass, and Buddy Enlow playing the drums.</p>\n<p>Kenny was born in Fairfield, Texas in 1924 and passed away at the age of 48 from kidney disease in New York City. He is known as a fine, yet underrated, bebop and hard bop trumpeter who wrote the standard "Blue Bossa". Although he was a significant member in the bands of many of the top acts of the day like <a href="http://www.uiweb.uidaho.edu/hampton/bio.html" target="_blank">Lionel Hampton</a>, Billy Eckstine, <a href="http://www.dizzygillespie.com/" target="_blank">Dizzy Gillepsie</a>, <a href="http://www.cmgww.com/music/parker/home.html" target="_blank">Charlie Parker</a>, <a href="http://www.monkzone.com/" target="_blank">Thelonious Monk</a> and<a href="http://sonnyrollins.com/" target="_blank">Sonny Rollins</a>. His most famous band was The Jazz Prophets which featured <a href="http://bobbytimmons.jazzgiants.net/" target="_blank">Bobby Timmons</a>, Sam Jones and J. R. Monterose. Check out the album <em>''Round About Midnight at the Cafe Bohemia</em>.</p>\n<p>Here''s Kenny with Thelonious Monk''s "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fSYv-bQMe6U" target="_blank">Monk''s Mood</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fSYv-bQMe6U" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/50f5558b93276.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing (songs by Kenny except where noted):</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"A Waltz" - 5:34</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Monk''s Mood" (Thelonious Monk) - 8:09</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"In Your Own Sweet Way" (Dave Brubeck) - 8:01</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Horn Salute" - 8:27</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Tonica" - 2:57</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"This Love of Mine" (Sol Parker, Henry W. Sanicola Jr., Frank Sinatra) - 6:49</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 60, '2015-01-25 18:21:55', 62, '', '2016-08-20 18:21:06', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-02-12 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 3, 0, 18, 'on this day in jazz, Kenny Dorham', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2138, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(319, 'On this day in jazz (February 13)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-february-13', '', '<p>On this day in 1959,   pianist/singer/songwriter <a href="http://moseallison.com/" target="_blank">Mose Allison</a> recorded the studio album <em>Autumn Song</em>. The album was his fifth and followed the fine album <em>Creek Bank</em>. Assisting Mose on the album were bassist Addison Farmer (Art''s twin) and Ronnie Free on drums.<span style="line-height: 1.3em;">allmusic.com gives the album four stars. In their review,   allmusic says: "</span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">One realizes why Allison was soon emphasizing his vocals; he was a much more distinctive singer than pianist although his piano playing was actually pretty inventive. This is an excellent all-round set."I agree--listen to Mose to hear him sing--</span>especially<span style="line-height: 1.3em;"> on his own compositions. </span></p>\n<p>Here''s Mose with Arthur Crudup''s "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1TR1RzXwG5c" target="_blank">That''s All Right</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1TR1RzXwG5c" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/mose-allison_1.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing (written by Mose unless otherwise noted):</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Promenade" - 4:09</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Eyesight to the Blind" (Sonny Boy Williamson II) - 1:41</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"It''s Crazy" (Dorothy Fields, Richard Rodgers) - 3:37</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"That''s All Right" (Arthur Crudup) - 2:27</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Devil in the Cane Field" - 4:02</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Strange" (Matthew Fisher, John La Touche) - 3:06</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Autumn Song" - 3:40</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Do Nothin'' Till You Hear from Me" (Duke Ellington, Bob Russell) - 3:11</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Spires" - 3:03</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Groovin'' High" (Dizzy Gillespie) - 5:39</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 60, '2015-01-25 19:18:11', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:46:59', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-02-13 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 17, 'on this day in jazz, Mose Allison', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1774, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(320, 'On this day in jazz (February 14)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-february-14', '', '<p>On this day in 1962,   the great <a href="http://sonnyrollins.com/" target="_blank">Sonny Rollins</a> completed the recording of the studio album<em>The Bridge </em>(including the title song itself on this day). Sonny is joined on the work by <a href="http://www.jimhallmusic.com/" target="_blank">Jim Hall</a> on guitar,   Bob Cranshaw on bass and Ben Riley on the drums.</p>\n<p>The interesting thing about this album is that it was Sonny''s first after a three year hiatus which he took because he was somewhat overwhelmed by his quick rise to fame. During those three years,   Sonny said that he would leave his apartment in the East Villiage and make the trek to the Williamsburg Brige to practice alone, sometimes for as much as sixteen hours straight no matter the season. allmusic.com calls it a "near classic" granting it a four and a half star rating.</p>\n<p>Here''s Sonny with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QuOy-B4gKRI" target="_blank">The Bridge</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QuOy-B4gKRI" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/The_Bridge_Sonny_Rollins.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Without a Song" (Edward Eliscu, Billy Rose, Vincent Youmans)  7:28</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Where Are You?" (Harold Adamson, Jimmy McHugh)  5:10</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"John S." (Sonny Rollins)  7:45</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Bridge" (Rollins)  5:58</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"God Bless the Child" (Arthur Herzog Jr., Billie Holiday)  7:29</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"You Do Something to Me" (Cole Porter)  6:49 </span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 60, '2015-01-25 19:33:36', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:45:10', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-02-14 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 16, 'on this day in jazz, Sonny Rollins', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1811, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(321, 'On this day in jazz (February 15)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-february-15', '', '<p>On this day in 1957,  <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jackie_McLean" target="_blank">Jackie McLean</a> completed recording his studio album <em>A Long Drink of the Blues</em>. Although the title song was recorded on August 30,  1957, the rest of the songs were recorded on this day. On this work you''ll hear Jackie playing the tenor sax on the title song and alto sax on the rest. Joining Jackie were <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Webster_Young" target="_blank">Webster Young</a> on trumpet,<span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Curtis Fuller on trombone, Gil Coggins and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mal_Waldron" target="_blank">Mal Waldron</a> on piano, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Chambers" target="_blank">Paul Chambers</a> and Arthur Phipps on bass and Louis Hayes and <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/art-taylor-mn0000505154/biography" target="_blank">Art Taylor</a> on the drums.</span></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Be sure to check out the rest of my blog for more on Jackie--there''s some interesting stories here. </span></p>\n<p>Here''s Jackie with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DkzsCf7G_AA" target="_blank">I Cover the Waterfront</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DkzsCf7G_AA" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/mclean.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"A Long Drink of the Blues" [Take 1] - 2:21</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"A Long Drink of the Blues" (McLean) [Take 2] - 20:49</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Embraceable You" (Gershwin, Gershwin) - 7:07</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I Cover the Waterfront" (Heyman, Green) - 6:27</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"These Foolish Things (Remind Me of You)" (Link, Marvell, Strachey) - 8:21</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 60, '2015-01-25 19:54:05', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:40:21', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-02-15 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 15, 'on this day in jazz, Jackie McLean', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1762, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(334, 'On this day in jazz (February 28)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-february-28', '', '<p>On this day in 1953,   Dizzy Gillespie completed recording the songs for the album Dizzy Digs Paris. The album actually contains three sets of sets. The first is a great concert recorded at Salle Pleyel in which Dizzy was assisted by a rhythm section of pianist Wade Legge, bassist Lou Hackney and drummer Al Jones. Guest stars for the concert included Joe Carroll, Kenny Clarke, Kenny Dorham, Al Haig, John Lewis and Sarah Vaughn. From datebooks kept by Dizzy, the following happened: in the previous 48-hour period, he cut albums for two different competing firms (ten collections have been published involving the material) and his rhythm section cut an album on the same day of the concert (also reissued at multiple times, and it was the sole effort by pianist Wade Legge as a leader). That''s a full slate. The second set was recorded at Studio Pathe Magellan on the 22nd and the third, of course, were the works recorded on this day in Paris.</p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Here''s Dizzy with "</span><a href="http://iisaphd.subsonic.org/share/UMegL" target="_blank" style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Dance of the Infidels</a><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">":</span></p>\n<p><a href="http://iisaphd.subsonic.org/share/UMegL" target="_blank"><img src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/f/f2/Dizzy_Digs_Paris.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing (only works recorded on this day):</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Perdido" (Juan Tizol) - 3:08</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Dream a Little Dream of Me" (Fabian Andre, Wilbur Schwandt, Gus Kahn) - 3:16</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Wade Legge''s Blues" (Wade Legge) - 3:44</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"A Swedish Folk Song" (Traditional) - 3:11</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Dance Of The Infidels" (Bud Powell) - 3:14</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Aren''t You Glad You''re You" (Jimmy Van Heusen, Johnny Burke) - 3:15</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"These Foolish Things" (Harry Link, Holt Marvell, Jack Strachey) - 2:52</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Why Don''t You Believe Me?" (Lew Douglas, King Laney, Roy Rodde) - 2:52</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 60, '2015-02-16 17:40:55', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:45:06', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-02-28 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 1, 'on this day in jazz, Dizzy Gillespie', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1800, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(322, 'On this day in jazz (February 16)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-february-16', '', '<p>On this day in 1958,   saxophonist <a href="http://www.stangetz.net/" target="_blank">Stan Getz</a> and trumpeter <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chet_Baker" target="_blank">Chet Baker</a> recorded <em>Stan Meets Chet</em> in Chicago. The album consists of four tracks with one being a medley of three songs. The rhythm section supporting the artists were Jodie Christian at the piano,   Victor Sproles on bass, and Marshall Thompson playing the drums. The work is non-essential to your collection, but as a big fan of Stan and (to a lesser extent) Chet, I thought I would point it out.</p>\n<p>Although the two men recorded several times with each other, Scott Yanow of allmusic.com notes that the two didn''t particularly like each other; however, due to the similarities in their west coast cool jazz styles, their sound together still works musically. In most (maybe all) of their recordings, I think it is pretty clear that Stan was the stronger musician by far. Check out my blog for many more entries for both of these two men. You can also find a fine biography of Stan on <a href="http://www.audible.com/pd/Bios-Memoirs/Stan-Getz-Audiobook/B0093671PY/ref=a_search_c4_1_1_srTtl?qid=1422910081&sr=1-1" target="_blank">audible.com</a>.</p>\n<p>Here''s the two playing "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ygjNVggmL38" target="_blank">Autumn in New York/Embraceable You/What''s New?</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ygjNVggmL38" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/GetzBakerSandvika1983.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I''ll Remember April" (Gene de Paul, Patricia Johnston, Don Raye) - 12:24</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Autumn in New York/Embraceable You/What''s New?" (Vernon Duke/George Gershwin, Ira Gershwin/Bob Haggart, Johnny Burke) - 14:34</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Jordu" (Duke Jordan) - 8:31</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Half-Breed Apache" (Ray Noble) - 14:49</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 60, '2015-02-02 20:49:29', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:40:41', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-02-16 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 14, 'on this day in jazz, Stan Getz, Chet Baker.', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1831, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(323, 'On this day in jazz (February 17)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-february-17', '', '<p>On this day in 1956,   trumpeter <a href="http://cliffordbrown.net/" target="_blank">Clifford Brown</a> and drummer <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/max-roach-mn0000396372/biography" target="_blank">Max Roach</a> completed recording their album <em>Clifford Brown and Max Roach at Basin Street</em>. This album was Clifford''s penultimate one--he would tragically die in an automobile accident four months after this work was recorded. Supporting the two giants on this album was another giant, <a href="http://sonnyrollins.com/" target="_blank">Sonny Rollins</a>, on saxophone as well as Richie Powell on piano and celesta and George Morrow on bass.</p>\n<p>A couple of notes that make this album important:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">this was the only album of Brownie and Max''s that Sonny would play on</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">it''s part of Scott Yanow''s 17 Essential Hard Bop recordings</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p></p>\n<p>Here''s the full list of Scott Yanow''s EHBRs: Miles Davis, Vol. 1 (Blue Note); Clifford Brown/Max Roach, At Basin Street (EmArcy); Sonny Rollins, ANight at the Village Vanguard (Blue Note); Horace Silver, And the Jazz Messengers (Blue Note); Art Blakey, Moanin'' (Blue Note); Art Farmer/Benny Golson, Meet the Jazztet (Chess); Jackie McLean, Bluesnik (Blue Note); Hank Mobley, Workout (Blue Note); Freddie Hubbard, Ready for Freddie (Blue Note); Donald Byrd, Chant (Blue Note); Wes Montgomery, Full House (Original Jazz Classics); Lee Morgan, The Sidewinder (Blue Note); Joe Henderson, Page One (Blue Note); Grant Green, Idle Moments (Blue Note); Cannonball Adderley, Dizzy''s Business (Milestone); Horace Silver, Song for My Father (Blue Note); Art Blakey, Straight Ahead (Concord Jazz).</p>\n<p>Here''s Clifford, Max and Sonny with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Gb_uG7dSGcs" target="_blank">What Is This Thing Called Love?</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Gb_uG7dSGcs" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/brown02.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"What Is This Thing Called Love?" (Cole Porter)  7:33</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Love Is a Many-Splendored Thing" (Sammy Fain, Paul Francis Webster)  4:46</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"I''ll Remember April" (Gene de Paul, Patricia Johnston, Don Raye)  9:15</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Step Lightly (Junior''s Arrival)" (Benny Golson)  3:33</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Powell''s Prances" (Richie Powell)  3:29</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Time" (Richie Powell)  5:06</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Scene Is Clean" (Tadd Dameron, arr. Dameron)  6:06</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 60, '2015-02-02 21:13:27', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:41:05', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-02-17 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 13, 'on this day in jazz, Clifford Brown, Max Roach, Sonny Rollins', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1730, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(324, 'On this day in jazz (February 18)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-february-18', '', '<p>On this day in 1969,   the great <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a> recorded the studio album <em>In a Silent Way</em> in New York City. Wikipedia denotes the genre as both "Jazz Fusion" and "Space Music". Most critics regard this album as Miles'' first foray in the fusion genre and despite the fact that hardly anybody knew how to regard the music when it was released,   over time it has become one of his more important contributions to music. In fact,   in 2001 it was re-released in a 3 disc boxed set where you can hear not only additional songs not included on the album but also the unedited recordings of the songs that made it to the album.</p>\n<p>The musicians that supported Miles on the work were quite strong and included the following:<span style="line-height: 1.3em;"><a href="http://www.wayneshorter.com/" target="_blank">Wayne Shorter</a> on the soprano saxophone, </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;"><a href="http://www.johnmclaughlin.com/" target="_blank">John McLaughlin</a> on the electric guitar, the great </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;"><a href="http://chickcorea.com/" target="_blank">Chick Corea</a> and <a href="http://www.herbiehancock.com/home.php" target="_blank">Herbie Hancock</a> playing the electric pianos, the wonderful </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joe_Zawinul" target="_blank">Joe Zawinul</a> at the organ, </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Dave Holland on bass and </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tony_Williams_(drummer)" target="_blank">Tony Williams</a> on the drums.</span></p>\n<p>Here''s Miles Davis with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MMINC9EOZME" target="_blank">In a Silent Way</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MMINC9EOZME" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/BIO_Bio-Shorts_0_Miles-Davis.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Shhh"/"Peaceful" (Miles Davis)  18:16</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"In a Silent Way"/"It''s About That Time" (Joe Zawinul, Miles Davis)  19:52</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 60, '2015-02-02 21:59:01', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:41:31', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-02-18 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 12, 'on this day in jazz, Miles Davis', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1711, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(325, 'On this day in jazz (February 19)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-february-19', '', '<p>On this day in 1954,   trumpeter <a href="http://www.maynardferguson.com/" target="_blank">Maynard Ferguson</a> began recording the studio album <em>Dimensions</em> in Los Angeles. The album doesn''t garner extremely high ratings from the various music rating services, it''s really not too shabby and features alto saxophonist Bud Shank (playing alto and flute), bassists <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Curtis_Counce" target="_blank">Curtis Counce</a> and <a href="http://www.redmitchell.com/redm/biography" target="_blank">Red Mitchell</a> as well as<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shelly_Manne" target="_blank">Shelly Manne</a> on the drums.</p>\n<p>Maynard is known for playing in very high registers (technically the extreme upper register) while maintaining a rich and full tone. He is credited for two important musical inventions: the ''Firebird'' (sort of a left-handed trumpet where the valves are played with the left hand) and the ''Superbone''(a trombone like instrument played with the right hand). Also of note, he was inducted into the <em>Down Beat</em> magazine Jazz Hall of Fame in 1992, and, if you are ever in Sherman, TX, you''ll find an extensive collection of Fergusonian memorabilia at the Sherman Jazz Museum.</p>\n<p>Here''s Maynard with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iyk10ZiCeNM" target="_blank">Maiden Voyage</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iyk10ZiCeNM" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/6a00e008dca1f0883401774427cbe3970d-500wi.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Egad, Martha" (Bill Holman) - 3:50</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Breakfast Dance" (Holman) - 4:00</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Maiden Voyage" (Willie Maiden) - 2:56</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Thou Swell" (Richard Rodgers Lorenz Hart) - 2:50</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Way You Look Tonight" (Dorothy Fields, Jerome Kern) - 2:50</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"All God''s Children Got Rhythm" (Bronislaw Kaper, Walter Jurmann, Gus Kahn) - 2:49</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Slow Stroll" (Holman) - 2:40</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Wonder Why" (Nicholas Brodzsky, Sammy Cahn) - 3:27</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Willie Nillie" (Maiden) - 2:41</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Hymm to Her" (Maiden) - 2:14</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Lonely Town" (Betty Comden, Adolph Green, Leonard Bernstein) - 2:56</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Somewhere Over the Rainbow" (Yip Harburg, Harold Arlen) - 3:00</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 60, '2015-02-05 00:26:49', 62, '', '2016-08-20 01:12:01', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-02-19 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 11, 'on this day in jazz, Maynard Ferguson', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1887, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(326, 'On this day in jazz (February 20)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-february-20', '', '<p>On this day in 1964,   the great <a href="http://www.artblakey.com/" target="_blank">Art Blakey</a> recorded the album <em>Kyoto</em> in New York. Joining Art on the work are <a href="http://www.freddiehubbardmusic.com/" target="_blank">Freddie Hubbard</a> on the trumpet,   <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Curtis_Fuller" target="_blank">Curtis Fuller</a> on trombone, <a href="http://www.wayneshorter.com/" target="_blank">Wayne Shorter</a> on tenor saxophone, <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/cedar-walton-mn0000741325/biography" target="_blank">Cedar Walton</a> on piano and Reggie Workman on bass. The album is listed, of course, under the band name "Art Blakey and the Jazz Messengers".</p>\n<p>Check out the rest of my site for more on <a href="index.php?searchword=art+blakey&ordering=&searchphrase=all&Itemid=1&option=com_search" target="_self">Art Blakey</a>.</p>\n<p>Here''s Art with Curtis Fuller''s "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TQGalG2bNQ8" target="_blank">The High Priest</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TQGalG2bNQ8" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Kyoto_(album).jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The High Priest" (Curtis Fuller) - 5:55</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Never Never Land" (Betty Comden, Adolph Green, Jule Styne) - 5:50</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Wellington''s Blues" (Art Blakey) - 5:03</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Nihon Bashi" (Sadao Watanabe) - 8:30</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Kyoto" (Freddie Hubbard) - 7:03</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 60, '2015-02-05 00:36:48', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:42:14', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-02-20 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 10, 'on this day in jazz, Art Blakey', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2034, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(327, 'On this day in jazz (February 21)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-february-21', '', '<p>On this day in 1954,   <a href="http://www.artblakey.com/" target="_blank">Art Blakey</a> recorded <em>A Night at Birdland</em>. The recording is available on two volumes (volume 1 was released in July 1954 and volume 2 followed in October) and features Art at the drums, the great <a href="http://cliffordbrown.net/" target="_blank">Clifford Brown</a> on trumpet, Lou Donaldson on the alto saxophone, Curley Russell on bass and the wonderful <a href="http://www.horacesilver.com/" target="_blank">Horace Silver</a> at the piano. The album is part of <em>The Penguin Guide to Jazz</em>''s Core Collection and received a four star rating from allmusic.com.</p>\n<p>If you''re not a huge jazz fan, you''ve still probably heard at least a few seconds of the work. When the rap band US3 recorded their debut album in 1992, they extensively sampled the Blue Note catalog and had a hit with the song "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JwBjhBL9G6U" target="_blank">Flip Fantasia</a>" (US #9) which begins with Pee Wee Marquette''s introduction to the recording of A Night at Birdland (volume 1).</p>\n<p>Here''s Art with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YUIQpgviWlQ" target="_blank">Split Kick</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YUIQpgviWlQ" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/81CQmVEy49L._SL1300_.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 60, '2015-02-08 16:24:59', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:42:33', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-02-21 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 9, 'on this day in jazz, Art Blakey', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1956, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(328, 'On this day in jazz (February 22)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-february-22', '', '<p>On this day in 1957,   the great <a href="http://www.artblakey.com/" target="_blank">Art Blakey</a> finished the recording of the studio album <em>Drum Suite</em> with his band The Jazz Messengers. The recording was made in two sessions,   with the first being on December 13 the preceding year. The first three songs from the album were the last to be recorded, the last three were the first. The personnel for the recording on this day were Art Blakey on the drums, Ray Bryant at the piano,<span style="line-height: 1.3em;"><a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/oscar-pettiford-mn0000896298/biography" target="_blank">Oscar Pettiford</a> on both bass and cello, Jo Jones on drums, Charles "Specs" Wright on drums, timpani and gong, and both Candido Camero and Sabu Martinez on the bongos. Yes, there was a lot of percussion. And yes, I realize that I''ve profiled Art for the past three days.</span></p>\n<p>Steve Leggitt said this of the work, which I quote:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">Drum Suite is a wonderful hybrid of African, Latin, and hard bop rhythms that prefigures the concept of Afro-beat by at least a decade, and the sheer energy, not to mention its very special and fresh-sounding intimacy, make it especially astounding. Even more amazing is that the three parts of the suite -- Blakey''s "The Sacrifice," Ray Bryant''s "Cubano Chant," and Oscar Pettiford''s "Oscalypso" -- were recorded straight through live, and were only intended to be a pre-take run-through, but as is obvious here, Blakey and company nailed the whole thing right out of the box.</p>\n<p>Here''s Art with the "<a href="http://iisaphd.subsonic.org/share/cvkVA" target="_blank">Drum Suite</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="http://iisaphd.subsonic.org/share/cvkVA" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/7cda558f9d604506b33beecdbea9f.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing: </span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Sacrifice" (Art Blakey) - 5:16</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Cubano Chant" (Ray Bryant) - 4:01</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Oscalypso" (Oscar Pettiford) - 8:48</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Nica''s Tempo" (Gigi Gryce) - 8:24</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"D''s Dilemma" (Mal Waldron) - 8:32</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Just for Marty" (Bill Hardman) - 5:56</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 60, '2015-02-08 17:18:22', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:42:51', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-02-22 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 8, 'on this day in jazz, Art Blakey', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1777, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(329, 'On this day in jazz (February 23)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-february-23', '', '<p>On this day in 1955,   <a href="http://cliffordbrown.net/" target="_blank">Clifford Brown</a> and <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/max-roach-mn0000396372/biography" target="_blank">Max Roach</a> began recording <em>Study in Brown</em> in New York City for EmArcy records. Assisting Clifford on the trumpet and Max on the drums were <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harold_Land" target="_blank">Harold Land</a> on tenor saxophone,   Richie Powell on piano and George Morrow on bass.</p>\n<p>Clifford, who would have probably rivaled <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a> as the most important jazz trumpeter in history, died a year after this album was recorded. On this work you''ll hear some great interpretations of standards like "Cherokee" and "Take the ''A'' Train", but you also get four originals by Clifford: "Swingin''", "George''s Dilemma", "Sandu" and "A Gerkin for Perkin". This one definitely should be part of anyone''s core collection.</p>\n<p>Here''s Clifford and Max with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lcKQ3wGI8ZQ" target="_blank">Sandu</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lcKQ3wGI8ZQ" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/348713.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Cherokee" (Ray Noble) - 5:44</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Jacqui" (Richie Powell) - 5:11</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Swingin''" (Clifford Brown) - 2:52</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Lands End" (Harold Land) - 4:56</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"George''s Dilemma" (Brown) - 5:36</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Sandu" (Brown) - 4:56</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Gerkin for Perkin" (Brown) - 2:56</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"If I Love Again" (Jack Murray and Ben Oakland) - 3:24</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Take the ''A'' Train" (Billy Strayhorn) - 4:18</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 60, '2015-02-08 17:43:18', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:43:09', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-02-23 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 7, 'on this day in jazz, Clifford Brown, Max Roach', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1813, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(330, 'On this day in jazz (February 24)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-february-24', '', '<p>On this day in 1973,   pianist <a href="http://www.keithjarrett.org/" target="_blank">Keith Jarrett</a> recorded the live album <em>Fort Yawuh</em> at the <a href="http://www.villagevanguard.com/" target="_blank">Village Vanguard</a> in New York.<span style="line-height: 1.3em;">If you''ve been following my blog,   you''ll know that Keith is one of my most </span>favorite<span style="line-height: 1.3em;"> jazz pianists and was accomplished not only in the jazz genre but also in the classical music genre as well. Keith Jarrett plays the piano and the soprano saxophone (and tambourine) on this work. He was joined by Dewey Redman on the tenor saxophone,   <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Piccolo_oboe" target="_blank">musette</a> and maracas, the great <a href="http://www.charliehadenmusic.com/" target="_blank">Charlie Haden</a> on bass, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Motian" target="_blank">Paul Motian</a> on drums and percussion and Danny Johnson on additional percussion.</span></p>\n<p>Although this album is quite different in sound than many of my favorite Keith Jarrett recordings, I still find it very satisfying hearing the both the breadth and depth that Keith could play with. Be sure to search my blog for more by <a href="index.php?searchword=keith+jarrett&ordering=&searchphrase=all&Itemid=1&option=com_search" target="_blank">Keith</a>.</p>\n<p>Here''s Keith Jarrett with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7n9mDZnKH6I" target="_blank">De Drums</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7n9mDZnKH6I" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/koln-concert.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"(If the) Misfits (Wear It)" - 13:15</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Fort Yawuh" - 18:22</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"De Drums" - 12:10</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Still Life, Still Life" - 8:38</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Roads Traveled, Roads Veiled" - 20:36</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 60, '2015-02-08 18:05:33', 62, '', '2016-08-20 18:20:38', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-02-24 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 6, 'on this day in jazz, Keith Jarrett', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1872, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(331, 'On this day in jazz (February 25)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-february-25', '', '<p>On this day in 1964,   avant garde jazz musician <a href="http://www.ericdolphy.net/" target="_blank">Eric Dolphy</a> recorded <em>Out to Lunch</em> which was his only recording (as a leader) for Blue Note Records. Eric Dolphy plays bass clarinet, flute and alto saxophone on this work and is joined by the great <a href="http://www.freddiehubbardmusic.com/" target="_blank">Freddie Hubbard</a> on trumpet, the awesome <a href="http://www.bluenote.com/artists/bobby-hutcherson" target="_blank">Bobby Hutcherson</a> on vibraphone, Richard Davis on bass and an eighteen year old <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tony_Williams_(drummer)" target="_blank">Tony Williams</a> (credited as Anthony Williams) on the drums. What an incredible line-up! For a great review of the album, go to <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/album/out-to-lunch-mw0000241418" target="_blank">allmusic.com</a>.</p>\n<p>Here''s Eric with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tCfWOWIA0Iw" target="_blank">Hat and Beard</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tCfWOWIA0Iw" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/71RUuKQQREL._SL1300_.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Hat and Beard"  8:24</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Something Sweet, Something Tender"  6:02</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Gazzelloni"  7:22</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Out to Lunch"  12:06</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Straight Up and Down"  8:19</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 60, '2015-02-08 18:30:59', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:44:00', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-02-25 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 5, 'on this day in jazz, Eric Dolphy', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1830, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(332, 'On this day in jazz (February 26)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-february-26', '', '<p>On this day in 1975,   pianist <a href="http://www.andrewhilljazz.com/" target="_blank">Andrew Hill</a> recorded the album <em>Blue Back</em>. Jimmy Vass joined Andrew on the flute,   soprano and alto saxophones, Chris White played the bass and Leroy Williams was on the drums. The album consists of five original Andrew Hill compositions called "challenging" by Ken Dryden of allmusic.com. Playing originals was not at all unusual for Andrew. Whereas others jazz musicians of the day were heavily into playing standards and covers, Andrew had to create his own compositions in order to express himself musically.</p>\n<p>Personally, I prefer Andrews earlier works from the sixties: So In Love (1960), Andrew! (1964) and Judgement! (1964); however, this one''s not too bad, so check it out.</p>\n<p>Here''s Andrew with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tpjo9q9BVaI" target="_blank">Blue Black</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tpjo9q9BVaI" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/pianist-andrew-hill-during-the-recording-session-for-his-judgement-album-1964-francis-wolff.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Golden Spook" - 10:33</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Mist Flower" - 7:28</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Remnants" - 5:58</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Blue Black" - 7:18</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"One For" - 5:45</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 60, '2015-02-12 00:10:36', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:44:15', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-02-26 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 4, 'on this day in jazz, Andrew Hill', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2017, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(333, 'On this day in jazz (February 27)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-february-27', '', '<p>On this day in 1974,   pianist <a href="http://www.keithjarrett.org/" target="_blank">Keith Jarrett</a> began recording the studio album <em>Treasure Island</em> at Generation Sound Studios in New York City. All of the compositions (like yesterday''s blog highlight <a href="index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=332:on-this-day-in-jazz-february-26&catid=60:february&Itemid=41" target="_self">Andrew Hill''s Blue Black</a>) were written by the pianist himself. Keith was assisted on the album by a very strong cast including Dewey Redman on tenor saxophone (and tambourine),   the great <a href="http://www.charliehadenmusic.com/" target="_blank">Charlie Haden</a> on bass,   <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Motian" target="_blank">Paul Motian</a> on the drums, Danny Johnson and Guilherme Franco with percussion and Sam Brown on the guitar. Well known jazz critic, Thom Jurek, gives the album 4.5 stars at allmusic.com.</p>\n<p>1974 and 1975 were incredible years for Keith--you should take a listen to this album, <em>Death and the Flower</em> and <em><a href="index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=299:on-this-day-in-jazz-january-24&catid=59:january&Itemid=41" target="_self">The Kln Concert</a></em> (just to name a few) to understand just how incredible this man''s skill is at the piano.<span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Also of note, Keith Jarrett is the only artist to ever be the sole receipient of the <a href="http://www.polarmusicprize.org/" target="_blank">Polar Music Prize</a>--not even Paul McCartney, Elton John, Bruce Springsteen, Ray Chales, Stevie Wonder, Bob Dylan, B. B. King, Led Zeppelin, Sonny Rollins or Pink Floyd can claim that honor. </span></p>\n<p>Here''s Keith with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=N7_9KvB8IVw" target="_blank">The Rich and the Poor</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=N7_9KvB8IVw" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Keith-Jarrett-feat.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"The Rich (And the Poor)" - 9:24</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Blue Streak" - 2:35</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Fullsuvollivus (Fools of All of Us)" - 6:29</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Treasure Island" - 4:14</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Introduction/Yaqui Indian Folk Song" (Jarrett/Traditional) - 2:16</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Le Mistral" - 9:25</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Angles (Without Edges)" - 5:24</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Sister Fortune" - 4:27</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 60, '2015-02-12 00:30:24', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:44:39', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-02-27 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 3, 'on this day in jazz, Keith Jarrett', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2002, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(335, 'On this day in jazz (March 01)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-march-01', '', '<p>On this day in 1961,   <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oliver_Nelson" target="_blank">Oliver Nelson</a> and <a href="http://www.ericdolphy.net/" target="_blank">Eric Dolphy</a> recorded the album <em>Straight Ahead</em> at Rudy Van Gelder''s studio in Englewood Cliffs, NJ. On the work, Oliver plays alto and tenor saxes and the clarinet, Eric plays alto sax, bass clarinet and flute, and they were assisted by a rhythm section consisting of Richard Wyans on piano, George Duvivier on bass, and Roy Haynes on the drums.</p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Straight Ahead was the last appearance of Dolphy on a Nelson album following a series of collaborations recorded for Prestige. Author Joe Goldberg said this of the session: </span></p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">The session was scheduled for one in the afternoon and I arrived at 3:30, thinking that by then the music would have been rehearsed and the men would be starting to play. What I found was a studio empty of everyone but A&R man Esmond Edwards", the supervisor, "and engineer Rudy Van Gelder, who were packing up to leave and looking very satisfied.</p>\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">That is, all six songs were recorded in only one take each. allmusic.com gives the album a four and a half star rating. It should be noted that the album was remastered in 1989, so if you get that version you''ll have a really great sound. Check it out as it has some great, extended duets by Eric and Oliver.</span></p>\n<p>Here''s Oliver and Eric with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pgD0zagf3QE" target="_blank">Six and Four</a>"</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pgD0zagf3QE" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/220px-Straight_ahead.jpeg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Images" - 5:43</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Six and Four" - 7:15</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Mama Lou" - 5:04</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Ralph''s New Blues" (Milt Jackson) - 9:52</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"Straight Ahead" - 5:31</span></li>\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">"111-44" - 3:28</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 61, '2015-02-16 18:04:59', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:46:13', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-03-01 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 31, 'on this day in jazz, Oliver Nelson, Eric Dolphy', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1659, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(336, 'On this day in jazz (March 02)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-march-02', '', '<p>On this day in 1959,   <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a> began recording what would become the most important jazz album of all time,   <em>Kind of Blue</em>. Miles was joined by an all-star cast with <a href="http://www.johncoltrane.com/" target="_blank">John Coltrane</a> on the tenor saxophone,   <a href="http://www.cannonball-adderley.com/" target="_blank">Cannonball Adderley</a> on the alto sax, <a href="http://www.billevanswebpages.com/" target="_blank">Bill Evans</a> (all songs but "Freddy Freeloader") and <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/wynton-kelly-mn0000684253/biography" target="_blank">Wynton Kelly</a> ("Freddy Freeloader") at the piano, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Chambers" target="_blank">Paul Chambers</a> on the bass, and <a href="http://www.jimmycobb.net/" target="_blank">Jimmy Cobb</a> on the drums. On this day, the songs that would become side 1 of the album were recorded: "So What", "Freddie Freeloader" and "Blue in Green".</p>\n<p>The importance of this album on the music world cannot be understated and it''s why the album is usually at the #1 spot on most jazz enthusiasts charts. In fact, it''s probably the reason I eventually was moved to create this blog. You can find the album in mono, stereo, SACD format, and DVD audio. On some of the legacy editions they''ve even included the banter between Miles and the engineers and musicians--which is quite interesting to hear. On December 16, 2009, the United States House of Representatives passed a resolution which honored the albums 50th anniversary, "reaffirming jazz as a national treasure". If you want to learn more about the album, check out Ashley Khan''s <em><a href="http://www.amazon.com/Kind-Blue-Making-Miles-Masterpiece/dp/0306815583/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&ie=UTF8&qid=1424110432&sr=1-1&keywords=kind+of+blue" target="_blank">Kind of Blue: The Making of the Miles Davis Masterpiece</a></em><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">. It''s well written and is full of wonderful photographs and has some hilarious anecdotes. And, if you like the book, you can check out some of Ashley''s other works, too.</span></p>\n<p>Here''s Miles with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ylXk1LBvIqU" target="_blank">So What</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ylXk1LBvIqU" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/milesdavis3.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 61, '2015-02-16 18:28:27', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:46:30', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-03-02 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 3, 0, 30, 'on this day in jazz, Miles Davis', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1695, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(337, 'On this day in jazz (March 03)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-march-03', '', '<p>On this day in 1972,   the great <a href="http://www.stangetz.net/" target="_blank">Stan Getz</a> recorded one of his greatest albums,   <em>Captain Marvel</em>. He was joined by a very accomplished rhythm section of <a href="http://chickcorea.com/" target="_blank">Chick Corea</a> on piano,   Stanley Clarke on bass, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tony_Williams_(drummer)" target="_blank">Tony Williams</a> on drums and Brazilian master percussionist Airto Moreira. If you like latin jazz, but have never really gotten into the fusion genre that <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a> started in the late 1960s, give this one a listen--it will give you a different view of fusion. That is, while this is definitely a Stan Getz album, all of the songs except for Billy Strayhorn''s "Lush Life" were written by Chick, and all of the musicians (aside from Airto) had experience playing with Miles Davis'' fusion groups, so they were already accomplished in this genre (in fact Stanley was Chick''s regular bassist in Chick''s band Return to Forever).</p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">allmusic.com gave the album a 4.5 star rating and said this of it: "Along with Sweet Rain recorded for Verve, Captain Marvel is the finest recording Getz made in the 1970s." I agree. </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">If you want to see Captain Marvel live, here''s a <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=n7oo8EopEJ0" target="_blank">link</a> to a 1972 Montreaux recording with Stan rocking an awesome white track suit. If you want to know what Chick''s up to these days, check him out on <a href="https://www.facebook.com/chickcorea" target="_blank">facebook</a> (here''s a spoiler: Chick and Herbie Hancock are touring together during the spring of 2015--however, if you don''t already have tickets, many of the shows are already sold out).</span></p>\n<p>Here''s Stan and Chick with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cFuPGlCVhL0" target="_blank">La Fiesta</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cFuPGlCVhL0" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/albumcoverStanGetz-CaptainMarvel.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"La Fiesta"  8:21</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Five Hundred Miles High"  8:09</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Captain Marvel" - 5:06</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Times Lie"  9:46</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Lush Life" (Billy Strayhorn)  2:26</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Day Waves"  9:39</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 61, '2015-02-21 20:04:55', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:47:10', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-03-03 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 29, 'on this day in jazz, Stan Getz, Chick Corea', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1544, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(338, 'On this day in jazz (March 04)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-march-04', '', '<p>On this day in 1974,   composer/conductor/saxophonist <a href="http://www.rivbea.com/" target="_blank">Sam Rivers</a> recorded the gargantuan Crystals at Generation Sound Studios in New York City. The reason why it is gargantuan is because it is performed by a total of 64 musicians. Just a few of them include: Joe Ferguson on alto, tenor and soprano saxophones, flute; Paul Jeffrey on tenor saxophone, flute, clarinet, oboe, bassett horn and bassoon; Roland Alexander on soprano and tenor saxophones, and flute; Fred Kelly on soprano and baritone saxophone and flute; Ronnie Boykins on bass; Sinclair Acey, Ted Daniel and Richard Williams on trumpets; Charles Stephens and Charles Majeed Greenlee on trombones; Joseph Daley on trombone and tuba; Gregory Maker on acoustic and electric bass violins; Warren Smith and Harold Smith on drums and percussion (each).</p>\n<p>Jazz writer Thom Jurek said, "It''s difficult to note in the 21st century just how forward-thinking this avant-garde big band was, and how completely innovative Rivers'' compositions are." I totally agree. While avant-garde has never been my favorite jazz genre, this work is definitely worth listening to. You can even listen to it in quadraphonic format, if that''s your thing.</p>\n<p>Here''s Sam with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sK6wBT2Fi4Y" target="_blank">Tranquility</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sK6wBT2Fi4Y" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/SRMosaic.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Exultation" on 8:25</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Tranquility" on 8:58</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Postlude" on 2:31</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Bursts" on 6:51</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Orb" on 9:36</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Earth Song" on 4:09</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 61, '2015-02-21 20:24:36', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:47:31', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-03-04 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 28, 'On this day in jazz, Sam Rivers', 'On this day in jazz', 0, 1503, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(339, 'On this day in jazz (March 05)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-march-05', '', '<p>On this day 1949,   the great <a href="http://www.cmgww.com/music/parker/home.html" target="_blank">Charlie Parker</a> performed live at the Royal Roost. Specifically,   the following songs were recorded: "Scrapple from the Apple",   "Barbados" and "Salt Peanuts". These recordings are available on Savoy''s <em>The Complete Live Performances on Savoy</em> which cover recordings at the Royal Roost in 1948 and 1949, Carnegie Hall in 1947 and Chicago in 1950. On the recording, Charlie is joined by several jazz giants including: <a href="http://www.kennydorham.net/biography/" target="_blank">Kenny Dorham</a> on the trumpet, <a href="http://www.jazzinchicago.org/educates/journal/articles/my-time-al-haig" target="_blank">Al Haig</a> at the piano, Tommy Potter on bass and <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/max-roach-mn0000396372/biography" target="_blank">Max Roach</a> on the drums.</p>\n<p>As I''ve said before, hearing Charlie live is the best way to hear him, and this collection is a fine place to start.</p>\n<p>Here''s Charlie with "<a href="http://iisaphd.subsonic.org/share/xSKeU" target="_blank">Scrapple From the Apple</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="http://iisaphd.subsonic.org/share/xSKeU" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Charlie-Parker-Sampler---The-Com-156552.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 61, '2015-02-24 02:50:49', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:47:49', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-03-05 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 27, 'on this day in jazz, Charlie Parker', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1622, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(340, 'On this day in jazz (March 06)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-march-06', '', '<p>On this day in 1968,   <a href="http://www.herbiehancock.com/home.php" target="_blank">Herbie Hancock</a> began recording the studio album <em>Speak Like a Child</em>. Herbie is assisted by a fine set of musicians including: <a href="http://roncarter.net/JazzMaster/" target="_blank">Ron Carter</a> on bass,   Mickey Roker on drums,   Jerry Dodgion on alto flute, Thad Jones on flugelhorn and Peter Phillips on bass trombone. The album was recorded by engineer extraordinaire, Rudy van Gelder at his studio in Englewood Cliffs, NJ. This was Herbie''s first studio album as a leader since 1965''s classic <em>Maiden Voyage</em> (he did record a soundtrack in 1966: for Michelangelo Antonioni''s film <em><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blowup" target="_blank">Blow-Up</a></em>).</p>\n<p>Herbie said this of the work:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">This album is an extension of <em>Maiden Voyage</em> in terms of use of simple, singable melodies. I''ve been trying for a long time to work on swinging, and of all the albums I''ve done, this to me swings the most. [...] What''s different in <em>Speak Like a Child</em> as a whole has to do, first, with harmony. For the most part, the harmonies in these numbers are freer in the sense that they''re not so easily identifiable chordally in the conventional way. I''m more concerned with sounds than chords, and so I voice the harmonies to provide a wider spectrum of colors that can be contained within the traditional chord progression. [...] Similarly, in those tracks with the horns, I was more interested in sounds than in definite chord patterns. I tried to give the horns notes that would give color and body to the sounds I heard as I wrote.</p>\n<p>Here''s Herbie with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lTNLWi-xAkE" target="_blank">Speak Like a Child</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lTNLWi-xAkE" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Herbie_Hancock_-_Speak_Like_a_Child.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Riot"  4:40</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Speak Like a Child"  7:50</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"First Trip" (Ron Carter)  6:01</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Toys"  5:52</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Goodbye to Childhood"  7:06</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Sorcerer"  5:36</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 61, '2015-02-25 00:45:56', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:48:06', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-03-06 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 26, 'on this day in jazz, Herbie Hancock', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1612, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(341, 'On this day in jazz (March 07)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-march-07', '', '<p>On this day in 1957,   pianist <a href="http://moseallison.com/" target="_blank">Mose Allison</a> recorded his debut album <em>Back Country Suite</em> at Rudy van Gelder''s studio in Hackensack,   NJ. Taylor LaFargue played bass and Frank Isola played the drums. The suite is about eighteen minutes long and is composed of ten short movements. Also included on the album are covers such as "Blueberry Hill" and "I Thought About You".</p>\n<p>There are a couple of degrees of separation between today''s and yesterday''s profiled artists--in a most unusual way. Yesterday,   I mentioned that <a href="http://www.herbiehancock.com/home.php" target="_blank">Herbie Hancock</a>''s previous album was the sound track to Michelangelo Antonioni''s movie Blow-up. In that movie, Jeff Beck and Jimmy Page make cameos playing in one of the scenes. In that scene Beck smashes his guitar ala Pete Townshed of The Who....Then, on February 14, 1970, The Who would record the fourth song on this album, "Blues", for their live album "Live at Leeds" (along with 32 other songs!).</p>\n<p>Here''s Mose with "<a href="http://iisaphd.subsonic.org/share/Hltjn" target="_blank">Blues</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="http://iisaphd.subsonic.org/share/Hltjn" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/mose-allison-e1266153036425.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Back Country Suite: New Ground" - 2:05</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Back Country Suite: Train" - 1:50</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Back Country Suite: Warm Night" - 1:47</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Back Country Suite: Blues" - 1:28</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Back Country Suite: Saturday" - 1:24</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Back Country Suite: Scamper" - 2:15</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Back Country Suite: January" - 1:38</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Back Country Suite: Promised Land" - 2:03</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Back Country Suite: Spring Song" - 1:23</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Back Country Suite: Highway 49" - 1:39</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Blueberry Hill" (Al Lewis, Vincent Rose, Larry Stock) - 3:00</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"You Won''t Let Me Go" (Buddy Johnson) - 3:46</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"I Thought About You" (Jimmy Van Heusen, Johnny Mercer) - 3:53</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"One Room Country Shack" (Mercy Dee Walton) - 3:05</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"In Salah" - 3:45</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 61, '2015-02-25 01:05:39', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:48:43', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-03-07 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 25, 'on this day in jazz, Mose Allison', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1542, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(342, 'On this day in jazz (March 08)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-march-08', '', '<p>On this day in 1953,   <a href="http://www.cmgww.com/music/parker/home.html" target="_blank">Charlie Parker</a> was recorded live in concert at the Howard Theater in Washington,   DC (the city which I currently call my work home). The session was composed of Charlie on the alto saxophone, Jack Holiday on the piano, Franklin Skeete on the bass and the great <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/max-roach-mn0000396372/biography" target="_blank">Max Roach</a> on the drums. The songs that were recorded were: "Ornithology", "Out of Nowehere", "Cool Blues" and "Anthropology".</p>\n<p>The picture below is my contribution to the graffiti at <a href="http://chinachilcano.com/" target="_blank">China Chilcano''s</a> men''s room wall. For a better interpretation of "Bird Lives", read <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Don_DeLillo" target="_blank">Don Dellilo''s</a> wonderful book, <em><a href="http://www.newyorker.com/books/page-turner/don-delillos-annotated-underworld" target="_blank">Underworld</a></em>.</p>\n<p>Here''s Charlie with "<a href="http://iisaphd.subsonic.org/share/VBeDx" target="_blank">Cool Blues</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="http://iisaphd.subsonic.org/share/VBeDx" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/524224_10206013887203866_7921066096248691306_n.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 61, '2015-02-26 02:02:27', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:49:02', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-03-08 07:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 24, 'on this day in jazz, Charlie Parker', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1663, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(343, 'On this day in jazz (March 09)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-march-09', '', '<p>On this day in 1958,   the great <a href="http://www.cannonball-adderley.com/" target="_blank">Cannonball Adderley</a> recorded the studio album <em>Somethin'' Else</em> at Rudy van Gelder''s studio in Hackensack,   NJ. This is truly one of the best jazz albums of all time. In fact, if I had a list of my top ten, it might even be as high as number two. The personnel on this work are: Cannonball on the alto saxophone, <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a> on the trumpet, Hank Jones on the piano, Sam Jones on the bass, and <a href="http://www.artblakey.com/" target="_blank">Art Blakey</a> on the drums. Now that <em>is</em> somethin'' else.</p>\n<p>This album definitely belongs in your collection solely due to the great music contained in it; however, it also is important because it is one of the very few times that Miles Davis appeared as a guest on other people''s albums after 1955. <a href="http://jazz100.sffjazz.com/top100.html" target="_blank">sffjazz.com</a> ranks this work at number five on their poll while <em>The Penguin Guide to Jazz</em> puts it in their Core Collection. Essentially every song on the album is now considered a jazz standard including Johnny Mercer''s "Autumn Leaves", Cole Porter''s "Love for Sale", Miles Davis'' "Somethin'' Else" and Nat Adderley''s "One for Daddy-O" (Nat''s wife had recently given birth to their daughter, Alison).</p>\n<p>Here''s Cannonball with the song that starts the album, "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=u37RF5xKNq8" target="_blank">Autumn Leaves</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=u37RF5xKNq8" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/71DZbeuvLiL._SL1300_.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Autumn Leaves" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">(Joseph Kosma, Johnny Mercer, Jacques Prvert)</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">10:55</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Love for Sale" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">(Cole Porter)</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">7:01)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Somethin'' Else" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">(Miles Davis) </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">8:15)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"One for Daddy-O" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">(Nat Adderley) </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">8:26</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Dancing in the Dark" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">(Arthur Schwartz, Howard Dietz) </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">4:07</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 61, '2015-02-28 17:32:55', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:49:28', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-03-09 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 23, 'on this day in jazz, Cannonball Adderley, Miles Davis', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1658, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(344, 'On this day in jazz (March 10)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-march-10', '', '<p>On this day in 1964,  pianist/vocalist <a href="http://moseallison.com/" target="_blank">Mose Allison</a> recorded the studio album <em>The Word from Mose</em>. Assisting Mose were Ben Tucker on bass and Roy Lundberg on the drums. I''ve written about Mose several times on this blog,   so feel free to <a href="index.php?searchword=mose+allison&ordering=&searchphrase=all&Itemid=1&option=com_search" target="_self">search </a>my site for biographical and other musical information.</p>\n<p>This album was the second full-length studio album and is chocked-full of great songs with Moseian satire. Take a listen to "Foolkiller",  "One of These Days", "Days Like This", "Your Red Wagon" and "New Parchman" (not quite as funny as the original "Parchman Farm"). <em>The Penguin Guide to Jazz</em> even includes it in their Core Collection.</p>\n<p>Here''s Mose with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Esxk9VEhJYs" target="_blank">Foolkiller</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Esxk9VEhJYs" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/MI0001849675.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Foolkiller"  2:25</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"One of These Days"  3:02</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Look Here"  2:12</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Days Like This"  2:51</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Your Red Wagon" (DePaul, Jones, Raye)  2:14</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Wild Man" (Everett Barksdale, Stanley Willis)  1:58</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Rollin'' Stone" (Muddy Waters)  2:58</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"New Parchman"  3:04</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Don''t Forget to Smile"  2:48</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"I''m Not Talking"  2:30</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Lost Mind" (Percy Mayfield)  4:08</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 61, '2015-03-03 19:27:04', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:50:01', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-03-10 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 22, 'on this day in jazz, Mose Allison', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1749, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(345, 'On this day in jazz (March 16)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-march-16', '', '<p>On this day in 1965,   drummer <a href="http://www.joyousshout.com/" target="_blank">Chico Hamilton</a> recorded the song "Chic Chic Chico" in Hollywood,   CA. The song would be combined with seven songs recorded on January 4,   1965 and packaged into a studio album entitled <em>Chic Chic Chico</em>. Chico is joined on the track by flautist Charles Lloyd, tenor saxophonist Jimmy Woods, the excellent guitarist Gbor Szab (who also wrote four of the songs), Albert Stinson on bass and Willie Bobo on percussion. allmusic.com says it is "non-essential" but still rates it with four stars.</p>\n<p>For the other seven songs that make up the album, it should be noted that <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harold_Land" target="_blank">Harold Land</a> was on that session providing as always some great wind on the tenor sax.</p>\n<p>Here''s Chico with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VlUzuHw0YUM" target="_blank">Chic Chic Chico</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VlUzuHw0YUM" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/chicchicchico.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Chic Chic Chico" (Manny Albam) - 2:47</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Corrida De Torres" - 5:35</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Tarantula" - 3:03</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"What''s New?" (Bob Haggart, Johnny Burke) - 6:02</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"St. Paddy''s Day Parade" (Chico Hamilton) - 3:09</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Carol''s Walk" (Chico Hamilton) - 6:36</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Swampy" - 2:45</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Fire Works" - 5:52</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 61, '2015-03-03 19:31:31', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:50:28', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-03-16 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 5, 0, 21, 'on this day in jazz, Chico Hamilton', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1432, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(346, 'On this day in jazz (March 11)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-march-11', '', '<p>On this day in 1985,   pianist <a href="http://kennybarron.com/" target="_blank">Kenny Baron</a> recorded <em><a href="http://kennybarron.com/recordings/scratch/" target="_blank">Scratch</a></em> with bassist Dave Holland and drummer Daniel Humair. Enja Records says that this is "one of the finest and most challenging recordings Kenny Barron has ever made". That''s saying a lot. Kenny has recorded with many jazz legends including Barney Kessel,   <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chet_Baker" target="_blank">Chet Baker</a>,   <a href="http://www.dizzygillespie.com/" target="_blank">Dizzy Gillespie</a>, Ella Fitzgerald, <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/jj-johnson-mn0000119111/biography">J.J. Johnson</a>, <a href="http://www.joehendersonsax.com/" target="_blank">Joe Henderson</a>, and <a href="http://www.yuseflateef.com/" target="_blank">Yusef Lateef</a>. Kenny went on to record several more albums on the Enja label after this one--with a quintet setting.</p>\n<p>Here''s Kenny with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QynEbYMT5BQ" target="_blank">Scratch</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QynEbYMT5BQ" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/MI0000492258.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Scratch </span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Quiet Times </span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Water Lillie </span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Song For Abdullah </span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Third Eyes </span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Jacob''s Ladder </span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">And Then Again</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 61, '2015-03-03 19:44:41', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:50:58', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-03-11 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 20, 'on this day in jazz, Kenny Barron', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1858, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(347, 'On this day in jazz (March 12)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-march-12', '', '<p>On this day in 1968,   pianist <a href="http://www.keithjarrett.org/" target="_blank">Keith Jarrett</a> recorded <em>Restoration Ruin</em> for Vortex Records. On the work,   Keith not only plays piano but also guitar,   harmonica, soprano saxophone, recorder, organ, electric bass, drums, tambourine and sistra--I think he may even have been wearing cymbals on his knees. And, he even sings! Quite strange to someone that associates him with jazz and classical piano only. Richie Unterberger reviewed it for allmusic.com and said this: "not a jazz vocal album, either, but a folk-rock one in which he alternates -- quite literally, track to track -- sub-Dylan outings and more folk-Baroque ones that echo the late-''60s work of artists like Love and Tim Buckley".</p>\n<p>If you''re a fan of Keith, it''s worth attempting a listen. If you''re not, then what''s your problem? I mean, if you''re not, you should probably skip this one.</p>\n<p>Make sure to search my site for some of Keith''s must listen performances.</p>\n<p>Here''s Keith with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5k1Jn2UJERc" target="_blank">Restoration Ruin</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5k1Jn2UJERc" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/824368.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Restoration Ruin" - 2:20</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"All Right" - 2:47</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"For You and Me" - 2:40</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Have a Real Time" - 2:51</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Sioux City Sue New" - 2:50</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"You''re Fortunate" - 2:21</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Fire and Rain" - 2:50</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Now He Knows Better" - 2:58</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Wonders" - 4:02</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Where Are You Going?" - 3:53</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 61, '2015-03-03 20:00:34', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:51:16', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-03-12 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 19, 'on this day in jazz, Keith Jarrett', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1709, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(348, 'On this day in jazz (March 13)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-march-13', '', '<p>On this day in 1961,   the great <a href="http://www.cannonball-adderley.com/" target="_blank">Cannonball Adderley</a> completed recording the studio album <em>Know What I Mean?</em> at the Bell Sound Studios in New York City. The recording is an essential one,   featuring an all star cast: Cannonball on the alto saxophone,   <a href="http://www.billevanswebpages.com/" target="_blank">Bill Evans</a> (Cannonball''s partner on Miles Davis'' Kind of Blue) on piano, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Percy_Heath" target="_blank">Percy Heath</a> on bass and <a href="http://www.drummerworld.com/drummers/Connie_Kay.html" target="_blank">Connie Kay</a> on the drums. You might recognize that Percy and Connie were members of the Modern Jazz Quartet (aka MJQ and Milt Jackson Quartet). From the track listing below, the songs recorded on this day were Evans'' standard "Waltz for Debby", <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Lewis_(pianist)" target="_blank">John Lewis</a>'' (also of the MJQ) "Venice", and another Evans song, the title track, "Know What I Mean".</p>\n<p>All the men were in great form during this period of their careers, and I''m sure that you will enjoy this album. This is also one of the last times that you''ll hear Cannonball playing the only wind instrument during a studio recording, so it''s a great chance to hear his virtuosity.</p>\n<p>Here''s Cannonball with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dJqkN1w0fFg" target="_blank">Waltz for Debby</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dJqkN1w0fFg"><img src="images/tdij/knowwhat.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Waltz for Debby" (Bill Evans, Gene Lees)  5:15</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Goodbye" (Gordon Jenkins)  6:15</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Who Cares?" (Take 5) (George Gershwin, Ira Gershwin)  5:57</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Who Cares?" (Take 4)  5:55</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Venice" (John Lewis)  2:55</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Toy" (Clifford Jordan)  5:09</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Elsa" (Earl Zindars)  5:52</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Nancy (With the Laughing Face)" (Phil Silvers, Jimmy Van Heusen)  4:08</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Know What I Mean?" (Re-take 7) (Evans)  4:54</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Know What I Mean?" (Take 12)  7:01</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 61, '2015-03-03 20:05:10', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:51:38', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-03-13 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 18, 'on this day in jazz, Cannonball Adderley', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1859, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(349, 'On this day in jazz (March 14)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-march-14', '', '<p>On this day in 1968,   pianist <a href="http://chickcorea.com/" target="_blank">Chick Corea</a> started recording <em>Now He Sings,   Now He Sobs</em> with bassist Misoslav Vitou and drummer Roy Haynes at A&R Studios in New York City. The original album only contained five songs,   but EMI/Blue Note later acquired it and added several additional tracks for the CD re-release. Of the original five, all are Chick originals, but with the bonus tracks there are also two were standards: "Me and My Only Love" and Thelonious Monk''s "Pannonica". The trio would unite 13 years later to record <em>Trio Music</em> and again five years later to record <em>Trio Music Live</em>.</p>\n<p>Chick is still very active today and in fact on tour with jazz legend Herbie Hancock during the spring of 2015. Go see them live!</p>\n<p>Here''s Chick with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3YyzYMJDm0k" target="_blank">Now He Beats The Drum, Now He Stops</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3YyzYMJDm0k" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Chick-Corea-e1340641581845.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Steps - What Was"</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Matrix"</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Now He Sings, Now He Sobs"</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Now He Beats The Drum, Now He Stops"</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Law Of Falling And Catching Up"</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>\n<p>CD release bonus tracks</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Samba Yantra"</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Bossa"</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"I Don''t Know"</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Fragments"</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Windows"</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Gemini"</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Pannonica" (Thelonious Monk)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"My One and Only Love" (Wood/Mellin)</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 61, '2015-03-03 20:10:12', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:52:05', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-03-14 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 17, 'on this day in jazz, Chick Corea', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1651, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(350, 'On this day in jazz (March 15)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-march-15', '', '<p>On this day in 1957,   tuba player <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ray_Draper" target="_blank">Ray Draper</a> recorded his debut album <em>Tuba Sounds</em> at Rudy van Gelder''s studio in Hackensack,   NJ. The album is important to me due to the fact that trumpeter <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Webster_Young" target="_blank">Webster Young</a> appears on it and wrote two of the songs: "Terry Anne" and "House of Davis". In fact,   the cover includes the words "Introducing Webster Young". Jazz legend <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jackie_McLean" target="_blank">Jackie McLean</a> adds the alto sax and the rhythm section consisted of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mal_Waldron" target="_blank">Mal Waldron</a> on the piano, Spanky DeBrest on bass and Ben Dixon on drums.</p>\n<p>Tuba players don''t often get a lot of press, but Ray is entitled to it. He would follow up this album with his second at the ripe old age of seventeen: <em>The Ray Draper Quartet Featuring John Coltrane</em>. Ray had significant drug issues in the sixties and would only record a handful of albums as a leader; some will argue that he is owed the credit for creating the jazz fusion genre--having predated Miles Davis'' <em>Bitches Brew</em> by a couple of years with his band in the late sixties. The band, after its first performance at Hollywood''s Whisky a Go Go, was offered several record deals and booked at rock venues for the rest of the year, even opening for Jimi Hendrix and Jethro Tull.</p>\n<p>Unfortunately, Ray would turn back to heroin and would only record another couple of times in his lifetime. In 1982, at the age of 42, he was held up by several minors. He gave them his money, but they shot him anyway. He had been clean of drug use at the time of the attack and had an unfinished composition in his attache at the time of his death. Perhaps he was on his way back, but perhaps it would have been the same story over again. So sad.</p>\n<p>Here''s Ray with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wcyEJluUgRs" target="_blank">House of Davis</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wcyEJluUgRs" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/DraperRay_RDfeatJC_crop3.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<div><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></div>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Terry Anne" (Webster Young) - 6:39</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"You''re My Thrill" (Sidney Clare, Jay Gorney) - 6:48</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Pivot" (Mal Waldron) - 5:13</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Jackie''s Dolly" - 4:54</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Mimi''s Interlude" - 8:14</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"House of Davis" (Webster Young) - 5:28</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 61, '2015-03-03 20:10:28', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:52:31', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-03-15 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 16, 'on this day in jazz, Ray Draper', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1662, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(351, 'On this day in jazz (March 17)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-march-17', '', '<p>On this day in 1965,   <a href="http://www.herbiehancock.com/home.php" target="_blank">Herbie Hancock</a> recorded his fifth album, <em>Maiden Voyage </em>at Rudy van Gelder''s studio (produced by Albert Lion) in Englewood Cliffs, NJ. Joining Herbie on the work was an all-star cast including <a href="http://www.freddiehubbardmusic.com/" target="_blank">Freddie Hubbard</a> on trumpet, George Coleman on the tenor saxophone, <a href="http://roncarter.net/JazzMaster/" target="_blank">Ron Carter</a> on the bass and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tony_Williams_(drummer)" target="_blank">Tony Williams</a> on the drums.</p>\n<p>All songs were originals and all are quite good, especially the title track and "The Eye of the Hurricane".</p>\n<p>The album was selected for the Grammy Hall of Fame (in 1999), received a five star rating from allmusic.com (whose Stephen Erlewine said of it: "arguably his finest record of the ''60s, reaching a perfect balance between accessible, lyrical jazz and chance-taking hard bop."), and is part of The Penguin Guide to Jazz''s Core Collection (which said this of the album: "a colossal achievement for a man still just 24 years old").</p>\n<p>Here''s Herbie with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hwmRQ0PBtXU" target="_blank">Maiden Voyage</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hwmRQ0PBtXU" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Maiden_Voyage_(Hancock).jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Maiden Voyage"  7:53</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Eye of the Hurricane"  5:57</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Little One"  8:43</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Survival of the Fittest"  9:59</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Dolphin Dance"  9:16</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 61, '2015-03-09 17:04:33', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:53:01', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-03-17 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 3, 0, 15, 'on this day in jazz, Herbie Hancock', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1622, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(352, 'On this day in jazz (March 18)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-march-18', '', '<p>On this day in 1974,   vibraphonist <a href="http://www.bluenote.com/artists/bobby-hutcherson" target="_blank">Bobby Hutcherson</a> completed recording the studio album <em>Cirrus</em> in Los Angeles, CA for Blue Note Records. All songs on the album are originals except for the first song, "Rosewood", which is a <a href="http://www.woodyshaw.com/" target="_blank">Woody Shaw</a> classic. In fact, Woody plays trumpet on the album along with Emmanuel Boyd and the wonderful <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harold_Land" target="_blank">Harold Land</a> on tenor saxophones and flutes, William Henderson on piano and electric piano, Ray Drummond on bass, Larry Hancock on drums and Kenneth Nash adding additional percussion.</p>\n<p>allmusic.com gives the album a four star rating saying that although this particular Hutcherson / Land pairing isn''t quite as good as some of their earlier collaborations--it''s still pretty good. Personally, I consider Bobby one of the very top vibraphonists of all time, so I''m a little prejudiced when I say, "take a listen".</p>\n<p>Here''s Bobby with: "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9hoqPOw6fzs" target="_blank">Rosewood</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9hoqPOw6fzs" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Bobby_Hutcherson.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Rosewood" (Woody Shaw) - 7:40</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Even Later" - 8:56</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Wrong or Right" - 7:26</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Zuri Dance" - 8:25</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Cirrus" - 7:18</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 61, '2015-03-09 17:11:08', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:53:21', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-03-18 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 14, 'on this day in jazz, Bobby Hutcherson', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1424, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(353, 'On this day in jazz (March 19)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-march-19', '', '<p>On this day in 1963,   <a href="http://www.stangetz.net/" target="_blank">Stan Getz</a> and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jo%C3%A3o_Gilberto" target="_blank">Joo Gilberto</a> completed the recording of their album Getz/Gilberto at A&R Recording Studios in New York City. Even if you''re not a serious jazz fan,   you''ve heard some of the music off this one. It won the following awards:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">1965 Grammy Awards for Best Album of the Year</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">1965 Best Jazz Instrumental Album - Individual or Group </span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">1965 Best Engineered Album, Non-Classical.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p>The lead song, "The Girl from Ipanema", won the award for 1965 Record of the Year. The album was the first jazz album to win Album of the Year and it would be the only won with this distinction until Herbie Hancock won it in 2008 with River: The Joni Letters.</p>\n<p>Here''s Stan andJoo (and Astrud Gilberto) with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UJkxFhFRFDA" target="_blank">The Girl from Ipanema</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UJkxFhFRFDA" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/astrud-gilberto-and-stan-getz---the-girl-from-ipanema---.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Girl from Ipanema" Antnio Carlos Jobim, Vinicius de Moraes, Norman Gimbel (5:24)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Doralice" Dorival Caymmi, Antonio Almeida (2:46)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"P''ra Machucar Meu Corao" Ary Barroso (5:05)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Desafinado" Jobim, Newton Mendona (4:15)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Corcovado" Jobim, Gene Lees (4:16)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"S Dano Samba" Jobim, de Moraes (3:45)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"O Grande Amor" Jobim, de Moraes (5:27)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Vivo Sonhando" Jobim (3:04)</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 61, '2015-03-09 17:18:39', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:54:47', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-03-19 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 13, 'on this day in jazz, Stan Getz, Joo Gilberto', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1547, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(354, 'On this day in jazz (March 20)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-march-20', '', '<p>On this day in 1961,   <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a> completed recording the songs that would comprise the studio album <em>Someday My Prince Will Come</em>. Although the album is not at the top of my favorite Miles Davis albums, it should be listened to for no other reason than for the crew who appeared on it: Miles on trumpet, both <a href="http://www.johncoltrane.com/" target="_blank">John Coltrane</a> and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hank_Mobley" target="_blank">Hank Mobley</a> on tenor saxophone, and <em>Kind of Blue</em>''s rhythm section: <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/wynton-kelly-mn0000684253/biography" target="_blank">Wynton Kelly</a> on piano, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Chambers" target="_blank">Paul Chambers</a> on bass and <a href="http://www.jimmycobb.net/" target="_blank">Jimmy Cobb</a> on the drums. If you''re familiar with <em>Kind of Blue</em>, you''ll probably really enjoy this one and find it as a kind of bridge between <em>Kind of Blue</em> and <em>Sketches of Spain</em>.</p>\n<p>Here''s Miles with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kVgKHpSY_WM" target="_blank">Blues No. 2</a>" (cf "All Blues" from <em>Kind of Blue</em>):</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kVgKHpSY_WM" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/51TvSQ25yJL.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Someday My Prince Will Come" (Frank Churchill, Larry Morey) 9:02</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Old Folks" (Willard Robison, Dedette Lee Hill) 5:14</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Pfrancing" (also known as "No Blues") (Miles Davis) 8:30</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Drad-Dog" (Miles Davis) 4:49</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Teo" (Miles Davis) 9:33</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"I Thought About You" (Jimmy Van Heusen, Johnny Mercer) 4:52</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Blues No. 2" (Miles Davis) 7:05</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Someday My Prince Will Come" (alternate take) (Frank Churchill, Larry Morey) 5:34</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 61, '2015-03-09 17:27:04', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:55:10', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-03-20 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 12, 'on this day in jazz, Miles Davis', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1403, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(355, 'On this day in jazz (March 21)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-march-21', '', '<p>On this day in 1964,   pianist <a href="http://www.andrewhilljazz.com/" target="_blank">Andrew Hill</a> recorded the album <em>Point of Departure</em> at Rudy van Gelder''s studio in Englewood Cliffs, NJ. Andrew was assisted by an all-star crew of <a href="http://www.kennydorham.net/biography/" target="_blank">Kenny Dorham</a> on trumpet, <a href="http://www.ericdolphy.net/" target="_blank">Eric Dolphy</a> on alto saxophone, bass clarinet and flute, <a href="http://www.joehendersonsax.com/" target="_blank">Joe Henderson</a> on tenor saxophone, Richard Davis on bass and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tony_Williams_(drummer)" target="_blank">Tony Williams</a> on drums. Essentially all of the musicians would go on to have careers as leaders. All of the songs were composed by Andrew.</p>\n<p>An interesting note on the album: the song "Dedication" was originally going to be titled "Cadaver"--the song itself means to present the feelings associated with great loss--and it is said that Kenny Dorham even got choked up playing it. Wow. But don''t let the sadness of "Dedication" stop you from listening. All-star reviewer Thom Jurek wrote this for allmusic.com: "essential for any representative jazz collection, and a record that, in the 21st century, still points the way to the future for jazz." allmusic.com gives the album its top five star rating, and The Penguin Guide to Jazz gave it one of its "crown" designations (when it used to still do that) as well as making it part of their "Core Collection".</p>\n<p>Here''s Andrew with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nPHUz8apHjY" target="_blank">Refuge</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nPHUz8apHjY" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/4167-andrew-hill-point-of-departure-cover-1600.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Refuge" 12:16</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"New Monastery" 7:05</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Spectrum" 9:47</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Flight 19" 4:18</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Dedication" 6:45</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 61, '2015-03-11 11:07:39', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:55:29', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-03-21 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 11, 'on this day in jazz, Andrew Hill', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1472, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(356, 'On this day in jazz (March 22)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-march-22', '', '<p>On this day in 1970,   <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ant%C3%B4nio_Carlos_Jobim" target="_blank">Antonio Carlos Jobim</a> completed recording of the album <em>Stone Flower</em>. Tom, as he was better known to his friends, wrote all songs on the album except for the standard "Brazil" (which is an Ary Barroso tune) and assembled a strong, large ensemble to play with him. Although Tom is best know for his guitar work, he also played piano, electric piano and sang vocals on the work. Notable other guitar work was performed by <a href="http://roncarter.net/JazzMaster/" target="_blank">Ron Carter</a> (on bass) and <a href="http://www.eumirdeodato.com/ed/dtct_true.php" target="_blank">Deodato</a> (on guitar).</p>\n<p>"Brazil" is truly a great song--as well as a really wonderful Terry Gilliam <a href="http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0088846/" target="_blank">movie</a> (which also features the song heavily), and this recording is definitely one of my favorite versions of it.</p>\n<p>Here''s Tom with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=V8goep7fVXk" target="_blank">Brazil</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=V8goep7fVXk" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/418M4Cdo0GL.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Tereza My Love" 4:23</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Children''s Games" 3:30</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Choro" 2:10</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Brazil" (Ary Barroso) 7:25</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Stone Flower" 3:21</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Amparo" 3:41</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Andorinha" 3:32</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"God and the Devil in the Land of the Sun" 2:23</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Sabia" 3:58</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 61, '2015-03-11 11:19:27', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:55:47', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-03-22 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 10, 'on this day in jazz, Antonio Carlos Jobim', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1466, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(357, 'On this day in jazz (March 23)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-march-23', '', '<p>On this day in 1970,   German jazz musician <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Albert_Mangelsdorff" target="_blank">Albert Mangelsdorff</a> recorded <em>Never Let It End</em> at Walldorf Studio in Frankfort,   Germany. The album was released under the band name,   "The Albert Mangelsdorff Quartet" with Albert on the trombone, Heinz Sauer on the tenor and alto saxophones, Gnter Lenz on bass and Ralf Hbner on drums / percussion.</p>\n<p>Although free-jazz is not my favorite jazz subgenre, it''s occasionally nice to change things up and try something new. This album will definitely do that.</p>\n<p>Here''s Albert with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XAQZzmUSe_A" target="_blank">Never Let It End</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XAQZzmUSe_A" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/albert-mangelsdorff-120904.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Wide Open . . . 3:45</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Never Let It End . . . 9:48</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Certain Beauty . . . 9:14</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">The 13th Color . . . 6:54</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Open Mind . . . 4:17</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Roitz And Spring . . . 7:14</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Nachwort . . . 1:59</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 61, '2015-03-15 14:04:28', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:56:04', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-03-23 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 9, 'on this day in jazz', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1449, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(358, 'On this day in jazz (March 24)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-march-24', '', '<p>On this day in 1958,   <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ornette_Coleman" target="_blank">Ornette Coleman</a> completed the recording of the seminal album <em>Something Else!!!</em> Don''t confuse this one with the album of the same name (less the exclamation points) by <a href="http://www.cannonball-adderley.com/" target="_blank">Cannonball Adderley</a>!!! But, consider it, like Cannonball''s album, one of the great jazz albums of the late 1950s. On this work you find Ornette on the alto saxophone, the most excellent <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Don_Cherry_%28trumpeter%29" target="_blank">Don Cherry</a> playing the cornet and a rhythm section consisting of Walter Norris at the piano, Don Payne on bass and Billy Higgins on the drums.</p>\n<p>This album is generally considered the one which ushered in a new era in jazz--that of free jazz. It wasn''t the first free jazz album recorded, but it was the first great one. Like I said on yesterday''s blog post, free jazz isn''t my favorite jazz subgenre, but occasionally I like to switch things up.</p>\n<p>Ornette''s story is an interesting one. While working as an elevator operator in Los Angeles, he (as a teenager) assembled a group consisting of several men who would later become jazz royalty into a band to experiment with his new style: Don Cherry, <a href="http://www.charliehadenmusic.com/" target="_blank">Charlie Haden</a>, Billy Higgins and Ed Blackwell.</p>\n<p>As Morrissey said "If you can grit your teeth for just three minutes", take a listen to "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8eDRTzXVaKs" target="_self">The Disguise</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8eDRTzXVaKs" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/claxtoncolemanl.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Invisible"  4:11</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Blessing"  4:45</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Jayne"  7:17</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Chippie"  5:37</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Disguise"  2:46</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Angel Voice"  4:19</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Alpha"  4:09</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"When Will the Blues Leave?"  4:58</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Sphinx"  4:13</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 61, '2015-03-15 14:10:10', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:56:22', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-03-24 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 8, 'on this day in jazz, Ornette Coleman', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1526, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(359, 'On this day in jazz (March 25)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-march-25', '', '<p>On this day in 1952,   the great <a href="http://www.dizzygillespie.com/" target="_blank">Dizzy Gillespie</a> was recorded live at the Theatre Des Champs-Elysees is Paris,   France. The album containing the material is entitled <em>Cognac Blues</em>. Dizzy, on trumpet of course, was joined by Don Byas on tenor sax, Art Simmons on piano, Joe Benjamin on bass, Bill Clark on drums and Humberto Morales on the congas.</p>\n<p>Dizzy''s early 1950''s European performances are probably some of his best--even though he would continue to be strong throughout the decade and into the early 1970s. Like his predecessor, some would discount Dizzy''s true virtuosity at the trumpet due to his magnificent showmanship. But, make no mistake, even though the man had incredible style, it was completely backed up with substance.</p>\n<p>Here''s Dizzy with "<a href="http://iisaphd.subsonic.org/share/UIPHp" target="_blank">Cognac Blues</a>"</p>\n<p><a href="http://iisaphd.subsonic.org/share/UIPHp" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/dizzy-gillespie.jpg" border="0" height="250" /><br /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 61, '2015-03-15 15:15:40', 62, '', '2016-08-20 01:03:37', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-03-25 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 7, 'on this day in jazz, Dizzy Gillespie', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1626, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(360, 'On this day in jazz (March 26)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-march-26', '', '<p>On this day in 1961,   the great <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hank_Mobley" target="_blank">Hank Mobley</a> recorded the album <em>Workout</em> for Blue Note records under the direction of Alfred Lion. Hank, one of my favorite tenor saxophonists, was joined by an all star crew of nothing but jazz royalty: <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grant_Green" target="_blank">Grant Green</a> on the guitar, <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/wynton-kelly-mn0000684253/biography" target="_blank">Wynton Kelly</a> on piano, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Chambers" target="_blank">Paul Chambers</a> on bass, and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philly_Joe_Jones" target="_blank">Philly Joe Jones</a> on drums. What a great group of musicians! I wished that Kelly, Chambers and Jones could have played together more often, but Kelly, Chambers and Cobb (from <em>Kind of Blue</em>) weren''t too shabby either.</p>\n<p>It''s not often that you hear such a great early 1960s jazz recording featuring some of the great bop artists with a guitar in the band, so give this one a listen for something a slight bit different.</p>\n<p>Here''s Hank with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Wjxc7y49hZ8" target="_blank">Workout</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Wjxc7y49hZ8" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/51YS5GGDHZL.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Workout" - 10:00</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Uh Huh" - 10:45</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Smokin''" - 7:28</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Best Things in Life Are Free" (Brown, DeSylva, Henderson) - 5:16</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Greasin'' Easy" - 6:59</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 61, '2015-03-15 15:19:39', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:56:36', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-03-26 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 6, 'on this day in jazz, Hank Mobley', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1599, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(361, 'On this day in jazz (March 27)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-march-27', '', '<p>On this day in 1961,   <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ornette_Coleman" target="_blank">Ornette Coleman</a> completed his studio album <em>Ornette On Tenor</em> for Atlantic Records. It was his eighth album in a very short period of time and further pushed the envelope on the free jazz genre. One of the songs on the album was recorded on the 22nd of the moth,   but the rest were recorded on this day.</p>\n<p>The reason for the title is because Ornette usually plays the alto saxophone rather than the tenor. allmusic.com said this, his last album for his Atlantic contract: "(this album was) wrapping up one of the most controversial and free-thinking series of recordings in jazz history" and "still far ahead of its time"--although this really isn''t one of his best efforts. He is joined by <a href="http://www.newyorker.com/books/page-turner/v-at-l-pynchons-first-novel-turns-fifty" target="_blank">the whole sick crew</a> of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Don_Cherry_%28trumpeter%29" target="_blank">Don Cherry</a> on trumpet, Jimmy Garrison on bass and Ed Blackwell on drums (you''ll recall this cast from the blog post from three days ago).</p>\n<p>Here''s Ornette with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v3GAg0J-874" target="_blank">Cross Breeding</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v3GAg0J-874" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/orig_Ornette_Coleman_01.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Cross Breeding" March 27 11:17</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Mapa" March 27 9:05</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Enfant" March 27 6:27</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Eos" March 22 6:35</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Ecars" March 27 7:34</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 61, '2015-03-15 15:23:57', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:56:49', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-03-27 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 5, 'on this day in jazz, Ornette Coleman', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1438, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(362, 'On this day in jazz (March 28)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-march-28', '', '<p>On this day in 1957,   pianist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kenny_Drew" target="_blank">Kenny Drew</a> began recording the studio album <em>This Is New</em> in Mew York City. Kenny was supported by a very strong cast including <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Donald_Byrd" target="_blank">Donald Byrd</a> on trumpet,   the great <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hank_Mobley" target="_blank">Hank Mobley</a> on tenor saxophone for the first three tracks,   <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wilbur_Ware" target="_blank">Wilbur Ware</a> on bass and G.T. Hogan on the drums.</p>\n<p>Kenny''s albums were always good and this one is very likable. 1957 was indeed a busy year for Kenny who had started releasing works as a leader in 1953. In 1957 he released five albums as a leader as well as playing as sideman on <a href="http://www.johncoltrane.com/" target="_blank">John Coltrane</a>''s classic <em>Blue Train</em> (highly, highly recommended). If you like this one, you can branch out and listen to some of the other great jazz musicians that Kenny played with such as: <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buddy_DeFranco" target="_blank">Buddy DeFranco</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coleman_Hawkins" target="_blank">Coleman Hawkins</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lester_Young" target="_blank">Lester Young</a> and <a href="http://www.cmgww.com/music/parker/home.html" target="_blank">Charlie Parker</a>.</p>\n<p>Here''s Kenny with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bUMBnFi0HSA" target="_blank">This Is New</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bUMBnFi0HSA" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/220px-Kenny_Drew.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"This Is New" (Ira Gershwin, Kurt Weill) - 6:56</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Carol" (Kenny Drew) - 4:32</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"It''s You or No One" (Sammy Cahn, Jule Styne) - 8:08</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"You''re My Thrill" (Sidney Clare, Jay Gorney) - 5:21</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Little T" (Donald Byrd) - 6:08</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Paul''s Pal" (Sonny Rollins) - 6:38</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Why Do I Love You?" (Oscar Hammerstein II, Jerome Kern) - 5:12</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 61, '2015-03-15 16:40:10', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:57:21', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-03-28 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 4, 'on this day in jazz, Kenny Drew', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1620, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(363, 'On this day in jazz (March 29)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-march-29', '', '<p>On this day in 1960,   clarinetist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pee_Wee_Russell" target="_blank">Pee Wee Russell</a> recorded <em>Swingin'' with Pee Wee</em>. If you''re a fan of dixieland, Pee Wee is probably one of your favorites. If you''re more into the genres that started in the 1940s, 50s and 60s, you might not have heard too much of his work. On this album you''ll hear Pee Wee with trumpeter <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buck_Clayton" target="_blank">Buck Clayton</a>, pianist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tommy_Flanagan" target="_blank">Tommy Flanagan</a>, drummer Osie Johnson and bassist Wendell Marshall. It''s really "small-group swing" instead of dixieland--but you''ll get the idea of what Pee Wee was all about. allmusic.com gives it five stars and calls it "a gem".</p>\n<p>Here''s Pee Wee with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PtlwS54E0co&list=PLE1rZqo2QTgw9whCFZxWBg4NW1VjDT_Hx&index=1" target="_blank">What Can I Say After I Say I''m Sorry?</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PtlwS54E0co&list=PLE1rZqo2QTgw9whCFZxWBg4NW1VjDT_Hx&index=1" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Pee_Wee_Russell_48f72d999e8de.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 61, '2015-03-15 16:53:27', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:57:44', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-03-29 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 3, 'on this day in jazz, Pee Wee Russell', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1632, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(364, 'On this day in jazz (March 30)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-march-30', '', '<p>On this day in 1961,   trumpter <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blue_Mitchell" target="_blank">Blue Mitchell</a> completed recording the studio album <em>Smooth as the Wind</em> for Riverside records. The album was produced by Orrin Keepnews. There''s an awful lot of wind on this album including four trumpets (including Blue and legend <a href="http://clarkterry.com/" target="_blank">Clark Terry</a>),   four trombones (including Jimmy Cleveland and Julian Priester), Willie Ruff on the french horn and an excellent rhythm section of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tommy_Flanagan" target="_blank">Tommy Flanagan</a> at the piano, Tommy Williams on bass, and a combination of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philly_Joe_Jones" target="_blank">Philly Joe Jones</a> and Charlie Persip on the drums. In addition to all of these greats, Tadd Dameron and <a href="http://www.bennygolson.com/" target="_blank">Benny Golson</a> provide the arrangements.</p>\n<p>The album was recorded in three sessions starting on December 27, 1960 and continuing on March 29 and March 30 and features songs by Dameron, Johnny Burke, <a href="http://www.horacesilver.com/" target="_blank">Horace Silver</a>, Hoagie Carmichael and Frank Sinatra (just to credit a few).</p>\n<p>Here''s Blue with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mthjsSHLQmk" target="_blank">But Beautiful</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mthjsSHLQmk" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/blue-mitchell-trumpet-the-birdhouse-chicago-il-december-1960.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Smooth as the Wind" (Tadd Dameron) - 5:10</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"But Beautiful" (Johnny Burke, Jimmy Van Heusen) - 3:35</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Best Things in Life Are Free (Brown, DeSylva, Henderson) 3:18</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Peace" (Horace Silver) - 3:53</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"For Heaven''s Sake" (Elise Bretton, Sherman Edwards, Donald Meyer) - 3:32</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Nearness of You" (Hoagy Carmichael, Ned Washington) - 3:22</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"A Blue Time" (Dameron) - 4:52</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Strollin''" (Silver) - 3:16</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"For All We Know" (J. Fred Coots, Sam M. Lewis) - 3:21</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"I''m a Fool to Want You" (Joel Herron, Frank Sinatra, Jack Wolf) - 3:37</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 61, '2015-03-20 13:35:32', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:57:59', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-03-30 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 2, 'on this day in jazz, Blue Mitchell', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1637, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(365, 'On this day in jazz (March 31)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-march-31', '', '<p>On this day in 1959,   guitarist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barney_Kessel" target="_blank">Barney Kessel</a> started recording the album <em>Some Like It Hot</em> (it would be completed on April 3). You''re probably familiar with the movie of the same name featuring Marilyn Monroe,   Tony Curtis and Jack Lemon--this is the soundtrack. Joining in with Barney on the album were <a href="http://straightlife.info/apbio.html" target="_blank">Art Pepper</a> who played alto and tenor saxophones as well as the clarinet, and tenor), Joe Gordon on the trumpet, Jimmy Rowles on the piano, Jack Marshall on the rhythm guitar, Monty Budwig on the bass, and the great <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shelly_Manne" target="_blank">Shelly Manne</a> on the drums.</p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">With such a crew as mentioned above, you''d expect that this is probably going to be filled with newer songs interpreted in a cool west coast bop fashion; however, most of the songs were vintage even in 1959, dating from the 1920s. What you get are cool west coast interpretations of classic tunes with modern arrangements with a hint of the 1920s. The great reviewer Scott Yanow suggests getting the reissue version which features a few extra takes of the some of the songs (e.g. "Sweet Sue" and "Runnin Wild") so that you can hear how they vary in their interpretation. Oh, and the Art Pepper solos are really good, too. </span></p>\n<p>Here''s Barney with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BaJPlHQwkgk" target="_blank">Some Like It Hot</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BaJPlHQwkgk" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Barney-Kessel.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Some Like It Hot 4:15</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">I Wanna Be Loved by You 3:37</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Stairway to the Stars 3:16</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Sweet Sue 4:42</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Sweet Sue 4:48</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Runnin'' Wild 3:19</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Runnin'' Wild 6:31</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Sweet Georgia Brown 3:39</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Down Among the Sheltering Palms 4:01</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Sugar Blues 3:24</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">I''m Thru with Love 3:14</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">By the Beautiful Sea 3:10</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 61, '2015-03-20 13:41:09', 62, '', '2016-08-17 17:58:19', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-03-31 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 1, 'on this day in jazz, Barney Kessel', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1583, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(366, 'On this day in jazz (April 01)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-april-01', '', '<p>On this day in 1960,  <a href="http://www.ericdolphy.net/" target="_blank">Eric Dolphy</a> recorded the studio album <em>Outward Bound</em> at Rudy van Gelder''s studio in Englewood Cliffs,   NJ. On this album Eric plays the flute, bass clarinet and alto saxophone, the wonderful<a href="http://www.freddiehubbardmusic.com/" target="_blank">Freddie Hubbard</a> pays the trumpet and the rhythm section is composed of Jacki Byard on piano, George Tucker on bass and Roy Haynes on the drums.</p>\n<p>The album contains three originals by Eric (none titled longer than three characters!) and three covers including the jazz standard "On Green Dolphin Street". I find it quite interesting to hear free jazz interpret the standards--it makes for understand free jazz a little bit easier. For more on Eric personally, see my <a href="index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=188:on-this-day-in-jazz-october-07&catid=56:october&Itemid=41" target="_self">October 7 blog page</a>.</p>\n<p>Don''t be a fool, take a listen to Eric on "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wKyYJMgrmUo" target="_blank">On Green Dolphin Street</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wKyYJMgrmUo" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/426x500xeric-dolphy-val-wilmer.jpg.pagespeed.ic.WcLh1q5NDH.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"G.W." - 7:57</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"On Green Dolphin Street" (Bronislaw Kaper, Ned Washington)  5:44</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Les" - 5:12</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"245" - 6:49</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Glad To Be Unhappy" (Richard Rodgers, Lorenz Hart) - 5:26</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Miss Toni" (Charles "Majeed" Greenlee) - 5:40</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 62, '2015-03-20 13:49:57', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:18:55', 62, 62, '2016-08-20 00:03:01', '2015-04-01 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 30, 'on this day in jazz, Eric Dolphy', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1686, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(367, 'On this day in jazz (April 02)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-april-02', '', '<p>On this day in 1960,   pianist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Red_Garland" target="_blank">Red Garland</a> recorded the album <em>Red Alone</em> at Rudy van Gelder''s studio in Englewood Cliffs,   NJ. During the session, Red recorded sixteen ballads although only half of them appear on the CD reissue (you''ll have to get <em>Alone With the Blues</em> to hear the rest). If you want to relax and hear a true jazz master interpret some of the best songs in the world, take a listen to this one. Ken Dryden said this of the album:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">The subtlety of his interpretation of "You Are Too Beautiful" and the delicate rendition of "The Nearness of You" are also memorable. But the obvious high point of this release is his stunning exploration of Duke Ellington''s "I Got It Bad (And That Ain''t Good)," which succeeds in conveying the powerful emotions of this ballad without a singer. This remarkable collection of standards should appeal to any fan of jazz piano.</p>\n<p>Here''s Red with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q9ljKgo4Zik" target="_blank">When I Fall In Love</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q9ljKgo4Zik" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Red-Garland-Red-Alone-L025218710220.JPG" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"When Your Lover Has Gone" (Swan) - 6:45</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"These Foolish Things" (Link, Marvell, Strachey) - 5:08</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"My Last Affair" (Haven Johnson) - 3:39</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"You Are Too Beautiful" (Hart, Rodgers) - 4:45</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"I Got It Bad (And That Ain''t Good)" (Ellington, Webster) - 7:09</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Nearness of You" (Carmichael, Washington) - 5:04</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Nancy (With the Laughing Face)" (Silvers, VanHeusen) - 5:25</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"When I Fall in Love" (Heyman, Young) - 5:06</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 62, '2015-03-20 14:07:46', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:19:15', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-04-02 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 29, 'on this day in jazz, Red Garland', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1765, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(368, 'On this day in jazz (April 03)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-april-03', '', '<p>On this day in 1965,   <a href="http://www.bluenote.com/artists/bobby-hutcherson" target="_blank">Bobby Hutcherson</a> recorded the album Dialog at Rudy van Gelder''s studio in Englewood Cliffs,NJ. On the album Bobby plays the vibraphone and marimbas, Sam Rivers plays tenor saxophone, soprano saxophone, bass clarinet and flute, the great <a href="http://www.freddiehubbardmusic.com/" target="_blank">Freddie Hubbard</a> is on the trumpet, and the excellent rhythm section consisted of <a href="http://www.andrewhilljazz.com/" target="_blank">Andrew Hill</a> (one of my favorites) on piano, Richard Davis on bass and <a href="http://www.josephachambers.com/" target="_blank">Joe Chambers</a> on drums. Hill received writing credits for three of the tracks and Chambers received credit for the other two.</p>\n<p>I was surprised that this album was Bobby Hutcherson''s first as a leader--but what a debut it was. The album received a five star rating from the<em>Penguin Guide to Jazz</em> as well as a "Crown" selection. allmusic.com also gave the album five stars calling it a "most adventurous, "outside" album" and says that it is "arguably his greatest musical achievement". I don''t know if I would go that far, but it is certainly a great set.</p>\n<p>Here''s Bobby with Joe Chambers'' "Dialogue":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9jZycoxXNgIhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9jZycoxXNgI" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/dialogue.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Catta" (Hill) - 7:19</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Idle While" (Chambers) - 6:37</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Les Noirs Marchant" (Hill) - 6:41</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Dialogue" (Chambers) - 9:59</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Ghetto Lights" (Hill) - 6:1</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 62, '2015-03-20 15:21:00', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:02:55', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-04-03 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 28, 'on this day in jazz, Bobby Hutcherson', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1673, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(369, 'On this day in jazz (April 04)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-april-04', '', '<p>On this day in 1992,   pianist <a href="http://www.ahmadjamal.net/" target="_blank">Ahmad Jamal</a> recorded the live album <em>Live In Paris 1992</em> at Salle de Spectacles in Colombes,   France. Ahmad was joined by James Cammack (tracks 1-5,   7 & 9) and Todd Coolman (track 6) on the bass and David Bowler (tracks 1-5, 7, & 9) and Gordon Lane (track 6) on the drums.</p>\n<p>Although Ahmad started recording professionally in 1951, he''s still in fine form here at the age of 62. As you can expect, his long and strong career garnered a lot of recognition. Here''s a short list of some of the accolades that Ahmal has received:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">1980: Distinguished Service Award from City of Washington D.C., Anacostia Neighborhood Museum, Smithsonian Institution<br /> 1994: National Endowment for the Arts American Jazz Masters award<br /> 1994: Duke Ellington Fellow at Yale University<br /> 2001: Arts & Culture Recognition Award from the National Coalition of 100 Black Women, Inc.<br /> 2003: American Jazz Hall of Fame from New Jersey Jazz Society<br /> 2003: Gold Medallion from Steinway & Songs 150 Years Celebration (18532003)<br /> 2007: Named Living Jazz Legend by the Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts<br /> 2007: Order of the Arts and Letters by French Culture Minister Renaud Donnedieu de Vabres, naming him Officier de l''Ordre des Arts et des Lettres<br /> 2011: Induction into Downbeat Magazines 76th Readers'' Poll Hall of Fame.</p>\n<p>Here''s Ahmad with "<a href="http://www.allmusic.com/album/live-in-paris-92-mw0000104873" target="_blank">Caravan</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="http://www.allmusic.com/album/live-in-paris-92-mw0000104873" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/MI0001581111.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing (songs by Ahmad unless noted):</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Tube" - 7:53</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Alone Together/Laura/Wild Is the Wind" (Arthur Schwartz, Howard Dietz/David Raksin, Johnny Mercer/Dimitri Tiomkin, Ned Washington) - 7:09</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Caravan" (Duke Ellington, Irving Mills, Juan Tizol) - 5:19</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Easy Living" (Ralph Rainger, Leo Robin) - 6:27</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Acorn" - 8:41</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Dreamy" (Erroll Garner) - 7:13</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Appreciation" (Johnny Pate) - 5:16</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Look for the Silver Lining" (Buddy DeSylva, Jerome Kern) - 3:08</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Aftermath" - 5:08</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 62, '2015-03-20 15:46:17', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:20:28', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-04-04 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 27, 'on this day in jazz, Ahmad Jamal', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1873, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(370, 'On this day in jazz (April 05)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-april-05', '', '<p>On this day in 1972,   pianist <a href="http://www.keithjarrett.org/" target="_blank">Keith Jarrett</a> began recording the album <em>Expectations</em>. It would be completed three weeks later. On this album you''ll not only hear Keith at the piano but also at the organ,   soprano saxophone,   tambourine and even on percussion. All recordings were composed by Keith who was joined by Dewey Redman on tenor saxophone and percussion, Sam Brown on guitar, <a href="http://www.charliehadenmusic.com/" target="_blank">Charlie Haden</a> on bass, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Motian" target="_blank">Paul Motian</a> on drums and Airto Moreira on percussion.</p>\n<p>Jarrett, who had been a member of Miles Davis'' band until shortly before making this album, recorded this one for Columbia Records (like Miles). Although they signed him to his own contract, they broke the contract by dropping him shortly after the record''s release. I find that amazing and incredibly short sighted. Just <a href="index.php?searchword=keith+jarrett&ordering=&searchphrase=all&Itemid=1&option=com_search" target="_self">search my blog</a> for some of the other great works by Keith.</p>\n<p>Here''s Keith with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=b1nTwRdo1BQ" target="_blank">Expectations</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=b1nTwRdo1BQ" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Keith-Jarrett-feat.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Vision"  0:51</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Common Mama"  8:14</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Magician in You"  6:55</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Roussillon"  5:25</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Expectations"  4:29</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Take Me Back"  9:33</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Circular Letter (for J.K.)"  5:04</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Nomads"  17:23</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Sundance"  4:31</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Bring Back the Time When (If)"  9:53</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"There Is a Road (God''s River)"  5:32</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 62, '2015-03-20 15:59:32', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:20:50', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-04-05 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 26, 'on this day in jazz, Keith Jarrett', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2041, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(371, 'On this day in jazz (April 06)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-march-06', '', '<p>On this day in 1994,   multi-instrumentist <a href="http://www.joelovano.com/" target="_blank">Joe Lavano</a> began recording the album <em>Rush Hour</em>. It would be completed six days later. Joe played tenor and soprano saxophones, bass clarinet and drums on the work and was backed by a small orchestra. Scott Yanow, writing for allmusic.com said that the album was "one of the most exciting jazz releases of 1995". It features four songs with a string section, four songs with a stringless big band (woodwinds and brass), one song, Ornette Coleman''s "Kathline Gray", with a chamber group, two songs as duets (with wife Judi Silvano''s wordless vocals), etc. Psew! Scott also said:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">this very well-conceived release would not have succeeded were it not for the talent, versatility and risk-taking of Joe Lovano. His improvisations (mostly on tenor) push the boundaries of this already adventurous music and his sound (which occasionally hints a little at Clifford Jordan) is quite original; on the basis of this date alone, Lovano must rank as one of the top tenors of the 1990s.</p>\n<p>Here''s Joe with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bz2X_mhn5i4" target="_blank">Prelude to a Kiss</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bz2X_mhn5i4" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Joe-Lovano-image-by-Jimmy-Katz.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Prelude to a Kiss" (Duke Ellington, Irving Gordon, Irving Mills) - 3:58</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Peggy''s Blue Skylight" (Charles Mingus) - 3:33</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Wildcat" - 2:57</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Angel Eyes" (Earl Brent, Matt Dennis) - 5:09</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Rush Hour On 23rd Street" (Gunther Schuller) - 8:53</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Crespuscle With Nellie" (Thelonious Monk) - 5:43</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Lament For M" (Schuller) - 5:41</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Topsy Turvy" - 4:27</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Love I Long For" (Howard Dietz, Vernon Duke) - 3:11</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Juniper''s Garden" - 2:40</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Kathline Gray" (Ornette Coleman) - 3:26</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Headin'' Out Movin'' In" (Schuller) - 11:13</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Chelsea Bridge" (Billy Strayhorn) - 3:41</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 62, '2015-03-20 16:19:26', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:21:23', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-04-06 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 25, 'on this day in jazz, Joe Lavano', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2148, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(372, 'On this day in jazz (April 07)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-april-07', '', '<p>On this day in 1958,   organist supreme <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jimmy_Smith_(musician)" target="_blank">Jimmy Smith</a> recorded the live album <em>Cool Blues</em> for Blue Note records. It was produced by hall of fame producer Alfred Lion at recorded at Small''s Paradise in New York City. Jimmy was supported on the album by Lou Donaldson on the alto saxophone,   Tina Brooks on the tenor saxophone,   Eddie McFadden on guitar and a combination of <a href="http://www.artblakey.com/" target="_blank">Art Blakey</a> (tracks 1, 2 & 4) and Donald Bailey (tracks 5-8) playing the drums.</p>\n<p>While the original release of the album only contained five songs, the CD re-release contains three bonus tracks that were recorded at the same performance. The song that I picked to share below is that jazz standard "A Night In Tunisia" (although Babs Gonzales announces it as "An Insane Night In Small''s Paradise") because you just <em>have</em> to hear Art Blakey on the drums for this song. And, for another instance (my favorite, by the way) or Art performing this song, check out my <a href="index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=228:on-this-day-in-jazz-november-14&catid=57:november&Itemid=41" target="_self">November 14 blog entry</a>.</p>\n<p>Also, for many other Jimmy Smith albums that I''ve profiled over the past year, just use the search feature. In fact, <a href="index.php?searchword=jimmy+smith&ordering=&searchphrase=all&Itemid=1&option=com_search" target="_blank">lmgtfy</a></p>\n<p>Here''s Jimmy (and Art) with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KFWV1O76MkQ" target="_blank">A Night In Tunisia</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KFWV1O76MkQ" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/jimmy%20smith%2001.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Dark Eyes" (Traditional) - 11:43</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Groovin'' at Small''s" (Babs Gonzales) - 12:01</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Announcements by Babs Gonzales - 0:26 Bonus track on CD reissue</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"A Night in Tunisia" (Dizzy Gillespie) - 17:04</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Cool Blues" (Charlie Parker) - 11:07</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 62, '2015-03-20 16:23:39', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:21:44', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-04-07 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 24, 'on this day in jazz, Jimmy Smith', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2344, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(373, 'On this day in jazz (April 08)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-april-08', '', '<p>On this day in 1957,   <a href="http://www.dizzygillespie.com/" target="_blank">Dizzie Gillespie</a> began recording the album <em>Birks'' Works</em>. The album has been released several times over the years; the original effort contained ten songs,   the re-releases contain between 19 and 23 songs with a great selection of additional takes. The album in its re-release form was included in the <em>Penguin Guide to Jazz</em>''s Core Collection. On the original release the personnel included: Dizzy on trumpet assisted also by Talib Daawud,   <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lee_Morgan" target="_blank">Lee Morgan</a>, Ermit V. Perry and Carl Warwick playing additional trumpets, Melba Liston, Al Grey and Rod Levitt on trombones, Ernie Henry and Jimmy Powell on alto saxophone, the great <a href="http://www.bennygolson.com/" target="_blank">Benny Golson</a> and Billy Mitchell on tenor saxophone, Billy Root on baritone saxophone and a rhythm section of <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/wynton-kelly-mn0000684253/biography" target="_blank">Wynton Kelly</a> on piano, Paul West on bass and Charlie Persip on drums.</p>\n<p>Scott Yanow in his review for allmusic.com says to pay particular attention to "Dizzy''s Business," "Jessica''s Day," "The Champ," "Cool Breeze," "Birks Works," "Whisper Not," "Stablemates," and "I Remember Clifford".</p>\n<p>Here''s Dizzy with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nW8i_UfqYNw" target="_blank">Birks'' Works</a>"</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nW8i_UfqYNw" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/61z1f0qbNbL._SY300_.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Jordu" (Duke Jordan) - 4:13</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Birks'' Works" - 4:56</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Umbrella Man" (Vincent Rose, Larry Stock, James Cavanaugh) - 3:02</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Autumn Leaves" (Joseph Kosma, Jacques Prvert, Johnny Mercer) - 3:11</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Tangerine" (Victor Schertzinger, Mercer) - 3:43</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Over the Rainbow" (Harold Arlen, Yip Harburg) - 4:37</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Yo No Quiero Bailar" (Joe Willoughby) - 4:42</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"If You Could See Me Now" (Tadd Dameron, Carl Sigman) - 3:30</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Left Hand Corner" (Ernie Wilkins) - 2:26</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Whisper Not" (Benny Golson, Leonard Feather) - 5:17</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 62, '2015-04-06 15:40:15', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:22:00', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-04-08 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 23, 'on this day in jazz, Dizzy Gillespie', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2322, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(374, 'On this day in jazz (April 09)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-april-09', '', '<p>On this day in 1975,   the great <a href="http://www.zootsims.org/" target="_blank">Zoot Sims</a> and legend <a href="http://www.thecountbasieorchestra.com/" target="_blank">Count Basie</a> recorded the album <em>Basie & Zoot</em>. The personnel on the work consists of Basie at the piano, Zoot on the tenor saxophone, John Heard on bass and Louie Bellson on the drums. Although the two men were exceptional leaders and hardly needed to play together, it''s nice to see that they took the time to record this together in such an intimate setting.</p>\n<p>Zoot has always been one of my favorite saxophonists and Basie, of course, is one of the more important figures in the jazz genre. Having them come together with only the addition of bass and drums really allows you to hear them in all their virtuosity. In fact, in his review of the album, Scott Yanow goes so far as to call out John and Louie''s contributions as "playing at the peak of their creative powers". Hope you enjoy this one as much as I did.</p>\n<p>Here''s the Count and Zoot with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=12ioAB0YyDw" target="_blank">I Never Knew</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=12ioAB0YyDw" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Count-Basie-and-Zoot-Sims-Basie-Zoot-1975-FLAC.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"I Never Knew" (Ted Fio Rito, Gus Kahn)  4:38</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"It''s Only a Paper Moon" (Harold Arlen, Yip Harburg, Billy Rose)  5:33</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Blues for Nat Cole" (Count Basie, Zoot Sims)  6:32</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Captain Bligh" (Basie, Sims)  6:36</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Honeysuckle Rose" (Andy Razaf, Fats Waller)  6:23</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Hardav" (Basie, Sims)  4:41</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Mean to Me" (Fred E. Ahlert, Roy Turk)  6:30</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"I Surrender, Dear" (Harry Barris, Gordon Clifford)  6:05</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 62, '2015-04-06 15:43:20', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:22:46', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-04-09 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 22, 'on this day in jazz, Zoot Sims, Count Basie', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2122, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(375, 'On this day in jazz (April 10)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-april-10', '', '<p>On this day in 1963,   <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pee_Wee_Russell" target="_blank">Pee Wee Russell</a> completed recording the album <em>Ask Me Now!</em> Joining Pee Wee''s clarinet were Marshall Brown on trombone, Russell George on bass and Ronnie Bedford on the drums. This is a truly great way to experience Pee Wee if you are only familiar with the music that brought him to fame (Dixieland). Essentially, Pee Wee''s claim to fame was the way in which he improvised "unusual and unpredictable" clairnet solos while playing in those Dixieland bands--however, here you''ll hear him in a small group setting with only trombone and rhythm section (sans piano) attacking works with gusto that were made famous by his followers (John Coltrane, Ornette Coleman and Thelonious Monk) as well as hitting some classic ballads.</p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Here''s Pee Wee with "</span><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4jQcgUIifdc" target="_blank" style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Angel Eyes</a><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">":</span></p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4jQcgUIifdc" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/B00007KMSQ.01_SL75_.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Turnaround" (Ornette Coleman) - 4:14</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"How About Me?" (Irving Berlin) - 4:16</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Ask Me Now!" (Thelonious Monk) - 2:30</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Some Other Blues" (John Coltrane) - 3:16</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"I''d Climb the Highest Mountain" (Lew Brown, Sidney Clare) - 3:26</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Licorice Stick" (Marshall Brown) - 3:36</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Prelude to a Kiss" (Duke Ellington, Irving Gordon, Irving Mills) - 2:41</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Baby, You Can Count on Me" (Freddie Stewart) - 5:01</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Hackensack" (Monk) - 3:37</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Angel Eyes (Earl Brent, Matt Dennis) - 2:51</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Calypso Walk" (Marshall Brown) - 2:34</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 62, '2015-04-06 15:48:09', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:23:04', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-04-10 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 21, 'on this day in jazz, Pee Wee Russell', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2111, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(376, 'On this day in jazz (April 11)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-april-11', '', '<p>On this day in 1982,   drummer <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bob_Moses_%28musician%29" target="_blank">Bob Moses</a> recorded the album <em>When Elephants Dream of Music</em>. The music was played by Bob on the drums,   David Gross on alto saxophone, Jim Pepper on tenor saxophone, Terumasa Hino on cornet, Barry Rogers on trombone, Jeremy Steig on flute, Howard Johnson on electric contrabass clarinet and tuba, and the rhythm being supplied by David Friedman on vibraphone, Lyle Mays on keyboards, the talented Bill Frisell on guitar and Steve Swallow on the electric bass. Vocals were supplied by a host of personnel, but most notably were Sheila Jordan and Jeanne Lee. allmusic.com calls the music "quite lyrical and laid-back".</p>\n<p>On the album, songs consist of tributes to <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a> and <a href="http://www.billystrayhorn.com/" target="_blank">Billy Strayhorn</a> as well as parodies (e.g., "Nobody Knows You When You''re Down and Out" parodied as "Everybody Knows You When You''re Up and In" and "Embraceable You" parodied as "Embraceable Jew").</p>\n<p>Here''s Bob with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Zb1K0VVrwYs" target="_blank">Trevor</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Zb1K0VVrwYs" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/R-622723-1153169578.jpeg.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing (all songs composed by Moses):</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Trevor   5:00</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Picolo And Lulu   2:52</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Everybody Knows You When You''re Up and In   4:28</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Lava Flow   9:19</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Happy To Be Here Today   2:42</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">For Miles   7:11</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Embraceable Jew   4:55</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Bugs Bunny   8:28</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Black Orchid   5:58</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Disappearing Blues   2:10</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Ripped Van Winkle   7:22</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Blame It On The Egg   1:18</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">The River   4:33 </span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 62, '2015-04-06 15:57:15', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:23:33', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-04-11 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 20, 'on this day in jazz, Bob Moses', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1928, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(377, 'On this day in jazz (April 12)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-april-12', '', '<p>On this day in 1957,   pianist <a href="http://www.oscarpeterson.com/" target="_blank">Oscar Peterson</a> recorded the live album <em>Oscar Peterson Trio at the Concertgebouw</em>. Joining Oscar were <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ray_Brown_(musician)" target="_blank">Ray Brown</a> on the bass and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Herb_Ellis" target="_blank">Herb Ellis</a> on the guitar. Note the lack of percussion! The songs on the work are generally all jazz standards but interpreted in Oscar,   Ray and Herb''s way. You''ll hear everything from Hart & Rogers'' "The Lady Is a Tramp" to the wonderful Milt Jackson''s "Bluesology" to the great Miles Davis / Bud Powell standard "Budo" (and that''s just in the first four songs--keep listening and you''ll hear some really great music all the way through the set).</p>\n<p>Here''s Oscar with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-dXF_AY-cKI" target="_blank">Budo</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-dXF_AY-cKI" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/The_Oscar_Peterson_Trio-Oscar_Peterson_Trio_At_The_Concertgebouw-Front.JPG" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Lady Is a Tramp" (Lorenz Hart, Richard Rodgers) - 4:51</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"We''ll Be Together Again" (Carl T. Fischer, Frankie Laine) - 2:34</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Bluesology" (Milt Jackson) - 9:23</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Budo" (aka "Hallucinations") (Miles Davis, Bud Powell) - 4:42</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"I''ve Got the World on a String" (Harold Arlen, Ted Koehler) - 6:41</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Daahoud" (Ray Brown) - 7:00</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"When Lights Are Low" (Benny Carter, Spencer Williams) - 4:03</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Eurev" (Oscar Peterson) - 4:51</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Should I?" (Nacio Herb Brown, Arthur Freed) - 5:16</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Big Fat Mama" (Lucky Millinder, Stafford Simon) - 7:34</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"(Back Home In) Indiana" (James F. Hanley, Ballard MacDonald) - 4:07</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Joy Spring" (Clifford Brown) - 5:33</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Elevation" (Elliot Lawrence, Gerry Mulligan) - 3:28</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 62, '2015-04-06 16:04:02', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:24:24', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-04-12 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 19, 'on this day in jazz, Oscar Peterson', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1857, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(378, 'On this day in jazz (April 13)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-april-13', '', '<p>On this day in 1953,   guitarist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chuck_Wayne" target="_blank">Chuck Wayne</a> recorded the album <em>Tasty Pudding</em>. Although Chuck''s works are a little obscure these days,   he was well known in the 1940s and 1950s (playing swing with greats such as Billy Eckstine and <a href="http://www.dizzygillespie.com/" target="_blank">Dizzy Gillespie</a>). On this album you''ll hear him belting out the bebop with the great <a href="http://www.zootsims.org/" target="_blank">Zoot Sims</a> and Brew Moore on tenor saxophones, Harvey Leonard at the piano, George Duvivier on bass and Ed Shaughnessy on the drums. You''ll find both standards and seven originals on the work (including five composed by Chuck).</p>\n<p>The music is definitely not cutting edge--instead its simply just very listenable. In his review, Dave Nathan said:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">While there is virtually no inventiveness going on, the playing is entertaining. One quality that comes through with the Wayne guitar is its hornlike sound, which adds a dimension to his playing and is especially complementary when either Sims or Moore is soloing....its regrettable they were not offered more interesting or challenging music to perform.</p>\n<p>Here''s Chuck with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=M0B9BGs6B-s" target="_blank">Tasty Pudding</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=M0B9BGs6B-s" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/tastypudding.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">You Brought a New Kind of Love To Me</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">S.S. Cool</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Mary Ann</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Butterfingers</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Taking a Chance on Love</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Sirod</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">While My Lady Sleeps</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Tasty Pudding</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Prospecting</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Sidewalks of Cuba</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Uncas</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Stella by Starlight</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 62, '2015-04-06 16:19:14', 62, '', '2016-08-20 01:05:35', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-04-13 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 18, 'on this day in jazz, Chuck Wayne', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1811, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(379, 'On this day in jazz (April 14)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-april-14', '', '<p>On this day in 1967,   trumpeter <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lee_Morgan" target="_blank">Lee Morgan</a> began recording the album <em>Sonic Boom</em> at Rudy van Gelder''s studio in Englewood Cliffs,   NJ. The album was not originally released--it took 12 more years before Blue Note would release it. The album was also re-released on CD with several more recordings from 1967 that were not on the original. Note that the added tunes on the CD do not feature the same personnel as the original release which featured Lee on trumpet,   David Newman on tenor saxophone, the wonderful<a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/cedar-walton-mn0000741325/biography" target="_blank">Cedar Walton</a> at the piano, the prolific<a href="http://roncarter.net/JazzMaster/" target="_blank">Ron Carter</a> (more than 2000 albums to his credit) on bass and Billy Higgins on the drums. The second set does not feature as strong of a cast but they''re a good compliment to the originals.</p>\n<p>Talking about originals, all songs on the album were originals written by Lee except for "I''ll Never Be the Same". allusic.com gives the album a strong 4.5 star rating. Check out the search function on my site for plenty more of Lee Morgan if you like the song featured below.</p>\n<p>Here''s Lee with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3ahWj6TrR60" target="_blank">Sonic Boom</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3ahWj6TrR60" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/51UNvWMk9WL.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Sneaky Pete" - 5:45</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Mercenary" - 7:10</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Sonic Boom" - 6:18</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Fathead" - 5:27</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"I''ll Never Be the Same" (Kahn, Malneck, Signorelli) - 7:16</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Mumbo Jumbo" - 5:29</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 62, '2015-04-06 16:25:11', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:25:02', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-04-14 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 17, 'on this day in jazz, Lee Morgan', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1900, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(380, 'On this day in jazz (April 15)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-april-15', '', '<p>On this day in 1959,   the wonderful <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cecil_Taylor" target="_blank">Cecil Taylor</a> recorded the album <em>Love for Sale</em> for United Artists at Nola''s Penthouse Studios in New York City. On the work you''ll hear Cecil on the piano,   Buell Neidlinger on bass, Denis Charles on drums and (on the last three tracks) wind added by Bill Barron''s tenor saxophone and Ted Curson''s trumpet.</p>\n<p>If you''re familiar with jazz you''ll know that Cecil was one of the greatest and earliest players of free/avant-garde jazz. This album doesn''t really fit that genre as it is essentially an homage to Cole Porter. Thom Jurek wrote this for allmusic.com in his review: "This may be the straightest record Cecil Taylor ever recorded, but it is far from uninspiring... <em>Love for Sale</em> is a delightful anomaly in Cecil Taylor''s long career".</p>\n<p>If you like what you hear also check out some of the other blog entries I''ve written on Cecil for more and make sure to check out his album <em>Jazz Advance</em>--it''s one of my favorites.</p>\n<p>Here''s Cecil with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bZxnPAIbpIE" target="_blank">Love for Sale</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bZxnPAIbpIE" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/MI0001580947.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Get Out of Town" (Cole Porter) - 9:12</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"I Love Paris" (Porter) - 5:11</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Love for Sale" (Porter) - 8:15</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Little Lees" (a.k.a. "Louise") - 9:04</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Matie''s Trophies" (a.k.a. "Motystrophe" or "Blues") - 10:13</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Carol/Three Points" - 8:16 Bonus track on CD</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 62, '2015-04-06 16:32:02', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:25:25', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-04-15 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 16, 'on this day in jazz Cecil Taylor', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1830, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(381, 'On this day in jazz (April 16)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-april-16', '', '<p>On this day in 1965,   pianist <a href="http://www.horacesilver.com/" target="_self">Horace Silver</a> began recording the songs that would appear on the live album <em>The Natives Are Restless Tonight</em>. The album is composed of songs recorded from three different concerts performed from April 16, 1965 until February 18, 1966. The personnel that appeared on this album were <a href="http://www.joehendersonsax.com/" target="_blank">Joe Henderson</a> on tenor saxophone, Carmell Jones / <a href="http://www.woodyshaw.com/" target="_blank">Woody Shaw</a> on trumpet, and a rhythm section of Horace Silver on the piano, Larry Ridley / Teddy Smith on bass and Roger Hamphries on the drums. What a great lineup.</p>\n<p>The album was released by Horace''s own label a couple of decades after the recordings were made. It features Horace''s great song "Song for My Father",<span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 15.8079996109009px;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 15.8079996109009px;">the title song, "The Natives are Restless Tonight", </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Que Pasa", and two versions of "The African Queen". The reason to get excited about the release is that Horace tended (like <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a>) not to be interested in playing songs later in his career that had made him famous earlier in his career. Jazz reviewer Scott Yanow said "this live set gives one a rare opportunity to hear his quintet stretching out on songs that were more familiar to them." If you''re not familiar with Horace, he truly is one of the greats, and this album was recorded during while he and the band were at the top of their game. </span></p>\n<p>Here''s Horace with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=klMU-4IBYM4" target="_blank">The Natives Are Restless Tonight</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=klMU-4IBYM4" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/2211107.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 15.8079996109009px;">"Song for My Father"</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 15.8079996109009px;">"The Natives are Restless Tonight"</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Que Pasa"</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 15.8079996109009px;">"The African Queen"</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 15.8079996109009px;">"The African Queen" [alternate take]</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 15.8079996109009px;"> </span></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 15.8079996109009px;"> </span></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 62, '2015-04-07 23:54:31', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:26:55', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-04-16 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 15, 'on this day in jazz, Horace Silver', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1844, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(382, 'On this day in jazz (April 17)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-april-17', '', '<p>On this day in 1956,   tenor saxophonist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Johnny_Griffin" target="_blank">Johnny Griffin</a> recorded his debut album <em>Introducing Johnny Griffin</em> at Rudy van Gelder''s studio in Hackensack, NJ. Joining Johnny were an all star rhythm section of <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/wynton-kelly-mn0000684253/biography" target="_blank">Wynton Kelly</a> at the piano, Curly Russell on bass and <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/max-roach-mn0000396372/biography" target="_blank">Max Roach</a> on drums--wow. By the way, it''s documented that Johnny and Rudy did not get along--the only time I''ve ever heard that Rudy didn''t have a good relationship with the artist.</p>\n<p>I know that Johnny isn''t a household name these days, but during the 1940s and 1950s he was in high demand--he just didn''t record that often as a leader. While he was in high school (DuSable High School in Chicago), Johnny played clarinet, oboe and alto saxophone. At the ripe old age of 15, he was a member of T-Bone Walker''s brother''s band (at this point <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/T-Bone_Walker" target="_blank">T-Bone</a> wasn''t a leader). Then, three days after graduating high school he was ''enlisted'' to play with <a href="http://www.uiweb.uidaho.edu/hampton/bio.html" target="_blank">Lionel Hampton</a>''s big band. It was Lionel that convinced Johnny to take up the tenor saxophone--and the rest, as they say, is history.</p>\n<p>I really wish that history had been a little kinder to Johnny (with respect to the credit that his name garners), but I think Johnny was pretty happy about how he lived his life--i.e., quite content to be one of the best saxophonists in the world, but not wanting to have the spotlight always shining on him.<span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Johnny moved to Europe in the 1963 and from that point onwards he was essentially the tenor sax in residence that all touring US leaders would pick up to play with them. Johnny passed away in 2008 at the wonderful age of 80 years--four days after his last concert. </span></p>\n<p>One last note on Johnny: in 1957 he recorded <em>A Blowin'' Session</em> with <a href="http://www.johncoltrane.com/" target="_blank">John Coltrane</a> and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hank_Mobley" target="_blank">Hank Mobley</a> (two of my favorite saxophonists). Johnny was nicknamed "The Fastest Tenor in the West" due to the ease he could execute runs of short notes while maintaining excellent intonations.</p>\n<p>Here''s Johnny with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GNLR76Ss2WY" target="_blank">Lover Man</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GNLR76Ss2WY" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/1356286465_folder.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Mildew" (Griffin) - 3:56</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Chicago Calling" (Griffin) - 5:38</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"These Foolish Things" (Link, Marvell, Strachey) - 5:12</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Boy Next Door" (Martin, Blane) - 4:57</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Nice and Easy" (Griffin) - 4:22</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"It''s All Right with Me" (Cole Porter) - 5:02</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Lover Man" (Davis, Ram Ramirez, Sherman) - 7:56</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 62, '2015-04-08 00:03:21', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:32:19', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-04-17 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 14, 'on this day in jazz, Johnny Griffin', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1813, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(383, 'On this day in jazz (April 18)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-april-18', '', '<p>On this day in 1969,   pianist <a href="http://www.herbiehancock.com/home.php" target="_blank">Herbie Hancock</a> began recording the album <em>The Prisoner</em> at Rudy van Gelder''s studio in Englewood Cliffs,   NJ. This was Herbie''s final album for Blue Note Records--and,   oh!, what a run it was. If you''ve never treated yourself to some of the greatest modern piano jazz ever written, skip back fifty years and listen to Herbie Hancock''s mid 1960s'' works. They sound as fresh today as they must have sounded back then--and that is why they stand the test of time.</p>\n<p>On the album, Herbie plays both standard and electric pianos, and just a short list of people who assisted on the recording were: Johnny Coles on flugelhorn, Garnett Brown on trombone, <a href="http://www.joehendersonsax.com/" target="_blank">Joe Henderson</a> on tenor saxophone and alto flute, Buster Williams on the bass, and Tootie Heath on the drums.</p>\n<p>If you are familiar with pop culture, you might think that the title is in some way related to the British cult classic TV show of the same name. It''s not. It was a social statement regarding "how black people have been imprisoned for a long time." (Herbie Hancock). For the song "Firewater", he said that it represents the social duality of the oppressor and the oppressed: the fire symbolizes the heat in violence and (abuse of) power, whilst the feeling of water recalls Martin Luther King. The song "He Who Lives in Fear" is also linked to King (due to the atmosphere of intimidation he worked in). You wouldn''t think that such a song would end up as a jingle--but it did for Silva Thins Cigarettes'' TV commercial. The song "Promise of the Sun" symbolizes "how the sun promises life and freedom to all living things, and yet blacks are not yet free."</p>\n<p>At the time of this writing (2015), Herbie is on tour with <a href="http://chickcorea.com/" target="_blank">Chick Corea</a>--go see them! Pretty much all the shows are already sold out, but you can still find tickets through brokers.</p>\n<p>Here''s Herbie with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NiCsgkhTp7Y" target="_blank">The Prisoner</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NiCsgkhTp7Y" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/20327362.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"I Have a Dream"  10:58</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Prisoner"  7:57</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Firewater" (Buster Williams)  7:33</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"He Who Lives in Fear"  6:51</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Promise of the Sun"  7:52</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 62, '2015-04-08 00:16:53', 62, '', '2016-08-20 00:55:02', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-04-18 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 7, 0, 13, 'on this day in jazz, Herbie Hancock', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1686, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(385, 'On this day in jazz (April 20)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-april-20', '', '<p>On this day in 1965,   the one and most definitely, only, <a href="http://www.sunraarkestra.com/" target="_blank">Sun Ra</a> recorded <em>The Heliocentric Worlds of Sun Ra, Volume One</em> at RLA Studio in New York City. The number of musicians who contributed to the album are too many to mention here, but suffice it to say that it was a very eclectic bunch comprising the standard jazz instruments (saxophones, trombones, flutes, clarinets, piano, bass and drums) plus some more unusual ones: electric <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Celesta" target="_blank">celeste</a>, timpani, piccolo, bells, <a href="http://www.serpentcymbals.com/images/Serpent%20scaled%20360.jpg" target="_blank">spiral cymbals</a> and woodblocks.</p>\n<p>Gene Tyranny reviewed the album, saying: "<span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">The astonishing sessions that went light years beyond ''free jazz'' improvisation to create a music of deeply felt explosive and gentle gesture made from sound itself without reference to previous notions of melody or harmony."</span></p>\n<p>Here''s Sun Ra with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JSueTJVavG0" target="_blank">Heliocentric</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JSueTJVavG0" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/rc2013037_530.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Heliocentric"  4:00</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Outer Nothingness"  7:40</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Other Worlds"  4:18</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Cosmos"  7:20</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Of Heavenly Things"  5:40</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Nebulae"  3:16</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Dancing in the Sun"  1:50</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 62, '2015-04-10 14:45:10', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:33:26', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-04-20 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 3, 0, 11, 'on this day in jazz, Sun Ra', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1733, 'robots=\nauthor=');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(386, 'On this day in jazz (April 21)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-april-21', '', '<p>On this day in 1967,   pianist <a href="http://mccoytyner.com/" target="_blank">McCoy Tyner</a> recorded the album <em>The Real McCoy</em> at Rudy van Gelder''s studio in Englewood Cliffs,   NJ. This album is his debut on the Blue Note label. Joining McCoy, who composed all of the songs on the album, was a true all star cast including <a href="http://www.joehendersonsax.com/" target="_blank">Joe Henderson</a> on tenor saxophone, <a href="http://roncarter.net/JazzMaster/" target="_blank">Ron Carter</a> on bass and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elvin_Jones" target="_blank">Elvin Jones</a> on drums.</p>\n<p>This is truly one of the greatest small ensemble albums recorded after 1965. It is part of the <em>Penguin Guide to Jazz</em>''s Core Collection, received a four and a half star rating from allmusic.com. While Penguin called the work the best in McCoy''s entire discography, Scott Yanow was a little more descriptive when writing for allmusic saying that it''s important because McCoy was entering a period of struggle in which he was growing tremendously--all of which comes out in the music. The song profile below is the fourth piece on the album, "Search for Peace", which McCoy titled not only due to its tranquil sound, but also because it "has to do with a man''s submission to God" and "giving over of the self to the universe" (quote from Nat Hentoff''s liner notes).</p>\n<p>Here''s McCoy playing "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LDYkdd1FkaA" target="_blank">Search for Peace</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LDYkdd1FkaA" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/tumblr_lda5ts7Rmw1qzn0deo1_1280.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Passion Dance"  8:47</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Contemplation"  9:12</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Four by Five"  6:37</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Search for Peace"  6:32</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Blues on the Corner"  5:58</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 62, '2015-04-10 14:49:52', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:33:42', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-04-21 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 10, 'on this day in jazz, McCoy Tyner', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1824, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(387, 'On this day in jazz (April 22)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-april-22', '', '<p style="color: #333333;">On this day in 1959,   Miles Davis completed recording what would become the most important jazz album of all time,  <em>Kind of Blue</em>. Miles was joined by an all-star cast with<a href="http://www.johncoltrane.com/" target="_blank" style="color: #333333; text-decoration: underline;">John Coltrane</a> on the tenor saxophone,<a href="http://www.cannonball-adderley.com/" target="_blank" style="color: #333333; text-decoration: underline;">Cannonball Adderley</a> on the alto sax,<a href="http://www.billevanswebpages.com/" target="_blank" style="color: #333333; text-decoration: underline;">Bill Evans</a>(all songs but "Freddy Freeloader") and<a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/wynton-kelly-mn0000684253/biography" target="_blank" style="color: #333333; text-decoration: underline;">Wynton Kelly</a> ("Freddy Freeloader") at the piano,<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Chambers" target="_blank" style="color: #333333; text-decoration: underline;">Paul Chambers</a> on the bass, and<a href="http://www.jimmycobb.net/" target="_blank" style="color: #333333; text-decoration: underline;">Jimmy Cobb</a> on the drums. On this day, the songs that would become side 2 of the album were recorded: "All Blues" and "Flamenco Sketches".</p>\n<p style="margin: 1em 0px; padding: 0px; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; line-height: 18px;">The importance of this album on the music world cannot be understated and it''s why the album is usually at the #1 spot on most jazz enthusiasts charts. In fact, it''s probably the reason I eventually was moved to create this blog. You can find the album in mono, stereo, SACD format, and DVD audio. On some of the legacy editions they''ve even included the banter between Miles and the engineers and musicians--which is quite interesting to hear. On December 16, 2009, the United States House of Representatives passed a resolution which honored the albums 50th anniversary, "reaffirming jazz as a national treasure". If you want to learn more about the album, check out Ashley Khan''s<em><a href="http://www.amazon.com/Kind-Blue-Making-Miles-Masterpiece/dp/0306815583/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&ie=UTF8&qid=1424110432&sr=1-1&keywords=kind+of+blue" target="_blank" style="color: #333333; text-decoration: underline;">Kind of Blue: The Making of the Miles Davis Masterpiece</a></em><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">. It''s well written and is full of wonderful photos.</span></p>\n<p style="margin: 1em 0px; padding: 0px; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; line-height: 18px;"><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Here''s Miles with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uRBgy43gCoQ" target="_blank">All Blues</a>":</span></p>\n<p style="margin: 1em 0px; padding: 0px; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; line-height: 18px;"><span style="line-height: 1.3em;"><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uRBgy43gCoQ" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/milesdavis3.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a><br /></span></p>\n<p style="margin: 1em 0px; padding: 0px; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; line-height: 18px;">In addition to <em>Kind of Blue</em>, April 22nd is also very important due to the songs Miles recorded on this day in 1949. Those songs would later be released on one of the best albums of all time, <em>Birth of the Cool</em>. If you want to start building a jazz collection, get this album and then branch out to recordings made by the other personnel on the album such asKai Winding, J. J. Johnson, Lee Konitz, Gerry Mulligan, Al Haig, John Lewis, Al McKibbon, Max Roach and Kenny Clarke.</p>\n<p style="margin: 1em 0px; padding: 0px; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; line-height: 18px;">Here''s one of those songs (which happens to be one of my absolute favorites): "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1X6h2TxA18c">Venus de Milo</a>":</p>\n<p style="margin: 1em 0px; padding: 0px; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; line-height: 18px;"><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1X6h2TxA18c" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Birth_of_the_Cool.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 62, '2015-04-15 17:20:17', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:34:31', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-04-22 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 9, 'on this day in jazz, Miles Davis, Kind of Blue, Birth of the Cool', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2129, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(388, 'On this day in jazz (April 23)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-april-23', '', '<p>On this day in 1967,   <a href="http://www.johncoltrane.com/" target="_blank">John Coltrane</a> was recorded in his live performance for Billy Taylor''s radio show on WLIB. Two songs were recorded on this date: "Ogunde" and "My Favorite Things". While "My Favorite Things" was a Coltrane staple throughout the 1960s,   "Ogunde" was a new song that ended up being part of his final album,   <em>Expression</em>. John was joined by <a href="https://pharoahsanders.wordpress.com/" target="_blank">Pharoah Sanders</a> on tenor sax, Alice Coltrane on piano, Jimmy Garrison on bass, and Rashied Ali & Algie DeWitt on drums/percussion.</p>\n<p>Although there were rumors that John was very ill and unable to stand during the session, Rashied Ali said that this was not the case--he said that John may have just been tired that day. However, less than a month after this show, John started complaining of intense abdominal pain; he died in July 1967 from liver cancer at the age of 40. Please note, that this was not Coltrane''s last show, just the last recorded one. His last show was in Baltimore on May 7.</p>\n<p>Here''s John with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EPGsroRcEU4" target="_blank">Ogunde</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EPGsroRcEU4" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Frontal.jpg" border="0" height="250" /><img src="images/tdij/Posterior.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 62, '2015-04-15 17:36:59', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:34:48', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-04-23 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 8, 'on this day in jazz, John Coltrane', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2099, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(389, 'On this day in jazz (April 24)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-april-24', '', '<p>On this day in 1962,   tenor saxophonist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Teddy_Edwards" target="_blank">Teddy Edwards</a> recorded the studio album Heart & Soul. Teddy was joined by Gerry Wiggins on organ,   Leroy Vinnegar on bass and Milt Turner on the drums. The interesting thing about the album is the use of organ instead of piano (Gerry''s primary instrument). Although Gerry is definitely no <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jimmy_Smith_(musician)" target="_blank">Jimmy Smith</a>,   the album is still pretty good as Teddy was in excellent form.</p>\n<p>Teddy was born in Jackson, MS, and played with many of jazz''s greats such as <a href="http://www.cmgww.com/music/parker/home.html" target="_blank">Charlie Parker</a> (his close personal friend), <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vince_Guaraldi" target="_blank">Vince Guaraldi</a> and Joe Castro. His real fame began when he recorded <em>The Duel</em> in 1947 with <a href="http://www.dextergordon.com/" target="_blank">Dexter Gordon</a>. Throughout his life he would challenge other sax players to similar duels.</p>\n<p>Here''s Teddy with a great version of Hoagy Carmichaels standard, "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fPrE9A1WO0E" target="_blank">Heart and Soul</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fPrE9A1WO0E" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/has.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Smokin''" (Teddy Edwards, Gerry Wiggins) - 6:08</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"No Regrets" - 4:48</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Secret Love" (Sammy Fain, Paul Francis Webster) - 8:22</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Little Steddy" - 6:08</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Wiggin''" (Wiggins) - 6:27</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"A Bag of Blues" - 6:22</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Heart and Soul" (Hoagy Carmichael, Frank Loesser) - 3:29</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 62, '2015-04-15 18:20:28', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:35:25', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-04-24 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 7, 'on this day in jazz, Teddy Edwards', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2324, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(390, 'On this day in jazz (April 25)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-april-25', '', '<p>On this day in 1965,   the great <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/max-roach-mn0000396372/biography" target="_blank">Max Roach</a> completed recording the studio album <em>Drums Unlimited</em>. Assisting Max on the album were <a href="http://www.freddiehubbardmusic.com/" target="_blank">Freddie Hubbard</a> on trumpet,   Roland Alexander on soprano saxophone,   James Spaulding on alto saxophone, Ronnie Mathews on piano and Jymie Merritt on bass. There is a significant amount of Max on this one, so if you''re into drums, this one is for you.</p>\n<p>Max is pretty much on everyone''s list of the top 10 jazz drummers of all time. Max had a very long career and garnered a long list of awards and accolades. Here''s a select list of them:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">1988 MacArthur Foundation "genius" grant</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">1989 Commander of the Order of Arts and Letters in France</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">French Grand Prix du Disque (2x)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">International Percussive Art Society''s Hall of Fame</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Downbeat Magazine Hall of Fame</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Harvard Jazz Master</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">eight honorary doctorate degrees</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Here''s Max with </span><em style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;"><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=e6xiYL-T494" target="_blank">Drums Unlimited</a></em><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">:</span></p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=e6xiYL-T494" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/maxroach.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Drum Also Waltzes" - 3:34</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Nommo" (Jymie Merritt) - 12:43</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Drums Unlimited" - 4:23</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"St. Louis Blues" (W.C. Handy) - 5:22</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"For Big Sid" - 3:04</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"In the Red (A Christmas Carol)" - 12:21</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 62, '2015-04-16 16:56:47', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:35:48', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-04-25 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 6, 'on this day in jazz, Max Roach', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2032, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(391, 'On this day in jazz (April 26)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-april-26', '', '<p>On this day in 1945,   <a href="http://www.dukeellington.com/" target="_blank">Duke Ellington</a> (and his famous orchestra) recorded one of my favorite songs, "Kissing Bug". Joya Sherril'' performed the vocals and shared the writing credit with <a href="http://www.billystrayhorn.com/" target="_blank">Billy Strayhorn</a>. If Duke isn''t a big part of your collection, try to find <em><a href="http://www.amazon.com/Black-Brown-Beige-Duke-Ellington/dp/B000002WA4/ref=sr_1_2?s=music&ie=UTF8&qid=1429203602&sr=1-2&keywords=black+brown+and+beige" target="_blank">Black, Brown & Beige</a> </em>as it includes this song an many many other Duke Ellington classics (including another vocal of Joya''s "I''m Beginning to see the Light".</p>\n<p>Here''s Duke and Joya with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IPTmGU_9BKE" target="_blank">Kissing Bug</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IPTmGU_9BKE" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/dukejoya.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 62, '2015-04-16 17:05:10', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:36:14', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-04-26 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 5, 'on this day in jazz, Duke Ellington', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2010, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(392, 'On this day in jazz (April 27)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-april-27', '', '<p>On this day in 1957,   trumpeter <a href="http://clarkterry.com/" target="_blank">Clark Terry</a> recorded the album <em>Serenade to a Bus Seat</em> at Reeves Sound Studios in New York City. Clark was assisted on the album by an all-star cast of <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/johnny-griffin-mn0000213510/biography" target="_blank">Johnny Griffin</a> on the tenor saxophone, <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/wynton-kelly-mn0000684253/biography" target="_blank">Wynton Kelly</a> on piano, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Chambers" target="_blank">Paul Chambers</a> on bass and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philly_Joe_Jones" target="_blank">Philly Joe Jones</a> on the drums. What a wonderful lineup with possibly one of the greatest rhythm sections ever. Clark wrote five of the eight songs himself including the title track. If you''re wondering which bus seat he is referring to, it''s related to his time on the road with yesterday''s profiled artist, <a href="http://www.dukeellington.com/" target="_blank">Duke Ellington</a>.</p>\n<p>If you''re familiar with Clark you''ll know that he''s a multi-instrumentalist. Less than a year later, he pretty much switched over to flugelhorn, so this is one of his last leading on trumpet before that switch. If you want to check him out on flugelhorn, I suggest <em>In Orbit</em> from 1958 where he was accompanied by another all-star rhythm section (<a href="http://www.monkzone.com/" target="_blank">Thelonious Monk</a>, Sam Jones and Philly Joe Jones). FYI, I''ll profile <em>In Orbit</em> on May 7.</p>\n<p>Here''s Clark with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ALm_gwRXZGM" target="_blank">Serenade to a Bus Seat</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ALm_gwRXZGM" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Clark_Mumbles_Terry.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Donna Lee" (Charlie Parker) - 4:04</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Boardwalk" - 7:01</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Boomerang" - 6:01</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Digits" - 4:08</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Serenade to a Bus Seat" - 4:37</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Stardust" (Hoagy Carmichael, Mitchell Parish) - 5:15</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Cruising" - 8:27</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"That Old Black Magic" (Harold Arlen, Johnny Mercer) - 1:59</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 62, '2015-04-16 17:18:31', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:36:30', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-04-27 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 4, 'on this day in jazz, Clark Terry', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1992, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(393, 'On this day in jazz (April 28)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-april-28', '', '<p>On this day in 1958,   trombonist <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/bennie-green-mn0000160618/biography" target="_blank">Bennie Green</a> recorded the album Soul Stirrin'' at Rudy van Gelder''s studio in Hackensack,   NJ for Blue Note Records. Alfred Lion produced this classic. Bennie was assisted on the album by <a href="http://www.geneammons.net/" target="_blank">Gene Ammons</a> and Billy Root on tenor saxophones, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sonny_Clark" target="_blank">Sonny Clark</a> on piano, Ike Isaacs on bass and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elvin_Jones" target="_blank">Elvin Jones</a> on drums. Babs Gonzales and Bennie provided "vocals".</p>\n<p>Bennie''s style has been described as laid-back and friendly, and this album is a good example of that.</p>\n<p>Here''s Bennie with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VZyFKfPyi6Q" target="_blank">Soul Stirrin''</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VZyFKfPyi6Q"><img src="images/tdij/imagesCA7DCMAT.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Soul Stirrin''" (Babs Gonzales) - 6:50</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"We Wanna Cook" - 6:38</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"That''s All" (Alan Brandt, Bob Haymes) - 6:25</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Lullaby of the Doomed" (Gonzales) - 6:01</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"B. G. Mambo" - 8:15</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Black Pearl" (Bill Graham) - 5:45</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 62, '2015-04-17 17:33:57', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:36:57', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-04-28 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 3, 'on this day in jazz, Bennie Green', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1998, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(394, 'On this day in jazz (April 29)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-april-29', '', '<p>On this day in 1969,   <a href="http://www.charliehadenmusic.com/" target="_blank">Charlie Haden</a> completed recording the album <em>Liberation Music Orchestra</em>--his first as a leader. The Orchestra that Charlie assembled was 13 members strong including <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dewey_Redman" target="_blank">Dewey Redman</a> on the alto & tenor saxophones,   <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Don_Cherry_%28trumpeter%29" target="_blank">Don Cherry</a> on cornet,   flute, Indian wood & bamboo flutes, <a href="http://www.roswellrudd.com/docs/main/frame.htm" target="_blank">Roswell Rudd</a> on trombone, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Motian" target="_blank">Paul Motian</a> on drums and, of course, Charlie on bass. The Orchestra would record three more times over the next quarter century: <em>The Ballad of the Fallen</em> (ECM, 1982), <em>Dream Keeper</em> (Blue Note, 1990) and <em>Not in Our Name</em> (Verve, 2005).</p>\n<p>Charlie said that songs from the Spanish Civil War are what inspired him to create the music for this album. In fact, three songs ("El Quinto Regimiento", "Los Cuatro Generales", and "Viva la Quince Brigada") are Spanish folk songs that were given new lyrics during the war. The album also contains an <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ornette_Coleman" target="_blank">Ornette Coleman</a> song, "War Orphans", three songs by Carla Bley and two original compositions. The first of the originals, "Song for Che" is of course dedicated to <a href="http://en.wikiquote.org/wiki/Che_Guevara" target="_blank">Che Guevara</a>. If you''d like to learn more about Charlie, there is a movie about his life titled <em>Rambling Boy</em> (2009). Some of the accolades bestowed on Charlie:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">2012: NEA Jazz Masters Award.</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">2013: Grammy Lifetime Achievement Award. </span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">2014: Chevalier de l''Ordre des Arts et des Lettres by the French Ministry of Culture. </span></li>\n</ul>\n<p></p>\n<p>Here''s Charlie with the trilogy "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Z-JdKhfPu98" target="_blank">El Quinto Regimiento / Los Cuatro Generales / Viva la Quince Brigada</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Z-JdKhfPu98" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Liberation_Music_Orchestra.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Introduction" (Bley) / "Song of the United Front" (Brecht, Eisler)  3:07</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"El Quinto Regimiento" ("The Fifth Regiment") (trad., arr. Bley)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Los Cuatro Generales" ("The Four Generals") (trad., arr. Bley)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Viva la Quince Brigada" ("Long Live the Fifteenth Brigade") (melody trad., words Bart Van Derschelling)  20:58</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Ending to the First Side" (Bley)  2:07</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Song for Ch" (Haden)  9:29</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"War Orphans" (Coleman)  6:42</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Interlude (Drinking Music)" (Bley)  1:24</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Circus ''68 ''69" (Haden)  6:10</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"We Shall Overcome" (Horton, Hamilton, Carawan, Seeger) 1:19</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 62, '2015-04-17 17:56:46', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:37:32', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-04-29 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 2, 'on this day in jazz, Charlie Haden', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 1998, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(396, 'On this day in jazz (May 01)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-may-01', '', '<p style="text-align: left;">On this day in 1958,  trumpeter <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/art-farmer-mn0000502199/biography" target="_blank">Art Farmer</a> completed the recording of the album <em>Portrait of Art Farmer</em>. Joining Art on the album were Hank Jones on piano,   Addison Farmer on bass and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roy_Haynes" target="_blank">Roy Haynes</a> on drums. Essentially, this album was recorded shortly after Art left <a href="http://www.horacesilver.com/" target="_blank">Horace Silver</a>''s quintet and prior to his joining the pianonless <a href="http://www.gerrymulligan.com/" target="_blank">Gerry Mulligan</a> Quartet.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>The album received allmusic.com''a highest rating and the <em>Penguin Guide to Jazz</em> selected it as part of its Core Collection. Penguin said this of the album: "The rhythm section is beautifully balanced and offers exemplary support to the leader, whose playing summons elegance, fire and craftsmanship in almost perfect accord, with his ballad playing particularly refined".</p>\n<p>Here''s Art with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=phzCxs-KtqQ" target="_self">Stablemates</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=phzCxs-KtqQ" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Art_Farmer_beim_MPS_Festival_1971_(Heinrich_Klaffs_Collection_20).jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Back in the Cage"  5:04</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Stablemates" (Benny Golson)  4:32</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Very Thought of You" (Ray Noble)  5:41</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"And Now..."  6:07</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Nita" (George Russell)  4:28</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"By Myself" (Howard Dietz, Arthur Schwartz)  6:15</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Too Late Now" (Burton Lane, Alan Jay Lerner)  5:55</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Earth"  4:10</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 63, '2015-04-26 15:12:41', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:38:15', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-05-01 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 31, 'on this day in jazz, Art Farmer', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2087, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(397, 'On this day in jazz (May 02)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-may-02', '', '<p>On this day in 1963,   trumpeter <a href="http://www.freddiehubbardmusic.com/" target="_blank">Freddie Hubbard</a> completed recording the album <em>The Body and the Soul</em> at Rudy van Gelder''s studio in Englewood Cliffs,   NJ (on this day) and Capitol Studios in New York City for other sessions. The album was recorded in three different sessions with three different sets of personnel. On this day,   tracks #1, #4 and #5 were recorded with and incredible cast including <a href="http://www.wayneshorter.com/" target="_blank">Wayne Shorter</a> on tenor saxophone, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Curtis_Fuller" target="_blank">Curtis Fuller</a> on trombone, the great <a href="http://www.ericdolphy.net/" target="_blank">Eric Dolphy</a> on alto saxophone and flute, the wonderful <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/cedar-walton-mn0000741325/biography" target="_blank">Cedar Walton</a> at the piano, <a href="http://sculpturedsounds.com/" target="_blank">Reggie Workman</a> on bass, and Louis Hayes on the drums.</p>\n<p>This album was Freddie''s eighth as a leader and his last for the Impulse! label. On some of the other tracks you''ll hear Freddie backed by orchestra and string section. Rating and reviewing service allmusic.com gave the album a strong four star rating--so give it a listen, it''s really a wonderful and diverse work.</p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Here''s Freddie with the title track "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=48fiNLK39Xs" target="_blank">Body and Soul</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=48fiNLK39Xs" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Freddie_Hubbard1_medium.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Body and Soul" (Heyman, Sour, Eyton, Green) - 4:39;</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Carnival (Manha de Carnaval)" (Bonf, Creatore, Peretti, Weiss) - 5:21</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Chocolate Shake" (Ellington, Webster) - 3:58</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Dedicated to You" (Cahn, Chaplin, Zaret) - 3:24</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Clarence''s Place" - 3:31</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Aries" - 3:07</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Skylark" (Carmichael, Mercer) - 4:34</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"I Got It Bad (And That Ain''t Good)" (Ellington, Webster) - 3:43</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Thermo" - 4:15</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 63, '2015-04-26 15:18:02', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:38:29', 62, 62, '2016-08-17 21:54:14', '2015-05-02 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 30, 'on this day in jazz, Freddie Hubbard', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2222, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(398, 'On this day in jazz (May 03)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-may-03', '', '<p>On this day in 1976,   saxophonist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eddie_%22Lockjaw%22_Davis" target="_blank">Eddie "Lockjaw" Davis</a> and the Tommy Flanagan Trio recorded the album Straight Ahead. The trio in support we actually Ella Fitzgerald''s trio at the time as consisted of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tommy_Flanagan" target="_blank">Tommy Flanagan</a> at the piano,  Keter Betts on the bass,   and Bobby Durham on the drums. All but one of the songs are covers (Eddie wrote "The Chef"); however, it''s still really interesting to hear some of these standards covered by this group--especially <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ant%C3%B4nio_Carlos_Jobim" target="_blank">Antonio Carlos Jobim</a>''s song "Wave". "Lover" and "On a Clear Day (You Can See Forever)" are very good also.</p>\n<p>Scott Yanow of allmusic.com said this of the album:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">A perfect example of Eddie "Lockjaw" Davis'' playing, this superior quartet set (a Pablo date that has been reissued on CD) features the tough-toned tenor swinging hard on standards, showing his warmth on ballads, and coming up with inventive ideas within the swing/bop tradition.... Lockjaw sounds at his best on such numbers as "Lover," "On a Clear Day," and even "The Good Life."</p>\n<p>If this album interests you, then also check out <em>Live at the Widder</em>.</p>\n<p><img src="images/tdij/6a00e008dca1f088340192ac0b7f14970d-500wi.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Lover (Jimmie Davis / Lorenz Hart / Roger "Ram" Ramirez / Richard Rodgers / Jimmy Sherman) 4:41</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Wave (Antonio Carlos Jobim) 5:20</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">On a Clear Day (You Can See Forever) (Burton Lane / Alan Jay Lerner) 4:05</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">The Chef (Eddie "Lockjaw" Davis) 3:52</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Gigi (Alan Jay Lerner / Frederick Loewe) 4:22</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Last Train from Overbrook (James Moody) 6:19</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">The Good Life (Sacha Distel / Jack Reardon) 5:08</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">I''ll Never Be the Same (Gus Kahn / Matty Malneck / Frank Signorelli) 5:13</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Watch What Happens (Michel Legrand) 5:59</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 63, '2015-04-26 16:59:32', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:40:49', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-05-03 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 29, 'on this day in jazz, Eddie Lockjaw Davis', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2329, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(399, 'On this day in jazz (May 04)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-may-04', '', '<p>On this day in 1959,   the great <a href="http://www.johncoltrane.com/" target="_blank">John Coltrane</a> began recording on of my favorite albums,   <em>Giant Steps</em>. Joining John''s tenor saxophone were <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tommy_Flanagan" target="_blank">Tommy Flanagan</a> and <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/wynton-kelly-mn0000684253/biography" target="_blank">Wynton Kelly</a> on the piano, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Chambers" target="_blank">Paul Chambers</a> on bass, <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/art-taylor-mn0000505154/biography" target="_blank">Art Taylor</a> and <a href="http://www.jimmycobb.net/" target="_blank">Jimmy Cobb</a> on the drums. These men truly played well together. Remember that just two weeks earlier, John, Wynton, Paul and Jimmy recorded <em>Kind of Blue</em> with <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a>,<a href="http://www.cannonball-adderley.com/" target="_blank">Cannonball Adderley</a> and <a href="http://www.billevanswebpages.com/" target="_blank">Bill Evans</a>.</p>\n<p>The album is truly one of the greatest jazz albums of all time (<a href="http://jazz100.sffjazz.com/top100.html" target="_blank">sffjazz</a> ranks it #7). In 2004 the Library of Congress added the album to the National Recording Registry (only fifty albums across all genres are selected each year). It is also selected as part of the <em>Penguin Guide to Jazz</em>''s "Core Collection" with the appelation: "(it was) Trane''s first genuinely iconic record.". Also, in 2003, Rolling Stone magazine''s list of the 500 greatest albums of all time listed it at #103</p>\n<p>As part of the Atlantic 50th Anniversary Jazz Gallery series (in 1998) it was re-released with eight bonus tracks, so try and get that version if you are going to add it to your library.</p>\n<p>Here''s John with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=30FTr6G53VU" target="_blank">Giant Steps</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=30FTr6G53VU" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/coltrane-giant-steps-1600-cover.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Giant Steps" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">4:43</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Cousin Mary" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">5:45</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Countdown" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">2:21</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Spiral" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">5:56</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Syeeda''s Song Flute" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">7:00</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Naima" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">4:21</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Mr. P.C." 6:57</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 63, '2015-04-26 17:25:18', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:41:10', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-05-04 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 28, 'on this day in jazz, John Coltrane', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2464, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(400, 'Changing audio channels (left to right, right to left), etc.', 'changing-audio-channels-left-to-right-right-to-left-etc', '', '<p>On this day in 1959,   the great <a href="http://www.johncoltrane.com/" target="_blank">John Coltrane</a> began recording on of my favorite albums,   <em>Giant Steps</em>. Joining John''s tenor saxophone were <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tommy_Flanagan" target="_blank">Tommy Flanagan</a> and <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/wynton-kelly-mn0000684253/biography" target="_blank">Wynton Kelly</a> on the piano, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Chambers" target="_blank">Paul Chambers</a> on bass, <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/art-taylor-mn0000505154/biography" target="_blank">Art Taylor</a> and <a href="http://www.jimmycobb.net/" target="_blank">Jimmy Cobb</a> on the drums. These men truly played well together. Remember that just two weeks earlier, John, Wynton, Paul and Jimmy recorded <em>Kind of Blue</em> with <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a>,<a href="http://www.cannonball-adderley.com/" target="_blank">Cannonball Adderley</a> and <a href="http://www.billevanswebpages.com/" target="_blank">Bill Evans</a>.</p>\n<p>The album is truly one of the greatest jazz albums of all time (<a href="http://jazz100.sffjazz.com/top100.html" target="_blank">sffjazz</a> ranks it #7). In 2004 the Library of Congress added the album to the National Recording Registry (only fifty albums across all genres are selected each year). It is also selected as part of the <em>Penguin Guide to Jazz</em>''s "Core Collection" with the appelation: "(it was) Trane''s first genuinely iconic record.". Also, in 2003, Rolling Stone magazine''s list of the 500 greatest albums of all time listed it at #103</p>\n<p>As part of the Atlantic 50th Anniversary Jazz Gallery series (in 1998) it was re-released with eight bonus tracks, so try and get that version if you are going to add it to your library.</p>\n<p>Here''s John with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=30FTr6G53VU" target="_blank">Giant Steps</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=30FTr6G53VU" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/coltrane-giant-steps-1600-cover.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Giant Steps" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">4:43</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Cousin Mary" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">5:45</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Countdown" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">2:21</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Spiral" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">5:56</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Syeeda''s Song Flute" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">7:00</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Naima" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">4:21</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Mr. P.C." 6:57</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>\n<p>Here''s a short tutorial on how to switch audio channels for your music. First,   get the tool ffmpeg. Here''s a link to another tutorial on how to compile it on linux (they have tutorials for other OSs,   too): <a href="https://trac.ffmpeg.org/wiki/CompilationGuide/Ubuntu" target="_blank">https://trac.ffmpeg.org/wiki/CompilationGuide/Ubuntu</a></p>\n<p>Once you have ffmpeg installed,   what you need to do to switch an audio channel from right to left and left to right is the following statement:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">ffmpeg -i input.mp3 -af "pan=stereo|c0</span></p>\n<p>I did the above to switch audio channels for one of my Coltrane albums because I was camped out on my deck beside one speaker and was only really hearing the rhythm section. Switching the channels allowed me to hear John first with the rhythm section in the background.</p>\n<p>Another thing you might want to do is to mix both channels into both channels. That way you can sit by one speaker and hear both John and the rhythm section all together. It is pretty simple to accomplish--just do this:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">ffmpeg -i input.mp3 -af "pan=stereo|c0</span></p>\n<p>Now that you have the hang of it, just put it in a loop to get all the songs in a directory:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">for i in *.mp3; do ffmpeg -i $i -af "pan=stereo|c0</span></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">After running the command above, you''ll have another set of recordings prefixed with the letter "o" then with the same name as the originals. You could just create a new directory and redirect the output there with the original file names.</span></p>\n<p>More examples are <a href="https://trac.ffmpeg.org/wiki/AudioChannelManipulation" target="_blank">here</a>:</p>', '', 0, 7, 0, 51, '2015-04-27 15:23:40', 62, '', '2015-04-27 15:33:01', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-04-27 15:12:35', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 6, 0, 1, '', '', 0, 0, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(401, 'On this day in jazz (May 05)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-may-05', '', '<p>On this day in 1959,   the great <a href="http://mingusmingusmingus.com/" target="_blank">Charles Mingus</a> began recording the studio album <em>Mingus Ah Um</em> at Columbia 30th Street Studio in New York City (you''ll recall that <em>Kind of Blue</em> was finished there 2 weeks prior to this recording). The personnel on this work were: John Handy on alto sax clarinet and tenor sax,   Booker Ervin on tenor sax, Shafi Hadi on tenor and alto sax, Willie Dennis and Jimmy Knepper on trombone, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Horace_Parlan" target="_blank">Horace Parlan</a> on piano, Charles Mingus on bass (and piano track 10) and Dannie Richmond on the drums.</p>\n<p>The album, like yesterday''s profiled album, <em>Giant Steps</em>, is one of the greatest jazz albums of all time and was chosen by the Library of Congress to be added to the National Recording Registry in 2003. The album is rated #3 by <a href="http://jazz100.sffjazz.com/top100.html" target="_blank">sffjazz</a> behind <em>Kind of Blue</em> and Coltrane''s <em>A Love Supreme </em>and all rating services give this album their highest ratings. One bit of trivia for the album: the recordings didn''t fit on the new technology of the day (long playing disc or LP) in their originally intended form--so they were shortened to fit the LP format for their original release. Now that we are less constrained by things such as physical space, the album has been re-released with the songs played at their intended lengths.</p>\n<p>There''s really little else I feel I need to say as the album''s music says it all. However, if you want to know more about the songs, take a look at wikipedia''s <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mingus_Ah_Um" target="_blank">article</a>.</p>\n<p>Here''s Charles with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Z-R11B7EGt0" target="_blank">Better Git It in Your Soul</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Z-R11B7EGt0" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Mingus_Ah_Um_-_Charles_Mingus.jpg" border="0" height="250" /><img src="images/tdij/613fF+gkC4L.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Better Git It in Your Soul"  7:23</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Goodbye Pork Pie Hat"  5:44 (4:46)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Boogie Stop Shuffle"  5:02 (3:41)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Self-Portrait in Three Colors"  3:10</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Open Letter to Duke"  5:51 (4:56)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Bird Calls"  6:17 (3:12)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Fables of Faubus"  8:13</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Pussy Cat Dues"  9:14 (6:27)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Jelly Roll"  6:17 (4:01)</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p>Times in parentheses are the times of the songs for the LP format. The songs were later released with their intended length. Tracks 1, 6, 7, 8, 9 and 10 recorded on May 5, 1959, the rest were recorded on May 12.</p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 63, '2015-04-27 16:31:35', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:41:29', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-05-05 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 27, 'on this day in jazz, Charles Mingus', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2225, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(402, 'On this day in jazz (May 06)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-may-06', '', '<p>On this day in 1961,   one of jazz''s true greats,   <a href="http://www.dextergordon.com/" target="_blank">Dexter Gordon</a>,   recorded the album <em>Doin'' Allright</em> at Rudy van Gelder''s studio in Englewood Cliffs, NJ. On the album you''ll find Dexter on the tenor sax, <a href="http://www.freddiehubbardmusic.com/" target="_blank">Freddie Hubbard</a> on trumpet, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Horace_Parlan" target="_blank">Horace Parlan</a> (who was also on yesterday''s featured work, <em>Mingus Ah Um</em>) on piano, George Tucker on bass and Al Harewood at the drums.</p>\n<p>Scott Yanow reviewed the album for allmusic.com, giving it a four star rating and saying that:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">The title of this Blue Note set, Doin'' Allright, fit perfectly at the time, for tenor saxophonist Dexter Gordon was making the first of three successful comebacks. Largely neglected during the 1950s, Gordon''s Blue Note recordings (of which this was the first) led to his rediscovery</p>\n<p>Here''s Dexter with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fBQxsQlPDkU" target="_blank">Society Red</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fBQxsQlPDkU" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/dexter-gordon-doin-alright-front-1600.jpg" border="0" height="250" /><img src="images/tdij/dexter-gordon-doin-alright-back-1600.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"I Was Doing All Right" (George Gershwin, Ira Gershwin) - 9:18</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"You''ve Changed" (Bill Carey, Carl T. Fischer) - 7:26</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"For Regulars Only" - 5:45</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Society Red" - 12:21</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"It''s You or No One" (Sammy Cahn, Jule Styne) - 6:13</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 63, '2015-04-27 16:44:11', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:42:06', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-05-06 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 26, 'on this day in jazz, Dexter Gordon', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2298, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(403, 'On this day in jazz (May 07)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-may-07', '', '<p>On this day in 1958,   <a href="http://clarkterry.com/" target="_blank">Clark Terry</a> recorded <em>In Orbit</em> with <a href="http://www.monkzone.com/" target="_blank">Thelonious Monk</a>. Besides Terry on flugelhorn and Thelonious at the piano, Sam Jones played bass and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philly_Joe_Jones" target="_blank">Philly Joe Jones</a> played the drums. It''s a little bit unusual to see Thelonious Monk as a sideman at this point in his career, but this one is definitely all about Clark. Clark wrote most of the songs on the album, but Thelonious did add one, "Let''s Cool One".</p>\n<p>allmusic.com gave the album four and a half stars in a review by Scott Yanow who especially recommends the following two songs: "One Foot in the Gutter" and "Argentia."</p>\n<p>Clark sadly passed away back in February of this year (2015), but was still going strong until his passing. Clark amassed over 250 awards over his long career and here are some of the highlights:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Inducted into the Jazz at Lincoln Center Nesuhi Ertegun Jazz Hall of Fame (2013)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">The 2010 Grammy Lifetime Achievement Award, two Grammy certificates, three Grammy nominations</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">The National Endowment for the Arts Jazz Master Award (1991)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Sixteen honorary doctorates</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Jazz Ambassador for U.S. State Department tours in the Middle East and Africa</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">A knighthood in Germany</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">The French Order of Arts and Letters (2000)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Trumpeter of the Year by the Jazz Journalists Association (2005)</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Here''s Clark with "</span><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xUIFAMNjgmM" target="_blank" style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">One Foot in the Gutter</a><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">":</span></p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xUIFAMNjgmM" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/20121231_1.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>(image from his blog site)</p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"In Orbit" (Terry)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"One Foot in the Gutter (Terry)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Trust in Me"</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Let''s Cool One" (Monk)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Pea-Eye" (Terry)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Argentina" (Terry)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Moonlight Fiesta" (Mills, Tizol)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Buck''s Business" (Terry)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Very Near Blue" (Cassey)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Flugelin'' the Blues" (Terry)</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 63, '2015-04-29 14:29:25', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:42:31', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-05-07 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 25, 'on this day in jazz, Clark Terry', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2380, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(404, 'On this day in jazz (May 08)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-march-08', '', '<p>On this day in 1957,   the wonderful <a href="http://www.horacesilver.com/" target="_blank">Horace Silver</a> recorded the album <em>The Stylings of Silver</em> at Rudy van Gelder''s studio in Hackensack,   NJ. Horace had some excellent help on this album from <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/art-farmer-mn0000502199/biography" target="_blank">Art Farmer</a> on trumpet, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hank_Mobley" target="_blank">Hank Mobley</a> on tenor saxophone, Teddy Kotick on bass, and Louis Hayes on the drums. Alfred Lion produced the album. This is a follow up to the very popular <em>Six Pieces of Silver</em> (which I profiled on <a href="index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=224:on-this-day-in-jazz-november-10&catid=57:november&Itemid=41" target="_self">November 10</a>).</p>\n<p>Although this is definitely not his best album, it''s very listenable, especially "Soulville", "My One and Only Love" and "Home Cookin''." Horace wrote all of the songs on the album except for "My One and Only Love". Scott Yanow gave the album a three and a half star rating calling it "consistently superb and swinging".</p>\n<p>Here''s Horace with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MtexiPL3KTE" target="_blank">Home Cookin''</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MtexiPL3KTE" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/The_Stylings_of_Silver.jpg" border="0" height="250" /><img src="images/tdij/Horace Silver - Stylings of Silver (back).jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"No Smokin''" - 5:33</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Back Beat" - 6:23</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Soulville" - 6:16</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Home Cookin''" - 6:28</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Metamorphosis" - 7:18</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"My One and Only Love" - (Robert Mellin, Guy Wood) - 6:59</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 63, '2015-04-29 14:43:23', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:42:45', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-05-08 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 24, 'on this day in jazz, Horace Silver', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2448, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(405, 'On this day in jazz (May 09)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-may-09', '', '<p>On this day in 1961,   <a href="http://www.dextergordon.com/" target="_blank">Dexter Gordon</a> recorded the album <em>Dexter Calling</em> at Rudy van Gelder''s studio in Englewood Cliffs, NJ. Dexter''s tenor sax is joined by and all-star rhythm section composed of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kenny_Drew" target="_blank">Kenny Drew</a> at the piano, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Chambers" target="_blank">Paul Chambers</a> on bass, and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philly_Joe_Jones" target="_blank">Philly Joe Jones</a> at the drums.</p>\n<p>Michael G. Nastos reviewed the album for allmusic.com and gave it 4 stars saying:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">Dexter Gordon''s second recording for the Blue Note label is a solidly swinging affair, yet constantly full of surprises... The excellent band, solid musicianship, and memorable music on every track make this one of the more essential recordings of Gordon''s career.</p>\n<p>Highlights of the album are "Soul Sister", "The End of a Love Affair" and "Landslide". For much more on Dexter, just <a href="index.php?searchword=dexter+gordon&ordering=&searchphrase=all&Itemid=1&option=com_search" target="_blank">search for him on my blog</a>.</p>\n<p>Here''s Dexter with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Jf8AfAr4v88" target="_blank">Soul Sister</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Jf8AfAr4v88" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/dexter-calling.jpg" border="0" height="250" /><img src="images/tdij/dexter-calling-back.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Soul Sister" - 7:45</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Modal Mood" (Kenny Drew) - 5:23</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"I Want More" - 5:20</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The End of a Love Affair" (Edward Redding) - 6:53</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Clear the Dex" (Drew) - 4:54</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Ernie''s Tune" - 4:16</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Smile" (Charlie Chaplin) - 3:23</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 63, '2015-04-29 14:55:37', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:43:02', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-05-09 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 23, 'on this day in jazz, Dexter Gordon', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2258, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(406, 'On this day in jazz (May 10)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-may-10', '', '<p>On this day in 1989,   we lost virtuoso trumpeter,   flugelhornist, cornetist, composer and band leader <a href="http://www.woodyshaw.com/" target="_blank">Woody Shaw</a> <span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">at the young age of 44. NPR Music called him <a href="http://www.npr.org/blogs/ablogsupreme/2013/08/14/210572029/woody-shaw-the-last-great-trumpet-innovator" target="_blank">"the last great trumpet innovator"</a>. Although Woody''s career was cut tragically short, he had a great one.Here is a short list of some of the awards and accolades he received:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Talent Deserving Wider Recognition, Downbeat International Jazz Critics Poll (1977)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Jazz Album of the Year, Downbeat Readers Poll: Rosewood (Columbia 1978)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Best Trumpeter, Downbeat Readers Poll (1978)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Grammy Nomination  Best Jazz Instrumental Performance, Soloist: Rosewood (1979)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Grammy Nomination  Best Jazz Instrumental Performance, Group: Woody Shaw Concert Ensemble, Rosewood (1979)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Best Trumpeter, Downbeat Readers Poll (1980)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Downbeat Hall of Fame (1989)</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p></p>\n<p>A little more on the sad story that cut Woody''s life short: Shaw suffered from an incurable degenerative eye disease that caused him to lose most of his sight. On February 27, 1989, he was struck by a subway car in Brooklyn, NY, severing his left arm. While in the hospital he suffered complications and died of kidney failure on May 10, 1989.<span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">He was survived by his mother, two brothers, a sister, and his son, Woody Louis Armstrong Shaw III. See my <a href="index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=253:on-this-day-in-jazz-december-08&catid=58:december&Itemid=41" target="_self">December 08</a> page for more on Woody.</span></p>\n<p>Here''s Woody with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2CznUIGjeko" target="_blank">Stepping Stone</a>" performed live in Italy in 1979:</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2CznUIGjeko" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/woody1-eb3913f585ef33e522e9ef4712a61cbe37e04c7f-s800-c85.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 63, '2015-04-29 15:01:10', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:43:33', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-05-10 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 22, 'on this day in jazz, Woody Shaw', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2266, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(407, 'On this day in jazz (May 11)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-may-11', '', '<p>On this day in 1956,   <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a> began the first of two sessions at Rudy van Gelder''s studio in Hackensack,   NJ,   that would result in four studio albums: <em>Relaxin'' with the Miles Davis Quintet</em>, <em>Steamin'' with the Miles Davis Quintet</em>, <em>Workin'' with the Miles Davis Quintet</em> and <em>Cookin'' with the Miles Davis Quintet</em>. Performing on the sessions was the "classic" Miles Davis quintet with <a href="http://www.johncoltrane.com/" target="_blank">John Coltrane</a> on tenor saxophone, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Red_Garland" target="_blank">Red Garland</a> on piano, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Chambers" target="_blank">Paul Chambers</a> on bass and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philly_Joe_Jones" target="_blank">Philly Joe Jones</a> on the drums backing Miles'' trumpet.</p>\n<p>It''s quite unusual to have so many albums from just two days of work, but the music was just so good (even considering the fact that Miles was perhaps trying to fulfill his commitment to Prestige so that he could start recording with Columbia) that "Each of these is considered not only to be among the pinnacle of Davis'' work, but of the entire bop subgenre as well" (Lindsay Planer of allmusic.com). That''s an overstatement, but the work is really, really good.</p>\n<p>To focus on the first album, <em>Steamin''</em>, note that the first four songs that appeared on that album were recorded on this day. Also, the album was one of the ones selected to be remastered by Rudy Van Gelder fifty years later by Prestige Records. This re-release is interesting not only due to the superior sound, but also because it includes dialogue taken from the original master reel where you can hear Miles talking with the players and producers. I recommend getting all of the albums that Rudy has remastered.</p>\n<p>Here''s Miles with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=36wafFjFdYs" target="_blank">If I Were a Bell</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=36wafFjFdYs" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Relaxin-LP1-1.jpg" border="0" height="250" /><img src="images/tdij/PRLP7129.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"If I Were a Bell" (Frank Loesser)  8:15</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"You''re My Everything" (Harry Warren)  5:18</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"I Could Write a Book" (Richard Rodgers)  5:09</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Oleo" (Sonny Rollins)  6:18</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"It Could Happen to You" (Jimmy Van Heusen)  6:37</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Woody ''n'' You" (Dizzy Gillespie)  5:02</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 63, '2015-05-01 15:35:10', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:43:50', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-05-11 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 21, 'on this day in jazz, Miles Davis', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2254, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(408, 'On this day in jazz (May 12)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-may-12', '', '<p>On this day in 1959,   <a href="http://straightlife.info/apbio.html" target="_blank">Art Pepper</a> began recording the studio album <em>Art Pepper + Eleven</em>. The songs were directed and arranged by Marty Paich and his big band. Although Art would record several times with Marty that year,   this album is the only one where Art is credited as the leader. The recording focuses jazz standards arranged for big band,  including "Move", "Round Midnight" and "Walkin'' Shoes". On this work you''ll not only hear Art on the alto saxophone (the instrument which he played most) but also on the tenor and clarinet. In fact, two of the best songs on the album feature him on the clarinet: "Anthropology" and the alternate takes of "Walkin''" (alternate takes are available on the Modern Jazz Classics edition). Other tracks to pay attention to are "Move", "Four Brothers", "Shaw Nuff" and "Donna Lee".</p>\n<p>Highlighted below is "Move"--take a listen to it and then to <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a>'' version <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4WjU4eXYWg4" target="_blank">here</a>.</p>\n<p>Here''s Art with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eZpNlhL9D-U" target="_blank">Move</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eZpNlhL9D-U" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/plus-eleven-cover1.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Move" (Denzil Best) 3:26</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Groovin'' High" (Dizzy Gillespie) 3:22</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Opus de Funk" (Horace Silver) 3:13</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"''Round Midnight" (Hanighen, Thelonious Monk, Williams) 3:32</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Four Brothers" (Jimmy Giuffre) 2:57</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Shaw ''Nuff" (Brown, Fuller, Gillespie) 2:58</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Burnie''s Tune" (Leiber, Miller, Stoller) 2:44</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Walkin'' Shoes" (Gerry Mulligan) 3:31</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Anthropology" (Gillespie, Charlie Parker) 3:19</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Airegin" (Sonny Rollins) 3:01</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 63, '2015-05-01 15:51:57', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:44:58', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-05-12 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 20, 'on this day in jazz, Art Pepper', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2493, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(409, 'On this day in jazz (May 13)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-may-13', '', '<p>On this day in 1969,   pianist <a href="http://chickcorea.com/" target="_blank">Chick Corea</a> completed recording the album <em>Is</em>. There are four songs on the album,   "This",   "Is", "It" and "Jamala". Joining in on the album were <a href="http://www.woodyshaw.com/" target="_blank">Woody Shaw</a> on trumpet, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hubert_Laws" target="_blank">Hubert Laws</a> on flute and piccolo, <a href="http://benniemaupinmusic.com/" target="_blank">Bennie Maupin</a> on tenor saxophone, <a href="http://daveholland.com/" target="_blank">Dave Holland</a> on bass and both <a href="http://www.jackdejohnette.com/" target="_blank">Jack DeJohnette</a> and <a href="http://horaceearnold.com/" target="_blank">Horace Arnold</a> on drums.</p>\n<p>Scott Yanow said this of the album: "The music on the sextet date ... is often quite free and explorative, exploring a variety of moods (some of them rather violent). Rambling and uneven (particularly during the 29-minute "Is"), this set is not essential but has its interesting moments." While I''m definitely not an overly huge fan of free jazz, I take Scott''s view of sometimes it is pretty interesting.</p>\n<p>Chick is currently <a href="http://chickcorea.com/concerts/" target="_blank">on tour</a> with fellow pianist <a href="http://www.herbiehancock.com/home.php" target="_blank">Herbie Hancock</a> at the time of this writing (2015), so go them if you get a chance.</p>\n<p>Here''s Chick with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GJ0W09ZPLn8" target="_blank">Jamala</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GJ0W09ZPLn8" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/chick-corea-652x367-538x301.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Is"  28:54</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Jamala"  14:04</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"This"  8:18</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"It"  0:30</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 63, '2015-05-02 17:08:58', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:45:31', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-05-13 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 19, 'on this day in jazz, Chick Corea', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2781, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(410, 'On this day in jazz (May 14)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-may-14', '', '<p>On this day in 1957,   <a href="http://www.artblakey.com/" target="_blank">Art Blakey</a> and <a href="http://www.monkzone.com/" target="_blank">Thelonious Monk</a> began recording the studio album <em>Art Blakey''s Jazz Messengers with Thelonious Monk</em>. Art had supported Thelonious on several records over the years,   so this was Monk''s chance to return that favor. Assisting on the work were the rest of the Jazz Messengers which included Bill Hardman on the trumpet,   <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/johnny-griffin-mn0000213510/biography" target="_blank">Johnny Griffin</a> on tenor saxophone and Spanky DeBrest on bass.</p>\n<p>Professional rating services give this album extremely high ratings. Billboard said that it contained "mighty good jazz", while allmusic gives it four out of five stars, saying that Art and Thelonious "are at the peak of their respective prowess with insightful interpretations of nearly half a dozen inspired performances". Additionally, the <em>Penguin Guide to Jazz</em> gave it a "Crown". On item of trivia: during the time of this recording Thelonious had lost his cabaret card and was banned from playing in New York City clubs. He would regain it a month later and take up a residency at the famed Five Spot with his quartet--a quartet that would feature <a href="http://www.johncoltrane.com/" target="_blank">John Coltrane</a> coming into his own. It was those sessions that really made Monk marketable and led to the studios releasing this record about a year after it was actually recorded.</p>\n<p>Note that on February 16, 1999, Rhino Records reissued the album remastered for compact disc. Three bonus tracks were included--all outtakes from the May 1957 sessions.</p>\n<p>Here''s Art and Thelonious with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gnGLy1l1A8I" target="_blank">In Walked Bud</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gnGLy1l1A8I" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/MI0001953595.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Evidence" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Thelonious Monk</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">6:46</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"In Walked Bud" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Thelonious Monk</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">6:39</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Blue Monk" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Thelonious Monk</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">7:54</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"I Mean You" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Thelonious Monk</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">8:02</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Rhythm-A-Ning" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Thelonious Monk</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">7:20</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Purple Shades" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Johnny Griffin</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">7:48</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 63, '2015-05-07 11:23:09', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:45:53', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-05-14 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 2, 'on this day in jazz, Thelonious Monk, Art Blakey', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 3007, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(411, 'On this day in jazz (May 15)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-may-15', '', '<p>On this day in 1950,   the great <a href="http://www.cmgww.com/music/parker/home.html" target="_blank">Charlie Parker</a> was recorded live at Birdland for the album <em>Charlie Parker -- One Night In Birdland</em>. Joining in with Charlie''s alto saxophone were Curly Russell on bass,   the wonderful <a href="http://www.artblakey.com/" target="_blank">Art Blakey</a> and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roy_Haynes" target="_blank">Roy Haynes</a> on drums,   the awesome <a href="http://www.budpowelljazz.com/" target="_blank">Bud Powell</a> and Walter Bishop on piano and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fats_Navarro" target="_blank">Fats Navarro</a> on the trumpet. The album is important for a few reasons:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Each of the recordings are quite long featuring some incredible solos</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">The music selected was superb and features the ONLY time that Charlie played a <a href="http://www.monkzone.com/" target="_blank">Thelonious Monk</a> tune ("''Round Midnight")</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">The ensemble itself is remarkable and they played extremely well together, especially the first three sides of the work which featured Charley, Curley, Art Blakey, Bud Powell and Fats Navarro </span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">The best way to hear Charley is to hear him live.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p></p>\n<p>Here''s Charlie with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LphuCadyQi0" target="_blank">Ornithology</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LphuCadyQi0" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Charlie-Parker-001.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Wahoo</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">6:34</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">''Round Midnight</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">5:07</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">This Time The Dream''s On Me</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">6:13</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Dizzy Atmosphere</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">6:52</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Night In Tunisia</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">5:38</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Move</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">6:30</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">The Street Beat</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">9:27</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Out Of Nowhere</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">6:20</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Little Willie Leaps / 52nd Street Theme</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">5:44</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Ornithology</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">7:50</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">I''ll Remember April / 52nd Street Theme</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">9:23</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Embraceable You</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">6:20</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Cool Blues / 52nd Street Theme 9:09</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 63, '2015-05-07 11:37:14', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:46:15', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-05-15 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 18, 'on this day in jazz, Charlie Parker', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2680, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(412, 'On this day in jazz (May 16)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-may-16', '', '<p>On this day in 1969,   one of my favorite pianists,  <a href="http://www.andrewhilljazz.com/" target="_blank">Andrew Hill</a>, began recording the album <em>Lift Every Voice</em> at Rudy van Gelder''s studio in Englewood Cliffs, NJ. The album features all composed by Andrew and includes vocals--something you rarely hear on an Andrew Hill record. Joining Andrew on the album were <a href="http://www.woodyshaw.com/" target="_blank">Woody Shaw</a> on trumpet, Carlos Garnett on tenor saxophone, Richard Davis on bass, and Freddie Waits on the drums. Vocals were supplied by Joan Johnson, LaReine LaMar, Gail Nelson, Antenett Goodman Ray and Lawrence Marshall (who also conducted the choir).</p>\n<p>Andrew actually once wrote a jazz opera and the vocals on this one are actually very operatic.<span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 15.8079996109009px;">The CD re-release actually includes another entire unreleased album, so if you find Lift Every Voice, you''ll not only get the five songs listed below but also six other Andrew Hill originals. </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">allmusic.com gives the album four out of five stars (Richard Ginell wrote the review and said that the extra tracks were not that great--the reason why the album was probably shelved). </span></p>\n<p>Here''s Andrew with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=x7-Fd6qYBMs" target="_blank">Lift Every Voice</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=x7-Fd6qYBMs" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/MI0000308940.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Hey Hey" - 7:55</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Lift Every Voice" - 8:06</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Two Lullabies" - 5:44 </span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Love Chant" - 5:42</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Ghetto Lights" - 5:13</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 63, '2015-05-07 11:54:33', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:46:39', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-05-16 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 17, 'on this day in jazz, Andrew Hill', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 2489, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(413, 'On this day in jazz (May 17)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-may-17', '', '<p>On this day in 1960,   tenor saxophonist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harold_Land" target="_blank">Harold Land</a> began recording the album <em>West Coast Blues!</em> in San Francisco (it would be completed the next day). Joining Harold on this out were Joe Gordon on trumpet, the wonderful <a href="http://www.wesmontgomery.com/" target="_blank">Wes Montgomery</a> on guitar, Barry Harris on piano, Sam Jones on bass, and Louis Hayes at the drums. Scott Yanow reviewed the album for allmusic.com and gave the album four out of five stars, saying that "the music is as well-played and swinging as one would expect from this superior bop group."</p>\n<p>The album includes three originals by Land as well as several other excellent covers including <a href="http://www.cmgww.com/music/parker/home.html" target="_blank">Charlie Parker</a>''s "Klactoveedsedstene" and Arthur Herzog, Jr. & Billy Holiday''s "Don''t Explain".</p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Here''s Harold with "</span><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OJBJYPseE2o" style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Klactoveedsedstene</a><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">":</span></p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OJBJYPseE2o" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Harold_Land2.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Ursula" (Harold Land)  7:07</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Klactoveedsedstene" (Charlie Parker)  9:59</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Don''t Explain" (Arthur Herzog Jr., Billie Holiday)  4:54</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"West Coast Blues" (Wes Montgomery)  6:02</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Terrain" (Land)  7:46</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Compulsion" (Land)  6:48</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 63, '2015-05-07 15:53:45', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:47:03', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-05-17 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 16, 'on this day in jazz, Harold Land', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 3886, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(414, 'On this day in jazz (May 18)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-may-18', '', '<p>On this day in 1973,   <a href="http://www.oscarpeterson.com/" target="_blank">Oscar Peterson</a>,   <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joe_Pass" target="_blank">Joe Pass</a> and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Niels-Henning_%C3%98rsted_Pedersen" target="_blank">Niels-Henning rsted Pederse</a>n recorded the live album <em>The Trio</em>. The album consists of five songs including two of Peterson''s originals: "Blues Etude" and "Chicago Blues". Scott Yanow says that the real reason to listen to the album is solely because of Oscar, but I think that Joe and Niels do a great job on the guitars backing him up and completing the sound. Oscar was indeed in great form during this performance and you can even hear him play multiple piano styles such as "stride" and "boogie woogie". The album won the Grammy Award in 1975 for Best Jazz Performance by a Group.</p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Here''s Oscar, Joe and Niels with "Blues Etude":</span></p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=R86TSg_nymw" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/thetrio.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Blues Etude" (Oscar Peterson)  5:31</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Chicago Blues" (Peterson)  13:45</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Easy Listening Blues" (Nate Robinson)  7:48</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Come Sunday" (Duke Ellington)  3:46</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Secret Love" (Sammy Fain, Paul Francis Webster)  7:14</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 63, '2015-05-12 17:22:28', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:47:29', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-05-18 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 15, 'on this day in jazz, Oscar Peterson', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 3932, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(415, 'On this day in jazz (May 19)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-may-19', '', '<p>On this day in 1966,   pianist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cecil_Taylor" target="_blank">Cecil Taylor</a> recorded the ground breaking album <em>Unit Structures</em> at Rudy van Gelder''s studio in Englewood Cliffs,   NJ. Cecil was supported by Eddie Gale on the trumpet, Jimmy Lyons on alto sax, Ken McIntyre on alto sax, oboe and bass clarinet, Henry Grimes and Alan Silva on bass and Andrew Cyrille on the drums. All songs were originals written by Cecil.</p>\n<p>The album is consitently listed in top 100 album lists and is indeed one of the great jazz albums of all time. The Penguin Guide to Jazz gave it four and a half stars, saying that the album was as "mathematically complex as its title suggests and as rich in colour and sound as the ensemble proposes". Scott Yanow of allmusic.com said this of the album:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">After several years off records, pianist Cecil Taylor finally had an opportunity to document his music of the mid-''60s on two Blue Note albums (the other one was <em>Conquistador</em>). Taylor''s high-energy atonalism fit in well with the free jazz of the period but he was actually leading the way rather than being part of a movement. In fact, this septet outing with trumpeter Eddie Gale, altoist Jimmy Lyons, Ken McIntyre (alternating between alto, oboe and bass clarinet), both Henry Grimes and Alan Silva on basses, and drummer Andrew Cyrille is quite stunning and very intense. In fact, it could be safely argued that no jazz music of the era approached the ferocity and intensity of Cecil Taylor''s.</p>\n<p>If this album is a little "too much" for you, I suggest checking out <em>Jazz Advance</em> or <em>Looking Ahead!</em> before trying to tackle this one....and if those are too much, start with <em>Love for Sale</em>.</p>\n<p>Here''s Cecil with "Steps":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_woT6Mgp64c" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/unitstructuresfront.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /><img src="images/tdij/unitstructures-back.jpg" border="0" width="228" height="228" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Steps"  10:20</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Enter, Evening"  11:06</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Enter, Evening [alternate take]"  10:11 Bonus track on CD release</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Unit Structure/As of a Now/Section"  17:47</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Tales (8 Whisps)"  7:14</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 63, '2015-05-12 17:40:53', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:48:51', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-05-19 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 14, 'on this day in jazz, Cecil Taylor', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 4105, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(416, 'On this day in jazz (May 20)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-may-20', '', '<p>On this day in 1955,   <a href="http://www.pas.org/experience/halloffame/JacksonMilt.aspx" target="_blank">Milt Jackson</a> recorded <em>Milt Jackson Quartet</em> at Rudy van Gelder''s studio in Hackensack,   NJ. Joining Milt''s vibraphone on the album were <a href="http://www.horacesilver.com/" target="_blank">Horace Silver</a> at the piano, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Percy_Heath" target="_blank">Percy Heath</a> on bass and <a href="http://www.drummerworld.com/drummers/Connie_Kay.html" target="_blank">Connie Kay</a> on the drums. Essentially this is the Modern Jazz Quartet minus <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Lewis_(pianist)" target="_blank">John Lewis</a> plus Horace. If you are a fan of the MJQ, then you''ll also like this one.</p>\n<p>What this album gives you that MJQ works with Jonn Lewis do not is a hard bop style to the rhythm section (due to Horace Silver''s playing at the piano). Richard Mortifoglio of allmusic.com said that also it is "a chance to hear a hitherto unknown, lushly romantic side of both Jackson and Silver, two blues-oriented players who rarely if ever recorded standards in this sort of style. With its excellent recording quality, it''s a perfect album for intimate dinners and other late-night activities. Artie Shaw''s exotic "Moonray" is rarely heard in any sort of context, while "My Funny Valentine" and "The Nearness of You" set the mood throughout."</p>\n<p>Here''s Milt with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oQdFZBLFS20" target="_blank">Moonray</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oQdFZBLFS20" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/018.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Wonder Why" (Nicholas Brodszky, Sammy Cahn) - 5:26</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"My Funny Valentine" (Lorenz Hart, Richard Rodgers) - 4:41</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Moonray" (Paul Madison, Arthur Quenzer, Artie Shaw) - 5:05</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Nearness of You" (Hoagy Carmichael, Ned Washington) - 4:04</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Stonewall" - 7:47</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"I Should Care" (Axel Stordahl, Paul Weston, Sammy Cahn) - 4:20</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 63, '2015-05-12 18:25:01', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:49:24', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-05-20 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 13, 'on this day in jazz, Milt Jackson', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 4216, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(417, 'On this day in jazz (May 21)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-may-21', '', '<p>On this day in 1965,   saxophonist <a href="http://www.rivbea.com/" target="_blank">Sam Rivers</a> recorded the album <em>Contours</em> at Rudy van Gelder''s studio in Englewood Cliffs,   NJ. Sam was assisted by an all-star cast including <a href="http://www.freddiehubbardmusic.com/" target="_blank">Freddie Hubbard</a> on trumpet,   <a href="http://www.herbiehancock.com/home.php" target="_blank">Herbie Hancock</a> on piano, <a href="http://roncarter.net/JazzMaster/" target="_blank">Ron Carter</a> on bass and <a href="http://www.josephachambers.com/" target="_blank">Joe Chambers</a> on the drums. What an incredible lineup! The album consists of four songs, all written by Sam. If you''re looking for some post-bop with a bit of avant-garde thrown in, take a listen to this album--especially for Freddie''s incredible solos and Herbie''s strong rhythm lines.</p>\n<p>Stephen Thomas Erlewine reviewed the album for allmusic.com saying that Sam had:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">fully embraced the avant-garde, but presented his music in a way that wouldn''t be upsetting or confusing to hard bop loyalists. Rivers leads a quintet ... through a set of originals that walk a fine line between probing, contemplative post-bop and densely dissonant avant-jazz. Each musician is able to play the extremes equally well while remaining sensitive to the compositional subtleties. Rarely is Contours anything less than enthralling, and it remains one of the high watermarks of the mid-''60s avant-garde movement.</p>\n<p>Here''s Sam with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7jWGd7k8aXQ" target="_blank">Point of Many Returns</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7jWGd7k8aXQ" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/SRMosaic.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Point of Many Returns" - 9:20</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Dance of the Tripedal" - 10:07</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Euterpe" - 11:43</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Mellifluous Cacophony" - 8:58</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 63, '2015-05-16 16:09:47', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:49:52', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-05-21 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 12, 'on this day in jazz, Sam Rivers', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 4778, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(418, 'On this day in jazz (May 22)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-may-22', '', '<p>On this day in 1959,   the one and only <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ornette_Coleman" target="_blank">Ornette Coleman</a> recorded the album <em>The Shape of Jazz to Come</em> in Hollywood,  CA. The album was originally going to be called <em>Focus on Sanity</em>, but at the urging of producer Nesuhi Ertegun, it was changed. Nesuhi felt that the uniqueness of the music was something that needed to come across in the title, hence the change. On this album you will hear six originals all written by Ornette who plays the alto saxophone. He was assisted by an incredibly good set of musicians including <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Don_Cherry_%28trumpeter%29" target="_blank">Don Cherry</a> on the cornet, <a href="http://www.charliehadenmusic.com/" target="_blank">Charlie Haden</a> on bass and Billy Higgins on the drums. This album is only the third from Ornette as a leader and one of the first albums that Charlie Haden played on (Charlie previous had played with Paul Bley starting in 1957).</p>\n<p>The thing that seems to make Ornette''s music so different and free is that his quartet lacks and chordal instruments (Gerry Mulligan did the same thing, but to a much different effect). When listening, keep in mind that the songs consist of a starting theme followed by improvisations and then a return to the main theme--it will help you keep your bearings if you are an avant-garde neophyte. This is really a great album, so grit your teeth and settle in. The album received the following accolades:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Ranked #248 on Rolling Stone magazine''s 500 greatest albums of all time</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Identified by Chris Kelsey as one of the 20 Essential Free Jazz Albums</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">The <em>Penguin Guide to Jazz</em> awarded it a "crown" and a perfect four star rating</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Added the album to the National Recording Registry in 2012 by the Library of Congress</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Inducted into the Grammy Hall of Fame in 2015</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Here''s Ornette with "</span><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DNbD1JIH344" target="_blank" style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Lonely Woman</a><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">":</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DNbD1JIH344" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/claxtoncolemanl.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Lonely Woman" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">4:59</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Eventually" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">4:20</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Peace" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">9:04</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Focus on Sanity" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">6:50</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Congeniality" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">6:41</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Chronology" 6:05</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 63, '2015-05-16 16:31:48', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:50:22', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-05-22 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 11, 'on this day in jazz, Ornette Coleman', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 5007, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(419, 'On this day in jazz (May 23)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-may-23', '', '<div>On this day in 1963,   <a href="http://www.dextergordon.com/" target="_blank">Dexter Gordon</a> recorded the album <em>Our Man in Paris</em> at CBS Studios in Paris. Gordon, who had moved to Copenhagen in 1962, teamed up with USA expatriates <a href="http://www.budpowelljazz.com/" target="_blank">Bud Powell</a> (piano) and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kenny_Clarke" target="_blank">Kenny Clarke</a> (drums) and native Parisian Pierre Michelot (bass) to create this essential album which was remastered in 2003 by Rudy van Gelder.</div>\n<div>An interesting bit of trivia about the album: originally pianist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kenny_Drew" target="_blank">Kenny Drew</a> was picked to play piano on the album; however, that plan fell through and Bud Powell was picked to play. Due to this decision, the entire concept of the album changed. The initial plan for the album was that it would consist of all originals written by Dexter. Well, let''s just say that Bud didn''t want to play any of the new songs, so the compromise that was made was for the album to consist entirely of jazz standards. That''s too bad, but the album still became one of Dexter''s most beloved works and won several accolades including being selected as part of the <em>Penguin Guide to Jazz</em>''s core collection (along with a perfect four-star rating). allmusic.com gave it a high rating (four and a half out of five stars), also.</div>\n<div>Here''s Dexter with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MjJFft1QQeU" target="_blank">A Night in Tunisia</a>":</div>\n<div><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MjJFft1QQeU" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/omip.jpg" border="0" height="250" /><img src="images/tdij/omipb.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;"> </span></div>\n<div>Track listing:</div>\n<div><ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Scrapple from the Apple" (Parker)  7:22</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Willow Weep for Me" (Ronell)  8:47</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Broadway" (Billy Byrd, McRae, Henri Woode)  6:44</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Stairway to the Stars" (Malneck, Parish, Signorelli)  6:57</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"A Night in Tunisia" (Gillespie, Frank Paparelli)  8:15 </span></li>\n</ol></div>', '', 1, 8, 0, 63, '2015-05-16 17:19:23', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:50:42', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-05-23 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 10, 'on this day in jazz, Dexter Gordon', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 5184, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(420, 'On this day in jazz (May 24)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-may-24', '', '<p>On this day in 1968,   one of my favorite pianists,   <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/cedar-walton-mn0000741325/biography" target="_blank">Cedar Walton</a>, recorded the album <em>Spectrum</em> in New York City. Cedar was assisted by a stellar line up of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blue_Mitchell" target="_blank">Blue Mitchell</a> on trumpet, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clifford_Jordan" target="_blank">Clifford Jordan</a> on tenor saxophone, Richard Davis on bass and <a href="http://www.jackdejohnette.com/" target="_blank">Jack DeJohnette</a> on the drums.</p>\n<p>If you are unfamiliar with Cedar, here''s some brief points. He started playing professionally in 1957 after 2 years of service in the US Army with Kenny Dorham, making his recording debut on <em>This Is The Moment!</em>. He later joined <a href="http://www.bennygolson.com/" target="_blank">Benny Golson</a>''s band, The Jazztet. In the early 1960s, he was in <a href="http://www.artblakey.com/" target="_blank">Art Blakey</a>''s band, The Jazz Messengers. Throughout the 1960s he played for various jazz stars like <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lee_Morgan" target="_blank">Lee Morgan</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abbey_Lincoln" target="_blank">Abbey Lincoln</a> and <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/sonny-criss-mn0000755431/biography" target="_blank">Sonny Criss</a>, and in the 1970s he founded a funk band named Mobius. In the 1990s, he arranged and recorded Etta James'' <em>Mystery Land: Songs of Billie Holiday</em> which won the Grammy for Best Jazz Vocal Album. In 2010, he was inducted as a Jazz Master by the National Endowment for the Arts. His best known recordings are the following: "Firm Roots", "Bolivia", "Holy Land," "Mode for Joe" and "Cedar''s Blues".</p>\n<p>Here''s Cedar with the Henry Mancini/Johnny Mercer tune, "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HbWDSR3Qn4g" target="_blank">Days of Wine and Roses</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HbWDSR3Qn4g" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/spectrum-front.jpg" border="0" height="250" /><img src="images/tdij/spectrum-back.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Higgins Holler" - 10:20</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Days of Wine and Roses" (Henry Mancini, Johnny Mercer) - 8:56</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Jake''s Milkshakes" - 3:55</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Spectrum" - 5:39</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Lady Charlotte" (Cal Massey) - 6:14</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 63, '2015-05-17 18:30:32', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:51:16', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-05-24 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 9, 'on this day in jazz, Cedar Walton', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 4941, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(421, 'On this day in jazz (May 25)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-may-25', '', '<p>On this day in 1998,   drummer <a href="http://www.kahilelzabar.net/" target="_blank">Kahil El''Zabar</a> completed recording the album <em>Spirits Entering</em> at Riverside Studio in Chicago,   IL. The album consists of duets with violinist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Billy_Bang" target="_blank">Billy Bang</a>. The album is regarded as avant-garde-world-fusion and presents some rather unusual instruments such as the Berimbau and Kalimba played by Kahil. Derek Taylor writing for allaboutjazz.com said that "Bang is one of the few improvisors around that can completely complement and match El''Zabar''s measure of spiritual fire and passionate emotionalism in his instrument." That is,   they played well together. If you are looking for something a little off the beaten path, this album should meet that need. If you like this album, you''ll also like the live album they recorded together in 2005, <em>Live at the River East Art Center</em>.</p>\n<p>Now, a little about Kahil. He was born in Chicago in 1953 and attended the Chicagoland college, Lake Forest College. Into the early 1970s, he joined the Association for the Advancement of Creative Musicians and would later go on to become the chairman of that group. Throughout his career he has recorded mainly with two groups that he formed: Ritual Trio and Ethnic Heritage Ensemble; however, he has also collaborated with many of jazz''s royalty such as <a href="http://www.dizzygillespie.com/" target="_blank">Dizzy Gillespie</a> and <a href="http://www.cannonball-adderley.com/" target="_blank">Cannonball Adderley</a> as well as other well-known musicians such as Nina Simone, Paul Simon and Stevie Wonder. If you''re like me and live in the Chicago area, head over to <a href="http://chicago.jazznearyou.com/" target="_blank">jazznearyou.com</a> to see if he (or others) will be playing soon!</p>\n<p>Here''s Kahil with "Spirits Entering":</p>\n<p><img src="images/tdij/Kahil_El_Zabar_depth1.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Spirits Entering</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Was Now</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Sweet Irene</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Love Outside of Dreams</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">The Dream Merchant</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Song Of Myself</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">The Ituri Fantasy</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Old Time Religion</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Golden Sea</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 63, '2015-05-19 17:42:32', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:51:40', 62, 62, '2016-08-17 21:54:30', '2015-05-25 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 8, 'on this day in jazz, Kahil El''Zabar', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 4840, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(422, 'On this day in jazz (May 26)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-may-26', '', '<p>On this day in 1980,   <a href="http://www.patmetheny.com/" target="_blank">Pat Metheny</a> began recording the album entitled <em>80/81</em>. The musicians appearing on the album were: Pat Metheny on acoustic and electric guitars,   <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dewey_Redman" target="_blank">Dewey Redman</a> and <a href="http://www.michaelbrecker.com/" target="_blank">Michael Brecker</a> on tenor saxophones,   <a href="http://www.charliehadenmusic.com/" target="_blank">Charlie Haden</a> on bass, and <a href="http://www.jackdejohnette.com/" target="_blank">Jack DeJohnette</a> on drums. The album was a double LP release with 9 songs comprising the four sides. I''ve never been a huge Pat Metheny fan, but this album is almost listenable--probably due in large part to his supporting cast and the material they selected to record which includes songs by Haden and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ornette_Coleman" target="_blank">Ornette Coleman</a>.</p>\n<p>Richard Ginell says this of the album: "Pat Metheny''s credibility with the jazz community went way up with the release of this package, a superb two-CD collaboration with a quartet of outstanding jazz musicians that dared to be uncompromising at a time when most artists would have merely continued pursuing their electric commercial successes".</p>\n<p>Here''s Pat with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CgBzCl5HtgE" target="_blank">Two Folk Songs</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CgBzCl5HtgE" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Metheny_Pat_byJimmyKatz_4.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Two Folk Songs: 1st" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">13:17</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Two Folk Songs: 2nd" (Charlie Haden)</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">7:31</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"80/81" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">7:28</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Bat" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">5:58</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Turnaround" (Ornette Coleman)</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">7:05</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Open" (Metheny, Jack DeJohnette, Dewey Redman, Haden, Michael Brecker, Final Theme by Metheny)</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">14:25</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Pretty Scattered" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">6:56</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Every Day (I Thank You)" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">13:16</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Goin'' Ahead" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">3:56</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 63, '2015-05-19 18:10:31', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:52:08', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-05-26 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 7, 'on this day in jazz, Pat Metheny', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 4689, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(423, 'On this day in jazz (May 27)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-may-27', '', '<p>On this day in 1963,   saxophonist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harold_Vick" target="_blank">Harold Vick</a> recorded his debut album,   <em>Steppin'' Out</em> at Rudy van Gelder''s studio in Englewood Cliffs, NJ. Harold was joined by <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blue_Mitchell" target="_blank">Blue Mitchell</a> on trumpet, Big John Patton on organ, the wonderful <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grant_Green">Grant Green</a> on guitar and Ben Dixon onthe drums. If you are interested in hearing some soulful jazz, you''ll want to hear this one.</p>\n<p>Scott Yanow reviewed the album for allmusic.com and gave it a strong 4 and a half star rating saying: "There are no real surprises, but no disappointments either on what would be Harold Vick''s only chance to lead a Blue Note date. At 27 he was already a fine player." All songs except for "Laura" were originals written by the saxophonist.</p>\n<p>In addition to have a strong musical career, Vick had an interesting acting career, too. He appeared in several wonderful movies as a musician: <em>Stardust Memories</em>, <em>The Cotton Club</em>, and <em>School Days</em>. Unfortunately, Vick died at the age of 51 in his home in Manhattan from a heart attack; he was memorialized via the Sonny Rollins song "Did You See Harold Vick?", which can be found on Sonny''s 2000 album, <em>This Is What I Do</em>.</p>\n<p>Here''s Harold with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-P-X7RNHzOQ" target="_blank">Our Miss Brooks</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-P-X7RNHzOQ" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/vick_stepping_fr.jpg" border="0" height="250" /><img src="images/tdij/vick_steppin_bk.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Our Miss Brooks" - 7:27</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Trimmed in Blue" - 6:10</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Laura" (Johnny Mercer, David Raksin) - 4:39</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Dotty''s Dream" - 6:24</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Vicksville" - 5:39</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Steppin'' Out" - 5:50</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 63, '2015-05-21 17:27:44', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:57:58', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-05-27 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 6, 'on this day in jazz, Harold Vick', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 5094, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(424, 'On this day in jazz (May 28)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-may-28', '', '<p>On this day in 1962,   legendary pianist <a href="http://www.herbiehancock.com/home.php" target="_blank">Herbie Hancock</a> recorded his debut album,   <em>Takin'' Off</em>,   at Rudy van Gelder''s studio in Englewood Cliffs, NJ. The album is an incredible debut, containing six original songs by Herbie. One of them, "Watermelon Man", is considered to be a jazz standard today. Herbie was assisted by the fantastic <a href="http://www.freddiehubbardmusic.com/" target="_blank">Freddie Hubbard</a> on trumpet, the dynamic <a href="http://www.dextergordon.com/" target="_blank">Dexter Gordon</a> on tenor sax, Butch Warren on bass and <a href="http://www.drummerworld.com/drummers/Billy_Higgins.html" target="_blank">Billy Higgins</a> on the drums--what an excellent line up.</p>\n<p>All of Herbie''s albums from the 1960s are really good--sounding as good today as they did 50 years ago. If you haven''t listened to Herbie much, go ahead and start with this album plus <em>Empyrean Isles</em>, <em>Maiden Voyage</em>, and <em>Fat Albert Rotunda</em>. And. if you get a chance, go see him on tour.</p>\n<p>But back, to this album...Steve Huey, writing for allmusic.com said this of the work: "So even if, in retrospect, Takin'' Off is among Hancock''s most conventional albums, it shows a young stylist already strikingly mature for his age, and one who can interpret established forms with spirit and imagination....All in all, Takin'' Off is an exceptional first effort, laying the groundwork for Hancock to begin pushing the boundaries of hard bop on his next several records." I agree wholeheartedly.</p>\n<p>Here''s Herbie with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZbHJHPTikQA" target="_blank">Watermelon Man</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZbHJHPTikQA" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/takin-off-front.jpg" border="0" height="250" /><img src="images/tdij/takin-off-back.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track lsting:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Watermelon Man"  7:09</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Three Bags Full"  5:27</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Empty Pockets"  6:09</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Maze"  6:45</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Driftin''"  6:58</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Alone and I"  6:25</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 63, '2015-05-23 18:30:39', 62, '', '2016-08-17 21:59:38', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-05-28 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 5, 'on this day in jazz, Herbie Hancock', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 5076, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(425, 'On this day in jazz (May 29)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-may-29', '', '<p>On this day in 1965,   <a href="http://www.dextergordon.com/" target="_blank">Dexter Gordon</a> completed recording his album <em>Gettin'' Around</em> at Rudy van Gelder''s studio in Englewood Cliffs, NJ. The album features a great line-up with Dexter on tenor, <a href="http://www.bluenote.com/artists/bobby-hutcherson">Bobby Hutcherson</a> on vibraphone, Barry Harris on piano, Bob Cranshaw on bass and Billy Higgins on drums (note that Dexter and Billy were also on yesterday''s profiled album, <em>Takin'' Off</em> by Herbie Hancock). The album consists of five cover songs and the original "Le Coiffeur".</p>\n<p>As stated above, the album was recorded in the US, however it still resembles the two that preceded it (except for vibes instead of piano in the rhythm section) <em>Our Man in Paris</em> and <em>One Flight Up</em> in that it is laid-back compared to the hard bop of his earlier years. Billboard''s review of the album called it "cool and hot" and that the rhythm section was "A-1 all the way". It''s not his best album, but is still worth listening to. Go back to my <a href="index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=419:on-this-day-in-jazz-may-23&catid=63:may&Itemid=41" target="_self">May 23</a> post to see thoughts on <em>Our Man in Paris</em>.</p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 15.8079996109009px;">A little more about Dexter: in 1986 he was inducted into the French Order of Arts and Letters by the Ministry of Culture in France was nominated for an Academy Award for Best Leading Role </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">his acting performance in <em>Round Midnight</em> </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">(he didn''t win the Oscar, but he did win a Grammy for Best Soundtrack for this film). Also starring in <em>Round Midnight</em> were Franois Cluzet and<a href="http://www.herbiehancock.com/home.php" target="_blank">Herbie Hancock</a> (Martin Scorsese, Philippe Noiret and<a href="http://www.wayneshorter.com/" target="_blank">Wayne Shorter</a> have cameos). The movie received excellent reviews from critics and has a 100% rating at Rotten Tomatoes. </span></p>\n<p>Here''s Dexter with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Z9AC1NmIrSQ" target="_blank">Le Coiffeur</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Z9AC1NmIrSQ" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/4204-dextergordon-gettin-around-front-cover-1600.jpg" border="0" height="250" /><img src="images/tdij/4204-dextergordon-gettin-around-rear-cover-1600.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Manh de Carnaval" (Luiz Bonf, Antonio Maria) - 8:26</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Who Can I Turn To (When Nobody Needs Me)" (Leslie Bricusse, Anthony Newley) - 5:15</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Heartaches" (Al Hoffman, John Klenner) - 7:46</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Shiny Stockings" (Frank Foster) - 6:18</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Everybody''s Somebody''s Fool" (Howard Greenfield, Jack Keller) - 6:45</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Le Coiffeur" - 7:01</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 63, '2015-05-23 18:53:42', 62, '', '2016-08-17 22:00:17', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-05-29 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 4, 'on this day in jazz, Dexter Gordon', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 5073, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(426, 'On this day in jazz (May 30)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-may-30', '', '<p>On this day in 1963,   <a href="http://www.billevanswebpages.com/" target="_blank">Bill Evans</a> began recording his album <em>Bill Evans Trio at Shelly''s Manne-Hole,   Hollywood,   California</em>. The album features Bill at the piano, Chuck Israels on bass and Larry Bunker on the drums. Daniel Gioffre reviewed the album for allmusic.com saying:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">Although the Scott LaFaro-Paul Motian lineup of the Bill Evans Trio is generally considered to be the strongest, Chuck Israels and Larry Bunker make a strong case of their own on At Shelly''s Manne-Hole, a 1964 release that finds the entire band in classic form. This particular trio may lack some of the sheer combustive force of the better-known lineup, but it is, if possible, even more sensitive, melancholic, and nostalgic than the previous band.... Jazz is rarely as sensitive or as melodic as this. Another classic from Bill Evans and company.</p>\n<p>The album is comprised of 8 songs, 7 of which are covers, and most of them standards. If you''re in the mood for some relaxing classic jazz from a small group, you''ll enjoy this one.</p>\n<p>Here''s Bill with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fNg904EvTQo" target="_blank">Stella by Starlight</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fNg904EvTQo" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/be-smh-front.jpg" border="0" height="250" /><img src="images/tdij/be-smh-back.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Isn''t It Romantic?" (Richard Rodgers, Lorenz Hart)  4:37</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Boy Next Door" (Ralph Blane, Hugh Martin)  5:22</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Wonder Why" (Nicholas Brodszky, Sammy Cahn)  5:15</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Swedish Pastry" (Barney Kessel)  5:45</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Love Is Here to Stay" (George Gershwin, Ira Gershwin)  4:46</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"''Round Midnight" (Thelonious Monk, Cootie Williams)  8:54</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Stella by Starlight" (Ned Washington, Victor Young)  4:57</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Blues in F"  5:44</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 63, '2015-05-24 21:07:31', 62, '', '2016-08-17 22:00:59', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-05-30 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 3, 'on this day in jazz, Bill Evans', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 4788, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(427, 'On this day in jazz (May 31)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-may-31', '', '<p>On this day in 1957,   <a href="http://www.johncoltrane.com/" target="_blank">John Coltrane</a> recorded the album <em>Coltrane</em> at Rudy Van Gelder''s studio in Hackensack,   NJ for Prestige Records. Note,   that John also released an album with the same name for Impluse! in 1962--but they are totally different albums. John was supported by a strong cast that included <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mal_Waldron" target="_blank">Mal Waldron</a> and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Red_Garland" target="_blank">Red Garland</a> splitting time at the piano and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Chambers" target="_blank">Paul Chambers</a> supplying the bass. Rating services give the album very strong ratings--not bad for a debut album as a leader.</p>\n<p>1957 was a bit of a turbulent year for Coltrane. In April, <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a> fired him due to his drug issues with heroin--an act that saved John''s life (Miles himself had gone through the same problems with heroin. In order to kick the habit, Miles had moved back to his father''s home in 1954 when the addiction began having negative effects on his career. Miles spent several painful months going through the withdrawal, but of course came back to have the most successful career anyone in jazz has ever had). Shortly after the firing, John moved back to Philadelphia to kick the habit. This session represents his first foray back into the studio after that hiatus. Two of the songs were originals ("Straight Street" and "Chronic Blues") which paid homage to his struggles with addiction and the other four were covers (three of them being standards that fans could quickly identify with).</p>\n<p>Here''s John with "Straight Street":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jdeKliAn1G8" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/coltrane-1957.jpg" border="0" height="250" /><img src="images/tdij/coltrane-rearcover-1600.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Bakai" </span><span style="white-space:pre"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Calvin Massey</span><span style="white-space:pre"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">8:44</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Violets for Your Furs" </span><span style="white-space:pre"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Tom Adair, Matt Dennis</span><span style="white-space:pre"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">6:18</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Time Was" </span><span style="white-space:pre"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Gabriel Luna de la Fuente, Paz Miguel Prado, Keith Russell</span><span style="white-space:pre"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">7:31</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Straight Street" </span><span style="white-space:pre"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">John Coltrane</span><span style="white-space:pre"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">6:21</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"While My Lady Sleeps" </span><span style="white-space:pre"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Gus Kahn, Bronislau Kaper</span><span style="white-space:pre"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">4:44</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Chronic Blues" </span><span style="white-space:pre"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">John Coltrane</span><span style="white-space:pre"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">8:12</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 63, '2015-05-25 19:06:04', 62, '', '2016-08-20 01:03:21', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-05-31 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 5, 0, 1, 'on this day in jazz, John Coltrane', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 4106, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(428, 'On this day in jazz (June 01)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-june-01', '', '<p>On this day in 1964,   <a href="http://www.johncoltrane.com/" target="_blank">John Coltrane</a> completed recording the album <em>Crescent</em> at Rudy Van Gelder''s studio in Englewood Cliffs,   NJ for Impulse! Records. The album consists of five Coltrane originals with John back on the tenor saxophone,   <a href="http://mccoytyner.com/" target="_blank">McCoy Tyner</a> on the piano, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jimmy_Garrison" target="_blank">Jimmy Garrison</a> on bass, and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elvin_Jones" target="_blank">Elvin Jones</a> on drums. You can hear the same four musicians on many of John''s other albums such as <em>Live at Birdland</em>, <em>Impressions</em>, <em>Ballads</em>, and of course <em>A Love Supreme</em>. These men always played really well together, and with John at the helm, this one could be nothing less than spectacular.</p>\n<p>allmusic.com calls this album "an epic album, showing his meditative side that would serve as a perfect prelude to his immortal work <em>A Love Supreme</em>". They list the albums mood as "Elaborate", "Complex", "Searching", "Cerebral", "Passionate" and "Sophisticated". Others would add "Dark". Whatever you call it, it is essentialto any jazz collection.</p>\n<p>Here''s John with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VO_xsFSftDA" target="_blank">Bessie''s Blues</a>":</p>\n<p><img src="images/tdij/john-coltrane-crescent.jpg" border="0" height="250" /><img src="images/tdij/john-coltrane-crescent-back.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Crescent"  8:41</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Wise One"  9:00</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Bessie''s Blues"  3:22</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Lonnie''s Lament"  11:45</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Drum Thing"  7:22</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 64, '2015-05-25 19:29:14', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:26:54', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-06-01 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 30, 'on this day in jazz, John Coltrane', 'on thsi day in jazz', 0, 4211, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(429, 'On this day in jazz (June 02)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-june-02', '', '<p>On this day in 1964,   <a href="http://www.ericdolphy.net/" target="_blank">Eric Dolphy</a>''s last recorded concert was recorded in Hilversum, Holland. Eric played several instruments during the concert: the bass clarinet, the flute, and the alto saxophone. His rhythm section consisted of Misha Mengelberg at the piano, Jacques Schols on bass and Han Bennink on the drums.</p>\n<p>Eric would die in Berlin 27 days later on June 29, 1964. The details of his death are disputed, but it is generally believed that he died due to falling into a diabetic coma (this condition had not been diagnosed previously). Some said that he collapsed in this hotel room; however, others state that he collapsed on stage and the attending physicians believed the collapse was related to substance abuse (as was common to jazz musicians of that time) and was left in a hospital bed for the drugs to run their course which caused his death.</p>\n<p>Here''s Eric with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VO_xsFSftDA" target="_blank">Epistrophy</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VO_xsFSftDA" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/last-date-front.jpg" border="0" height="250" /> <span style="white-space: pre;"><img src="images/tdij/last-date-back.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></span></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Epistrophy" (Monk) 11:15</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"South Street Exit"  7:10</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The madrig speaks, the panther walks"  4:50</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Hypochristmutreefuzz" (Mengelberg) 5:25</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"You don''t know what love is" (Raye/De Paul) 11:20</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Miss Ann"  5:25</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 64, '2015-05-26 18:36:20', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:27:15', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-06-02 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 5, 0, 29, 'On this day in jazz, Eric Dolphy', 'On this day in jazz', 0, 4378, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(430, 'On this day in jazz (June 03)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-june-03', '', '<p>On this day in 1960,   The Modern Jazz Quartet began recording the album <em>The Modern Jazz Quartet & Orchestra</em> in Stuttgart,   West Germany. If you are not familiar with the MJQ,   they were four consummate musicians led by <a href="http://www.pas.org/experience/halloffame/JacksonMilt.aspx" target="_blank">Milt Jackson</a> on vibraphone, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Lewis_(pianist)" target="_blank">John Lewis</a> on piano (and musical director), <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Percy_Heath" target="_blank">Percy Heath</a> on bass and <a href="http://www.drummerworld.com/drummers/Connie_Kay.html" target="_blank">Connie Kay</a> on drums. The lineup played together for three decades on a regular basis until Milt Jackson quit the band for a time. They would occasionally get together and play after the split, recording their last album in 1993--the year before Connie died. On this album you''ll get a chance to hear them backed by a full orchestra (conducted by Werner Heider and Gunther Schuller), which is reason enough to take a listen. Scott Yanow, writing for allmusic.com, actually recommends listening to it several times. I agree.</p>\n<p>Here''s MJQ with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mubAP2biHew" target="_blank">Divertimento</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mubAP2biHew" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/mjq-and-o.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Around the Blues" (Andre Hodeir) - 8:25</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Divertimento" (Werner Heider) - 8:17</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"England''s Carol" (John Lewis) - 6:20</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Concertino for Jazz Quartet and Orchestra: First Movement" (Gunther Schuller) - 6:42</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Concertino for Jazz Quartet and Orchestra: Second Movement - Passacaglia" (Schuller) - 6:38</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Concertino for Jazz Quartet and Orchestra: Third Movement" (Schuller) - 5:54</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 64, '2015-05-27 18:36:51', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:27:37', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-06-03 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 28, 'on this day in jazz, Modern Jazz Quartet', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 4332, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(431, 'On this day in jazz (June 04)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-june-04', '', '<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">On this day in 1975,   virtuoso trumpeter </span><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roy_Eldridge" target="_blank" style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Roy Eldridge</a><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;"> recorded the album Happy Time. Roy can also be heard singing quite a bit on this one. He was joined by the great pianist </span><a href="http://www.oscarpeterson.com/" target="_blank" style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Oscar Peterson</a><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">, guitarist </span><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joe_Pass" target="_blank" style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Joe Pass</a><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">, bassist </span><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ray_Brown_(musician)" target="_blank" style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Ray Brown</a><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">, and drummer Eddie Locke. The album consists of ten songs, most of them jazz standards. </span></p>\n<p>A little bit about Roy: Roy was a true virtuoso on the trumpet who essentially occupies the gap between <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Louis_Armstrong" target="_blank">Louie Armstrong</a> (smooth and lyrical) and <a href="http://www.dizzygillespie.com/" target="_blank">Dizzy Gillespie</a> (bebop). In fact the impact that he made on Dizzy alone should cause him to be regarded as one of the most influential musicians of the swing era. He started playing in <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Artie_Shaw" target="_blank">Artie Shaw</a>''s band in 1944 and was the only non-Caucasian member of that band. As you can imagine, he faced a lot of racism when playing in predominantly white venues and while touring with the band. Artie once said this about Roy''s time with the band: "Droves of people would ask him for his autograph at the end of the night, but later, on the bus, he wouldn''t be able to get off and buy a hamburger with the guys in the band." Another time, while playing in Gene Krupa''s big band, Gene ended up in jail and was heavily fined for starting a fistfight with a restaurant manager who refused to let Eldridge eat with the rest of the band.</p>\n<p>Roy continued to play throughout his life until he suffered a heart attack in 1980 (at age 69). He died in 1989 at the Franklin General Hospital, three weeks after the death of his wife, Viola.</p>\n<p>Here''s Roy with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zK0xYqTA4ko" target="_blank">Makin'' Whoopee</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zK0xYqTA4ko" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Roy_Eldridge-Spotlite-Nov._1946_(William_P._Gottlieb_02271).jpg" border="0" height="250" /><img src="images/tdij/roy-eldridge-c2a9-serge-jacques.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Sweethearts on Parade" (Carmen Lombardo, Charles Newman)  4:20</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Willow Weep for Me" (Ann Ronell)  7:01</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Makin'' Whoopee" (Walter Donaldson, Gus Kahn)  4:42</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Gee Baby, Ain''t I Good to You" (Andy Razaf, Don Redman)  3:33</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"All of Me" (Gerald Marks, Seymour Simons)  4:45</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"I Want a Little Girl" (Murray Mencher, Billy Moll)  4:10</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"On the Sunny Side of the Street" (Dorothy Fields, Jimmy McHugh)  6:55</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"I Can''t Get Started" (Vernon Duke, Ira Gershwin)  4:43</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Call It Stormy Monday (But Tuesday Is Just as Bad)" (T-Bone Walker)  5:18</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Let Me Off Uptown" (Earl Bostic, Redd Evans)  3:04</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 64, '2015-05-27 19:03:28', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:28:01', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-06-04 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 27, 'on this day in jazz, Roy Eldridge', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 4640, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(432, 'On this day in jazz (June 05)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-june-05', '', '<p>On this day in 1956,   <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a> completed the second of three sessions that would comprise the recording of <em>''Round About Midnight</em>. The album is considered Miles Davis'' comeback from heroin addiction and was his first of several successful recordings for Columbia Records. The album has been re-released a couple of times including in 2005 which contained the 2001 enhanced album reissue along with a second disc that contained Davis'' 1955 Newport Jazz Festival performance of "''Round Midnight" and a recording from the 1956 Pacific Jazz Festival. The 1955 NJF performance featured a jam session with <a href="http://www.monkzone.com/" target="_blank">Thelonious Monk</a> (composer of "''Round Midnight"),   along with <a href="http://www.drummerworld.com/drummers/Connie_Kay.html" target="_blank">Connie Kay</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Percy_Heath" target="_blank">Percy Heath</a>, <a href="http://www.zootsims.org/" target="_blank">Zoot Sims</a>, and <a href="http://www.gerrymulligan.com/" target="_blank">Gerry Mulligan</a>. In fact, it was this performance that ended up getting Miles his contract offer with Columbia.</p>\n<p>The original album featured six songs by such greats at Thelonious Monk, <a href="http://www.cmgww.com/music/parker/home.html" target="_blank">Charlie Parker</a> and Cole Porter. Accompanying Miles'' trumpet were <a href="http://www.johncoltrane.com/" target="_blank">John Coltrane</a> on tenor saxophone, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Red_Garland" target="_blank">Red Garland</a> on piano, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Chambers" target="_blank">Paul Chambers</a> on bass, and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philly_Joe_Jones" target="_blank">Philly Joe Jones</a> on the drums--aka the Classic Quartet. The songs that were recorded on this day were "Dear Old Stockholm", "Bye Bye Blackbird" and "Tadd''s Delight".</p>\n<p>Here''s Miles with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1C7DyWdky_Y" target="_blank">Dear Old Stockholm</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1C7DyWdky_Y" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/miles-davis-roundabout-front-cover-1800-ljc.jpg" border="0" height="250" /> <img src="images/tdij/miles-davis-roundabout-back-cover-1800-ljc.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing (original album):</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">''Round Midnight" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Thelonious Monk, Bernie Hanighen, Cootie Williams </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">5:58</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Ah-Leu-Cha" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Charlie Parker </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">5:53</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"All of You" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Cole Porter </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">7:03</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Bye Bye Blackbird" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Mort Dixon, Ray Henderson </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">7:57</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Tadd''s Delight" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Tadd Dameron </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">4:29</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Dear Old Stockholm" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">traditional; arranged by Stan Getz </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">7:52</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 64, '2015-05-30 16:47:40', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:28:27', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-06-05 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 26, 'on this day in jazz, Miles Davis', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 4573, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(433, 'On this day in jazz (June 06)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-june-06', '', '<p>On this day in 1947,   tenor saxophonists <a href="http://www.dextergordon.com/" target="_blank">Dexter Gordon</a> and <a href="http://www.wardellgray.org/" target="_blank">Wardell Gray</a> recorded the songs that would be released on the 1977 live album,   <em>The Hunt</em>. Assisting the two tenors were <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/sonny-criss-mn0000755431/biography" target="_blank">Sonny Criss</a> on alto saxophone, Trummy Young on Trombone, Howard McGhee on Trumpet. The rhythm section was composed of one of my favorite pianists, <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/hampton-hawes-mn0000558596/biography" target="_blank">Hampton Hawes</a>, a fantastic guitarist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barney_Kessel" target="_blank">Barney Kessel</a>, bassists Harry Babasin and Red Callender and dummers <a href="http://www.drummerworld.com/drummers/Connie_Kay.html" target="_blank">Connie Kay</a> and Ken Kennedy. One of the reasons that the music wasn''t released when it was recorded was due to the length of the songs: the shortest song clocks in at 18:05 and the medium to play songs of this length, the 12-inch microgrove disc also known as the LP, wouldn''t be announced for another year.</p>\n<p>An interesting piece of trivia regarding the album--Jack Keroac mentions it in the great Beat Generation book <em>On the Road</em>.</p>\n<p>Here''s Dexter and Wardell with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JvGGG2yfvJs" target="_blank">The Hunt</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JvGGG2yfvJs" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/thehunt.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Disorder At The Border"  (19:20)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Cherokee"  (21:12)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Byas-A-Drink"  (19:15)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Hunt (A/K/A Rocks ''N Shoals)"  (18:05)</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 64, '2015-05-30 17:10:19', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:28:46', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-06-06 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 25, 'On this day in jazz, Dexter Gordon, Wardell Gray', 'On this day in jazz', 0, 4707, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(434, 'On this day in jazz (June 07)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-june-07', '', '<p>On this day in 1954,   <a href="http://www.davebrubeck.com/live/" target="_blank">Dave Brubeck</a> released the live album <em>Jazz Goes to College</em>. The album was Dave''s first for Columbia Records and was composed of recordings from his tour of various colleges that year. The idea, given to Dave by his wife Iola, was to use the album to introduce jazz to a new audience by playing for the younger generation. During the time, the band played about 90 concerts at 90 colleges over 120 days. That''s a lot of school work. The quartet was composed of Dave on piano, the wonderful <a href="http://www.puredesmond.ca/">Paul Desmond</a> on alto saxophone, Bob Bates on bass, and Joe Dodge on drums.</p>\n<p>If you''ve only listened to Dave via the great <em>Time Out</em> album, here''s a chance for you to hear him several years before that breakthrough.</p>\n<p>Here''s Dave with the first song off the album, "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=McqN3JZBgW8" target="_blank">Balcony Rock</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=McqN3JZBgW8" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/106746363.zGCNcfQP.College.jpg" border="0" height="250" /><img src="images/tdij/DaveBrubeck-College2.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Balcony Rock" (Dave Brubeck, Paul Desmond) (University of Michigan)  11:55</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Out of Nowhere" (Johnny Green, Edward Heyman) (University of Cincinnati)  8:04</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Le Souk" (Brubeck, Desmond) (Oberlin College, Ohio)  4:36</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Take the ''A'' Train" (Billy Strayhorn) (University of Michigan)  6:10</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Song Is You" (Oscar Hammerstein II, Jerome Kern) (University of Michigan)  5:38</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Don''t Worry ''bout Me" (Rube Bloom, Ted Koehler) (University of Michigan)  8:47</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"I Want to Be Happy" (Irving Caesar, Vincent Youmans) (University of Michigan)  6:36</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 64, '2015-06-02 23:30:58', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:29:05', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-06-07 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 24, 'On this day in jazz, Dave Brubeck', 'On this day in jazz', 0, 5039, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(435, 'On this day in jazz (June 08)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-june-08', '', '<p>On this day in 1989,   the great <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cecil_Taylor" target="_blank">Cecil Taylor</a> recorded the studio album <em>In Florescence</em> in New York City for A&M Records. By my unofficial count, this was his 56th album (his first was <em>Jazz Advance</em> in 1956--which is one of my favorite Cecil Taylor albums). Besides Cecil on piano, the album was also played by William Parker on bass and Gregg Bendian on percussion.</p>\n<p>Cecil is one of the all-time jazz greats and one of my favorite pianists (even though I am not a huge fan of free jazz). He started playing at age six and was classically trained, studying at the New York College of Music and the New England Conservatory. Val Wilmer, in his book <em>As Serious As Your Life: The Story of the New Jazz</em> (1977) said that his piano technique is similar to percussion, and described his piano as "eighty-eight tuned drums". In an interview with <em>The New York Times</em> in 1991, Cecil said this about his influences and himself in general:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">Literature, theater, it''s all important....You want to create the utmost that is possible, to continue the ideas of certain people who have enriched your life. The Nicholas Brothers or Bojangles, you see them and you start to dance. The love of and respect for the creative impulse everywhere is what I''m after. I''m of American, Indian, African and English heritage, and I follow all those paths. Someone once asked me if I was gay. I said, ''Do you think a three-letter word defines the complexity of my humanity?'' I avoid the trap of easy definition.</p>\n<p>Here''s Cecil from 1956 with "<a href="http://iisaphd.subsonic.org/share/rClYu" target="_blank">Bemsha Swing</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="http://iisaphd.subsonic.org/share/rClYu" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/cecil-taylor-4.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"J." - 2:52</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Pethro Visiting the Abyss" - 7:08</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Saita" - 3:00</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"For Steve McCall" (Gergg Bendian) 1:00</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"In Florescence" - 3:02</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Ell Moving Track" - 5:15</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Sirenes 1/3" - 0:48</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Anast in Crisis Mouthful of Fresh Cut Flowers" (William Parker) - 3:37</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Charles And Thee" - 8:00</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Entity" (Bendian) - 2:32</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Leaf Taken Horn" - 4:53</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Chal Chuiatlichue Goddess of Green Flowing Waters" - 11:29</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Morning Of Departure" - 3:13</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Feng Shui" (Taylor, Bendian, Parker) - 4:35</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 64, '2015-06-03 00:05:32', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:29:23', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-06-08 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 23, 'On this day in jazz, Cecil Taylor', 'On this day in jazz', 0, 4805, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(436, 'On this day in jazz (June 09)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-june-09', '', '<p>On this day in 1958,   the great <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cecil_Taylor" target="_blank">Cecil Taylor</a> recorded the studio album <em>Looking Ahead!</em> at Nola''s Penthouse Studios in New York City for Contemporary Records. This was Cecil''s second album as a leader (yesterday I profiled his 56th album,   <em>In Florescence</em>). The album features Cecil at the piano,   Buell Neidlinger on bass, Denis Charles on the drums, and Earl Griffith on vibes. The vibes really add a different dimension to Cecil''s music.</p>\n<p>Brian Olewnick of allmusic.com said this of the album:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><em>Looking Ahead!</em> does just that (sic) while still keeping several toes in the tradition. It''s an amazing document of a talent fairly straining at the reins, a meteor about to burst onto the jazz scene and render it forever changed...Griffith sounds as though he might have been a conceptual step or two behind the other three but, in the context of the time, this may have served to make the music a shade more palatable to contemporary tastes...<em>Looking Ahead!</em> is a vital recording from the nascence of one of the towering geniuses of modern music and belongs in any jazz fan''s collection.</p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Here''s Cecil with "</span><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1BWm7oU-K8w" target="_blank" style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Wallering</a><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">":</span></p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1BWm7oU-K8w" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/lookingahead-front.jpg" border="0" height="250" /><img src="images/tdij/lookingahead-back.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Luyah! The Glorious Step" - 6:25</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"African Violets" (Griffith, Taylor) - 5:12</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Of What" - 8:18</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Wallering" - 5:22</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Toll" - 7:38</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Excursion on a Wobbly Rail" - 9:04</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 64, '2015-06-03 00:21:05', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:30:13', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-06-09 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 22, 'On this day in jazz, Cecil Taylor', 'On this day in jazz', 0, 4934, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(437, 'On this day in jazz (June 10)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-june-10', '', '<p>On this day in 1965,   the great <a href="http://www.johncoltrane.com/" target="_blank">John Coltrane</a> began recording the album <em>Kulu S Mama</em> at Rudy Van Gelder''s studio in Englewood Cliffs, NJ. The album would be completed after a June 16th session at Rudy''s studio and an October 14th session in Los Angeles. To be specific, song #3, "Welcome" was recorded on this day, songs 2, 5, and 6 on the 16th, and the rest (including the title song) on October 14th. On this day, John played tenor saxophone (instead of soprano), <a href="http://mccoytyner.com/" target="_blank">McCoy Tyner</a> played piano, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jimmy_Garrison" target="_blank">Jimmy Garrison</a> played the bass, and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elvin_Jones" target="_blank">Elvin Jones</a> played the drums. These men were also known as "The Classic Quartet" and played together on many other of John''s albums.</p>\n<p>The album was not released until 1967 and was the last of John''s albums to be released in John''s lifetime. Although the album is not one of my favorite album''s by John, it does feature a couple of songs that are well worth listening to: "Welcome" and the title track, "Kulu S Mama". The title track was written by New Orleans native Julian Bertrand "Juno" Lewis who appears on the song singing in a Creole dialect and playing conch shells. Before the song was recorded, "Kulu S Mama," was a lengthy autobiographical poem written by Lewis that he said reflected his pride in his ancestors and strong sense of tradition.</p>\n<p>Here''s John with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Dhj9X0THMAk" target="_blank">Welcome</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Dhj9X0THMAk" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/john-coltrane-kulu-se-mama-front.jpg" border="0" height="250" /><img src="images/tdij/john-coltrane-kulu-se-mama.jpg" border="0" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Kulu S Mama (Juno S Mama)" - 18:50</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Vigil" - 9:51</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Welcome" - 5:34</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Selflessness" - 14:49</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Dusk Dawn" - 11:00</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 64, '2015-06-03 22:50:36', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:30:28', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-06-10 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 21, 'On this day in jazz, John Coltrane', 'On this day in jazz', 0, 4791, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(438, 'On this day in jazz (June 11)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-june-11', '', '<p>On this day in 1953,   trumpeter <a href="http://cliffordbrown.net/" target="_blank">Clifford Brown</a> began recording the album <em>Memorial</em> in New York City. He would complete the album on September 15 in Stockholm. For the session recorded on June 11, Clifford and <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/art-farmer-mn0000502199/biography" target="_blank">Art Farmer</a> were on trumpets, Arne Domnerus played the alto sax, Lars Gullin was on the baritone sax, and Ake Persson played the trombone. The rhythm section was supplied by Bengt Hallverg on piano, Gunnar Johnson on bass and Jack Noren was on the drums.</p>\n<p>Clifford is the true embodiment of "only the good die young". Unfortunately, he would die 3 years after this album was recorded at the young age of 25. Regarding this album the recording engineer said this:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">When Brownie stood up and took his first solo on "Philly J J", I nearly fell off my seat in the control room. The power, range and brilliance together with the warmth and invention was something that I hadn''t heard since Fats Navarro.</p>\n<p>Here''s Clifford with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=51R_5bLF4H8" target="_blank">Falling In Love</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=51R_5bLF4H8" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/Clifford-Brown-Clifford-Brown-Me-540837.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /><img src="images/tdij/CS554865-01B-BIG.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Stockholm Sweetnin''" (Quincy Jones) - 5:29</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"''Scuse These Blues" (Quincy Jones) - 4:29</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Falling in Love With Love" (Richard Rodgers, Lorenz Hart) - 5:25</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Lover Come Back to Me" (Sigmund Romberg, Oscar Hammerstein II) - 5:22</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Philly J J" (Tadd Dameron) - 5:14</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Dial ''B'' for Beauty" (Dameron) - 4:37</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Theme of No Repeat" (Dameron) - 5:23</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Choose Now" [#1] (Dameron) - 4:57</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Choose Now" [#2] (Dameron) - 3:26</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 64, '2015-06-04 18:42:31', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:31:19', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-06-11 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 20, 'On this day in jazz, Clifford Brown', 'On this day in jazz', 0, 4579, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(439, 'On this day in jazz (June 12)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-june-12', '', '<p>On this day in 1964,   guitarist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grant_Green" target="_blank">Grant Green</a> recorded music for the album <em>Solid</em> at Rudy Van Gelder''s studio in Englewood Cliffs, NJ. Although the album was recorded in 1964, it didn''t get released until Blue Note released it in 1979. That''s very odd given how good the music is:<span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 15.8079996109009px;">allmusic.com rated it four and a half stars and The Rolling Stone Jazz Record Guide gave it five stars.</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;"> It''s true that it was recorded only a month after his album </span><em style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Matador</em><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;"> was recorded--but you would think the label would have found a way to release it sooner. Grant was joined by James Spaulding on the alto saxophone, <a href="http://www.joehendersonsax.com/" target="_blank">Joe Henderson</a> on the tenor saxophone, the wonderful <a href="http://mccoytyner.com/" target="_blank">McCoy Tyner</a> at the piano, Bob Cranshaw on bass and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elvin_Jones" target="_blank">Elvin Jones</a> on the drums--that''s a very fine lineup.</span></p>\n<p>Steve Huey of allmusic.com said this of the album:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">Solid is a bright, hard-charging affair. There''s a little modal jazz, but Solid''s repertoire is chiefly complex hard bop, full of challenging twists and turns that the players burn through with enthusiasm. Green didn''t tackle this kind of material  or play with this kind of group  very often, and it''s a treat to hear him do so on both counts... one of Green''s strongest jazz outings and a unique standout in his catalog.</p>\n<p>Here''s Grant with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jcbfBH2t4to" target="_blank">Grant''s Tune</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jcbfBH2t4to" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/gg-solid-f.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;"></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Minor League" (Pearson)  7:05</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Ezz-Thetic" (Russell)  10:41</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Grant''s Tune" (Grant Green)  7:01</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Solid" (Rollins)  7:23</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Kicker" (Henderson)  6:23</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 64, '2015-06-04 18:59:44', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:31:40', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-06-12 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 19, 'On this day in jazz, Grant Green', 'On this day in jazz', 0, 4860, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(440, 'On this day in jazz (June 13)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-june-13', '', '<p>On this day in 1980,   pianist <a href="http://www.andrewhilljazz.com/" target="_blank">Andrew Hill</a> began recording his 22nd album, <em>Strange Serenade</em> at Barigozzi Studios in Milano, Italy. The album consists of four songs: three originals and the song "Andrew" which was written by his wife, Laverne Hill. Completing the trio were Alan Silva on bass and Freddie Waits on the drums. allmusic.com rates the album with four stars, calling it "stirring".</p>\n<p>Hill was born in Chicago in 1931 where he took up the piano at age 13 and attended the University of Chicago Experimental School. As a teenager he joined legends such as Miles Davis and Charlie Parker when their tours came to town. In the 1950s he played with jazz greats such as Eric Dolphy, Bobby Hutcherson, Joe Henderson, Freddie Hubbard, Woody Shaw, Hank Mobley and Tony Williams (just to name a few). In 1961, while he was an accompanist for Dinah Washington, he moved to New York City and shortly thereafter primarily recorded as a leader.</p>\n<p>Andrew had a very long career lasting from the early 1950s until his death in 2007. In the years 2000-2008, he won the following awards:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">2001: "Dusk" was the Down Beat Album of the Year; Down Beat Winner Critics Poll Jazz (also in 2000)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">2006: Jazz Journalist Composer of Year Awards (as well as in 2000, 2001 and 2003); "Time Lines" was Down Beat Album of the Year; Playboy Jazz Artist of the Year</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">2007: election to the Downbeat Hall of Fame; Jazz Journalist Association Pianist of the Year, Composer of the Year and Lifetime Achievement Award; conferred an honorary Doctorate of Music-Berklee College of Music</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">2008: National Endowment for the Arts (NEA) Jazz Master (our nation''s highest jazz honor)</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p></p>\n<p>Here''s Andrew with "<a href="http://iisaphd.subsonic.org/share/nRPFE" target="_blank">Mist Flower</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="http://iisaphd.subsonic.org/share/nRPFE" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/hilla.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Mist Flower" - 15:26</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Strange Serenade" - 7:03</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Reunion" - 8:50</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Andrew" (Laverne Hill) - 10:40</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 64, '2015-06-07 19:18:13', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:32:03', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-06-13 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 18, 'on this day in jazz, Andrew Hill', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 4811, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(441, 'On this day in jazz (June 14)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-june-14', '', '<p>On this day in 1957,   cornetist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Webster_Young" target="_blank">Webster Young</a> recorded the album <em>For Lady</em> (for Lady Day,   Billie Holiday) at Rudy Van Gelder''s studio in Englewood Cliffs,   NJ. The album was the only one which Webster would record as a leader, but it includes one of my all time favorite songs, "Moanin'' Low". Most of the songs were songs that Billie Holiday had made famous; however, Webster did throw in one original--the title track, "For Lady". Webster was joined by Paul Quinichette on tenor saxophone, the wonderful <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mal_Waldron" target="_blank">Mal Waldron</a> on piano, Joe Puma on guitar, Earl May on bass, and Ed Thigpen on the drums.</p>\n<p>Jim Todd reviewed the album for allmusic.com, saying: "While trumpeter Webster Young pays tribute to Billie Holiday on this, his only studio date as a leader, the set is equally a tribute to Young''s musical role model, <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a>". It''s too bad that he didn''t record more often. Instead of touring and recording he decided to move from New York City back to Washington, DC, during the mid-1960s to teach music theory at the University of the District of Columbia. Later, he became the director of the District of Columbia Music Center jazz workshop band. Webster died in 2003 from brain cancer.</p>\n<p>Here''s Webster with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Xthy56SVFXM" target="_blank">Moanin'' Low</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Xthy56SVFXM" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/wy-fl-front.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /><img src="images/tdij/wy-fl-back.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Lady" (Webster Young) - 7:00</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"God Bless the Child" (Billie Holiday, Arthur Herzog, Jr.) - 7:05</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Moanin'' Low" (Howard Dietz, Ralph Rainger) - 7:42</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Good Morning Heartache" (Ervin Drake, Dan Fisher, Irene Higginbotham) - 8:54</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Don''t Explain" (Holiday, Herzog) - 7:10</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Strange Fruit" (Abel Meeropol) - 4:18</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 64, '2015-06-07 19:34:41', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:32:25', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-06-14 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 17, 'on this day in jazz, Webster Young', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 4823, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(442, 'On this day in jazz (June 15)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-june-14', '', '<p>On this day in 1967,   <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ant%C3%B4nio_Carlos_Jobim" target="_blank">Antnio Carlos Jobim</a> completed recording the album <em>Wave</em> at Rudy Van Gelder''s studio in Englewood Cliffs,   NJ. It was a very successful album, reaching #5 on the US Jazz Album charts. On this album you will hear Tom (his preferred name) playing piano, guitar, celeste and harpsichord. He was assisted by a large cast including a string orchestra.</p>\n<p>allmusic.com gives the album a perfect five star rating and Rolling Stone Brazil lists the album as one of the 100 best Brazilian albums in history. In his review, Richard S. Ginell said this of the album:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">...this stunningly seductive record, possibly Jobim''s best. Jobim contributes his sparely rhythmic acoustic guitar, simple melodic piano style, a guest turn at the harpsichord, and even a vocal on "Lamento," while Claus Ogerman lends a romantically brooding hand with the charts. A pair of instant standards are introduced ("Wave," "Triste"), but this album is to be cherished for its absolutely first-rate tunes -- actually miniature tone poems -- that escaped overexposure and thus sound fresh today.</p>\n<p>If you''re looking for something relaxing to listen to, I think that this album is a great one to put on.</p>\n<p>Here''s Tom with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=a6KDpB6skA4" target="_blank">Wave</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=a6KDpB6skA4" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/wave.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Wave"  2:56</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Red Blouse"  5:09</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Look to the Sky"  2:20</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Batidinha"  3:17</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Triste"  2:09</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Mojave"  2:27</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Dilogo"  2:55</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Lamento" (lyrics by Vinicius de Moraes)  2:46</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Antigua"  3:10</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Captain Bacardi"  4:29</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 64, '2015-06-07 20:47:52', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:32:39', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-06-14 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 16, 'on this day in jazz, Antonio Carlos Jobim', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 4987, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(443, 'On this day in jazz (June 16)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-june-16', '', '<p>On this day in 1960,   <a href="http://www.geneammons.net/" target="_blank">Gene Ammons</a> recorded the album <em>Boss Tenor</em> at Rudy Van Gelder''s studio in Englewood Cliffs,  NJ. Gene was assited on the album by a rhythm section of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tommy_Flanagan" target="_blank">Tommy Flanagan</a> on piano,   Doug Watkins on bass and <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/art-taylor-mn0000505154/biography" target="_blank">Art Taylor</a> on the drums--quite a strong lineup (Ray Barretto was also on the album playing the congas). Be sure not to confuse this album with the one titled <em>Boss Tenors</em>--that album was recorded a year later in Chicago with <a href="http://www.sonnystitt.com/" target="_blank">Sonny Stitt</a> providing the other tenor (and it also had a completely different rhythm section).</p>\n<p>Mark Keresman reviewed the album for allmusic.com and said this: "...Ammons was of the generation of swing-era players that easily adapted to bop. But though he was a modernist, Ammons maintained that breathy, old-school romantic approach to the tenor. Boss Tenor, a quintet session from 1960, is one of Ammons'' very best albums."</p>\n<p>A little bit about Gene: he was born in Chicago and gained recognition while still in high school (1943). In 1944, he joined Billy Eckstine''s band. It was Billy who gave him the nickname, Jug, which was based on the size of his head. While in this band he was able to play alongside such jazz greats as Charlie Parker and Dexter Gordon. He was very prolific in the 1950s, but in 1958 he was convicted of narcotics possession and served time from 1958 to 1960. Unfortunately, he didn''t learn his lesson and ended up serving a second sentence from 1962 to 1969. However, when he was released from Joliet, he was signed the largest contract the Prestige label had ever given and recorded for them until he did from cancer in 1974. Although he only spent five years on the label, he produced 18 albums in that time. I guess he had a lot to make up for...</p>\n<p>Here''s Jug with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ol5E37pMaiw" target="_blank">Hittin'' the Jug</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ol5E37pMaiw" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/boss-tenor-f.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /><img src="images/tdij/boss-tenor-b.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Hittin'' the Jug" - 8:29</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Close Your Eyes" (Bernice Petkere) - 3:46</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"My Romance" (Lorenz Hart, Richard Rodgers) - 4:16</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Canadian Sunset" (Norman Gimbel, Eddie Heywood) - 5:24</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Blue Ammons" - 4:57</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Confirmation" (Charlie Parker) - 5:24</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Savoy" (Bill Doggett, Lucky Millinder) - 3:31</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 64, '2015-06-07 21:41:29', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:32:56', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-06-16 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 15, 'on this day in jazz, Gene Ammons.', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 4981, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(444, 'On this day in jazz (June 17)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-june-17', '', '<p>On this day in 1964,   <a href="http://www.herbiehancock.com/home.php" target="_blank">Herbie Hancock</a> recorded his fourth album,   <em>Empyrean Isles</em>, at Rudy Van Gelder''s studio in Englewood Cliffs, NJ for Blue Note Records. The album consists of four songs, all originals written by Herbie, and played by nothing less than jazz royalty: Herbie on the piano, <a href="http://www.freddiehubbardmusic.com/" target="_blank">Freddie Hubbard</a> on cornet (instead of trumpet), <a href="http://roncarter.net/JazzMaster/" target="_blank">Ron Carter</a> on bass and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tony_Williams_(drummer)" target="_blank">Tony Williams</a> on the drums. That''s a great, great, great lineup.</p>\n<p>Even if you''re not a huge jazz fan, you''ve still probably heard sample of "Cantaloupe Island". When the rap band US3 recorded their debut album in 1992, they extensively sampled the Blue Note catalog and had a hit with the song "Flip Fantasia" (US #9) which features samples of the song. US3''s song is really good--check it out <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JwBjhBL9G6U" target="_blank">here</a>.</p>\n<p>All of Herbie''s albums from the 1960s are really good--sounding as good today as they did 50 years ago. If you haven''t listened to Herbie much, go ahead and start with this album plus Takin'' Off, Maiden Voyage, and Fat Albert Rotunda. And, if you get a chance, go see him on tour this year with Chick Corea.Oh, and congratulations to Herbie for being awarded the <a href="http://www.paris.fr/english/english/paris-gears-up-to-host-international-jazz-day-2015/rub_8118_actu_155405_port_19237" target="_blank">Grand Vermeil medal</a> in Paris on International Jazz Day this year (April 30, 2015).</p>\n<p>Here''s Herbie with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8B1oIXGX0Io" target="_blank">Cantaloupe Island</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8B1oIXGX0Io" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/hh-ei-f.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /><img src="images/tdij/hh-ei-back.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"One Finger Snap"  7:20</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Oliloqui Valley"  8:28</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Cantaloupe Island"  5:32</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Egg"  14:00</span></li>\n</ol>\n<div>Although, I really like the above version of CI, <a href="http://iisaphd.subsonic.org/share/rmsMX" target="_blank">here''s a link to a slightly faster version</a> (assuming my Raspberry Pi is up and running).</div>', '', 1, 8, 0, 64, '2015-06-09 20:31:49', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:33:32', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-06-17 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 14, 'on this day in jazz, Herbie Hancock', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 4856, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(445, 'On this day in jazz (June 18)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-june-18', '', '<p>On this day in 1993,   tenor saxophonist <a href="http://www.joelovano.com/" target="_blank">Joe Lovano</a> recorded the album <em><a href="http://www.joelovano.com/albums/detail/10/Tenor-Legacy" target="_blank">Tenor Legacy</a></em> for Blue Note Records. The album consists of some old and some new (five originals by Joe).Joe was assisted on the album by Joshua Redman on tenor saxophone,   Mulgrew Miller on piano, Christian McBride on bass and Lewis Nash on drums (Don Alias added percussion).</p>\n<p>Scott Yanow reviewed the album saying:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">...rather than jam on standards, Joe Lovano composed five new originals, revived three obscurities and only chose to perform two familiar pieces. By varying the styles and instrumentation (for example "Bread and Wine" does not have piano or bass), Lovano has created a set with a great deal of variety and some surprising moments. The two tenors (who have distinctive sounds) work together fine and some chances are taken. This matchup works well.</span></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">I agree, it is a really good album. If you are not familiar with Joe, here''s a little bit about him. He was born in 1952 in Cleveland, OH to parents of Sicilian decent. His father was was a tenor player himself and was the one who taught Joe how to play (first on the smaller alto saxophone at 6, and then on the tenor at 11). </span>He''s had a strong career that''s seen him release almost 30 albums as a leader--and he still plays today (check out his web site for upcoming performances). His album <em>Quartets: Live at the Village Vanguard</em>, won <em>Down Beat Magazine</em>''s "Jazz Album of the Year" award. I''m sure that he will win others as time goes on.</p>\n<p>Here''s Joe with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YgqMcDOAUhU" target="_blank">Love Is a Many Splendored Thing</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YgqMcDOAUhU" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/jl-tl.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Miss Etna" - 6:30</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Love Is a Many Splendored Thing" (Sammy Fain, Paul Francis Webster) - 6:44</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Blackwell''s Message" - 5:36</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Laura" (Johnny Mercer, David Raksin) - 4:31</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Introspection" (Thelonious Monk) - 9:05</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"In the Land of Ephesus" - 6:58</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"To Her Ladyship" (Billy Frazier) - 9:03</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Web of Fire" - 5:51</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Rounder''s Mood" (Booker Little) - 8:20</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Bread and Wine" - 3:31</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 64, '2015-06-11 17:11:58', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:33:50', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-06-18 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 13, 'on this day in jazz, Joe Lovano', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 4528, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(446, 'On this day in jazz (June 19)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-june-19', '', '<p>On this day in 1969,   <a href="www.quincyjones.com" target="_blank">Quincy Jones</a> completed the recording of the album <em>Walking In Space</em> for A&M Records. The album features a couple of songs from the musical <em>Hair</em> (including the title song) played in a Big Band setting. Quincy,   as you might expect,   does not play on the album--he conducts it. Some of the most famous jazz musicians of the time are featured on it:<span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;"><a href="http://www.freddiehubbardmusic.com/" target="_blank">Freddie Hubbard</a> on trumpet; <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/jj-johnson-mn0000119111/biography" target="_blank">Jay Jay Johnson</a> on trombone; <a href="http://www.bjbear71.com/Winding/Kai.html" target="_blank">Kai Winding</a> on trombone; <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rahsaan_Roland_Kirk" target="_blank">Rahsaan Roland Kirk</a> on reeds; <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ray_Brown_(musician)" target="_blank">Ray Brown</a> on bass; and <a href="http://www.tootsthielemans.com/" target="_blank">Toots Thielemans</a> on guitar & harmonica. That''s quite a list!</span></p>\n<p>I''m sure most people know who Quincy Jones is, but feel it is appropriate to list some of the accolades he has garnered over his legendary career. Here is a short list (there is a whole <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_awards_and_nominations_received_by_Quincy_Jones" target="_blank">page on wikipedia</a> for the entire list):</p>\n<p></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">a record 79 Grammy Award nominations</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">27 Grammys wins (ranks 2nd in all-time wins)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">a Grammy Legend Award (1991)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">first African American to be nominated for an Academy Award for Best Original Song (Banning) and Best Original Score (In Cold Blood) both in 1967</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p></p>\n<p>Here''s Quincy with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VF_u0keV1Vs" target="_blank">Killer Joe</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VF_u0keV1Vs" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/qj-wis-f.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Dead End" (Galt MacDermot, James Rado, Gerome Ragni)  4:05</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Walking in Space" (MacDermot, Rado, Ragni)  12:06</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Killer Joe" (Benny Golson)  5:12</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Love and Peace" (Arthur Adams)  5:48</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"I Never Told You" (Arthur Hamilton, Johnny Mandel)  4:18</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Oh Happy Day" (Edwin Hawkins)  3:37</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 64, '2015-06-11 17:31:37', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:34:08', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-06-19 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 12, 'on this day in jazz, Quincy Jones', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 4792, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(447, 'On this day in jazz (June 20)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-june-20', '', '<p>On this day in 1974,   guitarist <a href="http://www.georgebenson.com/" target="_blank">George Benson</a> completed recording the album <em>Bad Benson</em> at Rudy Van Gelder''s studio in Englewood Cliffs,   NJ. Assisting George on the album were Phil Upchurch also playing guitar as well as electric bass and percussion,   <a href="http://kennybarron.com/" target="_blank">Kenny Barron</a> on piano, Jazz Master<a href="http://roncarter.net/JazzMaster/" target="_blank">Ron Carter</a> on bass and Steve Gadd on the drums. Not a bad lineup at all.</p>\n<p>Thom Jurek reviewed the album for allmusic.com saying that the album was "<span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">a collection of delicious, varied, and sometimes confusing choices. Benson''s own playing is precise and smooth as always, and guitarist Phil Upchurch keeps a large color palette for him to draw from, as in the funkified version of ''Take Five''."</span></p>\n<p>Here''s George with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FhSBK8VaLss" target="_blank">Take Five</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FhSBK8VaLss" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/bb-f.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Take Five" (Paul Desmond) - 7:08</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Summer Wishes, Winter Dreams" (Alan Bergman, Marilyn Bergman, Johnny Mandel) - 2:56</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"My Latin Brother" (George Benson) - 6:50</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"No Sooner Said Than Done" (Phil Upchurch) - 5:59</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Full Compass" (Upchurch) - 5:40</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Changing World" (Benson, Art Gore) - 4:53</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 64, '2015-06-14 01:56:22', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:34:24', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-06-20 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 11, 'on this day in jazz, George Benson', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 4019, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(448, 'On this day in jazz (June 21)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-june-21', '', '<p>On this day in 2000,   <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steve_Lacy" target="_blank">Steve Lacy</a> and <a href="http://www.roswellrudd.com/docs/main/frame.htm" target="_blank">Roswell Rudd</a> began recording the studio album <em>Monk''s Dream</em> for Verve Records in Paris. On the record,   Steve plays the soprano saxophone, Roswell plays the trombone, Jean-Jacques Avenel is on bass and John Betsch plays the drums. Singer Irene Aebi provides vocals on two of the tracks: "A Bright Pearl" and "Traces".</p>\n<p>The album is composed of only two songs written by <a href="http://www.monkzone.com/" target="_blank">Thelonious Monk</a> (of course, one of them is "Monk''s Dream"). Filling out the rest of the material is <a href="http://www.dukeellington.com/" target="_blank">Duke Ellington</a>''s "Koko" and six songs written by Steve. In his review, William Ruhlmann notes that the two had played together over the past 40 years and had very good chemistry; however, he would also add:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">they sound comfortable with each other, but also, given their long association and the mostly familiar material, they don''t seem to have been greatly challenged. They sound most comfortable with the Monk tunes and take some chances with the Ellington, but on Lacy''s tunes they sometimes stretch out pointlessly.</p>\n<p>Despite the harsh criticism in that sentence, he gives the album four out of five stars--so it''s definitely worth a listen.</p>\n<p>Here''s Steve and Roswell with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BfpHUbLsv6Y" target="_blank">Monk''s Dream</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BfpHUbLsv6Y" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/sl-md-f.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /><img src="images/tdij/sl-md-b.jpg" border="0" width="275" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Monk''s Dream" (Monk) - 7:35</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Bath" - 11:43</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Rent" - 10:45</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Pannonica" (Monk) - 9:26</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"A Bright Pearl" - 5:55</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Traces" (text by Ry?kan) - 8:03</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Koko" (Ellington) - 5:21</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Grey Blue" - 10:08</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Door" - 7:05</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 64, '2015-06-16 22:11:34', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:34:39', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-06-21 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 10, 'on this day in jazz, Steve Lacy, Roswell Rudd', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 4406, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(449, 'On this day in jazz (June 22)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-june-22', '', '<p>On this day in 1956,   jazz legend <a href="http://sonnyrollins.com/" target="_blank">Sonny Rollins</a> (who will celebrate his 85th birthday on September 7, 2015) recorded the magnificent album <em>Saxophone Colossus</em> at Rudy Van Gelder''s studio in Hackensack, NJ. The rhythm section supporting Sonny''s tenor were <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tommy_Flanagan" target="_blank">Tommy Flanagan</a> on piano, Doug Watkins on bass and the wonderful <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/max-roach-mn0000396372/biography" target="_blank">Max Roach</a> on the drums. The album is a real treat to listen to and is currently rated the eighth best jazz album of all time at <a href="http://jazz100.sffjazz.com/top100.html" target="_blank">http://jazz100.sffjazz.com/top100.html</a>. Check out their list--I have a hard time disagreeing with the first 50 or so--it''s a good place to go to in order to start building your jazz collection.</p>\n<p>The album consists of five songs including three originals written by Sonny. Probably the most famous of the songs on the album is "St. Thomas" which is truly one of the best played tunes in jazz history. I think the second best song on the album is "Moritat" which is from Weill & Brecht''s <em>The Threepenny Opera</em>. You probably know the song by its English name: "Mack the Knife". Another interesting song is "Blue 7" which is an 11+ minute song that was completely improvised during the recording.</p>\n<p>Here''s Sonny with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UA2XIWZxMKM" target="_blank">St. Thomas</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UA2XIWZxMKM" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/sr-sc-f.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /><img src="images/tdij/sr-sc-b.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"St. Thomas" Sonny Rollins 6:49</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"You Don''t Know What Love Is" Gene de Paul, Don Raye 6:30</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Strode Rode" Sonny Rollins 5:17</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Moritat" Kurt Weill, Bertolt Brecht 10:05</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Blue 7" Sonny Rollins 11:17</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 64, '2015-06-16 22:35:34', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:34:53', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-06-22 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 9, 'on this day in jazz, Sonny Rollins', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 4482, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(450, 'On this day in jazz (June 23)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-june-23', '', '<p>On this day in 1969,   the Art Ensemble of Chicago recorded the studio album <em>A Jackson in Your House</em> for the French label BYG Actuel. The personnel that played on the album were Lester Bowie on trumpet,   Malachi Favors Maghostut on bass and vocals,   Joseph Jarman on saxophones, and clarinets and Roscoe Mitchell on saxophones, clarinets, and flute. Oh, by the way, they ALL played percussion also.</p>\n<p>If you are not familiar with The Art Ensemble of Chicago, here is a little bit about them. They were an avant-garde jazz ensemble that formed from out of Chicago''s AACM (Association for the Advancement of Creative Musicians) in the late 1960s from members of the Roscoe Mitchell Sextet which had formed in 1966. The Sextet included saxophonist Roscoe Mitchell, trumpeter Lester Bowie and bassist Malachi Favors Maghostut, who (over the next year) became the Roscoe Mitchell Art Ensemble. It was in 1967 they were joined by fellow AACM members Joseph Jarman and Phillip Wilson and began to record as the Chicago Art Ensemble. The group continued to record through 2006 when their last album Non-Cognitive Aspects of the City was recorded for Pi Recordings. They are well known for integrating the musical styles across jazz''s entire history into their recordings and also for each of them being multi-instrumentalists. They were never afraid to pull in any kind of instrument that could produce the sound that they needed and have used bicycle horns, bells, birthday party noisemakers, wind chimes, and even "found objects"--in fact, for their European tour to support this album they had over 500 instruments at their disposal.</p>\n<p>Here''s the Art Ensemble of Chicago with "A Jackson In Your House":</p>\n<p><a href="http://iisaphd.subsonic.org/share/tljDq" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/aec-aj-f.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /><img src="images/tdij/aec-aj-b.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"A Jackson In Your House"  5:40</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Get In Line"  5:45</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Waltz"  1:15</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Ericka" (Jarman)  3:33</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Song For Charles"  17:30</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 64, '2015-06-20 18:26:19', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:35:13', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-06-23 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 8, 'on this day in jazz, Art Ensemble of Chicago', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 4491, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(451, 'On this day in jazz (June 24)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-june-24', '', '<p>On this day in 1972,   <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rahsaan_Roland_Kirk" target="_blank">Rahsaan Roland Kirk</a> was recorded in concert for the album <em>I, Eye, Aye: Live at the Montreux Jazz Festival, 1972</em>. During the concert, you can hear Rahsaan playing the tenor saxophone, manzello, stritch, clarinet and flute. His rhythm section was composed of Ron Burton at the piano, Henry "Pete" Pearson on bass, Robert Shy on the drums and Joe Habad Texidor with additional percussion.</p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Continuing with the avant-garde theme from yesterday, I thought that Rahsaan was a perfect follow up--plus I think that I have only featured him one other time on my blog. Like several other jazz giants of the 60s and 70s, Kirk was outspoken when it cam to both black history and civil rights--often breaking into monologue between songs. Jay Leno who opened for Rahsaan on one of his tours said that Kirk would introduce him by saying, "I want to introduce a young brother who knows the black experience and knows all about the white devils .... Please welcome Jay Leno!". I wonder who was the better comedian? One other bit of trivia: Jimi Hendrix, arguably the greatest rock guitarist of all time, had hoped to record with Rahsaan but unfortunately would die before that could happen.</span></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Thom Jurek in his review for allmusic.com said the following about the album:</span></p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">This live recording is a companion to a documentary called The One Man Twins...The set is absolutely electrifying. From the few short raps Kirk offers the crowd, one cannot be prepared for the honking, shouting, funky, gritty sets that follow... This is a hell of an introduction to one of the least-understood figures in jazz history, and an absolute necessity for fans.</p>\n<p>Here''s Rahsaan with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-6ryVryFnEY" target="_blank">Volunteered Slavery</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-6ryVryFnEY" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/rrk-eai-f.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Rahsaantalk, No. 1" - 0:38</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Seasons" - 6:00</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Rahsaantalk, No. 2" - 1:12</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Balm in Gilead" (Traditional) - 7:05</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Volunteered Slavery" - 10:20</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Rahsaantalk, No. 3" - 0:24</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Blue Rol, No. 2" - 9:04</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Solo Piece: Satin Doll/Improvisation" (Duke Ellington/Kirk) - 4:19</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Serenade to a Cuckoo" - 3:28</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Pedal Up" - 6:11</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 64, '2015-06-20 18:29:30', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:35:28', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-06-24 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 7, 'on this day in jazz, Rahsaan Roland Kirk', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 4445, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(452, 'On this day in jazz (June 25)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-june-25', '', '<p>On this day in 1972,   <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rahsaan_Roland_Kirk" target="_blank">Rahsaan Roland Kirk</a> was recorded in concert for the album <em>I, Eye, Aye: Live at the Montreux Jazz Festival, 1972</em>. During the concert, you can hear Rahsaan playing the tenor saxophone, manzello, stritch, clarinet and flute. His rhythm section was composed of Ron Burton at the piano, Henry "Pete" Pearson on bass, Robert Shy on the drums and Joe Habad Texidor with additional percussion.</p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Continuing with the avant-garde theme from yesterday, I thought that Rahsaan was a perfect follow up--plus I think that I have only featured him one other time on my blog. Like several other jazz giants of the 60s and 70s, Kirk was outspoken when it cam to both black history and civil rights--often breaking into monologue between songs. Jay Leno who opened for Rahsaan on one of his tours said that Kirk would introduce him by saying, "I want to introduce a young brother who knows the black experience and knows all about the white devils .... Please welcome Jay Leno!". I wonder who was the better comedian? One other bit of trivia: Jimi Hendrix, arguably the greatest rock guitarist of all time, had hoped to record with Rahsaan but unfortunately would die before that could happen.</span></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Thom Jurek in his review for allmusic.com said the following about the album:</span></p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">This live recording is a companion to a documentary called The One Man Twins...The set is absolutely electrifying. From the few short raps Kirk offers the crowd, one cannot be prepared for the honking, shouting, funky, gritty sets that follow... This is a hell of an introduction to one of the least-understood figures in jazz history, and an absolute necessity for fans.</p>\n<p>Here''s Rahsaan with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-6ryVryFnEY" target="_blank">Volunteered Slavery</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-6ryVryFnEY" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/rrk-eai-f.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Rahsaantalk, No. 1" - 0:38</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Seasons" - 6:00</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Rahsaantalk, No. 2" - 1:12</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Balm in Gilead" (Traditional) - 7:05</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Volunteered Slavery" - 10:20</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Rahsaantalk, No. 3" - 0:24</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Blue Rol, No. 2" - 9:04</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Solo Piece: Satin Doll/Improvisation" (Duke Ellington/Kirk) - 4:19</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Serenade to a Cuckoo" - 3:28</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Pedal Up" - 6:11</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>\n<p>On this day in 1964,   pianist Andrew Hill recorded the album Andrew!!! at Rudy Van Gelder''s studio in Hackensack, NJ. Also appearing on the album were John Gilmore on the tenor saxophone, the great Bobby Hutcherson on vibraphone, Richard Davis on bass and Joe Chambers on the drums. This was Andrew''s sixth album and features six songs of avant-garde & modal post-bop and is one of his least accessible albums for most casual jazz fans.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Stephen Thomas Erlewine reviewed the album for allmusic.com, saying "Andrew!!! is just as adventurous and challenging as any of his other albums, which is to Hill''s credit.... Often, the music has a floating, hypnotic quality, which only makes Hill''s dissonance, unusual voicings, and complex arrangements more compelling than usual.</p>\n<p>If this album seems to be a little too much for you, then check out some of his other more accessible recordings such as "So In Love", "Smoke Stack" or "Judgement!"</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Here''s Andrew with "Black Monday":</p>\n<p><img src="images/tdij/ah-a-f.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /></p>\n<p>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4FJritoqyMk</p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p><ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Groits" - 6:04</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Black Monday" - 8:55</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Duplicity" - 6:11</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Le Serpent Qui Danse" - 6:55</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"No Doubt" - 4:23</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Symmetry" - 7:08</span></li>\n</ol></p>', '', 1, 0, 0, 0, '2015-06-22 16:47:06', 62, '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-06-22 16:46:06', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 1, 0, 7, '', '', 0, 18166, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(453, 'On this day in jazz (June 25)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-june-25', '', '<p>On this day in 1964,   pianist <a href="http://www.andrewhilljazz.com/" target="_blank">Andrew Hill</a> recorded the album <em>Andrew!!!</em> at Rudy Van Gelder''s studio in Hackensack,NJ. Also appearing on the album were John Gilmore on the tenor saxophone, the great <a href="http://www.bluenote.com/artists/bobby-hutcherson" target="_blank">Bobby Hutcherson</a> on vibraphone, Richard Davis on bass and <a href="http://www.josephachambers.com/" target="_blank">Joe Chambers</a> on the drums. This was Andrew''s sixth album and features six songs of avant-garde & modal post-bop and is one of his least accessible albums for most casual jazz fans.</p>\n<p>Stephen Thomas Erlewine reviewed the album for allmusic.com, saying: "Andrew!!! is just as adventurous and challenging as any of his other albums, which is to Hill''s credit.... Often, the music has a floating, hypnotic quality, which only makes Hill''s dissonance, unusual voicings, and complex arrangements more compelling than usual."</p>\n<p>If this album seems to be a little too much for you, then check out some of his other more accessible recordings such as <em>So In Love,Smoke Stack</em> or <em>Judgement!</em></p>\n<p>Here''s Andrew with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4FJritoqyMk" target="_blank">Black Monday</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4FJritoqyMk" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/ah-a-f.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Groits" - 6:04</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Black Monday" - 8:55</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Duplicity" - 6:11</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Le Serpent Qui Danse" - 6:55</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"No Doubt" - 4:23</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Symmetry" - 7:08</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 64, '2015-06-22 16:47:42', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:35:47', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-06-25 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 5, 0, 6, 'on this day in jazz, Andrew Hill', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 4366, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(454, 'On this day in jazz (June 26)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-june-26', '', '<p>On this day in 1967,   guitarist <a href="http://www.wesmontgomery.com/" target="_blank">Wes Montgomery</a> finished recording the album <em>A Day In the Life</em>. The album was a very successful one, reaching #1 on Billboard''s Jazz album chart, #2 on the R&B chart, and #13 on the Billboard 200 chart. Additionally, the song "Windy" reached #44 on the singles chart. Although Wes is definitely a great jazz guitarist, this album almost slides into the realm of muzak. Assisting Wes on the album were a cast of over 25 musicians, mostly playing strings, but also included were jazz greats <a href="http://www.herbiehancock.com/home.php" target="_blank">Herbie Hancock</a> on piano and <a href="http://roncarter.net/JazzMaster/" target="_blank">Ron Carter</a> on bass.</p>\n<p>The song "A Day In the Life" is, of course, Lennon & McCartney''s song from <em>Sgt. Peppers Lonely Hearts Club Band</em> which had been released on June 1, 1967.</p>\n<p>Here''s Wes with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=a_0P1yBlvdw" target="_blank">A Day In the Life</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=a_0P1yBlvdw" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/wm-aditl-r.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /><img src="images/tdij/wm-aditl-f.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /><img src="images/tdij/wm-aditl-i.jpg" border="0" width="521" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"A Day in the Life" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">John Lennon, Paul McCartney</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">5:45</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Watch What Happens" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Jacques Demy, Norman Gimbel, Michel Legrand</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">2:43</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"When a Man Loves a Woman" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Calvin Lewis, Andrew Wright</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">2:52</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"California Nights" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Marvin Hamlisch, Howard Liebling</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">2:29</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Angel" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Wes Montgomery</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">2:46</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Eleanor Rigby" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Lennon, McCartney</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">3:04</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Willow Weep for Me" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Ann Ronell</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">4:31</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Windy" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Ruthann Friedman</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">2:20</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Trust in Me" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Milton Ager, Jean Schwartz, Ned Wever</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">4:25</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Joker" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Leslie Bricusse, Anthony Newley</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">3:26</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 64, '2015-06-22 17:12:40', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:36:07', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-06-26 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 5, 'on this day in jazz. Wes Montgomery', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 4526, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(455, 'On this day in jazz (June 27)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-june-27', '', '<p>On this day in 1981,   <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a> played live for the first time in almost five years at the Kix Club in Boston. Part of the music played on this day would be released on the live album <em>We Want Miles</em> which also includes music from a performance at Avery Fisher Hall (New York) on July 5,   and in Tokyo on October 4. Although the album wasn''t officially released in the US,   it can be found as part of the box set <em>The Perfect Miles Davis Collection</em>. Despite not being released in the US, it actually won the 1982 Grammy Award for Best Jazz Instrumental Performance by a Soloist. The album in its original form clocks in at around 80 minutes--the original vinyl was four sides long. However, in all that music, there are only six songs played.</p>\n<p>The personnel assisting Miles were <a href="http://www.billevanssax.com/" target="_blank">Bill Evans</a> on soprano saxophone, Mike Stern on electric guitar, Marcus Miller on bass guitar, Al Foster on the drums and Mino Cinelu with additional percussion. Yes, I said Bill Evans on soprano saxophone and not piano. That is because this is a different Bill Evans than the one that recorded with Miles in the late 1950s. That <a href="http://www.billevanswebpages.com/" target="_blank">Bill Evans</a> died in 1980 at the age of 51 from complications from chronic hepatitis. This Bill Evans was born in 1958 in Chicago suburb Claredon Hills and graduated from Hinsdale High School.</p>\n<p>Here''s Miles with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Onj1_BgQzI8" target="_blank">Back Seat Betty</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Onj1_BgQzI8" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/md-wwm-f.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /><img src="images/tdij/md-wwm-b.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Jean-Pierre"  10:30</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Back Seat Betty"  8:10</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Fast Track"  15:10</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Jean-Pierre"  4:00</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"My Man''s Gone Now" (DuBose Heyward, George Gershwin)  20:12</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Kix"  18:45</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 64, '2015-06-22 17:31:57', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:36:48', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-06-27 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 4, 'on this day in jazz, Miles Davis', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 4355, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(456, 'On this day in jazz (June 28)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-june-28', '', '<p>On this day in 1965,   the great <a href="http://www.johncoltrane.com/" target="_blank">John Coltrane</a> recorded the album <em>Ascension</em> at Rudy Van Gelder''s studio in Englewood Cliffs,   NJ. The album consists of just one song--however,   in order to release it--it had to be divided in half for the LP format. There were actually two takes of the song. The first take is referred to as Edition II and the second take as Edition I. As you may have guessed, Edition I was the one originally released on LP in 1966. John, however, preferred his first take (Edition II) and (maybe for the first time in history), they stopped printing the LP with the first Edition and moved to the second. If you have the record, you can look into the runout circle to see if you have the first or second edition. If it is the second, it will say EDITION II in the circle. When Atlantic re-released the album on CD in 2000, they included both versions.</p>\n<p>The album itself is considered to be an inflection point in John''s career with the albums coming before it more conventional (or structured) and the ones including this one and the ones that follow more free. I could go on talking about the album at length, but since this is a short blog, but let me just say a little bit about the band and then get directly to the music. John, who played tenor saxophone on this work, was assisted by a very strong cast which included wind from such greats as Freddie Hubbard on trumpet and both <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/?title=Pharoah_Sanders" target="_blank">Pharoah Sanders</a> and <a href="http://www.archieshepp.net/" target="_blank">Archie Shepp</a> also on tenor saxophones. The rhythm section was John''s standard section of <a href="http://mccoytyner.com/" target="_blank">McCoy Tyner</a> at the piano, Jimmy Garrison on bass and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elvin_Jones" target="_blank">Elvin Jones</a> on the drums.</p>\n<p>Here''s John with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KMNbW6DLB14" target="_blank">Ascension</a>" (Edition II):</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KMNbW6DLB14" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/jc-a-both.jpg" border="0" width="500" height="250" /><br /></a></p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KMNbW6DLB14" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/jc-a-inside.JPG" border="0" width="500" height="250" /></a></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 64, '2015-06-23 11:46:14', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:37:25', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-06-28 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 3, 'on this day in jazz, John Coltrane', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 4646, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(457, 'On this day in jazz (June 29)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-june-29', '', '<p>On this day in 1971,   pianist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mal_Waldron" target="_blank">Mal Waldron</a> recorded the live album <em>Black Glory</em> at the Domicile in Munchen,   West Germany for the Enja label. Mal was assisted on the album by Jimmy Woode on bass and Pierre Favre on the drums. allmusic.com gives it a strong four star rating saying:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">Waldron has continued to evolve through the decades while keeping his basic sound. A master at using repetition and brooding chords, Waldron is in excellent form on five of his originals plus Woode''s brief "M.C," playing with a knowledge of the avant-garde but still connected to the hard bop tradition.</p>\n<p>If this one is a little too avant-garde for you, check out his <em>Blues for Lady Day</em> album which I profiled on February 5--it''s essentially Mal playing songs that the great Billie Holiday had made famous<span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 15.8079996109009px;">(Mal had accompanied Billie from 1957 until her death in 1959)</span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 15.8079996109009px;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">. </span></p>\n<p>Here''s Mal with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nTx4g_zWaoA" target="_blank">La Glorie du Noir</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nTx4g_zWaoA" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/mw-bg-f.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"M.C." (Jimmy Woode)  0:35</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Sieg Haile"  17:39</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"La Glorie du Noir"  9:43</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"The Call"  6:38</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Rock My Soul"  6:36</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 64, '2015-06-25 11:00:15', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:38:20', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-06-29 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 2, 'On this day in jazz, Andrew Hill', 'On this day in jazz', 0, 5951, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(458, 'On this day in jazz (June 30)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-june-30', '', '<p>On this day in 1963,   the great <a href="http://mingusmingusmingus.com/" target="_blank">Charles Mingus</a> recorded the album <em>Mingus Plays Piano</em> for Impulse! Records. The album consists of Mingus playing eleven solos--six of them originals and several of them standards. Mingus is hands down one of the best composers in jazz history and was known as one of jazz''s greatest double bass players. However, he was also a pretty good piano player. With respect to the originals on the album, Scott Yanow said that the songs "are quite fascinating to hear, as if one were listening to Mingus think aloud." It''s also an album that some jazz fans would say is a go-to when they just want to unwind and hear something soothing.</p>\n<p>Here''s another reason Charles is considered one of the greatest composers in history: he wrote a 4000 bar piece called "Epitaph" (<a href="http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=92884124" target="_blank">which can be found on the internet</a>). You might wonder how long does it take to play 4000 bars? Well, it takes over 2 hours to play! The reason he titled it "Epitaph" was because (due to its length) he felt no one would ever play or record it while he was alive.<span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">With the help of a grant from the Ford Foundation, the score and instrumental parts were copied, and the piece itself was premiered by a 30-piece orchestra, conducted by Gunther Schuller (who, sadly, passed away on June 21, 2015). This concert was produced by Mingus''s widow, Sue Graham Mingus, at Alice Tully Hall on June 3, 1989--ten years after Mingus'' death. It was performed again at several concerts in 2007. The performance at Walt Disney Concert Hall </span><a href="http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=92884124" target="_blank" style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">is available on NPR</a><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">. The complete score was published in 2008 by Hal Leonard.</span></p>\n<p>Here''s Mingus with one of his originals "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eigRPbMEDJ8" target="_blank">Orange Was the Color of Her Dress, Then Blue Silk</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eigRPbMEDJ8" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/cm-mpp-f.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Myself When I Am Real"  7:38</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"I Can''t Get Started" (Vernon Duke, Ira Gershwin)  3:43</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Body and Soul" (Frank Eyton, Johnny Green, Edward Heyman, Robert Sour)  4:35</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Roland Kirk''s Message"  2:43</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Memories of You" (Eubie Blake, Andy Razaf)  4:37</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"She''s Just Miss Popular Hybrid" - 3:11</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Orange Was the Color of Her Dress, Then Silk Blue"  4:18</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Meditations for Moses" - 3:38</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Old Portrait" - 3:49</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"I''m Getting Sentimental Over You" (George Bassman, Ned Washington)  3:46</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Compositional Theme Story: "Medleys, Anthems and Folklore"  8:35</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 64, '2015-06-25 11:39:02', 62, '', '2016-08-18 19:38:37', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-06-30 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 1, 'on this day in jazz, Charles Mingus', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 8520, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(459, 'On this day in jazz (July 01)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-july-01', '', '<p>On this day in 1959,   <a href="http://www.davebrubeck.com/live/" target="_blank">Dave Brubeck</a> and <a href="http://www.puredesmond.ca/" target="_blank">Paul Desmond</a> recorded "Take Five" at Columbia 30th Street Studio in New York City. The song would appear on the album <em>Time Out</em>. The album is noted not only for the great music but also for the unusual time signatures the songs were based on. For example,   "Blue Rondo  la Turk" has both 9/8 and 4/4 signatures while "Take Five" uses quintuple time (5/4). "Take Five" was played by Dave on piano,   Paul (also the song''s composer) on alto saxophone, Eugene Wright on bass and Joe Morello on the drums.</p>\n<p>The album <em>Time Out</em> was the first jazz album to be certified platinum by the RIAA and actually reached #2 on the Billboard Pop Charts. It was added to the National Recording Registry in 2005. In 2009, Legacy Records released a 3-CD set with improved audio over the original CD release as well as previously unreleased concert recordings from the 1961, 1963, and 1964 Newport Jazz Festivals. It was also released in "<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DualDisc" target="_blank">DualDisk</a>" format along with 14 other albums in late 2004. However, due to a rights issue, it was recalled and only 50 known copies of the disk exist. Collectors lucky enough to have grabbed one have one valuable piece of plastic in their collection.</p>\n<p>Here''s Dave and Paul with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nzpnWuk3RjU" target="_blank">Take Five</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nzpnWuk3RjU" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/db-to-f.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /><img src="images/tdij/db-to-b.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing (all by Dave Brubeck except "Take Five"):</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Blue Rondo  la Turk" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">6:44</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Strange Meadow Lark" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">7:22</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Take Five" (Paul Desmond) </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">5:24</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Three to Get Ready" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">5:24</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Kathy''s Waltz" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">4:48</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Everybody''s Jumpin''" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">4:23</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Pick Up Sticks" </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em; white-space: pre;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">4:16</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 53, '2015-06-28 13:08:53', 62, '', '2016-08-16 21:43:46', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-07-01 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 8, 'on this day in jazz, Dave Brubeck, Paul Desmond', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 13974, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(460, 'On this day in jazz (July 02)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-july-02', '', '<p>On this day in 1990,   <a href="http://www.charliehadenmusic.com/" target="_blank">Charlie Haden</a> and <a href="http://www.jimhallmusic.com/" target="_blank">Jim Hall</a> were recorded live in concert at the Montreal International Jazz Festival. The set list is quite impressive including Thelonious Monk''s "Bemsha Swing",   Ornette Coleman''s "Turnaround",   the standard "Body and Soul", Hoagy Carmichael & Johnny Mercer''s "Skylark" and four originals by the two men. Also note that the entire concert is a series of duets.</p>\n<p>Pat Metheny, who considers both Charlie and Jim to be two of his musical heroes, said that the album is "a recording for the ages." I agree. Thom Jurek provides an excellent review of the album at allmusic.com. Here are the salient parts of that review:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">Given their respective careers up to this point, both men had nearly perfected the artistry of playing in this particular chamber jazz setting. That all said, it does not prepare the listener for the canny, intimate, yet absolutely electric interplay on offer here. From readings of standards such as "Bemsha Swing," "Body and Soul," and Skylark" through to Ornette Coleman''s "Turnaround" and excellent originals by both men -- including Haden''s bookends, the tenderly dissonant "First Song" and the knotty "In the Moment," and Hall''s sprightly melodic Latin waltz "Down from Antigua" and his fingerpopping "Big Man Blues" -- this music is an adventure top to bottom. It unfolds gradually and cannily over 76 minutes. Ethan Iverson''s liner essay is spirited, insightful, and illuminating to boot. This set is not only impossible to criticize, but adds an immeasurable depth to the catalogs of both artists.</p>\n<p>Here''s Charlie and Jim with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=U9lfJ98Hpck" target="_blank">Bemsha Swing</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=U9lfJ98Hpck" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/ch-jh.jpg" border="0" width="395" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Bemsha Swing (Thelonious Monk/Denzil Best)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">First Song (Charlie Haden)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Turnaround (Ornette Coleman)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Body & Soul (John Green/Edward Heyman/Robert Sour)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Down From Antigua (Jim Hall)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Skylark (Hoagy Carmichael/Johnny Mercer)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Big Blues (Hall)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">In The Moment (Haden)</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 53, '2015-06-28 13:21:46', 62, '', '2016-08-20 01:05:07', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-07-02 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 7, 'on this day in jazz, Charlie Haden, Jim Hall', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 14485, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(461, 'On this day in jazz (July 03)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-july-03', '', '<p>On this day in 1986,   pianist <a href="http://www.andrewhilljazz.com/" target="_blank">Andrew Hill</a> began recording the album <em>Shades</em> for Soul Note records at the Barigozzi Studio in Milano, Italy (it would be completed the next day). The album was Andrew''s first as a leader in six years and his twenty-fourth album overall. He was accompanied by the excellent <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clifford_Jordan" target="_blank">Clifford Jordan</a> on tenor saxophone, Rufus Reid on bass and Ben Riley on the drums.</p>\n<p>Scott Yanow reviewed the album for allmusic.com giving it a four star rating (users'' give it a four and a half), saying this about the music:</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">The quartet set (with bassist Rufus Reid and drummer Ben Riley) has six of Hill''s typically challenging and complex inside/outside originals, a perfect outlet for Jordan and the pianist to interact. Stimulating and unusual music that is difficult to classify as anything but "modern jazz".</p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">A little bit about Andrew: he was born in Chicago in 1931 where he took up the piano at age 13 and attended the University of Chicago Experimental School. As a teenager he joined legends such as <a href="http://www.milesdavis.com/us/home" target="_blank">Miles Davis</a> and <a href="http://www.cmgww.com/music/parker/home.html" target="_blank">Charlie Parker</a> when their tours came to town. In the 1950s he played with jazz greats such as <a href="http://www.ericdolphy.net/" target="_blank">Eric Dolphy</a>, <a href="http://www.bluenote.com/artists/bobby-hutcherson" target="_blank">Bobby Hutcherson</a>, <a href="http://www.freddiehubbardmusic.com/" target="_blank">Freddie Hubbard</a>, <a href="http://www.woodyshaw.com/" target="_blank">Woody Shaw</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hank_Mobley" target="_blank">Hank Mobley</a> and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tony_Williams_(drummer)" target="_blank">Tony Williams</a> (just to name a few). In 1961, while he was an accompanist for Dinah Washington, he moved to New York City and shortly thereafter primarily recorded as a leader. Andrew continued recording until his death in 2007. In fact, just in the years 2000-2008, he won the following awards:</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">2008: National Endowment for the Arts (NEA) Jazz Master (our nation''s highest jazz honor)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">2007: election to the Downbeat Hall of Fame; Jazz Journalist Association Pianist of the Year, Composer of the Year and Lifetime Achievement Award; conferred an honorary Doctorate of Music-Berklee College of Music</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">2006: Jazz Journalist Composer of Year Awards (as well as in 2000, 2001 and 2003); "Time Lines" was Down Beat Album of the Year; Playboy Jazz Artist of the Year</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">2001: "Dusk" was the Down Beat Album of the Year; Down Beat Winner Critics Poll Jazz (also in 2000)</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Here''s Andrew with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IuylQ1uQAAQ">Tripping</a>":</span></p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IuylQ1uQAAQ" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/ah-s-f.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Monk''s Glimpse" - 4:36</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Tripping" (aka "Naked Spirit") - 6:31</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Chilly Mac" - 5:29</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Ball Square" - 5:34</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Domani" - 7:28</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"La Verne" - 13:43</span></li>\n</ol>', '', 1, 8, 0, 53, '2015-06-28 15:51:24', 62, '', '2016-08-16 21:45:15', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-07-03 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 4, 0, 6, 'on this day in jazz, Andrew Hill', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 16805, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(462, 'On this day in jazz (July 04)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-july-04', '', '<p>On this day in 1970,    <a href="http://www.alicecoltrane.org/" target="_blank">Alice Coltrane</a> recorded the song "Isis and Osiris" at The Village Gate in New York City. The song would be the last song on her fourth album <em>Journey in Satchidananda</em>. Satchidananda refers to Satchidananda Saraswati (aka Yogiraj Sri Swami Satchidananda) whose religious teachings Alice followed. On the album Alice plays the harp and piano,   <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pharoah_Sanders" target="_blank">Pharoah Sanders</a> adds soprano saxophone and percussion, Vishnu Wood plays the oud (only on "Isis and Osiris"), <a href="http://www.charliehadenmusic.com/" target="_blank">Charlie Haden</a> plays the bass (only on "Isis and Osiris"--<a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/cecil-mcbee-mn0000739015/biography" target="_blank">Cecil McBee</a> plays bass on all other songs), Tulsi plays the tambura and Majid Shabazz plays bells & tambourine (on all tracks by "Isis and Osiris") and Rashied Ali plays the drums on all songs.</p>\n<p>Critics in general rate the album highly, and punk rocker Paul Weller of The Jam / The Style Council lists it as one of his favorite albums. I also like it a lot and agree with Thom Jurek''s view that the album is quite approachable and accessible. Thom also said this: "...a remarkable album, and necessary for anyone interested in the development of modal and experimental jazz". Give it a listen!</p>\n<p>Here''s Alice with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9lko1JUVh5w" target="_blank">Isis and Osiris</a>":</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9lko1JUVh5w" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/ac-jts-f.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /><img src="images/tdij/ac-jts-b.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Journey in Satchidananda" -6:39</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Shiva-Loka" - 6:37</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Stopover Bombay" - 2:54</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Something About John Coltrane" - 9:44</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Isis and Osiris" - 11:49</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 53, '2015-06-28 16:39:45', 62, '', '2016-08-16 21:28:10', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-07-04 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 5, 'on this day in jazz, Alice Coltrane', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 17301, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(463, 'On this day in jazz (July 05)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-july-05', '', '<p>On this day in 1960,   saxophonist <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harold_Land" target="_blank">Harold Land</a> began recording the album Eastward Ho! Harold Land in New York. On the album Harold plays the tenor,  <a href="http://www.kennydorham.net/biography/" target="_blank">Kenny Dorham</a> in on trumpet and the rhythm section consisted of Amos Trice on piano,   Clarence Jones on bass and Joe Peters on the drums. The album was produced by legendary jazz producer Orrin Keepnews. The song "O.K. Blues" was dedicated to Orrin.</p>\n<p>I haven''t profiled Harold Land on the blog and since I''m getting close to completing 1 year of blogging "On this day in jazz", I figured I might try and get in a couple of fresh faces. Here''s a few facts about Harold:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Born in Houston and grew up in San Diego</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Started playing at the age of 16</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">His first recording (as a leader) was in 1949</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">In 1954 he joined the Clifford Brown/Max Roach Quintet</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">In the 80s and 90s he was a member of the Timeless All-Stars which featured Cedar Walton on piano, Buster Williams on bass, Billy Higgins on drums, Curtis Fuller on trombone and Bobby Hutcherson on vibes.</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">He joined the UCLA Music Department in 1996</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p></p>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Here''s Harold with one of my favorite songs, Cole Porter''s "</span><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XwdYNNVv6Zs" target="_blank" style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">So In Love</a><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">":</span></p>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XwdYNNVv6Zs" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/hl-eh-f.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /></a></p>\n<p>Track listing:</p>\n<p></p>\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"So in Love" (Cole Porter) - 5:58</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Triple Trouble" (Amos Trice) - 5:46</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Slowly" (Kermit Goell, David Raksin) - 6:59</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"''On a Little Street in Singapore" (Peter DeRose, Billy Hill) - 7:07</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"O.K. Blues" - 12:23</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 53, '2015-07-04 17:21:19', 62, '', '2016-08-16 21:46:00', 62, 62, '2018-04-16 23:48:31', '2015-07-05 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 2, 0, 4, 'on this day in jazz, Harold Land', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 18800, '');
INSERT INTO `jos_content` VALUES(464, 'On this day in jazz (July 06)', 'on-this-day-in-jazz-july-06', '', '<p>On this day in 1957, trumpet virtuoso<a href="http://www.dizzygillespie.com/" target="_blank">Dizzy Gillespie</a> played the Newport Jazz Festival in Newport,  Rhode Island. The performance can be found on the album <em>Dizzy Gillespie at Newport</em>. Dizzy led a large band in this one (about 15 or so players) which included jazz greats such as <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lee_Morgan" target="_blank">Lee Morgan</a>, <a href="http://www.bennygolson.com/" target="_blank">Benny Golson</a>, and <a href="http://www.allmusic.com/artist/wynton-kelly-mn0000684253/biography" target="_blank">Wynton Kelly</a>. Scott Yanow reviewed the album for allmusic.com saying:</p>\r\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;">This CD features Dizzy Gillespie''s second great big band at the peak of its powers. On the rapid "Dizzy''s Blues" and a truly blazing "Cool Breeze," the orchestra really roars; the latter performance features extraordinary solos...This brilliant CD captures one of the high points of Dizzy Gillespie''s remarkable career and is highly recommended.</p>\r\n<p>The album features the song "Manteca" which is considered to be foundational to Afro-Cuban jazz. It was written by Dizzy, Chano Pozo and Gil Fuller in 1947. Gary Giddens of the Village Voice calls it "one of the most important records ever made in the United States". The song was the first tune based on the clave rhythmic pattern to become a jazz standard. If you listen closely, you can hear the band chant, "I''ll never go back to Georgia", during the song. This chant was in reference to racial prejudice that the band had experienced there in 1945.</p>\r\n<p>Here''s Dizzy with "<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Uy6tJFzZnts" target="_blank">Manteca</a>":</p>\r\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Uy6tJFzZnts" target="_blank"><img src="images/tdij/dg-an-f.jpg" border="0" width="250" height="250" /></a></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">Track listing:</span></p>\r\n<p></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Dizzy''s Blues" (Ahmad Kharab Salim)  11:51</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"School Days" (Will D. Cobb, Gus Edwards)  5:47</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Doodlin''" (Horace Silver)  7:56</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Manteca" (Gil Fuller, Gillespie, Chano Pozo)  7:11</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"I Remember Clifford" (Benny Golson)  4:48</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Cool Breeze" (Tadd Dameron, Billy Eckstine, Gillespie)</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Zodiac Suite: Virgo/Libra/Aries" (Mary Lou Williams)  10:28 Bonus track on CD reissue</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"Carioca" (Edward Eliscu, Gus Kahn, Vincent Youmans)  3:41 Bonus track on CD reissue</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-size: 12.1599998474121px; line-height: 1.3em;">"A Night in Tunisia" (Gillespie, Frank Paparelli)  10:00 Bonus track on CD reissue</span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p></p>', '', 1, 8, 0, 53, '2015-07-04 17:39:12', 62, '', '2018-04-16 23:48:17', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-07-06 06:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', '', 3, 0, 3, 'on this day in jazz, Dizzy Gillespie', 'on this day in jazz', 0, 18818, '');
